column11:
Came here for dinner tOnight and had a great experience. We got a last minute reservation at 8:45pm seating. Ordered :

1) clam chowder - interesting take on chowder
2) french onion soup - good, great for dipping 
3) giant prawn cocktail - huge size & fresh! 6 pieces
4) aged New York strip - cooked medium, great flavor 
5) abalone pasta - so fresh & delicious, a bit tarty 
6) lobster mac n cheese - good portion size, couldn't finish! 

They had delicious table side breads too. Really like the olive bread. So fluffy, perfect to dip in the soups. 

Very pricey meal, but nice ambiance and friendly staff.

column11: Real talk this place is the jam for some freaky fresh salads and sandwiches. I get the number 10 [sliced turkey, sun dried tomatoes, honey mustard...] and substitute  the regular cheese for brie. Their space is small inside but the outside is where you want to be anyways. Every experience has been phenomenal and they make a mean sandwich. Also, always order with focaccia its always on point.

column11:
What a gem---a delightful spot to be. We were at Jane last night for dinner with two new friends. We sat up in the balcony area and had an enchanting dinner for four. I had the Salmon and a Caesar Salad---wow. I love cozy family owned restaurants that have a distinctly California flair---and this one with a classic Santa Barbara feel. Classy, never stuffy----fresh, but creative. Service was wonderful, wine was delightful, food fantastic---and don't forget to have a bite of coconut cake before you head home. 

This is a perfect spot for a night out with friends, a dinner with clients, or your parents---perfect for any occasion. Lovely. Thank you. We will be back!

column11: Great casual spot for breakfast or lunch. The young staff is friendly and helpful and service was timely. I enjoyed sitting on the patio out front. There's ample seating both inside and out and Cafe Int'l can easily accommodate groups. I enjoyed delicious eggs Benedict one morning and an excellent hearty Italian omelet another day. Today I hit the cafe around noon and decided to sample the BLAT s sandwich with a side Caesar salad. It was great! Crispy bacon with lots of avocado and fresh slices of lettuce and tomato were perfect with the salad that had a really tasty Caesar dressing. The menu is so big, I look forward to trying some of the other offerings. Friends have said their soups and potato salad are really good too!

column11: Mesa Verde is consistently good but it's not going to blow you away. It's not my favorite place in town, but if you want some healthy options it's a good go-to. Personally, however, I think it's way overpriced for what you get. You can spend less and get more food at The Natural Cafe, which has similar options. I have tried both of their tacos--the street tacos and the rajas tacos. Both are average. The street tacos are very filling, and I recommend them if you like jackfruit! The rajas tacos are a bit of a let down. I can easily make the same tacos at home for a fourth of the price. They really just had grilled veggies, avo, and some vegan cheese. The tortillas are quite good and hold up to the toppings. I've also tried their curry, risotto, and Brussels sprouts. Each of the options looked so much better in the pictures but the flavors just did not go well together. I have left hungry each time, which is a bit of a disappointment after spending a lot of money (it's not cheap!). The Brussels sprout appetizer is about $15...seems to be way overpriced.

column11:
Located inside the Santa Barbara Inn, Convivo Restaurant was a Incredible dining experience!

We made reservations for outside but it was too chilly, even with heaters. We asked to sit inside and they accommodated us within minutes.

The restaurant has a wonderful view of the beach due to the large glass patio doors and  entry way next to the bar.

The table service was quick and the food was delicious. We had the seafood pasta, breaded pork chop and  margherita  pizzas.

Next time we're in SB, we'll definitely be returning!

Love this place!

column11:
Located inside an old tire shop in downtown Santa Barbara- fun atmosphere that doesn't take itself too seriously.  We were the first, and only ones there at 11am on a Sunday...obviously not God-fearing folk, nor do we care what people think if get our drink on before noon.

G. and I tasted several Oreana wines which are made on site- or so we were told. I was a bit disappointed there was no tour or explanation of the processes they use, the grapes they choose, etc. Favorites were a 2006 Viognier- nice and creamy,  and the 2005 "Tilly"- along the lines of a Super Tuscan, and named after the winemaker's Italian grandmother. The other wines were a tad bit forgettable, but keep trying and I promise to keep drinking.

I bought a bottle of the "Tilly"- part of the proceeds go toward helping people with Alzheimer's disease. G. bought a great tea-light candle holder made from an old wine barrel. Social and Environmental goodness was paid for and our conscious' were cleansed.

Oh, and the great girl who was working that day turned us on to both Hendry's Beach and Cold Spring Tavern. Sweet spots to spend the day.

column11:
Probably one of the better Chinese spots in SB/ Goleta area! I come to this spot every time my family is in town because it is one of the only authentic Asian food places in Goleta. On my last visit, the guy worker was so so sweet and attentive. One of my friends is gluten free and he was asking all the right questions to make sure her food accommodations were met! 

The beef noodle soup was actually really good, pretty authentic for santa barbara! I also really enjoy their satay broth with lamb! Their prices are really affordable for the amount of food you get! If you are ever craving hot spot/ shabu shabu in santa barbara, this place can definitely relieve that craving!

column11: I'm always searching for the best fried chicken and Finch & Fork didn't disappoint. I would actually give them 4-1/2 stars if i could. We started with the blistered shishito peppers and the cream caramelized onion soup. If i can only make that soup! For some reason i was expecting something like french onion soup, brothy. This was creamy heaven. The onion breadcrumb topping was yummy! My friend and i shared the buttermilk fried chicken. All i can say is thank god it was Tuesday! That was the special of the day. It came with mashed potatoes and pickles. I'm not sure i'm glad this is far from my home or not. I suppose I am or I'd be there every Tuesday. Super cute place and good service. If I'm in the area I will definitely be back to try some of their other choices.

column11:
I love this place! It's cheaper than Starbucks and it's better too! AND it has a drive thru! Very convenient. 

I worked at Starbucks for 2 years, so I know all about coffee, tea, etc. I go to Zizzo's all the time for their iced coffee, and I don't even like the iced coffee at Starbucks. 

I recommend buying an SB Axxess card for an extra 15% off. The service is always great. It's fast and the staff is very friendly. My only complaint is that they close too early.

Update: I've been going to Zizzo's a lot over the last few months and while I still love the place, I have some thoughts that I would love for management to see (although maybe I can just contact them directly) 

For a while, it seemed like whatever pastry I ordered was always sold out. Sometimes it was late in the day but not always. Either way, it seems like they should evaluate and anticipate their needs better. However, this seems like it has improved more recently, but I've been going less often so I'm not sure. 

I like the breakfast burritos a lot, but not the ones with bacon. I'd love to see Zizzo's have a chorizo or sausage breakfast burrito. They also have a breakfast sandwich I'd probably get if they had sausage instead of bacon. It seems like bacon is the meat of choice for a lot of their items. I'm sure I'm not the only one who would like more/better options. 

In regards to service, while the staff is friendly and does a great job, I often feel rushed when ordering in the drive thru. I'm often hearing the phrase, "Will that be all for you" (or something along those lines), even after only ordering one thing so far. And if I'm ordering multiple things, it gets annoying when it is asked after every item (which happens quite a bit). I'm sure the baristas are well-intentioned, but a phrase like, "can I get anything else for you," sounds a lot better, or perhaps even just saying "okay" to confirm they got it, so that the customer can continue ordering or let them know they're done.

column11:
Five stars for charm and romance. Four for food. 

Across from the Santa Barbara Harbor, with a view of the sailboats, water, sand. I found this when I was jogging on the far end of a stretch of tourist beach hotels. I was sure it would be a typical tourist joint with a good view, horrible food. But the strong Yelp reviews convinced my husband and I to make an impulse reservation when we were in town for our wedding anniversary.

We weren't disappointed! 

The location is so incredibly cute and European; I think I'd love it even if the food were bad. The tables are pressed up against the sidewalk windows, which have geraniums growing in window boxes. 

And the waiter had a lot of personality, sharing stories about the birthday present (wine) he got of his 80+-year-old father, who has the same birthday as me. I don't eat meat and had the handmade ricotta and tomato sauce ravioli and the tomato soup. They were good but not excellent. The thick ricotta filling in the pasta could have been improved by adding a variety of cheeses, in my opinion. My husband had the rigatoni with sausage and liked it but agreed it wasn't life changing. 

The drinks were memorable. There was a special marg on the menu for Fiesta weekend that was good. My husband had the Italian Stallion, kind of like an old fashioned. Both were awesome. 

I loved the people and vibe and can't wait to come back soon! Thanks guys.

column11:
I'm from Chicago, and I used to work at a Chicago style pizza restaurant. I have high standards, and this place exceeds my highest expectations. 

The pizza was just the way I remember it in Chicago. The service was excellent too. I used to have to drive all the way up to Zachary's in Berkeley to get legit Chicago style pizza. I am thrilled to now have this place in my own backyard. I'm surprised it took me so long to find out about it.

Concerning the negative reviews, most Californians don't know the first thing about Chicago style pizza, so they have a negative experience when it doesn't meet their expectations of what a pizza is supposed to taste like. Chicago style pizza is more like pie than it is like pizza.  It is very dense, and you normally can't eat more than two slices. So while a large pizza comes out to 40 bucks, each piece is the equivalent to three slices of a normal pizza. Working at a Chicago style pizza place I know it is not uncommon for the large pizzas with a lot of toppings to come out cold in the middle. I read some reviews that said this. This did not happen to my pizza, however, it does happen from time to time because it's such a thick pizza. It's no big deal, you just send it back and the manager will probably give you a discount.

column11:
State & Fig is a hidden gem with the cutest little outdoor patio. I came here with some girlfriends for big birthday brunch. There was a big group of 11 of us. They were accommodating and put tables together so that we could sit in the outdoor patio area. We were a little bummed that we did not get to order everything from the original menu, as they let us know that our menu would be different because we were such a big party. A few things were not available to order. I ended up opting for lunch and got the burger which was a great choice. 
A big reason why we came here is we wanted endless mimosas. The champagne was alright, not the best, but we stayed and enjoyed many anyway. The service was great and the food was amazing. I would come here again and skip the mimosas next time.

column11: I stopped in at Eureka on Thursday, 10/17/13, between 8 and 9.  I was in Santa Barbara on business and wanted a burger and something good to drink.  A live band was playing painfully loud music, but I decided to brave it.  A host was standing at the host stand on the phone.  She looked at me but did not greet me or acknowledge me.  I waited.  She continued to talk on the phone.  A second host came up and seated two people who had been waiting in the bar.  I waited.  Host 1 kept talking on the phone.  Host 2 returned to the host stand and proceeded to fiddle around with menus.  Host 1 looked at me again but didn't acknowledge me or indicate to Host 2 that she should help me.  The place was busy, but I could see plenty of empty tables.  I continued to wait, then gave up and went to a place that was willing to greet me and seat me.

column11:
I stopped by here on my way up the coastline and I'm glad I did. The donuts were fresh and the lady behind the counter was so friendly. She even slipped in a complimentary donut in the bag! I tried a maple bacon (with bacon strips on top), maple glaze, chocolate old fashioned, cinnamon crumb, and plain glazed cruller. All of them were delicious and tasted so fresh. 

This place also has bagels and boba tea. My girlfriend got the Thai Tea boba and she was impressed that the thai tea was brewed and not added as powder, which is the cheaper but less tasty option.

column11: I'm a huge wing fan and have been missing good wings since coming to UCSB. In september when I saw this place was opening up, I was very excited! I checked back every couple days asking when they'd open and got a few answers. They finally opened late October, and I went in the first day and got 6 habanero screamin and 6 angry evil wings. It was a bit slow, and I was maybe slightly disappointed by the wings, although I wouldn't have admitted it, having hyped the place up so much. I returned about a week later, and it was much, much better! Every time I've gone since then, it's just been better and better. Although it took them a little while to get off the ground, they have really figured things out and are operating fantastically. I went twice today, and now that they're working with a full menu, it's freakin awesome. I was very impressed with their burgers; these might be the best burgers in IV! Love this place.

column11: I was not a fan of Tap Thai on upper State street as it seemed like Thai food for people who don't want too much spice and flavors.  I always go to Your Choice if I am in the area.  I still decided to give the new Tap Thai a try after two bad experiences at the Goleta Meun Fan Thai.  I was pleasantly surprised at the fresh flavors and the spice level seemed higher than their State street location.  The portion size was also more generous than the other Thai places in Goleta, especially for the noodle entrees.  I enjoyed the fresh papaya salad, but wish they offer the option of adding salted crab to really kick up the flavor.  I ordered yellow curry, but received Panang curry instead.  I have never been to Thai, so I have no idea what authentic Panang curry taste like.  The Panang curry here is on the sweet side, which suits the American palate.  Pad see ew was standard, fat rice noodles stir fried with eggs, broccoli, fried tofu, and sweet soy.  Garlic fried chicken wing came with an order of 3 whole wings (6 sections of wings).  The wings were very crispy without being too dry, however, it could use more salt before they were fried.

column11:
My wife and I started going to Palazzio's in 1995 at the Monticeto location.  It was wonderful.....a 5 star restaurant!  As the years past and the owner opened the State St. location the brand has declined so much (to the one star rating that I have given it today) that I think my wife and will be looking for another place to go.

My rating is solely based on the service, or lack there of, that has become the norm at the State St. location.  The service was so bad the last time we were there I saw 2 different groups of people leave before they were seated because the staff didn't even acknowledge their presence.  My family and I waited for 10 mins. before I had to get someone's attention to get seated.  The hot rolls that we were accustomed to getting every 10 mins. we're non existent for our table, I again had to ask the busboy to bring us out some rolls as our waiter or waitress (we didn't have an assigned waitress) was nowhere to be found.  It took forever for someone to take our order, even longer to get the food, and getting the check was impossible.

If it were not for Jamie, the hostess, I am confident that my family would have gone with out food.  She seemed like she was the only one working that night.

All of my negative comments aside the food is still great, so if you do not mind waiting for service, refills, rolls, food or your bill, you will still leave Palazzio's feeling like you had a good meal.  However, I would recommend calling ahead and ordering your food to go and having a sunset picnic at the beach as opposed to dining in the restaurant.

column11: This is my favorite place for ice cream and I visit it each time I'm in Santa Barbara.  The original shop is on Mission Avenue, a bit farther uptown, and I like it because of the atmosphere of "old-timey ness", with photos of all the famous people, including President Reagan, who have had their ice cream.  Their outdoor patio uptown is also nice and there's a very small lot for parking.  Lots of flavors to choose from and the ice cream is very creamy and rich.

column11:
I've had it 3 times, at different places.  I've gotten the club sandwich which is delicious and HUGE.  It comes with turkey and chicken, which is a little weird.  First time I ordered it as is, then second time I got all turkey and it was a much better decision.  I asked to have them not put the middle piece of bread just because the sandwich is piled so high, and they said they couldn't do it... The chipotle mayo is really good but pretty spicy, my sandwich was smothered in it.  

I got the Reuben sandwich at the IV location, it was average.  Not big at all and pretty pricey, definitely won't get that again.

Overall, the club sandwich is really good, highly recommend.  A little on the pricey side, but the club is at least huge so it's worth it.  Not sure if the IV location just had a smaller portion for some reason or if it was just the sandwich I ordered.

column11:
There is nothing better than eating a fat burrito which stays together til the very end. Food Coma. 

I've only been to Santa Barbara 4 times, so I made it a point to revisit Freebirds, and this time (considering I was done with college, and not drunk) I wanted to really get a taste of what I was eating and remember it. 

I came here with a couple of other friends, per recommendation, and was not disappointed. I had a Super Burrito with chicken, which came with rice, salsa, guacamole, and sour cream. Now, it seems basic, but I mowed through this burrito like Clowney on Michigan (http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UalKtKcldvE). 

Get some chips and guacamole on the side, and call it a night when you're done :) You won't be awake much longer after.

column11:
The service is second to none. Reuben, the owner checked in with us twice and his menu recommendations were spot on. 

The scallop crudo would be my death row meal. -Melt in your mouth with a warm heat/peppery finish. 

The bone marrow bruschetta is like butter-radical, elevated, rich, inviting and satisfying. 

Wild boar short ribs had a gorgeous crust, fell off the bone and were served with a sweet, tangy sesame-soy sauce. 

Wagyu carpaccio was delicate and sauced beautifully with crispy taro chips. 

Our only gripe-we wouldn't order the flash-fried shu mai again. Very one note. Nothing special.

Our waiters were top-notch and incredibly well-informed. Lauren was a standout and treated us like family in the best possible way. Her suggestions were based upon menu items she enjoyed and her palate was quite sophisticated. The artwork on the walls was eye-catching. We can't wait to return!

column11: I've updated my earlier review because I think the Red Piano has really found its groove. As noted it my previous two star posting, the music still is a tad loud but once the party gets going with Jason at the piano, the high volume does support the best party on State Street. I've heard a few patrons also saying its a little tough to converse while the music is blasting, but as other reviews have stated, the point of the place is to sing along and get into the spirit above all else. So, if you haven't tried it yet, trust me the RP is THE best night out in Santa Barbara. If you get there early and grab a good spot you'll have more fun that you've had in years.

I've heard this is a dive bar. It's not. It would need to have shredded seats from a knife fight, a front window that has a permanent plywood patch, or a front door without a lock(always open). 
Instead, it has a boatload of different beers to offer, great music, four pool tables, and a great surf rocker atmosphere.
Locals will come up and challenge you to a game of pool, so be prepared :-)
And to top it off, Yelp got me 50% off my first 805.
Hats off to the owner

column11:
One of the few Yelpers here that found this place mediocre... 

I came here with a large group of 12 for a birthday celebration on a Saturday night. 

The setting is nice and all but we were the only large group that did not get any patio heater to warm us (we were there from 7:30-9:30pm). The waiters forgot to refill our waters multiple times even though we patiently reminded them to. 

I ordered the penne al salmone ($22) and that took 30 mins to come out. I get that it's busy but seriously...? The food looked delicious but I found the taste to be just OK and mediocre. I wasn't impressed. The salmon pieces were small and the sauce wasn't anything special. I've had a few tastes of my other friends' pasta dishes and they were ok too (seafood pasta, chicken Alfredo pasta). 

We got charged 20% gratuity so be careful in large groups as it does add up tremendously and they DON'T do separate checks and they have an 8 credit card limit. 

I don't get this place and I've had better pasta at a much more affordable price. MEH.

column11:
Personally, I think the hype for Los Agaves is a bit too high. But with so many Yelp reviews and long lines, I insisted that my girlfriend and I give them a try during our recent trip to Santa Barbara.

My first question is: What happens to the people that dine-in and have no place to sit? Considering my girlfriend and I barely found a seat, I'm guessing the crowds that piled in after us were forced to take all of their food to go?

Anyway, Los Agaves offers up Mexican food. A lot of Mexican food. The menu attempts to cover a lot of ground - probably too much, in fact. The food is priced as more of a mid-tier sit-down restaurant, but done using an order at the counter approach.

Los Agaves isn't bad by any means. My rajas con queso and carne asada tacos were both decent - with the asada being far, far better than what I experienced the previous day at Lilly's Tacos. 

My gringa al pastor, which is a greasy, cheesy quesadilla wasn't too bad, but by no means the best version I've ever tried. My girlfriend's Enchiladas Guadalajara were fine, but once again, weren't quite anything memorable in comparison to some of her favorites.

Beans and rice were both on-point, while guacamole was also what you'd expect.

Maybe for Santa Barbara's limited options, Agaves is a gold-mine. But if you're well acquainted with good Mexican food outside of the area, you'll realize that Agaves isn't really anything special. In other words, there's nothing here that feels exclusive.

In the end, it's worth a visit, but probably not a place I'd ever return to in the future. But for tourists and locals, it's easily a solid choice.

column11: We were extremely impressed with this restaurant ! My husband and I were visiting from Los Angeles and were getting tired of all the over priced touristy restaurants we were seeing.  Milk and Honey was a breath of fresh air : small and intimate and beautifully decorated.  And we could not believe the reasonable prices and impeccable presentation of all the tapas.  We went during happy hour and enjoyed pretty generous and inventively prepared sangria and mojitos for only $5 and $6 respectively .   Our server Julia was so attentive and sweet .  It was my birthday and she surprised us with warm brownies and 2 glasses of cava with a candle in one of them.  Our only lament is that there is not a place like this in Los Angeles .  We could really use one!

column11:
The good news: if you are absolutely hard up for a ball of pho and your car has broken down in Carpenteria, you have an option now.  Mind you, it's not even in the same freaking ballpark as any number of areas of Southern California where Vietnamese restaurants tend to herd... but it is an option I suppose.

If I had never eaten pho before, I probably would give us more than two stars.  After all, any idiot can enjoy a glass of wine at a wedding,  shake it off the next morning with a B vitamin, and forge ahead.  The more discriminating sommelier would likely not even order a glass.

As a self-professed omnivore, I am not pho snob... or maybe I am.  I just know that I've had better bowls of soup at lots of other places.  The basil, sprouts, and lime plate was pathetic.  It seriously looks like they brought me one that had already made it out to a table.  Why bother?

Broth wasn't balanced in my opinion, going a little heavy on the salt and not quite enough fennel/star anise flavor.  The noodles had the wrong chew, and got a little soggy too fast for my liking.  That nearly $12 for the big bowl, you're paying almost double for Carpinteria rents and beachside community ambience, I guess... Because most places in Westminster, Garden Grove, and Alhambra are half the price for a better bowl of soup.  If you live here, I suppose it comes out even by the time you're done paying for gas.

I tend not to judge a Vietnamese restaurant by its service, because most of them are drop and dash when it comes to bringing food to your table.  This one sort of brought it to a whole new level however.

Anyway, like I said... I'm not in Carpenteria with the pho bug often enough to really care.  Sometimes these little out-of-the-way places are hidden gems.

Other times, in the immortal words of Charlie Brown: "I got a rock!"

column11:
Food was amazing! We got brussle sprouts and pork belly, which were both simply irresistible. We ended up ordering about five other items which were all so delicious, with perfect portions. The alcohol options are also classy and unique and the mule we ordered was amazing.

The atmosphere is so classic and unique, it's a perfect dining experience. The tables have brown paper with crayons in a small cup to draw/write. My boyfriend and I had a ball playing games and writing jokes. 

The only reason I took a star away was because our actual waiter seemed a little disinterested and wasn't very helpful with our I inquiries. But everyone else was amazing and very friendly.

column11: I went there randomly for a date and I couldn't have been more happy with my mistake. I cannot remember our servers name but he obviously was either the owner or head chef. He talked about his dishes with such passion and excitement which only made the experience that much better. His passion for food was translated brilliantly on to the plates. If I had to give 1 recommendation for anyone eating here, ORDER THE BONE MARROW!! This dish is for sure one of the top 3 foods I have ever indulged upon. Our server connected with us on a personal level and his energy and love for the job is translated brilliantly to not only the guests, but the food as well. Cheers!

column11:
My family and I visited this restaurant on Sunday actually and I loved it. The second we walked in we were greeted by Cyndie who was such a sweetheart. They serve the best garlic rolls here so definitely a must try. The food portions were a tad bit much, but we were warned of that before ordering. The half portion will be enough for around two to three people depending on how much you eat. And the full portion will be enough for the whole family of that I'm sure. 

Great food and amazing service!

column11: Nice warm place on a rainy chilly day to get a tasty quick lunch. Clean and bright colors. Decided to try basic classic shrimp bowl with kelp noodles,  it was delicious, I do like a little more spice, so after adding some pepper flakes it was all good. Next time I'll go for spicy ceviche. Husband went for classic shrimp as well and mixed it up a little and added octopus. The scoop of crab salad they put on side is really tasty, yum. We were not crazy about the choice of music playing, a little loud and a bit to rap like beat for me. They did turn it down some when we asked. Let's just say I'm from a little older music type . Hopefully sun shining next time and I'll sit outside; people watch the shoppers in the mall.

column11:
After quite a few trips here, I thought I'd review this awesome scrumptious place.
Yes, it's on the pricier side for some noodle or soup, but it's fresh food, quick, and yummy. The Bangkok noodle or hangover noodle are my usual go to. Yet, a Thursday happy hour visit for the Tom Kha noodle was worth it! It is udon noodle with Tom Kha and they will deliver it to the wine bar next store. We sat and grabbed a bottle of wine and enjoyed our hot flavorful noodles. I highly recommend this for a quick stop or a wine do

column11:
RUN do not walk to Yoichi's. But seriously, please go experience this amazing, beautiful place and give it the attention it deserves. Every course was exceptional, both in presentation and in taste. From the homemade sesame tofu to the grilled, whole sweet fish to the mochi crepe at the end, I loved every bite. Service was spot on too. 

My husband and I both agree that it is the best meal we've ever had. Don't go there if you want a spicy tuna roll or fish smothered in sweet sauce. Yoichi's uses the freshest ingredients and lets them shine. There is a delicacy and grace to all the food. There is such attention to detail and precision to all the courses - they even have a local artist make new (gorgeous) dishes for each new monthly menu. 

Liquor license is pending and I'm looking forward to going back and trying the dishes with sake. The only bad part was that very few other people were there with us! Given the quality, this place should have a line out the door.

column11:
Love that they promote local beer and wine, and it's a really awesome little place. Live music, board games, dog friendly, and a great back patio. However, the food is overpriced, the drinks (outside of happy hour) are overpriced, and I've always received lukewarm service. Particularly the guy with the afro always makes me feel like he could care less about whether or not I buy a drink or enjoy my experience. I've never seen a bartender be so inattentive to someone sitting directly in front of him.

However, I keep going back because during HH it's reasonable, and I do enjoy the selection, both beer & wine.

column11:
Kim Cameron, Valencia, CA
I have eaten here countless times. I kept trying to find something I really liked because everyone else loved to eat here. I just never really liked it. I LOVE Breakfast Burritos and Phili Cheese Steak sandwiches, but I don't love theirs. The Breakfast Burrito is kind of boring and I always needed to add things to enjoy it. It's huge, but instead of making it sooo big, I think they should make it smaller and add more ingredients (add extra cheese, potatoes, steak/bacon/sausage, remove the beans), and also start making a fresh, more traditional-Mexican style salsa (they use a store-bought salsa, or at least it looks store bought). Also, for the Philadelphia sandwich, they use processed steak, and processed cheese (the kind where slices come individually wrapped). For me, it ruins the sandwich. The breakfast Cottage Fries are really yummy, but sometimes they are inconsistent. My friend got hers and they were perfect, then I was served mine and they were black (same table!). Also, the Mexican food that I've tried is too Americanized. Anyway. The food is OK, but I just don't like it as much as everyone else I guess...

column11: I have been staying at this B & B on an off for over 10 years. The rooms are very clean and well furnished. Everyone is cutting back these days, but a couple of really small changes would make it as special as it used to be. Oreo cookies?? They are the worst, get some decent cookies even if they have to be store bought or offer another choice. Also the cheese used to be really good, now it's not quite Cheese Whiz, but close, get better cheese for the wine. The breakfast is still good. I would suggest they get those half oval shower curtain rods as the tubs are quite narrow. Convenient location, quiet.

column11: As a figure skating coach and mother of a young skater, let me tell you how nice it is to have MJ Cafe at our local ice rink! The location is also very convenient for the people who go to Girsh Park for soccer games and practices! The place is spotless and the decor is beautiful and cozy.  We are at the rink 6 days/week and tried many things on the menu (breakfast to lunch and dinner), and everything we had was delicious! Love their oatmeal with fresh cut fruits, pizzas, non greasy fries and mozzarella sticks, homemade protein balls and PB&Chocolate cookies...They have lattes and a great beer and wine selection! You can sit inside or enjoy their outdoor terrasse next to Girsh Park!

column11: Oliver's was amazing. The deck is beautiful and the food is amazing. I could not believe it was vegan. We had great service and our waiter was spot on with suggestions. We decided to share everything so we could try different plates. We ordered the truffle asparagus soup, pear and Gorgonzola flatbread, cauliflower bucatini, and artichoke "crab" cakes. They also gave me a chocolate torte for my birthday for dessert. Can't wait to go back!

Worst place to go for cocktail drinks; a few of their bartenders don't even know what they're doing when they preparing your drinks. I went there a couple weeks ago and because it is a bar they think that every customer who goes there is drunk and they want to be disrespectful towards them. When I order the girl a drink she made it completely different of how it suppose to be, I was just watching her, I told her about it and she got super aggressive and offended. I am paying for what I am receiving I obviously can complaint if I see thinks different. She is super aggressive to customers, I have experience several problems with her for the same issues. She take advantage of people cause assumes they are drunk; she is an expert on stealing customers money if customers don't notice. Last problem I had with her I gave her a $100 bill and she denied it, but I ask her to call the manager, then she came and she was, "Oh yeah, here is the rest." She didn't even bother to give an apology for what she've done.. 
Be really careful when you go there! They like to take advantage of you..  This place is a rip of when this latina bartender is there, plus she has poor customer service.. Honestly don't waste your time with her.

column11:
Come here if you want a treat.  If you are hungry, you may have to burn a big hole in you wallet to fill up.  

About me:
I am your average restaurant lover.  I have not embraced organic food, or gluten free food.  I do love great taste, and value when it comes to food. 

The Story:
I took my wife and two kids here, and ordered a slice of quiche, a small beef pie, salad, and two sweet pies for desert.  The total cost was around $28.  The food taste good, but the servings were too small.  I thought for $28 I could have brought my family to the Habit.

Conclusion:
Simply Pie's fell short in value.

column11:
The tasting room is very well lit and has a fun feel that goes with the neighborhood. The El Paso area is great for walking around and exploring a few tasting rooms outside the funk zone area. 

You can't go wrong with any of the wines and I especially love the M5 (blend of 5 grapes - Syrah, Grenache, Mourvdre, Counoise and Cinsault) or a really yummy spin on a GSM (GSM is one of my go to favorite). 

I love what they have done over the past year to redecorate by adding some stainless steel countertops and a little market that has some really cool stuff. Overall the vibe is cool, the wines are great, reasonably priced = you can't go wrong here!

column11:
This might be my favorite restaurant in the world. You can't beat it for the price point. The fresh-made tortillas are amazing. The #16 is always good: marinated pork, peppers, and cheese. The chorizo quesadillas are fantastic. Some of the best meals though are on the Specials menu. On Mondays they have great chilaquiles. Not sure which days these are, but the fish tamales, veggie tamales, and veggie chile rellenos are incredible. 

It's not a standard taqueria: no chips, no burritos. It's cash only and closed on Tuesdays and Wednesdays. If it's peak hours on a weekend be prepared for a wait. But weekdays before 5:00 or after 8:15 or so it's usually not bad at all. And to all the people who say the food is not flavorful, I'm guessing you ordered the plain steak taco, what did you expect? There are tons of super flavorful choices. And again, the real gems are in the daily specials menu. I'd give it more stars if I could.

column11:
This is the best place to get an espresso drink in Goleta. This is also coincidentally the worst place to get pastries in Goleta. 

The coffee/espresso here is very good by Santa Barbara standards, though it's only just OK by any other place that has a respectable coffee culture (sorry SB! You have many wonderful things going for you, and I know you think you know coffee, but you don't.) The drinks are made with care and proportioned well. It's just the flavor itself that isn't quite there, like it's missing something crucial in the middle. 

The pastries are essentially dense, collapsed lumps of dough that never will never know their true potential as light, fluffy flaky pillows of heaven. It makes me so sad writing that. 

There is indoor and outdoor seating, and the high ceilings and spaciousness inside feel welcoming. The baristas and staff are really friendly and attentive to customers, and that's a lot of what keeps me coming back.

column11:
I was underwhelmed. 
I've been there three times now.  Once was a weekend lunch, once was a weekday work group lunch and recently was after work drinks with a couple people.

Burgers are above average, salads are generous. The onion rings, which  were rumored to be good, were good, but pricey at $5.95. 
The hummus is also pricey at $5.95, but plated nicely.

The macaroni and cheese, though, bleah. Another $5.95 item, and as the ultimate comfort food, it's not unreasonable to expect comfort food. What we got was discomfort food. Actually, the worst I think I've ever had. Worse than boxed mac and cheese. Everyone in the group tried it and said, "wow. that's seriously bad."
The pasta was undercooked, like crunchy. The sauce tasted just like Taco Bell nacho cheese sauce mixed 1:1 with water.  More like crunchy pasta cheese-flavored soup.  There must have been some bad mojo going on in the kitchen to produce a dish like this.

Thank goodness we had the onion rings to tide us over.

column11:
I really like this restaurant because not only did I have a smashing good brunch but I didn't pay for the delicious meal.  The girlfriend did .
I really liked their pastries like the Blueberry raspberry blackberry danish, which was semi-sweetness in a flaky crust.  The waiter said they baked the pastries in-house.  
The Endless summer scramble was awesome as was the Shrimp & grits.  
The service was top notch and although there was a wait it wasn't that long.  I guess because we got there before 10 am.  
I got to pick all the restaurants for the weekend because it was her birthday and she wanted me to show initiative.  In the end she said I did well

column11:
The Simpson House Inn is a true hidden gem.
It's walking distance from all the bars and restaurants. 
But it's in this quiet, secluded, relaxing location. 

I would recommend it for couples, friends, or anyone looking to de-stress.
This is the place to really enjoy some peace and feel pampered.

I suggest buying some local wine from the nearby wineries, and enjoying 
it in your room's private porch.

Cocktail Hour and breakfast were simple, yet delicious.
We stayed in the Tack Room and it was cozy, beautiful, and private.

column11:
Placed an order that included a breakfast sandwich on a bagel. We got everything we order within two minutes EXCEPT the breakfast sandwich. Waited for 15 minutes and then noticed they hadn't even started making it. A staff member had been walking around with my bagel. She hadn't even sliced it yet! 3 people who ordered after me got their food and left. WTF? I'm stopping to a quick bit to eat on the way to work. I can't wait 15 more fucking minutes. All staff generally seemed confused and unhelpful.
Never returning.

column11: I highly recommend The Creekside for private events. We rented the whole restaurant for my Mothers rustic wedding and we were completely satisfied. The renovation at this venue is beautiful and it truly provided a stunning setting! Dave was great to work with leading up to the wedding. Behnom was incredible with the day-of operations. He was like my personal assistant ensuring that I was happy and enjoying my family and friends. To be honest, all of the staff were very attentive and easy to work with. Our guests enjoyed all of the delicious options the buffet offered. I was a bit concerned about the parking but that went smoother than predicted as we encouraged guests to carpool. Again, I HIGHLY recommend this venue for a private event and for a causal bite to eat!

column11: 5 hour drive to what we thought would be a cool, ocean view, clean, updated hotel.  Not at all!  Ocean view was a joke, if you went to the corner of the room, sure it was a peak at the ocean.  Room was tiny!  They had a sticker on the door saying it was sanitized and clean.  Obviously not.  Someone had been in the room, used the bathroom and threw a towel on the bathroom floor, left their cocktail drink cup and had water all over the counter.  The floor maybe a terribly loud creaking sound with every step.  Ice was only available in the lobby.  Air conditioner works great but blows directly on the bed with the largest vent I've ever seen in a tiny room.  Kept me up all night with a high wind gust of cold air every 20 minutes when the AC kicked on.  We checked out after the 1st night

column11:
The Boathouse is a rightful staple sit-down restaurant in the Santa Barbara area. Its prices, although on the higher side, are well worth the food's portions, flavors, and creativity put into making them. And the servers are incredibly kind and accommodating. 

I love fish tacos, so I got those, but (although they were super tasty) I should've gone with my gut and gotten the Tuna Melt that my friend ordered. It had just the right amount of crunch, melt, moisture, and ZING of flavor. Too good!! The ceviche and shrimp were fresh and flavorful, and presented oh-so-beautifully. 

The only reason I put 4 stars is because of the wait... we were told we would wait an hour. Which was already stretching it, but it was understandable given the sheer amount of people waiting to eat at this place. We went for a walk on the beach, but when the hour had passed, there were still no tables to be sat at. An hour and a half into the wait, I decided to go up to the front and ask for the tables they hadn't assigned to anyone (since they were in direct sunlight). We were immediately seated! We all got a bit rosy/burnt (depending on our melanin levels) from sitting in the sun our entire meal, but at least it was away from the crowd and we got to eat! Definitely recommend going to this place at unconventional times/ days to avoid the wait. Or just be that group that doesn't mind sitting where no one else wants to sit!

Sound was mixed and EQ'ed better than a lot of live bands I've heard, and it's not "just" karaoke to him. The singers were almost all talented, too, which makes for a fun night. Great brews on tap. The volume was loud, so I recommend earplugs.

column11:
This place is simply awesome!  

I went for the very first time yesterday afternoon.  What caught my eye was the stylist, shabby chic look of the quaint shop.  Secondly when I looked inside I saw this bubbly woman standing behind the counter with such a warm and inviting smile; my family and I just HAD to stop in. *By the way, she plays great music jams too!*

The owner allowed us to sample any flavor that we wanted!  It was SO hard to choose, everything tasted fantastic!  I finally decided on the hazelnut gelato, it was so yummy!  My husband, son, daughter, mom, sister, cousin, aunt and 2 second cousin's ALL walked away with a different icy treat.  

I can't wait to be back in the Santa Barbara area, this is definitely one of my "go to" spots.

Thanks again, 

Your "Lucky Charms!"

column11:
Boy, do I dislike Palace Grill's food. I've dined here several times at the encouragement of my family members and out of town guests and each time I have been disappointed. Palace Grill is to cajun food, what Chilli's Bar & Grill is to mexican food. Exactly, not comparable! 

Everything that I have ordered is drowned in salt. Apparently, that's all you need to call it cajun food. Perhaps I'm spoiled because I lived in Louisiana for a few months and had real cajun food on the regular. The dishes they are serving up at Palace just don't hit the mark in my humble opinion. 

I do enjoy their cocktails, on the other hand, and their bread pudding. If' you're just drinking, eating dessert or don't mind a little hypertension, Palace Grill is your place! 

The atmosphere is quite lively and colorful which is a nice treat to some of Santa Barbara's more sterile dining ambiances.

column11:
My boyfriend and I recently moved to Santa Barbara, and so of course we're on the lookout for Mexican food that is good, cheap and authentic. I really can't say if Romanti-Ezer is authentic, but it meets the other two criteria hands down.

This place is not an indoor restaurant. It is a walk-up window and an adjoining patio with seating. You place your order, take your drink and free chips (topped with crumbly cheese and delicious mole, free of charge) and head to the table to wait.

We ordered the loco nachos ($8.50), which are loaded with sour cream, pico de gallo, multiple meats, cheese and beans and could easily feed two people. We also did the asada and chicken tacos, $2.75 each I believe, both of which came on what seemed like a fresh corn tortilla topped with pico de gallo. Yum. They also give you your choice of spicy red salsa and salsa verde at the table. Overall for around $17 we were stuffed and couldn't finish it all.

This is definitely a great place to grab a quick lunch or dinner outdoors off the main State Street drag. Not to mention these guys are open until 3am Thursday-Saturday, so I bet this is a great spot for the after-bar crowd.

column11: By far, the best meal I have had in months! I went with a group of girlfriends for dinner and we were all raving about how great our food was. One of my girlfriend's ordered the pork shank, which was so tender the meat practically melted in my mouth. Overall, the food is of high quality and very well prepared. Additionally, this place is known for pairing its meals with wines from the local wineries.

column11: Driving through downtown in search of good Mexican food and we came across Los Arroyos! What immediately caught our eye was the amount of traffic going in and out of the restaurant. Plan ahead when coming it stays busy!

column11:
The Night Market is so great for this time of year! I am glad they're using the space, and I hope to get some Christmas gifts from here.

The shops are somewhat varied, so you can definitely pick up a few Christmas gifts here. Go with an idea in mind, though - there is a LOT in here. My favorite was a local jeweler's stand. I picked up a piece for myself and my sister!

The food selection is AWESOME! I plan to go back just for the Cubano and some Rori's. The food is clustered together, so stop there first, then browse while eating dessert.

The bar/wine area is also so so good. Most have little nooks to sit in with comfy chairs and games. I grabbed some mulled wine (for only $6), and it made my night.  

One downside is how piecemeal the area becomes... it is so easy to get turned around or miss entire collections or sections. I'd recommend more clear categorization of the booth locations in the future, e.g. food, food gifts, clothes, jewelry, misc. It felt hard to take it all in because you'd see olive oil tastings flanked by local clothes and jewelry, go several booths down and see other food.

I can't wait to go back, and I hope this becomes an annual tradition!

column11:
The one positive thing I can say about this place is that they let us leave after one night without charging us for the second night, and the guy was nice about it.

you could not see the ocean from our "ocean view room." The deck was tiny, with a deck above us (so, no sun) and the view was straight into a hillside. The ocean was on the other side of the hill. Despite what they say -- no rooms in this hotel are on the beach. You have to walk down a trail to get to the beach.

The room was in no way a five star hotel room: small, dated, not laid out well, very low ceilings.

every restaurant was loud, with way too many tables. 

the beach is covered with tar. (tar is a natural occurrence on some beaches in CA. It wasn't the result of an oil spill, as some guests think,)

that said -- they REALLY should mention on their site that you can't walk on the beach or swim without bringing LOTS of alcohol wipes to clean tar off of your feet and shoes. And I would NEVER let my kid onto this beach -- totally unsafe and unhealthy. Yes, it's natural tar, but this is the most tar I've ever seen on a beach. It smells like a gas station. there's oil rigs RIGHT off shore. 

Come on guys -- you should tell people: this is not a beachfront hotel, and the beach has a toxic level of tar.

we left after one night. We would have left immediately, but it was too late to get another hotel room that night.

column11:
Great pizza! We were looking for a spot to eat on state street ( last Saturday night) and pizza was an easy choice. 
I'm so pleased that we tried this place out, it was excellent pizza. We had the plain cheese, and a medium fed 5 of us. ( one of us was only 2 years old though). The sauce was authentic tomato sauce, fortunately without a lot of overpowering oregano, it was smooth, mild, deliciousness. The dough/crust tasted fresh and oh so good! We ate it while it was still too hot, so the cheese was sliding off of it. That didn't matter, it was all wonderful. I'm glad we only got a medium (2 slices each),  because this pizza was so good - that I probably would have made myself sick, stuffing my face. 
There is a little bar counter with a decent beer selection and the Italian music really added a nice touch. 
I must also note that ( because it was past bedtime) our two year old was a total mess. She even spilled some of her bubbles on the floor as I tried to wrestle them from her. The guys working that night, were so incredibly nice. They mopped up the bubbles and said "don't worry about it- it's fine" Just laughed off how ridiculous my child was as she started to unravel. Made my night! We had truly delicious NY style pizza, enjoyed the whole italiano atmosphere, and left without being looked at as jerks because our kid was wiped out. 
Thanks Uncle Rocco's- see you the next time we're in SB, as you're now one of our new favorite spots.

column11: My family went here last night and after hearing good things we were rather disappointed.  Our waitress was nice but she was either very busy with other tables or asleep.  It took 20 plus minutes to order then 15 plus minutes every time to asked for something.  One of us requested a glass of Sangiovese wine but instead got sangria.  I requested fries with old bay seasoning but got plain fries.  I also got the lobster bisque which was pretty good but was served lukewarm at best.  My daughter and wife wanted to split a seafood pasta but were just served just the bowl and had to request separate bowls or plates.  After a long wait one small plate was brought.  Lastly, it was a birthday celebration which we mentioned to our waitress.  Nothing, not a word, no offer of anything or congratulations.  Too bad, this place has an incredible location.

column11:
Took my beautiful wife out to Oppi'z for date night and it was really a great experience! The outdoor seating was so comfortable and with Italian music in the background we felt like we were back in Florence. 
Our server, Sara, was so sweet. She guided us through the menu and catered to our every need. She was calm, professional and really made our first time there very enjoyable. 
As far as the food.... It was fantastic! 
Delicious "salad in a jar" ( check it out, it's a thing), we tried the Ceci jar and the flavors were so good. 
For mains we split both the  Tagliatelle pasta with bolognese sauce as well as the Black Parma Pizza with black dough.
The pasta was sublime! Obviously house made and cooked to perfection. The sauce had so many delicious layers, really good.
The pizza was also off the charts! Cheese that just made you happy inside right when you bite into it. 
 First time trying Oppi'z, we will be back! Thank you to Sara for making our evening a romantic one! Highly recommend!

column11: Having read all of these positive reviews, my husband and I were looking forward to some treats from Chocolate Maya. Our visit exceeded our expectations. If you love chocolate, this place is a must!  They have incredibly high-quality chocolate products, many of which are made right there on the premises. We were helped by a lady named Carmen who was very friendly and quite knowledgeable about the different chocolates. You could tell she delighted in our enjoyment of chocolate and was happy to give us some samples of different bars. We especially loved the drinking chocolate and their signature truffle Pave, a "simple" dark chocolate ganache--amazing!! We also appreciated the attention given to fair trade products and the emphasis on local ingredients for their house-made items. We will definitely be back!

column11:
We stayed here for 2 nights in May (2018) in a ground floor unit that had been recently refurbished. The motel was chosen because it was the least expensive motel (with free parking) in the downtown area in proximity to the Arlington theater where were going to a concert.  The bed was comfortable and the room was clean and compelling; the best feature being the semi-private balcony overlooking the pool area and the nicely maintained surrounding gardens.  The staff were very helpful.  We had one meal (dinner) at the adjoining Crocodile restaurant and it sucked.   

Note: the water pressure is poor to the extent of making it overly time consuming to rinse off.  That & the restaurant caused me to deduct a star.

I would go back again if I needed to stay in the State street downtown area & the prices remain lower than the others in he area.

column11:
I never leave a Yelp review but I'm going to leave one here. We ordered the Dungeness Crab and asked them to leave the guts in, which we expected to be sweet, we're COMPLETELY bitter. Thinking it was the hand sanitizer we had just put on our hands, I went to wash it. came back and it was still very bitter. We then tried to the meat and it was also bitter! If we would've known that bitterness means that the crab had spoiled. 2 hours later after we ate, I felt very nauseous, dizzy, bloated, and ended up vomiting. Basically, it wasn't until my friend told me that bitter meat was spoiled. 

However the uni was really tasty and fresh. 

We heard good things from this place, and if it wasn't for the crab, I would have such a good experience. But because of that I'm traumatized.

column11:
I always loved going to Renauds so I promised my husband a great breakfast there today..however it was a very disappointing experience.  I ordered poached eggs (soft) with bacon (crisp) and a decaf coffee with almond milk (I'm allergic to dairy). The cashier said I could "switch out" a croissant for the baguette that came with my order so I did. 
My husband ordered just an almond croissant. Both of us asked that our croissants be heated.
Here's what we got: hard poached eggs, soft bacon (opposite of what I ordered); cold croissant for me; we had to ask 3 times for utensils;  my husband's almond croissant never arrived even though we reminded 3 different people. 
Also, we were not told by the cashier when ordering that there would be an extra charge for "switching out" the croissant and for my almond milk...And we were charged for a latte even though I ordered a simple decaf.
So our bill came to over $25 for a very unsatisfactory breakfast (that I ate by myself since my husband's never arrived). 
Unacceptable, especially for the price. He says he won't ever go again. Sad.

column11:
I love the atmosphere. My hubby and i have been to luckys before and enjoyed our dinner/evening. Today was mothers day brunch. The restaurant was surprisingly empty. Most everyone at the restaurant smiled and was helpful. But our server fell short. He just didn't project the image of fine dining. My husband and I frequent many upscale restaurants in Santa Monica where we live and lucky's just didn't measure up. Our server couldn't describe a particular dish on the menu and he himself said he should know. Yes, you should. We had to track him down when we needed him. The two other people i was with asked for coffee about 30 minutes after i did. when they received their coffee, mine was almost empty and i wasn't offered a refresher. The crumbs on our table were never wiped off. Little things that an upscale customer comes to expect/notice. The busboys and everyone else was cool, thus the 3 star rating. However at such an upscale establishment, there should be no missing links. On to the food: 
Bloody mary's-the best
Burger-very good
Open face steak sandwich-tender but SALTY
Eggs Benedict-such a disappointment. Sadly. Two very small poached eggs on top of sliced Canadian bacon over soggy English muffins that had been drizzled with butter. The proportions were so off, too much bacon, too small of a muffin and  ridiculously tiny eggs. I had to ask for a third egg. I was too embarrassed to return my dish cuz the muffin was soggy. Side fruit just ok, cut into TOO tiny of pieces, reminding me of canned fruit.
No fancy, unique presentations. 
Coffee is great. Go there if you want. I'm indifferent. Maybe, maybe not?

column11:
Bottom line, this place is delicious. it would be worth going to even for folks who are all a hour meat-everything is flavorful and delicious. But-bonus for me- I am a meat eater and my partner is veg, so it's great to go somewhere she can eat everything. 
In particular, the Brussels sprouts were AMAZING, the hummus and baklava were maybe the best I've ever had, and the cashew cheese was fabulous. This isn't a place that tries to imitate meat and cheese, but does its own thing. We will definitely be back. Also great service, and the owner was very welcoming.

column11:
You take time to write a review if is really good or the opposite:(( 
I like this location, nothing really that can be criticized other then long lines every time but I like the crowd:)) the outside patio is great!!!!
But... I only give 3 stars because every time I go they misunderstand my order. Now I learned to read what they write on my cup... Misspelling my name is fun! But me repeating a few time "coconut milk please" is embarrassing! If I see they put my drink in dairy blender I know they got wrong and I ask again.... Some are funny and chat with you, make a nice comment but yesterday both girls(the one that took order and one made my drink) forced me write the review this morning:(( she took a long time to make this mocha  frap with coconut!!!! milk... Chat with her coworker that was carrying buckets of ice, making jokes between the two, got distracted with so many other moves around, meantime started like few other drinks... literally I saw my drink waiting at every step to get to the next... It was in blender for like over 2!minutes because she served a few other drinks.. She even took time to rinse the blender cup and top before she got a top for my drink to serve it... My drink got to me very watery because it was melting already  and not much flavor... I don't think I had all ingredients in it... But I had to run... Otherwise I would have told them to remake it... Did not risk it for another long wait. 

What can I say... I will go there again because the nice location and very convenient to enjoy a sunny morning...

Santa Barbara has a lot of restaurants. Go elsewhere.

column11:
I have been eating here for two decades, primarily because of its pleasant atmosphere and convenient location.  The quality of the food has gone steadily down hill, to the point at which it is simply terrible.  

This evening we had the Seafood Platter and Pork Satay w/ peanut sauce, both were touted as "House Specialties".  Both were terrible, and we felt ill all night after eating them.  The Seafood Platter somehow tasted like reheated seafood that was several days old.  The peanut sauce tasted canned, and also seemed several days old.

We will never eat here again.  This has happened to us too many times here over the last few years.

column11:
Two words: Gourmet Market

Lazy Acres is not your typical market, it is more of a high end market where you can find exotic and unique ingredients, products, and dishes. I see a lot of potential for Lazy Acres, but they need to improve their marketing. 

Yes, a lot of their products are pricey. Spend your money on products you like to indulge on. I bought the prosciutto di parma(16.99/lb). I sauteed it and put it in one of my pasta dishes. It had a very unique aroma to it.

I do not go to Lazy Acres to grocery shop, but I go here to try out their baked goods, deli, and salad bar. 

I would recommend checking out their deli and their salad bar. Their bars have given me ideas to come up with new recipes. They have interesting fusions that I have never thought about - many ethnic specialties. 

Also, this would be a perfect afternoon date. You can check out what products the store has to offer and laugh at some of their prices. Then, head on over to eat at the deli. If you cannot find a seat, go to the nearby beach park.

column11:
I am so glad we had our wedding here!!! I cannot say enough what a pleasure it was to work with Breanna, the venue manager and Eli, the food and beverage director. Our wedding here was a destination wedding, so we were very concerned about making sure all of our family and friends that travelled a long way to get to our wedding had a good time. Being a couple straight out of grad school, we were also very concerned with keeping the cost manageable. Everything worked out on all accounts! 

We first picked the venue for two reasons: the price was right and the venue is GORGEOUS. The pricing was very straightforward, which we really appreciated, and when looking at other options in the Santa Barbara area, the Riviera mansion was pretty comparable with other venues which are not all inclusive (ones where you have to find your own caterer, rent linens, etc etc). Planning a wedding without a coordinator and from across the country, it was also definitely worth it for us to go with a venue that minimized the amount of details we would have to think about.

The looks and layout of the place are what sold us though. With people coming from the east coast and middle of the country, we wanted something that would really showcase Santa Barbara's cool architecture and vibe. The mansion is exactly that.  The layout is also pretty perfect for a multigenerational wedding. We were able to enjoy the California weather for our ceremony and cocktail hour outside, then go inside for dinner, avoiding the cooler night air. Later, we could turn up the party in the bar/dance floor area, while the older folks talked and relaxed on the couches in the living room. It really has something for everyone.

What I didn't realize when we picked it was how absolutely awesome all the staff would be to work with. Breanna was super helpful, answering all my questions promptly and pleasantly, and accommodating my sometimes short notice visits to the area. When we did our walkthrough a couple of days before the wedding, Breanna and Eli paid attention to every detail and made sure we were taken care of, as they did the day of the wedding too. Eli was incredibly attentive and easy to work with! My dad is in the restaurant industry and was in charge of setting up desserts (we had family make some traditional desserts, as well as got some cupcakes from Enjoy Cupcakes- also a great idea!). Eli worked with him to get whatever he needed, risers, tablecloths, etc and was really sweet about it. 

The attention to bartending at the Riviera Mansion deserves a paragraph of its own. Breanna worked with me and the bartender (who's name I forget but has worked there for 20 years and is also incredibly awesome) to create a peach moscow mule as our signature drink (our colors were peach and green) and get it to taste just right. She even arranged it so we had fresh peaches! At the wedding, everyone raved about them, even guests who usually prefer something more manly sounding. The staff had all drinks ready to go for our cocktail hour, and also passed trays of drinks, so there was never a line at the bar (something guests also specifically mentioned that they appreciated). Hell, Eli even followed me with my drink for a couple of minutes around dinner since my hands were full of other things! Really spectacular and attentive service.

Five stars all around. It was absolutely a joy to have our wedding here.

column11:
Great way to see all the major spots in SB in just 90 minutes for just $20. I really enjoyed it.  I've been to Santa Barbara at least half a dozen times, but learned lots of new interesting facts and history, and had the chance to see some sights I hadn't seen before, like Montecito and the Mission.

Only real downside is that it only runs every hour, so that if you get off at one stop, you can't catch another trolley until an hour later. But overall, a great way to see the city.

column11:
Fresh local ingredients...sometimes even organic carrots and other items.  The chef - she is Thai and really is a natural.  The owners were at San Ysidro Ranch and El Encanto as head of F&B, thus their drink menu is excellent - short but well done with well priced glasses of bubbly, white, red, ....

The devil is in the detail and they got it right from the reusable washable colorful chopsticks in jars - easy reach if you want them....air plants for easy maintenance but a touch of the exotic....the made from scratch hot sauces, freshly roasted peanust done in house for their pad thai...so many details....

We are so lucky they have opened in SBA.  Find them in the SB newly opened covered market near Victoria and State.

column11:
This is my favorite soup and/or ramen place in town!  The ramen is bomb,  I love the shiro broth and the authentic soft-boiled egg add-on.  I've been here three times within a month since they've opened.  The noodles are nice, and the portion is satisfactory.  

Cons:  They don't do the Japanese greeting and goodbye when you come in and leave, like some other places you might be used to.  If you don't care for that, then this is your place.  
The egg is a bit cold in the middle.  Dunk it in your hot soup right away.  
The ramen bowls are on the tall side with a small bottom, doesn't seem very sturdy but it is.

column11:
So sad, as I was really looking forward to this meal.  First, it was difficult to determine where one was supposed to go to be seated.  As a guest in the Kimpton Canary, it should not be hard, but it was.  We were finally greeted by the hostess who ushered us to a very comfortable booth (imagine sitting in what feels like the material of a very nice bomber jacket - SWEET).  There was a light at the table, which was necessary, as this restaurant is dimly lit (oh, and it got even dimmer throughout our dinner).  I couldn't read the wine/cocktail menu due to the low light and small font size, and my eyes aren't that bad.
My husband helped in my wine selection, as I reviewed the menu.  I was super excited about the burrata and caramelized pears appetizer (proceeds go to charity) and the fried chicken special.  Housemade pickles were delivered to our table, as well as water and a water carafe (don't worry SB tap water tastes great!).  Our wine arrived just as some very loud women entered the restaurant.  They were seated at the other end of the restaurant, but their laughter was LOUD.  One table requested reseating immediately.  Then another.  One table actually left - not good.  
Then our burrata appetizer arrived.  It was not what I expected.  It had a lot of pesto, and not many pears.  The crostini were slightly charred toast triangles.  The burrata was fine, but there was a definite battle among the +10 ingredients.  We stopped eating it, and the gracious server removed it (yes, it was comped).
Then, the mains arrived.  This redeemed the experience to a 3 star from a single star.  The chicken and mashed potatoes and gravy and pickles were to die for!  Perfect chicken!  Probably the best fried chicken I've ever had.  I'm from the south, so that's a huge compliment. My husband's beef short rib was amazing as well, but the menu descriptor didn't quite match what he received.  But, it was really great.  
Positives - Amazing service, great wine list, very good food
Cons - Disruptive clientele, poor lighting, really dated and dirty carpets/rugs, and way too many ingredients in some dishes.
The chefs know how to cook - they just do too much.

column11:
I live up in the dorms at UCSB, and every time I come back from my hometown in LA my family and I ALWAYS stop here. Unfortunately, I'm leaving UCSB after my first year... I'm going to miss coming to this place!

Beachside is literally on the beach; it's at the base of a long pier, and the outdoor seating is only separated from the actual sandy beach by some bamboo blinds. You couldn't have better scenery than this while having a good lunch or dinner.

The seafood here is really fresh: I've tried halibut, salmon, scallops, mussels, clams, you name it. All of it is delish! Dinner comes with some (free hehe) freshly baked bread, and all entrees come with soup. My family and I always choose the clam chowder. At Beachside, the clam chowder is a lot more chow than you would normally imagine. Every bite is loaded with clams and potatoes! Yum! Prices are what you'd expect of fresh seafood... in fact, I'm surprised they don't charge more given theres no competition in the area.

column11: While lines can be intimidating, especially on weekends and holidays, this place runs like a well oiled machine so waits are totally tolerable and once you have a table, service is friendly and efficient. Breakfast served all day, which is great if you are traveling to/from the central coast wine tasting and get a late start! We got the Two by Two by Two, the Susan breakfast burrito, and plenty of treats for our two dogs. That's right... A TRULY dog friendly place! Eggs were light and fluffy, bacon perfectly crisp, and French toast moist and cinnamon-y. Any omelette can be turned into a burrito... Mmmm! Anyone who complains about their water policy (no tap, just $1 bottles of Voss at cost due to phase 2 drought conditions in area) seriously needs to rethink their priorities.

column11:
I was ecstatic when this place opened, SB has needed a cider spot for my fellow non-beer drinking  friends. Their 4-play tasting flights are a must try for your first time. The flavors are always rotating and the staff get really creative with suggesting great combinations and rim toppings. 

The indoor and outdoor seating is cozy and there's a ping pong table! There are also numerous board games and party games to play. This is a great place to bring out of town guests to get a taste of SB vibes or just enjoy happy hour. 

If you follow them on Instagram, you'll get sneak peeks into upcoming flavors, food vendors, and trivia nights!

column11: We were in the mood for pizza. Since this was our first trip to Santa Barbara, I relied on Yelp for suggestions. This restaurant got good reviews and was close to the art institute so we gave it a try. First, we loved the ambience. It has a European feel and a comfortable atmosphere. Our waiter was excellent. The food was delicious. We started out with the cauliflower, which was very tasty. We also ordered a pizza and a side of rapini. Both were outstanding. We like thin crust pizza and this one was delicious. I highly recommend this restaurant.

column11:
i have nothing but good to say about the lark and the wine bistro behind.... we arrived a little early for our dinner reservation so we sat at the bar at les marchands for a delightful, refreshing glass of wine. wonderful environment! we moved over to the lark where we sat a a booth where we could see all that was going on. we had such great service. the food kept coming, and it amazed me;  each dish served at the table got better and better (and it wasn't because of the moscow mules consumed). our party decided to share all the dishes we ordered. we started with the charcuterie plate, pork belly sliders, little gem wedge, the beet salad along with the fried olives. we moved onto the marys roasted chicken - so moist and simple yet flavorful. each dish came out at the perfect time, and each dish was more and more exceptional.  i just might have to go back for the desserts!!!  the milk chocolate pot de creme (an absolute, even if you are not a dessert person),  the cheesecake, black sesame dacquoise, and ice cream sandwich - we did share all of those with coffee. a great ending!
i can't get back soon enough. time to make another reservation!! thank you for such a wonderful evening!
ps...i had to go back the next morning to the lucky penny for a warm scone and latte! perfection!

column11:
My boyfriend and I woke up with an intense post new-year hangover and could not decide where to get brunch.  It being 1:30 when we woke up, we had the salty-sweet, breakfast or lunch debate...until his brilliant mind came up with the idea of dim sum.

Anyhow, we got to the restaurant, it was fairly empty, but nicely decorated.  But new year's day, I was not going to ambiance.  I just needed to settle my stomach.  A hot pot of jasmine tea came out right away, which was nice.

We ordered the usuals--har-gow, shu-mai, bao, and banh cuon (sorry i don't know the chinese name for this dish) and also some "scallion beef pie".  It was decent, but not phenomenal...but I'm biased as I usually have dim sum in Westminster or LA.  The bao was actually really great though.

All in all, it's good for dim sum in SB, which seems to be lacking in asian cuisine, except for the yummy array of Japanese we have.  It satisfies my cravings but is nothing to rave about.

column11: So this place get one star and not because of service. Yes I know! The food was just terrible. Maybe because I'm from the bay area and have tried various Chinese places, but I couldn't even eat the food. Everything was extremely salty. Fried rice tasted like it was soaked in soy sauce. The other fried rice dish, the curry one, was even worse. They charged extra $1 to make the curry fried rice vegetarian using tofu. They said the fried rice had veggies which is why they charge $1 more for the tofu. If you view the picture, it came with hardly any veggies to even count it as a veggie fried rice. It seriously is a joke. It was a waste of money for sodium overload that just gives you high blood pressure and puts terrible strain your on your body. Not worth it.

The last time I stayed here I was awakended at 4 am as I heard the neighbors electronic bed toys then the strange sounds of moaning. gross me out!  
The cheap toiletries are seriously appalling. Total waste of the plastic bottles they come in. 
They have good beer on tap at the Crocodile Bar. Ralph's grocery store is walking distance. As is the saltiest restaurant ever: The Chicken Ranch. An easy location for shows at The Bowl. 
The price is high for as horrid and uncomfortable as the beds are. Polyester blankets and beadspreads anyone???? Definately bring the Xanax if you need your rest. 
The good part: and I mean so good that I swim here EVERY chance I get: THE POOL! It is not chlorinated, and oh-so SUPER warm, and 9.5 feet deep...they do not seem to mind if you enjoy its depth! 
I cannot say this place hotel matches up to it's pool. How hilarious, I will be back to swim here again!

column11:
Nice atmosphere and the booths are quiet and pleasant.  But ...Our halibut was overcooked.  A fish restaurant should know how to cook fish and not overcook it.  It was also over-salted.  It wasn't bad, but neither was it very good.
Service can be spotty.  It's hardly the best seafood spot in Santa Barbara!  Hungry Cat deserves that award and Julienne cooks a fine fish too.  Please teach your cooks to cook fish!.  NOt to keep picking, but on other visits, lobster has been slightly overcooked as well.

column11:
How do I love thee, Goodland Kitchen...well, let me count the ways:

1) A friendly, cozy grab-and-go place for utterly delicious sandwiches and more--breakfast/lunch/brunch
2) A super talented staff, so convivial and considerate--just like the gracious owner
3) OMG bakery goods--go ahead--try and choose just one
4) That Monday special, a perfect porchetta sammie--totally kills it
5) Picnic tables out front for amazing alfresco repasts
6) Fresh-made lemonade to quench and soothe the spirit
7) Simple, fresh, delish cuisine--tucked away in the middle of an industrial area 

My single regret is that I did not get to try the Wednesday special, bahn mi sandwich. I'll just have to go back...soon.

column11: First time eating here for dinner and the dining room is beautiful, but it is very loud. It's difficult to have conversation. The pasta dish i had was amazing. It was a daily special orecchiette. My 9 year old loved it too. The service was great. The dessert pizza wasn't good. The crust tasted stale, and although the chocolate and marscapone topping was tasty, it couldn't compensate for the dry, tasteless crust. My daughter thought the gelato was too sweet. She like things more sweet than I do, so I didn't want to try it. The creme brulee was okay, but there was half a container left at the end and that's a sure sign that the taste wasn't fantastic.
