column11:
Oh what a discovery !!!!! I just moved from San Diego where I'm surrounded by large variety of Asian stores and now in Santa Barbara and it's hard to find one. But this store is special, just the name was already standing out and calling me to come check me out. We were actually suppose to go to Kmart when I saw the name of this place in huge letters and I'm like monkey, I gotta see what sup here. 

I was in for a surprised. It was no regular Asian store but a mixture I've never really seen before. It had Thai, Vietnamese, Indians (various groups) and British ;-) I can't believe I use to have to drive two hours to grab me a small bottle of Nam pla wan dipping sauce for fruits and now it's only like 10 mins away. I have been here 3 times and still loving it and will come back for more. It's cost is a bit more than home in SD but there is competition there and still it's cheaper than all around here for sure ;-) 

When I have my Asian cravings and don't want to get cheated, this is the place to be and the cashier and owners were all nice and friendly so it's cool.  I love this place that some time I just love to stroll inside every isle and see what they got ;-)

column11: Well this was a pleasant surprise...I expected a mediocre meal and both of us actually liked our food. I took the advice of a fellow yelper and ordered the fried artichokes and as a southerner, I actually thought they were good. The Coq au Vin was very good and the cobb salad was yummy but a bit too much dressing. The service and prices(!) were very good too but the wine list is terrible. I would go again, bring my own vino, and think "finally....a decent restaurant in this vicinity for spontaneous dining in my sweats"

column11:
There was a while where I thought Esau's Cafe was closed and gone. That was a sad time since Esau's is an essential part of my stay in Santa Barbara. Discovering that they were: 
1) Open (Yeah!), and 
2) In a larger location (Light! Airy! Creative Surf Decor!) made for a happy day.

Normally an exotic scrabble kind of girl, I opted for the ADD option of sides and crafted my own breakfast of potatoes, sausage, tortillas with salsa. Easy (and SO much more fun when someone else makes it for you)! 

The fresh fruit that topped off my ADD breakfast was the only thing that left me disappointed as the fruit on top was great but the rest of the fruit had clearly been sitting in the fridge for a while. 

Alas, besides the not-so-fresh fruit, it was another great weekend in SB, made even better by a good breakfast with friends before heading home.

column11:
Found another great place via Yelp! We decided to try a new place while on a day trip to Santa Barbara and this place was top of the list.

The place is nice but it is order at the counter and get a number style so not too fancy - dress as you please. 

Our group sampled several items including chile relleno, crunchy and soft taco combos, etc. All were very good or better. Free chips and salsa bar all tasted fresh and delicious.

I thought prices could have been a little better but place was packed and house margaritas were only $5.

Definitely going back.

column11: The threats of power outages made me come to this place. I am forcing myself to learn how to cook on an outdoor gas stove (I'm a city person, not a camper!) The attendent couldn't have been nicer or more friendly. He explained how to care for a brand new tank and he fills it up on the spot, in front of you, so you know they are being honest. The tank is over $50 bucks but refill is around $18. If you care for your tank, it should last 12 years or so. He then showed us his dry ice after we inquired about how they come packaged. Did you know they also sell real ice as well? This is the only place in town I trust to get ice and propane. I felt safe being around such knowledgeable and experienced people. P.S. Drive down the long corridor toward the back of the building. They have parking in the back and the propane and ice is back there too. Thank you!

column11:
Best ice cream we have had in awhile!
We each had the 3 scoops samplers so i got to enjoy bites of 9 different flavors and loved them all!
My favorites were the lemon blackberry and the seasonal flavor with peaches and raspberrys.
Also got their seasonal sauce, rhubarb, and it just made my day, I am obsessed with rhubarb and it  is hard to find places that offer it.
Prices are high, $20 for 9 mini scoops, 3 per cone, but the cones made to order, the smell and taste is out of this world!
The service is stellar, even though they always have a crowd, they are nice and let you take your time to take it all in.
I get what all the hype is about and can't wait to come back again!
A must stop while in Santa Barbara!

column11:
This place came highly recommended by my friends in SB. 

All I can say is you better come hungry. The steak burrito is HUGE. Now I'm latino, more specifically I'm a mexican and I can tell you that when I say HUGE it doesn't mean "wow that's a lot of food" I mean "GOD DAMN is that a COW in your tortilla???"

I can't imagine people actually finishing these things. I mean unless you have four stomachs or such a fast metabolism that you get rid of half before eating the other half. 

The food wasn't half bad, it was definately a college place. Much like buck fidies in Westwood however much bigger servings and more sitting space. The location is right in the middle of IV and has a cool atmosphere. 

If I were back in IV I'd eat there again after a looong day of hiking, biking, surfing, running, and any other activity to make me so hungry I could eat a cow. Then and only then I would actually be able to eat their "cow in a blanket" which they call burritos.

column11:
This place may be a good spot to watch a game since they have a lot of TVs all over the place.  The interior was cool with fancy lighting and "Day of the Dead style murals on the wall.  It's not really my style though, they seemed to be trying to hard to be "Mexican" but it just seemed like a sports bar in a college town.  If that's what you're into, you may enjoy this place.   

They have no idea how to make a Michelada though.  They made me one of the worst ones I've ever had using Bloody Mary mix rather than Clamato!  That seems odd for a place that's Mexican themed do't you think?

column11: This place is AMAZING.  The service is really wonderful.  It's a mom and pop shop and you can tell the owners really work hard and they do a great job, which is totally evident by how this place fills up.  The food rocks.  The pho here is almost as good as my mother's and probably the best I've had at any restaurant.  But for me, this place is all about the Vietnamese Pancakes.  If you haven't had them, try them.  In college, this used to save me so many times.  And they're very generous about the veggies if you ask for more.  Just a feel good place.  Parking is street parking or on the side of the building.  TRY TRY TRY TRY TRY.

column11:
WHAT THE HELL! Do people usually finish their whole burrito!? Just think of this place like Chipotle. You go down a line and you tell them what you want in your burrito. BUT it tastes so much more like Mexican food..like that greasy good feeling where as Chipotle would feel more of a healthy "mexican" food vibe. 

Try the "Quesa-rito" (?). It's a burrito inside a quesidilla! They melt cheese onto your toritilla and then use that as the "outside" of your burrito." Price is great considering how much food you're getting. Next time, I'm going to share it with a friend or have it for lunch AND dinner!:P

column11:
I'll start with the good stuff first (cause there is a lot of bad!!)

Good stuff:

The view and location is awesome. There is something about eating delicious baja fish tacos with your toes in the sand. The food is actually pretty darn good!

Bad stuff:

Service. Wait, what service? It's more like you're treated like you're interrupting them here. First off, my girlfriend and I asked to sit on the beach for lunch. After waiting 15 minutes to sit, our host takes us to the beach, which was actually just a patio next to the beach. I asked if we could get the empty table on the sand instead and she said "No. I have somebody who specifically asked for that". So I told her we'd just wait for the next one. So, she did what any good host would do and put us ALL the way at the bottom of the waiting list again. 

Maybe the host was having a bad day... Okay, so we sit down on the sand after waiting another 20 minutes for a table. Our server was no better. She always had a snobby remark to our questions and didn't let us finish what we were trying to ask. Rude all around. 

All in all, probably wouldn't come here again which is a shame because I really wanted to like this place.

column11:
When researching where to eat for my trip to SB, Scarlett Begonia made it to the top of my brunch list. The food look pretty, the outdoor area look pretty, and the reviews sounded promising. 

Upon arriving my friends and I could not find the entrance to Scarlett Begonia. So many alleys and shops, confusing. We were given the option to sit either inside or outside, both looked nice but in the end we sat outdoors since it was a nice day. 

There were many things on the menu that caught my attention; I ended up ordering the Endless Summer Scramble with a side of Multigrain Toast. My friends and bf ended up ordering the other things I had in mind so it worked out! 

The Scramble was very flavorful. The potatoes were roasted nicely, the eggs were fluffy, the veggies added freshness. Tbh, the toast wasn't worth it. It was $3 for a tiny slice with butter and very liquid-y fruit preserve/compote. It was good but too expensive. 

My bf ordered the Pork Chilaquiles (special) and it was good (also expensive though). My bestie ordered the Biscuit Sampler with a Buttermilk Biscuit and a Maple Bacon Biscuit. Both were flaky and buttery. The bacon one sprinkled with sea salt. She seemed to like them. Her bf ordered the Meyer Lemon Pancakes which were my second choice. He kindly let me try them and they had a great lemon flavor! Many lemon pancakes that i've tried are lacking in lemon flavor but not Scarlett Begonia's. 

Overall, service was pretty good! The waiters were friendly and give you a sample of toffee with your check. It's definitely a pricer restaurant but if you're looking for a cute brunch spot to catch up with friends at, it's a great option! They're also dog friendly!

column11:
My group of 6 came here over the Fourth of July weekend for dinner. We lucked out and were able to snag one of the picnic tables outside. We were all pretty hungry, and ended up splitting four pizzas and the burrata & prosciutto appetizer. It was just the right amount of food, though we probably could have eaten more if we had ordered it. 

The highlight for me was definitely the burrata and prosciutto appetizer; it was super fresh & really tasty. The pizzas were also good (loved the crunchy crust), just nothing incredibly unique. There was something on the menu for everybody.

Great ambiance and very fast service (under 15 minutes). Would recommend this place for any group that wants a quick yet nice meal.

column11: I nicely want to say I was very disappointed on the margarita pitchers. Since Corazon opened in the public market and in the project I have been coming and enjoying their food and drinks. Yesterday I spent 50 dollars for a margarita pitcher that was full of ice filled up to the top that was served with two cups that were full of ice before pouring drink. The pitcher itself only contained about two glasses of the drink, but not even because the glasses were already pre-full of ice so barely 2 full glasses. The pitcher was also served with a wooden spoon to help prevent the ice from falling out when pouring. I understand restaurants are trying to get back on their feet, but it is upsetting for locals and regulars who want to enjoy this fun restaurant setting but are getting gipped for what you are paying for. If you are going to charge customers that amount please be truthful to what you say you are serving. Overall Corazon serves delicious high quality food, but I will not be buying any drinks there soon if they continue not see how this is wrong and unprofessional in the hospitality industry.

column11:
I came back after my first experience and wow, have I changed my mind. In fact, I don't know if there's a better pizza around.

We ordered the baby gems with ranch, pickled onion and goat cheddar. There are no words. One of the best, most decadent salads I've ever had. The pickled onions, the cheese all complimented the other. Wow. This salad is incredible.

We then ordered the English Pea pizza with mint pesto. The spring onions, the cheeses... everything on this pizza was perfect and I would have never thought of mint on pizza but it is so subtle and the pesto is insane.  The pizza had a lovely char and was the perfect, chewy texture. Perfection.

The patio is charming and they allow dogs. What more can you ask for?

I'm so glad I came back. Now it is one of my favorite restaurants.

column11: I went to a show here recently and I have never felt so insulted, offended and discriminated against in my life. The bouncer that was short and fat is the rudest man ever. He would raise his voice at people that were causing no harm and get in their faces unnecessarily. They split a fence down the middle of the dance floor to separate 21+ from the under agers. I thought this was silly and pointless. I paid a good amount of money to come to this place to dance and hang out with my friends...but instead I was separated from them and insulted? I also asked if I could go outside to have a breath of fresh air because it was getting rather crowded and stuffy inside and they told me this wasnt "allowed" and that if I wanted air I needed to leave permanently. At the end of the night when all the bands finished, I stayed around a few minutes to talk with the musicians and my friends that I didnt get to see the whole show and the same bouncer approached me and ordered me to leave. Then he proceeded to raise his voice at me before I could say goodbye to my friends and stood in my face until I left. I stormed out very angry! This is not a good place to go if you want your night ruined. I don't recommend going back, ever. And no coat check? Horrible service and employees. Great music though. Edward Sharpe and the Magnetic Zeros should have picked a better venue!

column11: I'm going to start off with saying with we've been here before multiple times, and i work in the service industry so i am one of the THE MOST understanding people that can ever walk into a restaurant. We came to celebrate our anniversary, because we've had such great past experiences here. I'm sad to say that I'm very upset on the experience this time. We sat at the bar, you could clearly see that they were short handed (no bartender present) we sat for about 5-7 minutes when we were "greeted" by a young Asian girl who said 'we'll be with you.' Short and not so sweet. Who threw dirty menus at us, and continued to cash out and make drinks and chat up the one woman at the bar next to us. She left and was sat there for another 10 minutes when we saw a gentleman server come in clearly late grab keys from the original Asian server and leave, to come back a few minutes later fix himself and proceed to wait on tables. Yet to hear back from the young Asian girl. Now i know this is unlike the typical service, because we have sat a few times at the bar with Derek who's absolutely amazing! To just get disregarded this time around. I don't know what the issue was, however short handed or not, we shouldn't of sat there for 15 minutes plus with dirty menus, to be basically dismissed. We walked out after about 20 minutes and went and spent $200 somewhere else. 20 minutes was more than generous for us to sit there and wait for the young girl or whom ever to get to us and at least give us water to drink right? Needless to say, i won't be coming back here. After such great experiences tonight killed it, and it's unacceptable. Sorry Vincentas.

In a town where even Silvergreens is resorting to smaller salads and pushing burgers and fries, it's nice to know there is a forward thinking place with great organic food, where you actually feel good after your meal. Green Table is that place.

column11:
This place was empty at about 6pm when we rolled in.  And it's actually nicer that way.  Around 7pm is when it starts getting busy and loud...at least on a Saturday.

The prices worked well for us on a budget.  Special rolls were between 6-10 dollars-ish.  And they had regular rolls for less.  The serving sizes were smaller than I was used to, but it's probably more of the average (the sushi places in my town serve large rolls).  If anything, the portions were just right.  With an appetizer, three special rolls, and a tempura ice cream, the bill came out to about $35 for two people.

Oh yea, and they have quite an extensive appetizer list.  Pretty good portions for the price.  Would totally come back again.  Cute little venue.  Good service.  Great food.

column11: I love this place!  The food is excellent, and while it does cater to American "tastes" there are traditional influences throughout the menu.  My favorite is the Los Agaves Enchiladas. column11: I have been coming here for over 20 years. I enjoy the good service, and inside the environment is open and airy. No recent remodel, it's dated, but clean, and I really appreciate the off street parking. The food is good ( food wise this is one of our better Thai restaurants ) and incredibly consistent. A few years ago, the owner's son decided to start expanding the homemade ice cream... he calls it "Creaminal Minds". What a success!  Be sure to try the fusion flavors, they're excellent. Thai basil with mint and chocolate, Thai coffee mixture, a marvelous list... even some vegan choices. You can get pints of ice cream to go, so be sure to share!

column11:
For a new restaurant, this place totally hits the mark.  For a well established restaurant, this place still hits the mark.  The decor is vintage funk cool hip, unlike anything in Santa Barbara.  
The place is full of locals, and I mean full. It is getting rave reviews in all the local newspapers and deservedly so.  
The owners have created  tasteful, superb, friendly restaurant that has me in awe of a first time restarauntier.  
I am impressed, and have been there 2 times with excellent experiences, and will be continuing to go and make this my new go-to place and recommendation.

Still excellent. And the service is impeccable. They explain EVERY dish they bring to the table with a smile.

column11:
Great happy hour food/drink specials. 

I usually order chimichangas. Weird incident in which first 2 times i came here i had no cheese in them (which was fine, i didnt notice and they were delicious). Then came the third time and suddenly it was oooooozing w cheese (which is an oddly common trend in SB that i find unappetizing). The waiter gave me a hard time about this since the menu apparently states it has cheese, ignoring my comments that id ordered it several times before and it never been like that.....but usually Ive had good service. 

Another great dish is the garlic shrimp. The sauce is sooo good i mop it up with my garlic bread-which is also great.

They have 2 outdoor seating sections which are nice. Indoors theres a more restaurant-like section, and a larger section which is more sports bar like so it's a great place to catch a game too.

column11: My husband and I wanted to try this Restaurant, since we saw the little menu at our hotel.  Went to the movies at Arlington theater....loved it!!!  The restaurant is very conveniently located from the theater.  We arrived at the restaurant and there was no one greeting at the door.  We stood there for a couple of minutes to get sit ted. After being sitted, we were not given plates or utensil for the appetizers and my husband got up and took them from another table.  The waitress was  friendly and the food was amazing.  Although, no one really checked on us.  After dinner, we had discussed getting dessert. We asked for the menu and then... NO ONE CAME TO GET OUR ORDER!!! After about 5minutes we gave up. So, needless to say, we just paid and went to Starbucks across the street.  The food was amazing!!!! The staff needs to be more attentive.  Perhaps, they will read this and make some adjustments. Foods great  service  needs a lot of help.

column11:
We were in Santa Barbara for the day and needed. A bit of sustenance to get us to the beach. We drove Down a quaint street with Mediterranean style buildings and parked around the corner on a residential street. The amount of noise from the construction going on directly in front of the restaurant gave us pause. However as soon as we sat down at a picnic table to sip on our mimosas the construction crew took a break. Yay!
     The food was exceptional, hot, fresh, and delivered with a smile. We especially Liked the Caesar salad and the french fries. We felt quite safe as the tables were spread apart nicely.

column11:
I have been eating at the Taj Cafe on downtown State for several years. Over time food at the Taj has changed in quality much like at any restaurant. When I first started eating at the lunch buffet here in 2004 I was impressed with the solid variety and sauce and meat quality but saw some downturn after a couple years. More recently, however, since early 2008 I have been most impressed with the quality of almost every item in the buffet.

The highlight has been the vegetable korma which uses large chunks of vegetables and potato. The sauce of the korma is really well spiced and balanced with level of cream. In combination with some of their excellent garlic naan and basmati rice it is crave-worthy and has been the focus of many lazy Saturday brunches. Their curries have similarly improved using large tender chunks of white chicken meat which I look forward to each time.

The buffet has an excellent variety with a thorough salad bar and many excellent desert options. The rice pudding is subtly spiced and goes perfectly with their irresistable carat desert (Gajar ka Halwa). Other options include sliced melon and those brown colored dumplings of dried milk and flour soaked in sugar syrup (Gulaab Jamun).

Forget ordering items from the menu as the buffet has plenty variety at a reasonable price. Bring a big appetite and friends you want to impress.

column11: I'm in love! Such a great experience at Bouchon. I came here to celebrate my birthday with my husband. I was lucky enough to get a reservation just the day before and they decorated the table with rose petals and a personalized card for my birthday. We recently went to Paris over the summer and so it was nostalgic for us to be able to enjoy French cuisine done so well outside of France. I started with the savory foie gras that just melted in my mouth. Husband had trio of scallops- best scallops I've ever had! I ordered the Duck entree which the waiter said has been on their menu for 18 years. I can see why because this dish is definitely in the top 10 of dishes I've ever had. I wouldn't call myself a foodie or snotty when it comes to food. I just enjoy good food and good company. Husband got the rib eye, which was also amazing but he kept eyeing my duck so of course I shared. Ended the meal with the blueberry lemon upside down cake. Yum yum yum! I can't wait to make an excuse to come back to SB to have this meal again. Thank you Bouchon for a memorable dinner!

column11:
January 17, 2021
Life is all about second chances. And I'm grateful to be given this second chance to stay at the Upham Hotel. Our entire stay has been incredibly marvelous. I need to mention first & foremost the lovely person behind it all - Denise Spain, General Manager. Ms. Denise went above & beyond to rectify the unfortunate experience we previously had. She was there to greet us when we arrived and she even personally went with us to show us our room and we had a short but fun, light & positive conversation. Our experience this time started very delightful and pleasant and I didn't want it to end. The hotel grounds is such a unique space with its expansive garden areas with wooden beach chairs where you can quietly read a book or enjoy a glass of their wonderful complementary wine. There is even a smaller garden area beside the main garden where I envision to be a good space to meditate with the sound of water trickling from the small fountain. Or just enjoy the peace that the space brings. The gazebo is also a unique touch which gives a classy and elegant feel to the overall vibe of the outdoor area.  The room we stayed in was spacious and extremely comfortable. It was also well-lit.  The highlight of it all for me was our own private patio. We frequent hotels when traveling and very rare do I experience a hotel such as this where you can enjoy your coffee, your meals, a good read or just to lounge in your very own patio in the comfort of your hotel room.  The bathroom was newly renovated with a good space and great shower. There was that exquisite basket filled with delicious baked goods waiting when you arrived, along with the complementary bottle of wine (which I thought was a genuinely thoughtful touch). The bed was comfy with clean and fresh-smelling sheets. All the staff were wearing masks and were adhering to social distancing. This time around, I couldn't really mention any areas for improvement and I can only hope that this hotel continues to thrive in the leadership and guidance of their General Manager. Ms. Denise, please continue to move forward in leaps and bounds. Thank you very much for a memorable birthday weekend you allowed me to have.

column11:
Best. Bar. Ever.

I stumbled upon this place last week and boy, oh boy is it spectacular. The rum selection is amazing. I'm more of a whiskey drinker, and they have a decent selection on whiskey, but man, oh man can I not wait to try more of the rum they have to offer!

I tried one of their flights and the bartender, Susie, was v helpful in my rum journey! She suggested trying one of the flights and then picking my favorite and enjoying it neat. I'm now a huge Real McCoy rum fan. I will sing their praises  from now on!

I feel incredibly lucky to have come across this bar. Can't wait to try it again and drink all the rum!

column11:
As I stand in my kitchen (I brought it home) eating the amazing grilled cheese sandwich for the second day in a row, I think....why did I wait so long to try this place! Yes, I ate the same one yesterday! :-)

It is so delicious!  This isn't your typical grilled cheese.  And it comes with a little salad that compliments the sandwich so well!

Take my advice and go get one.  You will definitely thank me!

And as an added bonus, the people working there are so wonderful!  In my opinion The Blue Owl on Canon Perdido, just off State street is my latest "best of the best" in Santa Barbara!

Ask for Nadia, she will be thrilled to have you as a new customer after such a tough year! Tell her Beckie sent you!

Now what should I try next on the menu! :-)

column11: My mom and I went for our first wine tasting and were beyond satisfied with our experience with captain jacks tours. We had Amir as our personal chauffeur AND photographer and he was more than we could have wished for. So pleasant, funny, and interesting to talk to as well. Was a little nervous since we were the only two doing a tour that day (woohoo for midweek if you're looking for an absence of crowds!!) but he made us feel like queens and was happy to accommodate all of our wishes. He had a lot to offer in knowledge about the wineries and the general area as well. Will definitely be requesting him if we decided to do another, which very well may be in the future.

column11:
Potentially the best "value" restaurant in Santa Barbara. Great food for very reasonable prices.

If you are going for lunch, you should definitely try one of their burgers. I love the Jane burger, as the gooey cheese and perfectly caramelized onions make it for me. If you want something a little more unique the El Macho Burger is also delicious. All burgers are served on what must be a homemade bun that is incredibly moist. If you want an appetizer get the Firestone Red Rings. They are crispy red onion rings drizzled with a balsamic reduction, definitely a little different but very good.

If you are going for dinner, the chicken piccata is probably the best I have had, it is really just about perfect if you catch them on a good night. The grilled duck breast is also very good.

Every meal starts with free bread and butter, which is decent but nothing special. If you want dessert, the coconut chiffon cake is delightful. The service is always great and it's usually not too hard to get a seat.

column11: I stumbled upon this shelfish shack last year when I was in town for July 4th weekend and immediately I was hooked. This place is small and located at the end of the pier, parking can be a problem sometimes, but I guess you can valet it up front or wait it out. When you walk in you cant help but notice the variety of sizes of fresh crabs and lobsters in the large aquarium tanks to your left with a guy behind the glass counter chopping and steaming them. I always order the spider crab special which starts off with a cup of clam chowder; absolutely the best Ive had thus far. They also serve a few shrimp dishes along with different lobster dishes as well, apparently lobster is available about 6 of my 10 visits. Overall you can try alot of different fresh shellfish without paying as much as you will other places offereing the same items in their menu. Now that I write about it ... I think Im going to go today ..

column11: My girlfriends and I visited here on May 11, 2012, and we had so much fun.  Zack took great care of us, even taking the time to convince my very selective friend that she actually does like (some) oaked Chardonnay.  My other friend and I each tried a different beer tasting, and we really enjoyed nearly all the selections.  The pours, especially for the beer, were more than generous.  Zack was really great about explaining the characteristics of the different wines and beers, and he really went above and beyond recommending local restaurants for us and helping us make reservations.  Another plus, the owner has a totally adorable puppy - wine tasting and puppies, it doesn't get much better!  I only wish we had been there on a Sunday, my boyfriend and I had discovered their sparkling wine and cupcake pairing a couple of months before - wow.  If you're in Santa Barbara on a Sunday, don't miss it!

column11:
I didn't think that I could possibly eat the best sushi I have ever had in California, in Santa Barbara.

I am not particularly a fan of sea urchin, but the uni was to die for. I was informed Santa Barbara is one of the biggest supplying coasts where uni is harvested. So everything was fresh from the docks and you could certainly tell the quality was unmatched to most uni I have sampled. 

They have some pretty intense shots of quail egg, salmon roe, and uni...buttery, milky, creamy goodness. The fish was incredibly fresh and the plates seemed to come out at a decent pace. 

The atmosphere was wonderfully buzzing but not in an annoying way. Lots of conversation, tight seating, but with good company and a rumbling stomach, it's the perfect spot for a small group of friends to enjoy a meal.

column11: So We wandered into this shady small looking Sushi place. And I ordered ramen. KEEP IN MIND U PAY UPFRONT, shady m8. For some reason they only had spicy ramen. Hmmmmmmmmm. They didn't have normal ramen broth , only spicy for some reason. I wonder whyyyyy.... is it because they only have spicy packaged ramen in stock and they just add a fu*kin egg and some frozen beef to the instant ramen and called that shit beef ramen? Ramen looks like instant ramen when I got it. I'm very disappointed. Prices aren't reasonable. I literally paid 9 bucks for a pack of instant ramen. I'm so sad. The chef in the back ground touched somewhere else with his glove before putting it back on the sushi that he was making. Unsanitary too? What if he scratched his ass before putting his hands back on your food? Disgusting I wanted to dip but my aunt was hungry. So we Ordered the bulgogi too, the beef was so rough and the rice was so hard . Bruh was I eating like some kind of flavored sh*t, how long was that beef in the morgue. Going back there might put me in a morgue too and they r gonna use my corpse for "chicken ramen" bruh I swear I'm so mad.

column11:
What an interesting experience! Drove up here on a Sunday morning to try the tri-tip sandwich and it was well worth the drive! The meat was tender and there's sauce on the side if you like yours a little saucier. I also got the onion rings which were pretty crunchy. 
There are plenty of seatings outside and I kinda enjoyed sitting out in the sun and admiring the scenery with my sandwich. The drive up was a bit scary because it's just one narrow road up the mountain and there's no parking lots or anything, just find a spot along the road and park! Overall, I'd definitely come back again next time I'm in the area!

column11:
It should be mandatory that when an employee calls an order that they mention the name of the person who ordered as well (like Starbucks or Blenders). I have been to two locations and twice I have had someone take my bowl who had literally just ordered because only the name of the bowl was called. I waited 20 minutes, watching people continue to walk in and out with their orders and when I mentioned that I'd seen someone take my bowl, they tried to pass it off as if they just hadn't gotten around to mine yet.

I received a refund but with no apology and with blank stares, even though I'd explained my situation and asked very nicely.

column11:
Where else can you hit up a winery, or even do a wine tasting on a pier??? Well, I don't know of any in the midwest so this was certainly quite the treat for me!!!  I'm from the midwest and I've done a number of wine tastings...this one was super-cool because you can hang out right on the water on the pier.  I was undecided between ordering a glass or doing a tasting but I opted for a tasting (free taste of chardonnay with your yelp check in!)  They have some very nice, light summery white wines there to try or order a glass of.  Awesome atmosphere at this place! 
The service was super friendly as well!

column11:
We had an extremely bad experience with this restaurant last weekend.
Monday, Memorial day we called and they said it is open at 11:00. we arrived 11:05 and the door was locked, employee told us come back later so waited 15 minutes outside but they did not open the doors so we left and came back at 11:40 still closed so asked the employee what time do you open, he became frantic and with a nasty tone told us can't you hear me we are closed, I told him politely we are leaving and will not return again, from behind the locked door he replied good get the hell out of here. We left and that will be the last time we or any of our friends will be going to that restaurant, the employees are rude and deficient in customer service, all he had to say was, I apologize, we are running behind why don't you have a sit inside and we'll be right with you.  
I hope the owner will read this review and train these employees because with this kind of attitude this place will not survive.
We left the restaurant and went across the street to Bucatini restaurant and received an excellent service and a great pizza, I would highly recommend their pizzas.

column11:
I'll admit it, I like Pick Up Stix. The house special chicken is just really really good. I don't order much else when I go there. I have tried their orange tofu and kung pao tofu and both were good, but I keep coming back to the house special. They  have good lunch combos, and I also like that they have the option of brown rice. 
 I would prefer this place over any of the local chinese buffet restaurants. It sucks that it's a chain, but when I'm hungry it all comes down to what tastes good, and house special tastes good.

column11:
First timer to this highly recommended steakhouse. My companion and I had steaks...bone in rib eye and 10 oz filet. We had a soup and a salad to start off with and calamari. My med-well order was close to raw, but that happens and I'd have no complaints .....if the taste was there.....which it wasn't. 

Both steak surprisingly were bland. We started adding our own salt and pepper to make it palatable, but to no avail. I've been eating in top restaurants including steak houses for business for the past 12 yrs nationwide, so I know what quality is and this place just came up short. The place was packed and my waitress who I thought was new, but turned out to be the manager (LOL) advised she had no complaints "that night". I thought that was cleverly put....as maybe yesterday or last week there was similar feedback. 

Either way to show that I'm not just pissed and venting, the tomato soup was incredible. The calamari was avg at best. The baked potato was good and the fried onions they put the steak on was good, but tricky cuz the steak kept slippin on it. I have it home runs and streak outs in Santa Barbara and come to learn food consistency aint this cities thing.  

Reservations needed. Desserts not attempted. Bathroom ok for guys, unacceptable for girls or a classy joint that gets $50 a head. 

If someone can recommend a "top" steakhouse in SBA, please do :)

column11: Such yummy food!! We stopped by on a busy Saturday night after being rejected from several other restaurants in the area for not making a reservation (my bad!) but Santo Mezcal was great and found us a table in no time. We got the queso for an appetizer -- a MUST get! I was so full I didn't have a chance to take but a bite of my enchiladas. My husband opted for the salmon tacos and he said they were yummy. The service was amazing...atmosphere great...and the staff were as sweet and accommodating as could be! We will certainly be back. If for nothing else, thank the queso!!!

column11:
This store has such incredible customer service. I recently transferred my prescription there after CVS didn't bother to tell me until the day I needed it that they no longer carried it - and then told me "good luck finding it anywhere else." I called Walgreens and they had it ready for me that day, and told me they have no problem getting it - its a common prescription!  Each time I've gone in there the staff is helpful, friendly and warm. I went tonight, and the man at the pharmacy even apologized for the line while I was still waiting - I didn't mind waiting anyhow.  Plus, the prices on everyday items are way less expensive then CVS.  
After a long and really bad day today, I can honestly say the friendly staff at Walgreens turned my day around and made me a lot happier then I was.  This is a great store, and I will use them for all my rx needs as well as general shopping from now on.  
Thank you for treating me like I matter.  Its appreciated.

column11: We decided to try this place out since we were in the SB area for the weekend. We were greeted at the door by the bar tender (who seemed to pay more attention to the regulars), and he immediately warned us that their bathrooms were out of order. This would explained the foul smell we noticed as we walked in. My wife ordered a lemon drop martini, which tasted like crap. It was way too acidic (probably artificial lemon juice) so I played it safe and ordered a beer on tap. The place has potential, there are comfy chairs and many TVs for sporting events. Plus, they have a juke box with great music. Another reason for the low rating is because  they decided to close an hour and a half early even though there were several people still drinking.

column11:
Not impressed with the cocktails...there are wayyyy more creative ways to make cocktails. But I come from a more cultured city than SB. Having pineapple and rum in almost every "tiki" drink made me feel like I was in college. Why not try pears, persimmons, mangos, passion fruits, dragon fruits, kumquats, etc that would help reinvigorate each drink. I also messaged you all as well and asked if you had food/snacks. You replied with a yes. And we get there and you only had three choices of sad soggy empanadas. If your cocktails are going to be that sweet, have a snack that contrasts this. Even fresh French fries with spices (sumac etc) or pork rinds to get people to drink more. Anything with a some salt content obviously would get more money in your pockets. We were here for an hour and for a place that does cocktails in a small town that does wine and beer you guys should Be crushing it. For those that are going to try this place during the pandemic...Oaxacan dead was decent. Purple mai tai not worth it. 

Your IG made me wanna stop by but after seeing customers only stay for one drink, made me question how "exotic/crafty" your cocktails can be. 

You deserve 1 star but I gave you two cause you're open during a pandemic.

column11:
Professional Staff, Small Portions, and Unusual Menu

First, the staff, from the greeter, to the waiter, to the bus staff were professional and first rate.  That really can make or break a dining experience.

Second, the portions are quite small, so if you order a salad and a main course, you may walk away hungry.  

I had the roasted quail, which is a really tiny bird, in and of itself (a grown man could easily eat two), and the restaurant served up a drum stick and thigh, about 3 tablespoons of meat total.  Granted, it was served with delicious barley and persimmon, but is really more like a small appetizer.  

I also had the roasted vegis, which really should have named, burned vegetables.  Roasted to me means oven roasted so they are slightly tender.  These came out thoroughly blackened and tasted burnt.  No thanks.  

The brownie desert is excellent.

Finally, if you're in the mood for a standard lettuce salad or something really simple, don't come here.  You won't find typical beef  or chicken cuts.  Indeed, the only beef cuts this night was a beef cheek, e.g., a couple tablespoons of meat from the outside of the cow's mouth.  

The food is tasty but the menu is a little weird and it has very small dishes.  I think it is trying to be too upscale and loses sight of what a restaurant should offer in the way of a menu.

column11:
The Sandbar (SandB) is an old Santa Barbara (SB) throwback. Well, it's the only mega-fun, co-ed throwback on the State Street strip that is an enduring fixture. There are Madison's, O'Malley's (presently closed for violations), Sharkeez, & Olde King's Road, but let's just presume you're not looking for the "fogies escaping their wives" crowd. O_O

Yeah, so if you don't want to do the all-boy, sports bar crowd, you've got Sandbar and Sandbar as your options. If you want a lively & youthful crowd w/ music in the bg, you're back @ Sandbar. Period.
 
I resisted all of the Sandbar's lures for, like, ever. I have been coming to SB to hang since 2005, but I never stepped foot into SandB until fall of 2010. Why? I'm a natural resister of all places "must go," & the crowd outside always seemed to say "it's the place to be". (Yes, I *do* go to "place[s] to be", but I just cannot be seen at "everybody goes there" spots unless I'm really in the mood to be one of "everybody," which is rare--try almost NEver.)

My desire to knock back a few [Str]ong Islands after a long drive from SanFran one night dropped me off into the SandB's lap one Sunday eve in November. Flyers were strewn about, advertising a Reggae/Dancehall Tuesday night. Umm... Hel-looo! I'm soooo there!

Of course, I've never actually gotten the dander enough to drive up the coast on a Tuesday to peep the Reggae night, but I have returned for weekends @ SandB, & returned have I! I came one night, & "all's" I remember was partying so darned hard that I had to return the next day to pick up my change from the $100 I had given the bartender as a "tab" opener. 

What rocked? The bartenders were super honest about it, & they even had my name written on an envelope w/ my $60 change inside. Needless to say, I was overly impressed w/ the character exhibited by the SandB's staff. I was impressed so much so that I have returned for the UCF's Michael Bisping vs. Jorge Rivera fight today to soak up the atmos after a solitary day en las montaas. And SandB's everything I remember: fun, peopled, stiff-drink-serving. ;)

 Hey, I even got my new favorite saying here from the UFC fight, as delivered by Rivera: "I want my name to be synonymous with kicking ass." Is he a native New Yorker, too? :P Meet me @ SandB? Pic for pic. Lolz.

column11: I love shabu shabu food... so, when I was visiting SB, I searched Yelp for restaurants w/in walking distance from hotel and saw this restaurant, I decided to try it despite the ratings. column11:

column11: Great ambiance and a fun location, mixed with authentic Spanish tapas, make for a lovely dinner locale. We ordered a margarita and mojito, both were traditional and good. Then we went on to split the figs, fried cauliflower, grilled corn, camarones, and ahi tartar. Everything was tasty and warm, exciting flavors all around. Except the tartar, that is, which we sent back because it was dry and bland. The plate sizes are truly tapas, so if you're starving, this is probably not where you want to go. However, if you like a bit of everything and hot, fresh food, why not give it a try?

column11:
A gorgeous location for a wine tasting room! Surrounded by water, and other yummy restaurants, it's not hard to see why this place was bustling. Got here just before sunset and enjoyed a tasting. One of the owner/winemakers (John?) served us, and was very nice. If you are simply here to enjoy the view and chat with friends, this is the place to go!

We tried the $15 basic tasting and the $25 upgraded reds tasting. After a weekend of wine tasting at other spots, this location's wine wasn't high on our list. At times we considered not finishing our tasting. 

I noted that another reviewer said the check in offer isn't honored, but when I asked about it, they were open to honoring it for us. Because we weren't fans of the wine we declined, but I wanted to let you all know.

Parking was tough, but we ended up using the valet service nearby and from there things were easier. 

Likely won't return, with all of the other options available to try.

column11:
I already want to return as I just gobbled up one of their black and white cupcakes. We saw this place on our way into driving into downtown Santa Barbara after our lunch. Once we were done with our shopping, we came back to check it out. Turns out we made it in for Happy Hour. Buy three cupcakes, get a Fourth for free. 
As soon as we walked in, we were warmly and promptly greeted. I really loved the decor of the place and how inviting and clean it was. But their customer service is also stellar. Wish I would have caught the name of the woman helping us because she is pretty spectacular. 
We decided to ask what her favorite was and she told us about the black and white. We took her up on it and got two of those, a summer berry (seasonal), and a double chocolate. The black and white is a vanilla and chocolate cupcake marbled with chocolate and vanilla frosting. It is delicious! One didn't even make it back home to Los Angeles. We devoured it in the car. I have a new favorite cupcake place and it is two hours away. 
My husband said the double chocolate was delicious as well. Their cupcakes are the perfect ratio of frosting to cake. Not too sweet. 
I'm so impressed. It is my birthday weekend and this was such a nice place to find for a delicious treat.

column11: Stayed two nights for my boyfriends birthday and we wish we could have stayed longer. It is a cute Inn very close to the beach. The staff were friendly and recommended restaurants when we asked and we were not disappointed by their suggestions. The breakfast consists of cereal, yogurt, bagels and pastries. Afternoon offerings are cheese, crackers and wine. And throughout the day (7:30am-10pm) coffee, tea and water is available. There is also a nice outdoor patio with a fire pit. We definitely enjoyed our stay and appreciated the special touch to make my boyfriends birthday even more enjoyable.

column11:
We found this service through Yelp and booked purely off of the outstanding reviews it received.  After using them (Chris specifically) we can affirm that these reviews are spot on! We've been up to Santa Barbara many times for wine tasting and have used limo companies in the past, that truly rip you off in price.  This service is much more affordable and incredibly convenient.  Chris met us at our hotel in the valet area, jumped in the drivers seat of our car and off we went.  It was so easy.  There was also something really nice about being in our car all day.

Apparently all the drivers are locals in Santa Ynez, so they know the area well.  Chris had great recommendations for which wineries to visit (based on what we were looking for) and made a really great lunch recommendation that we would never have found on our own.  He was fun and professional.  It's safe to say we'll be calling Chris and his team from now on when we're up there!

column11: We had an opportunity to go to Bristol Farms Grocery in Santa Barbara today. What an amazing store with a fabulous selection of delicious fruit and vegetables. column11: A friend & I decided to eat here because we were super hangry & close by & I saw it was on the Axxess. I've always wanted to try it as well since i'm always grocery shopping by here too. Biggest regret coming here. The food was absolutely horrendous, I got a 1/4 chicken plate that came with 2 sides, I got fries & a macaroni salad. The chicken; bland, undercooked, cold, just absolutely gross. It had bbq sauce on it that tasted like the to go container ones you get from McDonalds with your chicken nuggets. The macaroni salad was awful, tasted sour & old, fries were mediocre. My friend got a cheeseburger with bacon & fries, nothing special about it what so ever. Came out to be about 30 bucks before the Axxess deal. The only "good" thing about this place was the ranch that made the fries taste better. Just avoid this place at all cost,  overpriced, food is horrible & made my stomach hurt. It hurts my eyes to see someone in the reviews say "best bbq place in town!", ummm where? Save your money go to Creekside restaurant,now they know about real good bbq food hands down!!

column11:
My husband and I along with a few of our friends went to eat here last night. We have eaten here in the past but mostly the Los Agaves downtown. We were all very disappointed with the food. I don't know if there is a new owner or what but the the food is not what it used to be. 

My husband order the salmon taco, they should of called it pineapple taco because there was more pineapples in the taco then salmon 

I had the homemade chille relleno compilation plate. Now if you have ever made homemade chille relleno before the chilles are grilled, stuffed with cheese, and coated with light fluffy egg batter. Well mine chille relleno was falay open, cheese dumped on top of it then cover in what tasted like a very thick coat of masa. It was so bad that I sent it back and asked for a chicken sope instead. The sope wasn't any better; the masa was way to thick and had no flavor.
 
We all left the restaurant dissatisfied...The only good thing I can say about last nights dinner was the rice was very flavorful

Later that night my friend called me saying she was very sick to her stomach and has been vomiting- she might be a victim of food poisoning. 
Today I am not feeling to well, very sick to my stomach  

NEVER GOING BACK

The diversity in produce is wonderful in that it pushes me to learn how to use it in my cooking; otherwise, I get mad at myself if I ever have to put it in the compost.

column11:
One of the more disappointing dining experiences I've had in a long while. The server dropped my meal and brought it back with 1/2 the amount of fries :/ then we had servers come to us 3 times with other people's food and drinks. Everything seemed very unorganized. However the atmosphere was pleasant and they go for an upscale modern look that's what gets them 2 stars instead of 1. It's just unfortunate the food quality and taste does not meet the appearance.

We waited quite some time for our food and it arcane out at different times. My ahi tuna sandwich came with a Cajun seasoning that was no where to be mentioned on the menu and was way too hot so I had to send it back. The waiter was nice to replace it and the manager himself brought out my dish. Special treatment! So they obviously care about their customers, which I appreciate. The chickens avocado sandwich was ehhh. Not much too it.

I'll maybe this place just isn't my taste buds because it seems like other people like it according to other reviews. Maybe I need to give it another try. But after having 2 items that were both thumbs down, it's hard to want to.

My friend's Cajun sandwich was not that good. She actually said she was suffering through it and my fianc's burger was a 2/5. The fries were tastey but cold.

My dog loved her chicken and mashed potatoes though!

column11: The food was fine, but I'm giving them 2 stars because of the experience. I flew in to see my sister who had just been released from the hospital. We were also both sick with the flu and wanted a nice dinner. We thought we would be walking in to a nice restaurant, but little did we know, we walked in to A HIGH SCHOOL CAFETERIA. A group of 30+ brought a speaker, were screaming, chanting, banging on the tables etc. I understand that it isn't the restaurant's fault if people are inconsiderate and rambunctious, but the management didn't bother to say anything even though the entire restaurant was clearly irritated. I didn't think it was fair to ruin the experience of several parties for fear of putting a small damper on one.

column11:
We were looking for a place to eat in Santa Barbara that would satisfy my hunger and sisters who were looking for good salad. We had a couple places in mind thanks to Yelp and we ended up going to The Middle Child. We are so glad that we did. Both my sisters enjoyed their salads and the rest of us our personnel pizzas. We loved this place so much we decided to come back here the next day before we had back to the Bay Area. Their menu doesn't have a lot of items, but It's simple food that taste really good. My sister wanted a Caesar salad and had them top it with their fried chicken. They were both great (I ordered the same thing when we came back the 2 time), my other sister had their arugula salad and she loved that. I had the avocado pizza, and that was good too and my nieces shared the farmers market pizza which changes each time, depending what they decide to get at the market that day. It was a potato pizza and they both loved it. If you come here, GET their fried chicken. It is soooooo good.

You order your food and pay at the counter. They have an upstairs for more seating and also a cute outdoor seating area in the back. Staff is really friendly too.

column11:
I love Lilly's Taqueria! It was the first Mexican place I tried after moving here. Let me begin by saying that I'm from Georgia, and ate quite a lot of good Mexican food in the rural, southern part of the state. Lilly's provided the best Mexican food I've had since leaving South Georgia ten years ago.

First of all, the tacos themselves are excellent. I've tried the more everyday meats - chicken, carne asada, etc. - but my favorite is the mejilla taco (beef cheek meat). It may sound adventurous, but it's more like very tender steak than anything. And  Lilly's does mejilla right: extremely tender and long on the flavor! (For food thrill-seekers, they also sell ojo tacos, or beef eyeballs...I'll admit I have yet to try them.)

I like the casual feel and incredible range of topping choices. The vegetables are always very fresh, and I think the salsas might be homemade. Finally, the people who work here are incredibly nice and the service is prompt, even when the line is out the door. For the best Mexican food in the area, look no further!

column11:
The service was a bit lacking, especially for the re-opening.  The girl that helped us looked like she didn't want to be there and was annoyed.  The atmosphere was not friendly - lighten up people, you work at an ice cream shop, not a morgue!  There is hardly any parking if someone parks their boat in the small lot.  There was no line when we got there.  The chocolate almond has a thin, cheap texture and is overrated.  The Brazilian coffee was pretty good, but half scoop was just about right.  

I like how you can have two flavors in one generous scoop.  Those two points = two stars.

column11: Food is good. Or...was good. Tonight we went in for dinner. We've been to Eureka over 10 times, at least. The food is always good. Until tonight. My husband and I, taking advantage of their happy hour, ordered their nachos. We've had them before and they are yummy. But tonight, instead of cubed moist chicken they gave us soggy, shredded, crock-pot like chicken. Also, the nachos are supposed to come with beans. I counted the beans.......there were 7 total beans (I sent it back asking for more beans and my plate came back with MAYBE 12 beans). Flavor was lacking. My son ordered the corn dog pops. He loves their cheddar-IPA sauce. Our server did not tell us that the restaurant no longer made this sauce (despite us requesting two sides of it), and instead brought two sides of spicy mustard sauce (he's a little kid! What was the thinking there??). I have one other complaint that I have felt for awhile, that being that the service is T.E.R.R.I.B.L.E. Don't go in there expecting to get your drinks in a timely manner. You are lucky if you get them before your meal. And even more lucky if a server comes up to you to take your order at all.

column11:
The Boathouse is a great restaurant tucked into a cove in Santa Barbara. I was there back in October 2020 with my girlfriend and originally went for breakfast, but due to the long wait (1.5-2 hours on a Sunday for a table for two) ended up having lunch. You'll want to keep that in mind and go early otherwise the menu will change and you'll be forced to pick from other options that you didn't originally plan for. 

The beach is beautiful, but busy with families and dogs (only half of the beach was dog-friendly). After putting down your name on the waiting list, definitely grab some drinks at the bar and relax on some benches looking out at the ocean. 

There was a good mix of indoor and outdoor dining, given the circumstances of 2020, and the service was great. They were attentive and helped move an umbrella once the sun started burning my neck haha! We ordered the Angus Burger ($14.95) and the Pulled Pork Grilled Cheese ($15.95). They were both big portions, but nothing to revel about. The burger was huge and can be easily split with someone or taken home for leftovers. The grilled cheese was misleading since it wasn't very cheesy and felt like a regular meaty sandwich with one slice of cheese. While the food was okay, I don't think it justified the price and it's clear that you're definitely paying a price for the location and the view.

column11: Came here for brunch one day to splurge and very much enjoyed the experience. Granted, that experience will cost you....worth it at least one time. It's a 3 course brunch with your choice of dishes from a prix fixe menu. Brunch also includes champagne, bellinis, or mimosas. The service was wonderful and the atmosphere is unparalleled in SB. The place and service are a bit stiff for my taste. I tried to self park my Camry without realizing that you must have the valet park your car. I'm sure my Camry felt a little awkward being parked next to Aston Martins, Teslas, and Mercedes. The other obvious choice for splurging on brunch in SB would be the Biltmore...for myself, I would rather dine at the Stonehouse. Someday, I hope to return.

column11:
I visited Creamistry for the first time yesterday.  Ordering was quick, but preparation was very slow.

Creamistry boasts that using liquid nitrogen results in smaller milk particles which leads to creamery ice cream.  The ice cream was indeed very creamy with an excellent mouthfeel, but I've been to other ice cream places whose ice cream was no less creamy.  I did notice that the ice cream melted much more slowly without being colder.

I ordered chocolate without toppings or sauces so that I could see how good the flavor is.  The chocolate tasted good, not like a cheap sauce, but the flavor was too weak.  I plan to return to ask for a stronger flavor of chocolate and to try a different flavor.

I doubt I'll return after that for three reasons.  First, the regular size is as big as a large somewhere else and is bigger than I would order on a regular basis.  Second, due to the way they make their ice cream individually, it's not possible to get more than one flavor at a time.  And third, it's expensive, too expensive to overcome the deficiencies of large size and inability to have more than one flavor at a time.

column11:
This is obviously the best and only place to get Sushi in Santa Barbara. 1/2 sushi is the BUSINESS and even when you come on the wrong day, you can always order "all you can eat sushi" at a decent price. 

If you're sitting on the bar- don't forget the option to order a lunch box or dinner box. You can never go wrong with that- it has miso soup, like 3 diff. sides, sushi, and tempura! Don't forget to upgrade to fried rice cause it's friggin AMAZING. 

Lastly, if you're looking for a special roll with a bit of a spicy twist, please please please order the Mexican roll. You won't be disappointed. It's an orgasmic experience of salmon, crab, avocado, spicy mayo, jalapeno and all kinds of other good ish! I'm wishing I had one this very moment...too bad I graduated and moved back home 3 hours away. *tears*

Anyways, for families with children, may I suggest coming at a reasonable dinner time...this restaurant does sell alchy && it IS on State st. so if you're coming after 8- expect to be bombarded with ready to party college students. 

Tis all.

column11:
Anniversary sushi dinner!!! Last year when we were in Santa Barbara, we had sushi on the other end of state street. This was much better then downtown!!! 

We started with seared albacore carpaccio. This was an amazing cut of fish, lightly seared and full of flavor! We then ordered three rolls: Tiger Roll, Mexican Roll and Spider Roll!  Two thumbs up for sure!!! The sushi chefs were amazing, staff very friendly, and service was great!!  Glad to find this little hole in the wall on the upper end of State Street!

column11: We decided last minute on a "weekend getaway" to Santa Barbara.  We live in LA and ironically, neither of us had ever been to Santa Barbara. Having always heard about the wine tasting in the area, decided to book a tour for one of our two days there.  After reading some reviews on various places, decided to go with Coastal Concierge.  I am so glad that we made this choice.  First of all, I can not say enough good things about our driver, Derek.  He was simply amazing and catered to our every need.  Also, just a wealth of knowledge.  We spent the entire afternoon riding around to various wineries, none of which were crowded, but all amazing.  Derek allowed us to go at our own pace which was really nice.  Never felt rushed at all.  We lost all track of time and before we knew it, it was time to head back.  Not before, we enjoyed three amazing wineries and received an awesome picnic lunch that Derek set up for us.  I recommend this company to anyone who is looking for a fun relaxing, no worries kind of day.  And if you are lucky enough to get Derek as your concierge/driver......you will not be disappointed.  We will definitely be back for more :-)

column11:
Our office volunteered for Habitat for Humanity and I had to choose the place for lunch. I had been here once before; I was tooling around Carpinteria like a tourist, and there really wasn't a sandwich shop on the main drag (linden) that appealed to me. I googled and found this, had a pastrami - so good! Anyways, I called to ask about ordering over the phone for our group of nine. Haley was SO helpful! she gave me the email so I could email the order which I did after hours. They got it first thing in the morning, and emailed me promptly and cheerily that they were happy to fill my order and looking forward to seeing me. The place is small but SO cute but the staff is STELLAR. Accommodated all of our quirky special requests, wrote everyone's name on each sandwich wrapper, and had the order ready and waiting on time. 

If you are in Carpinteria, go pick up sandwiches here to take to the beach.SO many fresh ingredients like cucumber and bell peppers, arugula and basil, etc. as well as of course literally PB and J. They have "spa" water as the free water (citrus and fruit infused) just one more excellent touch.

column11:
Underneath is my review from last night. I decided to change my review this morning because my complaint was heard and taken care of right away which impressed me. Someone from their affiliate resteraunt (brophy bros) saw my review and got into contact with me right away. I told him I was less upset on the wait for the food (it's understandable on a busy night!) however it was upsetting to me that the person in charge was rude. 
The man I spoke with was sincere, understanding and listened to what I had to say and was very professional!!  He explained to me what went on and it all made sense. All I wanted was to be heard and acknowledged which is what I received. Something as simple as a phone call to a customer can change their entire perspective and attitude! Thank you brophy bros!!!


Precious review: My boyfriend has been raving about this place so he took me to try it...and then the extremely rude manager went and ruined it for us forever! story: my boyfriends parents came to town spontaneously this evening on their way back from a trip. We wanted to take them to dinner at Brophy's but of course on a Friday night the wait was an hour and a half...we opted for On the Alley around the corner. We went in, ordered and sat...and sat...and sat some more...30 minutes later my food came out. This was understandable to me, they seemed very busy. I was expecting my boyfriends and his parents food to come out right after mine since we had all ordered at the exact same time. IT DID NOT.

My food is sitting there getting cold. There are about 5 other parties starting to complain to each other about what is taking so long. The poor girl who is supposed to bring out the food is getting angry complaints from everyone, manager nowhere to be seen. My boyfriend goes in to tell her that she should say something to her manager and that he should at least come out and take care of the problem. 30 minutes later the rest of our parties food comes (mine is completely cold by this time). There is a couple and there two young children sitting near us and we can hear them ask for the manager. Everyone else who is waiting has been sitting for 45 minutes to an hour..this family had ordered two kids meals!!!! kids meals!!!! waiting an hour for two hamburgers? these people (and the rest of us) clearly should have been apologized to for the mishap. The manager finally comes out to talk to this family. We join their group, telling him that we would have simply appreciated that they had let us know at some point that they wait was going to be extremely long...in that case we would have gone somewhere else. All the manager has to say is "I'm sorry you guys had a bad experience" in a very insincere tone. My boyfriend, pretty angry at this point, keeps his calm and tells the manager how he did not think it was fair that he was not taking responsibility for his own customers concerns and letting the poor server girl take all the slack for him. My boyfriend did not raise his voice or use profanities while saying this. The manager says "I didn't make anyone do anything! Ive been upstairs at brophys!", he then turns his back to all of us and says "that it" and walks back inside and goes upstairs.

WHAT!!!!???!!!!
We were so shocked. I don't have anything to say badly about the food, however it upsets me to see someone treat their customers with such rudeness especially when we are giving this guy our money!!! I will not support someone like that despite the fact that the food was fine. The only way id go back is if I knew they were under new management.

column11:
I chose this Bed and Breakfast because it was walking distance to a lot of restaurants, the pier and State Street.
We were seeing a concert at the Bowl but I knew we would Lyft there vs walk or drive so I took into account that it wasn't too far from the Bowl.
The employees at the front desk were more than helpful, the room was clean and somewhat spacious, the  bathroom had plenty of counter space, the shower had a handheld (love those) and the ice machine was a hop, skip and a jump from our room! 
I would definitely recommend the Casa Del Mar to anyone staying in Santa Barbara!

column11:
Pura Luna Apothecary has now relocated at 633 Chapala St., but  not officially open just yet. I was very fortunate to catch their soft opening over the weekend. I asked when they plan to open but no set date as of now. Follow them on IG @puralunaapothecary for updates. 

They offer a great selection of beautiful chakra crystals, high quality herbal tonics and natural remedies, spices, teas, perfume, body oils, and so much more. 

I firmly believe in the healing powers of herbal remedies and how much better they are for our bodies. I purchased lions mane mushroom extract which helps to increase mental clarity, elevate your mood, repairs nerve damage and enhances the immune system. 

I also purchased the Adaptogen powder for stress management because we all could use some help with reducing our stress levels these days. 

I'm in love with my citrine and jade chakras. I haven't seen pieces like these before so I had to grab them. 

I encourage everyone to support this locally owned black business once they officially open. We don't have very many black owned businesses here.  The two beautiful ladies that own this place; Ashe and Christin are kind hearted spirits who exude positive energy all around. Once you walk into this place you will feel it. 

They will eventually offer hair services in their salon area as well. 

Congratulations ladies on your new location and I wish you nothing but success. Looking forward to my next visit here!

column11:
Came here for the first time very recently. The outdoor patio was popping. I personally felt Covid-safe, however it might have seemed less so if my triad hadn't been able to find an empty corner. We had two rounds of beers, and our bartender was friendly and happy to provide samples and chat about flavors. I ordered the Chisme for my first drink, and an IPA (forget which, since I sampled them all!) for #2.

Here's why four stars instead of five: I'm nonbinary, and was even wearing a t-shit which says that. At the bar with my two queer cis women friends, the bartender's first words were, "hey ladies." I corrected him and told him not to make assumptions about people's genders and pronouns based on how they look, and he listened and was apologetic. So that's all good, but being misgendered in the first place made the whole guest experience one star less welcoming. 

On the bright side, the place has the bathroom situation figured out. As Yelp's helpful "Amenities and More" section lists, there are gender-neutral restrooms. Two clean, functional bathrooms allow all customers to feel comfortable using the facilities (unlike M Special--who need to get their s**t together, literally.)

The place is very doggo friendly; there were tons of pooches having a patio party. Also, the pop-up pizza was on point, and though they forgot the arugula on both pizzas my group ordered, they were totally willing to make a half-cheeseless pie so my non-vegan friend and I could share. 

A solid four stars for Captain Fatty's.

column11:
Awful experience, awful staff, awful food.

Went for dinner on a recent Wednesday night -- the place was half full. Ok, great! We have the pick of tables.  Not.

The greeter placed us at worst table in the house, and provided some half-baked explanation that they were understaffed, and certain sections were closed off. We asked to be moved. Not -- again.

Then "Patrick" -- the manager came out. He was completely officious, demeaning, and not interested in accommodating the customer. He then tried to immediately take our order, in particular the wine, after which I said "we'll order wine with rest of our meal." This did not sit well with Patrick, who insisted that the wine be ordered at that time. I refused and he left. 

On to the cuisine. I don't even know where to begin with this. There were SO many ingredients on each of the plates, that our heads were spinning. And in the end, completely unmemorable, other than the outrageous tab.

The wine list was short, expensive, and unimaginative -- considering the proximity to SB wine country.

I don't know what the hype is of this place. 

Avoid.

column11:
I had such joy and high hopes upon entering this place...

Only to be met by a woman who didn't even bother looking up to acknowledge me when I entered.  I awkwardly walked around a few minutes before finally introducing myself...then she said hello.

Onto the chocolate:  do not expect See's Candies or any of that fancy gourmet chocolate like in Santa Barbara.  This is lower end, lower quality.   And "homemade" (SOME of the chocolate is made in-house, but most of it comes from a supplier).  Some of it is nostalgic and fun...but the rest of it is meh or horrible.  Even the quality of the caramel in the chocolates is a bit weak.  If you're used to high end, you may find this a bit "boring"...but then again, to have been around for a while, obviously they've done something right for someone.  

The last issue I have:  I left my keys on the counter where I paid, and I feel like the same lady who didn't speak to me upon entering could have flagged me down to let me know once I left.  I practically hung out in front of the store a bit before walking away, and when I DID walk away, it was a slow walk cause I was eating the candy.  It would have been NOTHING to peek out of the store and alert me that I left my keys.  They ended up being locked in the store overnight 

Thank God the nice lady during the DAY helped me get them back.  I should have told her about the evening lady.

Either way, come here and see if you like this place.  But if you do not, I totally get it.  Candy ain't cheap, so go where it's really good.  This place you can skip.

column11:
I stayed here for about two weeks. So too did two of our guests.

This is one of the nicer properties in the area. it's situated about 15 minutes outside of Santa Barbara proper. Their rates for what they offer were better than those of similar properties within Santa Barbara.

They offer morning breakfast and an afternoon dessert with your room price. 

Breakfasts were delicious...but more so if you're someone who considers 'butter" to be it's own food group. Very un-heart healthy fare.

We switched rooms a couple of times so we tried several during our stay. All of our rooms were worth it for the price they asked. All were kept reasonably clean and in good repair.

Now...with this much of a nice experience with this place you may wonder why I award them only 3 stars. So here's the truth...they're a nice property...but none of the members of our party were ever "wowed" in any manner by either the property or the service. And we spent a good two weeks here.

They offer a private lot for your car...but it can be a cramped pullout...so beware. I inflicted a substantial amount of body damage here to my own car. There's not too much within walking distance but Santa Barbara is a close drive up the freeway.

column11:
Yes, there are McConnell's back home in Los Angeles... but when you are on a work trip in Santa Barbara, you make it a task to visit McConnell's as many times as you can and let your workplace pay the bill!

I had ice cream every night for three nights straight, to the point that the cashiers actually remembered us on the third night and called us out on it. We were all good about it, no shame.

With three nights worth of visits, I tried different flavors every time when sampling. My usual at McConnell's is LA is the Earl Grey Tea & Shortbread Cookies, but I've noticed that this store had a bigger selection than the shops in LA. For the first night, I ordered the Whiskey & Pecan Praline and the Pistachio Amaretto. For night two, I ordered the Pistachio Amaretto again and the Milk & White Chocolate Walnut. For night three, I ordered straight up Pistachio Amaretto (clearly I had a favorite). All the flavors were creamy and fulfilling. Flavors were bold and strong, but nothing was too harsh and abrasive. Other flavors that I enjoyed sampling were the Sea Salt Cookies & Cream and the Double Peanut Butter Chip. 

The staff were amazing on all three nights! Accommodating and very hospitable. Loved my experience every time I visited.

Overall, everything here is really good and if you were in my work life situation, you would totally eat ice cream here three days in a row as well. [Side note: I wish the Pistachio Amaretto existed in the LA shops like the one at grand central market!)

column11:
One of the worst dining experiences ever. Absolutely terrible service. 

For starters, as everyone around us was getting their complimentary chips and salsa, we had to ask for ours long after ordering our drinks. The food was only so-so, but we also had to ask for plates, napkins AND utensils to eat our food with! Silly me, thought these things normally came without asking at a restaurant. To top things off, I saw our server dip her hands into the heating drawer, take out a tortilla chip and dip it into the vat of salsa that they serve customers from and eat it. She did this several times! Now I'm no expert, but I'm pretty sure that is a health code violation of some sort. 

I will never go here ever again.

column11: The ambiance was a 10......open air courtyard patio seating.  Bar was 'pedestrian'....didn't go back for second margherita food was a major disappointment....albondigos soup too salty; meatballs no flavor. Fajitas served with 'authentic/homemade tortillas which had been steamed and proceeded to fall apart.  The carne asada (aka steak) was gristle heated up w/out ANY seasoning.....Needless to say there MUST be a better place to eat! MOST UNFORTUNATE BECAUSE THE AMBIANCE IS RIDICULOUS!!!.....I would go there again just for happy hour (see can't mess up chips, salsa, tacquitos) to enjoy the setting.....but pretty much would pass on the food....better Mexican food found on every food truck in town.
