column11: This place has it all: great eats, reasonable prices, live music, a hip yet quaint atmosphere, and perfect service. Plus parking was a breeze. They have plenty of vegetarian options as well as hearty meat items. I had the cheese and guava cubes (I am not sure what they are really called), Brussels sprouts, chipotle potatoes, the cheese plate, a salad, and some other items that I can't remember the names of. Each is is good for two people to share and we ended up ordering about 6 or 7 tapas. I recommend getting the sangria and don't miss dessert. The wait staff was really attentive and friendly. This is a good place to go if you want that upscale, chic restaurant feel for the "struggling college student" prices.

column11:
So I came over last night to have dinner, finished eating and paid within 30mins. (the WORST 30 mins meal EVER!)

First of all, food wasn't that great besides the Chili Cheese Fries. I got SMOKED CHICKEN, BACON & SPINACH PIZZA and it tastes like NOTHING! You can't taste the cheese, nor the bacon. I had to add salt and pepper to get some taste. But that's not the worst...

THE WORST PART WAS THEIR SERVICE!!

The server "N", asked us if we needed boxes when we weren't even half way done with our food. Like what is this? Rushing us to leave? WE JUST STARTED OUR FOOD! The restaurant wasn't packed, no one was waiting for a seat, AND! it wasn't even near the time of closing, it wasn't even 8pm yet. And she asked if we need boxes. I was on my second slice of pizza, and my friends still have 3/4 of food in their plate and we were asked if we need boxes. One of my friend said "No, I don't need boxes" and the server brought back boxes and asked her again if she wanted a box. She already said no, she doesn't want a box, just leave her alone. Before we even started boxing our food, the server brought over our checks. 

Yeah, probably not coming back again. Also, we left her some comments on the receipts "thanks for giving us boxes when we weren't even half way done with our food" and more...
So without mentioning her name, she knows who she is. 

If that happens to you in the future, let her know YOU WEREN'T DONE, so she can process it whatever is going on inside her head.

column11: I visited on a hot Saturday 10/3/20 for lunch with a friend. There was a 20 minute wait and the hostess directed us to a small cart serving a choice of two beverages: spritzer and margarita, we ordered one of each. The cost was $51.00, which I would not mind if it was not in plastic, no where to sit and no shade umbrellas while waiting. We ordered lunch from small menu: a hamburger and bratwurst with pretzel, waitress suggested fried pickles as well as there was no sides. The burger was average, the bratwurst juicy but the pretzel was stale. In both of our opinions the food was over salted and service below average.  The only redeeming elements were the setting with beach views, manicured gardens and smartly dressed staff.

column11: These guys are awesome!  My buddies and i went on a brewery tour this weekend, and Darin was an awesome guide and host. The bus is awesome!  Rock music, cool lights, and great company. They drove us frombrewery to brewery, and bar to bar. I got to taste some of the best beers I've had in a long long time.  At the end of the trip the guys even drove out our group and our car back to the hotel. We could have caught an Uber , but these guys really wanted to make sure we were safe. ... talk about going above and beyond. These guys are great people and it's not a matter of if, but of when, we're going back. Next time you want an awesome trip, forget vegas! This is the better choice!

column11: Steph and his team catered my wedding in august 2021. His crew did an amazing job. He was super easy going, service was great from beginning to end, made sure everything clicked and was taken care of and looked great. He and his staff were so friendly. column11: I'm really sad. Been coming to this bar for the past 3 years, I really enjoyed. We came back this year to a rude bartender who basically bur-rated me for not knowing that the menu changed 2 years ago. Well, maybe you guys should update your Yelp page. Yelp is one of the only ways out-of-towners like myself know what's popular and hopping. We chatted a bit and he said business has fallen off "because so many other places opened up." Nope, it's because of the service and food selections. Every bar on State St has over cooked burgers and deep fried chicken. Clearly these guys are interested only in hooking up their friends. Bummer. This place was great a year ago.

column11:
Maybe I just went on a horrible night... I sincerely hope I went on a horrible night.

The waitresses were nice and came when we waved our hands, but they never came by voluntarily. It would take a couple tries of trying to make eye contact in order to get them to come over to where my friend and I were sitting. When they came, they came with a smile and they were both nice, but the amount of time it took to get them to come over was quite ridiculous.

The more ridiculous aspect of this restaurant is the length of time they kept us waiting to get our food. I don't know about others, but I have never waited over an hour for a plate of raw fish. Sushi shouldn't be taking an hour to prepare and serve. We didn't even order hard or big dishes. One roll and one don plate. No cooking necessary and they weren't spectacular in presentation.

The fish was not fresh, the laver was chewy and old (been out for too long), and the price just did not match the quality and quantity.

We were thinking of just canceling our orders and going somewhere else, and we both wholeheartedly regret that we stayed.

I don't think I'll ever give this place another try, but hopefully... others have better experiences than me.

column11:
Love the relaxed vibe replete with table tennis tables and the warm welcome. Love that Old Town is locally owned and operated and the coffee is good. Only three stars however, due to the $1.00 upcharge for sustainable and cruelty-free plant milk. Other coffee shops in SB are treating all customers equally and we'd love to see OTC join the movement.

Thank you for your response, Rachel. I tried to respond back, but it wouldn't work so just updating this now:

Thank you for your kind message. I'm sorry that I had the price wrong on the upcharge. That was terrible of me! If you will give me another chance, I'd like to explain. There are other third wave places in town that do not penalize those of us who are concerned for our personal and planetary health, those who are allergic and/or lactose intolerant, etc. and they do not roast their own coffee. They simply choose to spread the cost of all milks across the board so everyone feels welcome. Even if we take the cruelty factor of the dairy industry off the table and just focus on the environment, I think we can all pitch in and do our part to help. Given that animal agriculture is a leading cause of our climate crisis, mass deforestation, and ocean dead zones, would you consider either penalizing cow milk drinkers to offset the cost of plant milk or at the very least, charging more across the board so everyone would feel welcome and be able to enjoy your establishment without being penalized for their choices? Also, lactose intolerance is primarily an issue for minorities so it penalizes people of color and other minorities more than those from European lineages. Some examples of third wave shops eschewing the upcharge are Merci Montecito, Mosto, Goat Tree, and Bossie's Kitchen. Anyway, I appreciate your correcting my mistake on the amount of your surcharge and also being open to hear my thoughts.

column11: The food here is very good. Portion sizes are large. I recommend sharing an entree and trying more starters. My only real complaint relates to the check-in process. We booked a table for 8 PM. We arrived a few minutes early. The hostess seemed a little put-off and told us we would have to wait while she tended to other guests. We did not feel welcome. We waited outside. Another couple arrived after us. We were both waiting outside. The hostess came back and asked who had arrived first. It was clear that we had arrived first, but the other couple claimed to have a 7:45 PM reservation (they were late, as it was after 8 PM at this point). My complaint, and it's a minor one, is that the hostess should have stuck to her "first come, first served" system. She should have remembered we arrived first and and immediately seated us, and not given the other couple an opportunity to weasel in.

column11: I come here regularly, and I leave satisfied every time! Their breakfast items are all delicious; my favorite is the egg bagel! So good! I usually get that with the Thai tea. The main lady is always so nice; always with a smile on her face. She sometimes gives me free donuts too if it's the end of the day. Today's service was especially exceptional because for the first time I asked for iced Thai tea with no sugar, and she usually has an already-made Thai tea with sugar so she made no-sugar ice tea for me from scratch. This is commendable because there was a long line, and she was accommodating my wishes with a smile on her face despite this fact. She's always so nice to other people too. Such a wonderful staff! Thank you! Highly recommended for breakfast items, donuts, tea, amazing boba! There's an outside place which reminds me of French cafes with little metal tables and chairs, separated from the parking lot with large flower pots. Wonderful in every way!

column11:
3.5 stars on this Ritz. About 15-30 minutes from downtown Santa Barbara BUT conveniently located near Sandpiper Golf Club, this Ritz Carlton is newer than many others. I was here with a good friend and her dog. I've stayed at many other Ritz's and this one didn't knock me over.

When you drive in, it doesn't have that "wow" factor. It was green and luscious due to all the rain Santa Barbara received this winter but I didn't like the steep walkways that are dominated by motorized carts to move people around. We had to hop out of the way several times although we were thanked, it's awkward. Valet service was exceptionally good.

Due to a couple parties, the room was noisy at night. You could hear noise outside and hear people walking around outside the room and above it. So, make sure your room is on the third floor in your villa.

There are heated pools and jacuzzis and there's a phenomenal view to the ocean from there. But you can see the oil rigs. 

There are several walking paths around the property and other trails. There's a path above the beach to the water. The beach itself wasn't crowded but it was early March and cool. Plus the water was brown from runoff due to rain. 

The gardens on the property are lovely.  The food at the bistro wasn't very good with both our fish and steak over cooked.  However, we didn't eat at Angel Oak restaurant and we didn't take advantage of the spa. 

We had a large dog with us and we were charged a crazy expensive pet fee of $250 and had to sign a letter about where the dog was allowed to go. However, the dog was treated like a god everywhere we went and even got serenaded in the lobby. 

The staff are super friendly and went out of the way to help us with the dog.

column11:
Really, really good.  We went on a Monday night, when they have a special where any bottle of wine is half-price with dinner.  (Try their nice Lebanese white wine.)  Anyway, before dinner came, they brought out pita bread with zaatar sauce, which is kind of like a very thick pesto, with a little garnish of tomatoes and onions, and saturated with sesame seeds.  I could not stop eating it -- which they picked up on, since they offered to bring out a second batch unbidden.

Dinner itself was tremendous.  The lamb kebab, which from the name could have been kind of mundane, was a colorful plateful not only of lamb, but a baba ganoush with a great smoky flavor; a nice tomato, greens, onion and radish salad; tabouli; and saffron (?) rice.  My honey had a plate (name temporarily forgotten; started with an "M") full of lamb, chicken, sausage baba ganoush, a zingy Middle Eastern cheese with the color and consistency of yogurt, and hummus.  Very nice indeed.  I can report that we waddled home in contentment.

The outdoor space they have (we didn't go inside) was very relaxing, especially on a balmy summer evening.  There's a little low, quietly bubbling (of course faux) waterfall along one wall, which sounds tacky, I know, but it's well executed and was properly calming and Zen.  The servers were attentive and knowledgeable (and, as a note to my fellow Yelpers, made plenty of eye contact).  And in Santa Barbara, it's refreshing to find a nice place that seems worlds away from State Street.

Oh, it's also a hookah lounge, but I don't smoke, and neither should you.

column11:
WOW! I have previously avoided handlebar due to overcrowding and inconvenient location in relation to my house, BUT that was all thrown to the wind today when I didn't have time to make coffee and found myself running errands in the area.  

As I was thinking about how badly I needed a pick me up I looked up and there was handlebar, my hero, with no line, my prayers to the coffee gods were answered. 

The latte was the perfect texture and temperature. As soon as I got my coffee the line was building up toward the door. I will now go out of my way to get a coffee here as it is THE BEST IN TOWN! Shout out to Taylor for being so sweet, cheerful and helpful. 
Hats off to you handlebar, that was a great latte matched by a great experience.

column11: I went in on a Saturday looking for a yummy flavored protein powder to increase my protein intake. I "researched" online and was happy to find exactly what I was looking for in the flavor I wanted. The store is very clean and organized. It has an open layout with well known products and supplements. There is a huge selection of bars and cookies as well. There were quite a few people there - ended up being a weigh in for a cool fat loss/muscle gain contest the store was having. I lingered and was overhearing their success stories and looking at all the other protein powders the store carried. Despite having 5+ people in the store, Ben Lopez still made sure to greet me and offer assistance. I was really concerned with the flavor and texture of the protein powder and Ben let me know that the flavor would be tasty...because of the added sugar and ingredients. Since I shared with him that my protein intake was super low he quickly recommended their highest gram product, Prozein Synthesis. He expressed his favorite was the chocolate which I am usually not a fan of. I prefer Vanilla, always have, but struggle with the chalky taste. Then without missing a beat he asked if I'd like to try it and whipped up a shake, on the spot! I could not believe how smooth it was. Nothing like I had anticipated and feared! I was won over. He then went into all the other benefit and ingredients. Recommendations for how to best intake it AND stressed the importance of using it as a supplement and not a meal replacement. The top leader in the contest they are running was there too and he also offered up his favorite flavor and the ways he enjoys taking it. It was one of those experiences you rarely have in retail anymore. Where someone is truly passionate about what they represent and want to help you reach your goals and not just take your money and sell you anything. So refreshing! Plus the sense of community and shared interest in health and wellness was palpable. I definitely recommend Nutrishop and Ben if you are just starting on your fitness journey or if you are looking to increase those gains because he knows what he's talking about and they have what you need there!

column11:
I have no idea why the reviews of this place are bad...the location is perfect, the service when I was there was stellar and super fast, the food was hearty and delicious and the prices are incredible considering you are on the water, literally!
Our gaggle of 10, I repeat 10 girls showed up here on a Sunday morning, let's say around 10:00 am...yes, prime Sunday breakfast time.  We quickly had a primo table on the gorgeous patio and get this, one of the girls asked for separate checks!!!  I was a bit mortified by that request, but it was met and with a smile!  Our orders were taken by 2 lovely ladies and delivered within minutes.  I docked a star because my eggs weren't cooked the way I asked and the inside of the restaurant is not very nice, but shoot, I sat on a patio next to the ocean and ate eggs and toast and coffee for $12 including tip!  What more can you ask for?

column11:
The poor service and food more than obliterated the casual and nice ambiance-don't bother. 

First, the tuna sandwich, was misdescribed by our inept server, Meghan, as "sushi grade" ahi. Not so--it was a cheesy (literally) unappetizing mixture of canned tuna, cheese and celery that looked like vomit and that even Star Kist would be embarrassed be associated with. 

Second, while there were only 5 of about 30 tables occupied for lunch (hardly a server demanding crowd) Meghan, could not have been slower, more inept or more rude. It took way too long to get menus, iced tea and order our meal. Then, when asked to serve some bread along with soup, she crisply answered: " We do not have bread at lunch." Then she brought the obnoxious sandwich on its roll thatI guess was not bread. 

Oh well....

column11: Its too early to tell if this place will turn the Public Market around.  The draft list is extensive and everyone can find something to their taste, but the price was high.  The decor was trendy, like taking a page out of an interior design magazine.  However the "no outside food allowed" policy was annoying.  I was there last night and ordered drinks in plastic cups due to this policy.  I don't buy that this is a full service restaurant, rather its a beer garden with the option of ordering some food to go with your beer.  All food had to traverse the entire length of the Public Market going from the kitchen way in the back to the customers seated at the Garden or various areas of the market.  I kept seeing servers wandering around with one plate of food looking for customers.  It was confusing and inefficient.  I had some incredible tacos from Corazon and 1/3 lb of ahi poke from i'a to go with my beer.  There was a big party that occupied Corazon's big table and most of them were eating tacos, but a few were also eating noodles and sharing it with others.  This is what Public Market is all about.  You can go with a big party and everybody can order what they like from various vendors and share everything.

column11:
REAL Indian cuisine with GREAT service.

The food itself was very much how indian food tastes...intense flavors. The flavors were super strong and very different from the Americanized Indian food that I am usually used to. 

1.) Appetizer Sampler: Samosa was good and was JAMMED to the top with all the filling. The onion ring-ish things were good but a tad salty. The lamb sausage thing was very very flavorful and soft. The tandoori chicken was good too.

2.) Lamb Vindaloo/Chicken Tikka Masala Combo Plate: The raita was very tangy and very different from what I used to have, but was good! The rice was of course good. The Lamb vindaloo and chicken tikka masala was more focused on the meats then the sauce. I hafta say I'm more of a thick sauce girl who like to dips her naan in it. But these curries were more focused on the meat with a thinner sauce. But they were extremely flavorful and tender. The paneer matar that came with it was awesome. The paneer was VERY soft and light.

3.) Naan: YUMMY! Very fresh and doughy/soft but very good taste to it.

I liked this place's service and the food, but I prefer more saucier sauces. But it was great and they're SO nice here! AWESOME service.

column11:
I don't know what to say here. The food is amazing, the location is stunning (during the day or at night). It is VERY popular for good reason. 

The service is always friendly even when busy. Camp out at the bar after checking in, the best seats in the house are at the bar. 

Fresh seafood, causal environment, just a great spot and any trip to Santa Barbara is not complete without a meal here. 

If you haven't been here already - don't bother because it's already too crowded. To the haters....if you let them know about a problem they will fix it if they can - or just don't come.

It is not gourmet fine dining (not Michelin ranked - go to the Biltmore for that), but it is just so simply good. 

If you don't like it, you don't like seafood. Order the burger (but why? It is really good too but...)

We had the beef with ginger and basil along with the szechuan shrimp.  Both were great.  We would obviously come here again and recommend this place to our friends.

column11:
We are on vacation here. After having read reviews of the restaurants near Stearns Wharf, I decided to try this restaurant.

It's located at the end of pier, a small and casual place. I signed up on the clipboard at the door for being seated. The special of the day was on a chalkboard just below the sign-in clipboard. It was a Friday night and there was a free outdoor movie right next to the restaurant. We waited abut 15 min and were seated at the bar, facing the kitchen.  I loved it because I could enjoy chef's action.

We ordered Oyster shooters, steamed claims, the special of the day Hardback shrimp and opinion ring, a paired with Pinot Grigio. It was the first time I tried the oyster shooter which wasn't bad. The claims were steamed with white wine sauce. They were a little bit over-cooked and the juice was a little bit sour. The hardback shrimp, OMG, they were delicious! They were cooked in salted water, accompanied with ketchup. We ate the shrimps without the ketchup. The natural flavor of the shrimp was preserved. They were tender and tasted of sea. The big fat onion rings were crispy and fresh. I regretted that I didn't order more shrimps. They also had crab, lobster and farm abalone. I'll try abalone the next time.

The environment was casual. Our neighbors sitting at the bar offered to take video clip of us drinking the oyster shooter and picture of us with the food.  The staff was friendly and efficient.

This is the place I'll go back and recommend. 

Tips: if you don't want to wait to be seated, you can order takeout. There are picnic table and benches just outside of the restaurant. The line is definitively shorted.

column11: When I have any reason to be near Santa Barbara, I make sure to save time for a meal at Stella Mare's.  Lunch or dinner, it's become a favorite.  I like everything about the experience.  Starting with the way it's decorated.  Everywhere your eye travels, there's something else interesting.  The staff offers exactly the right amount of attention - not hovering, but then you'll never want for anything either.  Did I mention the food?  While this part of California offers many great places to eat, the food at Stella Mare's is so good, and the decor and service both exceptional, so I keep postponing trying other nearby places. Sounds like I'm on the payroll.  I'm not, but I do believe in praise where praise is due.  If you want a memorable meal, lunch or dinner, alone or with a group, you'll find it at Stella Mare's.  If I didn't live hours away, I'd be there for lunch today.

column11:
I called in a pick up order for the special of the day, a bahn mi Vietnamese sandwich at around twelve fifty. St that point, both of their most popular sandwiches were sold out, and by the time I got to Goodland ten min later, so was the special.

Luckily they had already set aside my order, and I gladly paid the slightly pricy ten dollars for a heavenly bahn mi sandwich with spicy aioli and curried chicken. I definitely could have been full after the fifty half, however, and next time will probably go for the cheaper option.

The ingredients were fresh, staff were attentive, and the vibe is laid back organic all the way. A little pricey, but worth it for a special lunch. Just make sure to get there early!

column11: Took the family here for a weekend dinner and man we all had a blast.  From the food to the award winning service I can't praise this place more.  It was Mother's Day weekend so we waited for around 45 minutes but it's all worth it.  All seafood appetizers we ordered are fresh.  The waiter gave excellent service and checked on us maybe more than 5 times the whole time we were there.  He made sure that if we needed something he's just an eyeball away.  Grilled oysters are excellent (very fresh), fried calamari is bomb, crab cakes made me dream about it every night.  The ceviche is not bad either.  Overall I give this place 5 stars nothing less.

column11:
Super cool set up with open outdoor seating.  Great tasting beers.  Hard to find if you don't already know.  I went with a small group on a weekend and the place was packed.  We knocked back a few beers, and had a nice time before heading to dinner.  

There was a food truck there in case you get the munchies.

The staff was nice and attentive and there was a huge variety of beer.  If you like beer, there will be something here for you.

There is plenty of free parking available.

I will certainly come back the next time I'm in the area.

Give them a call for current prices and to see what they are pouring.

column11: The best seafood restaurant in southern CA. Every time I come here the service and food do not disappoint. Today we came for happy hour and let me tell you they have the most amazing happy hour of any other seafood place in Santa Barbara. $6 for a GIANT plate of ceviche, are you kidding!? Delicious! And not to mention the drinks are cheaper, beer $1 off aka corona for $4 not bad for SB prices. My boyfriend is really into oysters and at $1.75 each during happy hour it's a steal, we ordered 15 and he was happy as a clam or should I say oyster lol. The service is always spectacular. It can get a bit busy at happy hour and tables are first come first serve in the bar area. However, it's a pretty big open space (at least 20 tables) so you should be able to walk around and find one open! This place is also amazing for dinner! Either way you will not be disappointed with the food, staff or atmosphere.

column11:
This place is good for a hearty meal a cut above fast food. 

To me, Paneras are a cold weather kinda place - you know, the spot you go to warm yourself up in a cozy atmosphere with a savory bowl of soup. For some reason, their Broccoli Cheddar soup always seems to put a smile on my face. There have never been exceptions to this. 

This particular location is adjacent to a popular mall with ample parking. The restaurant itself is spacious, but not always the cleanest. However, it's never felt dirty to the point of me not wanting to eat there. I'm usually able to cozy up in a comfy booth with my number as I wait for my order to be delivered. 

The service and food are on par with other Panera locations: not the greatest but enjoyable enough. I like ordering the "Pick 2" deal where I can get a half sandwich plus a bowl of soup. The food has always been satisfactory to me and really does hit the spot on a cold winter day. 

Don't expect to be blown away eating here, but do come if you are seeking a trustworthy meal in a comfy setting.

column11: Not sure what's going on at the SB location, but the service has gone downhill for quite some time. I just started dining here again after taking off probably almost a year because of the same issues. Problem is not getting the food I order. For example, yesterday I ordered to go the You Pick 2: tomato soup and the turkey, avocado and bacon sandwich. Open up my sandwich and it's some turkey panini. Today, I ordered the exact same thing and asked the counter person who took the order to make sure that she orders the right sandwich. She even reiterated what was in the sandwich so I thought, great I'll get it this time. Received my order, looked in the bag and noticed the croutons that come with the soup weren't there so I had to ask for it, but didn't check my sandwich. Open it up at work and the sandwich was mostly right, except the bacon is missing. Not sure why it's so hard to get it right. This store definitely needs some training and quality control. Makes me not want to go back for another year.

column11:
This restaurant is not for anyone with any sort of diet restriction. 

We went here last night for a light dinner after some wine tasting. The ambiance is cute, dimly lit but very small. 
When we were ordering I had a convo with our server that I/we didn't eat any meat (except fish) or dairy; we came to eat the veggie sides and the fish. He told me the chef had the exact same diet. We ordered the burruta for my husband, the beet tartare, yellowtail and octopus. 
First they brought out the Bressaola (a dried beef loin) to our table. It was obvious it was meat so we sent it back. 
Next, they brought out stuffed red pepper which wasn't on the menu and was on the house. They said it was vegan but my husband said it tasted like sausages and had some brown looking meat crumble. I asked the server what is was fig. IDK. 
Next they brought us out Steak Tartare. My husband said he wasn't sure about it but the restaurant was so dimly lit and it sort of looked like shaved up beets so after triple checking with the waiter that was close by who gave me the visual thumbs up it was okay to eat, I trusted him and I took a bite. After over 25 years of not eating meat I was chewing on a piece of raw steak. I spit it out and we sent the dish back. It was also really disgusting tasting and wouldn't even order if I was a meat eater. They then sent out the beets we ordered but after that I was done so we asked for no more dishes. The server and chef both apologized and told us not to pay but at the same time I saw them laughing about it because they were standing 5 feet away from me! And when we walked out the cook looked at my husband and shrugged his shoulders in sort of a 'whoopsie' sort of way. I have no idea why that was so funny to serve someone who doesn't eat meat only meat and laugh about it or what that could have been about but it sucked and was a terrible experience.

column11:
On my first visit I had a bowl of squash soup and their Italian Grilled Avocado & Tomato salad. The soup had a nice, smooth mouthfeel and the salad was well dressed - flavorful, but not too much dressing. 

The servers were nice and attentive, but in my opinion, unnecessarily formal. I understand that they take pride in what they serve, but given the menu here, the formality seems inappropriate. 

I'll also note that they were out of both of the items I originally ordered - and not because it was a busy night. It was the middle of the week and empty, save me and a couple at one of the booths, so having to settle for second choices on two dishes was a bit disappointing. 

For me, the jury is still out on Spiritland Bistro, but since I can see it from my front door, I'm sure I'll spend some more time working through the menu.

column11:
This is like a Whole Foods or Sprouts farmer's market. For the most part, everything is au naturale and organic. They even have gluten-free beer!

The five stars is for their Aloha Poke Tuna in their seafood salad bar in their seafood section. It is so delicious and fresh! It definitely mimics Poke that I've had beach front. There is spicy and non-spicy and both are very good. The spicy is a bit too much for me to handle so I got half and half and mix it together for the perfect spiciness. It was so good that I went back for seconds before I left SB! It was too good to miss.

column11:
I stopped into Taffy's this weekend and has the good fortune of trying out the Tri-Tip sandwich. I was left speechless. Charles, the chef made me something that woke up my taste buds while blowing my mind. I've had Tri-Tip sandwiches before but his was a cut above. The layers of ingredients created a synergy of flavor that everyone needs to try at least once.

 First off, the buttered, toasted bun was spectacular. The cheese skirt gave the right amount of saltiness while fried Jalapenos delivered the correct amount of heat. What sealed the deal for me was how tender and not chewy the thinly cut tri tip was. The guacamole was fresh and the Cilantro Chimichurri didn't over power the other flavors.

If you pass by Taffy's you have to stop in and order this sandwich. You owe yourself the experience.

column11: I stopped at Savoy for lunch on my drive from LA to San Fran, and then spent the last 3 hours of my drive imagining a world where I could put this wonderful little deli in my pocket and keep it with me everywhere I go.  Totally normal response considering how killer my sandwich was.  I got the 9 Trails sandwich on gluten free bread, and FYI for my fellow Celiac-ers, the bread itself was awesome.  Not the dry cardboard stuff I'm sure we've all come across.  The fillings were just as good- turkey, homemade cranberry sauce, Dijon mustard, mayo, greens and cream cheese.  Yep, cream cheese.  Odd combination that makes for an absolutely delish sandwich!  My boyfriend built his own sandwich (on regular bread) with some turkey/bacon/avocado combo which he really enjoyed.  The serving sizes were really large, and there were plenty of gluten free and non-GF dessert options.  Definitely a winner!

column11:
Options aren't that plentiful on the wharf, but I'm glad I found this place!

BAJA FISH TACO- Yummy. Generous pieces of fresh fried fish (wow, that's a quite a mouthful, both figuratively and literally) and a huge slice of avocado. I didn't really care for the pickled onions, however. 

SHRIMP TACO- Okay. I liked the mango salsa, but the mango could have been more ripe. I also felt that the red and green peppers clashed with the rest of the ingredients. There was also too much sauce. 

SHRIMP ROLL- Good. I liked the tabasco mayo, as well as the simplicity of the sandwich (po' boy style). HUGE portion and came with a side of what I assume are homemade potato chips which were also good. 

Order at the counter and they'll bring your food to you. Seating is on the picnic tables outside which can get busy. Bring long sleeves-- it can be a little chilly with the breeze, even in the summer! 

The food is solid and I would not hesitate to come back if I'm in the area.

column11: The food is good but service is hit or miss and it's not worth the high prices.  We went there for brunch on a Sunday and got seated in one of the corner booths which was really nice!  But our waiter took forever to take our order (even though it wasn't crowded), was generally just not very friendly, plus he up-charged us for "garlic" fries that were basically normal fries with a sprig of thyme on top.  They lost a customer by trying to make an extra $2 on a crappy side dish.  Bummer!

column11:
I took one look at another Yelper's photo of charbroiled oysters, and added this place to my list.  I was not disappointed.

Actually, I wasn't sure we'd be able to fit Lure in during our short stay here in SB, but I needed to run an errand at Macy's (whachu know about Clinique Bonus Time?  I've been down since my mom shared her little yellow moisturizers with me in the 90s).

So, off I went to the mall, coworker in tow, and as we pulled around to the Macy's side of the shopping center, lo and behold!  It's right next to Lure.  God provides, y'all.

Those beautiful oysters are every bit as delicious as they are photogenic.  The happy hour price for 1/2 dozen is $11 (Sept 2019), and you can't eat just three.  So we got a second order.  I could have kept going, but I was also filling up on the bottle of wine we ordered, a perfectly grilled artichoke, and the BEST sourdough bread I've ever had.  Honestly, between those naughty oysters, the viognier, and the magic bread, I got dangerously close to tears of joy.

column11:
Going through a hit and miss phase, but still good. 

Frankly, I used to love this place. It was a 4-5 star yelp review, consistently in my book. In fact, I would have given it five stars today were it not for the past year of weird service and declining food quality.

I'm not sure what's going on but the food used to be pretty vibrant and fresh. It now often tastes bland or re-heated. It used to be amazing service. Prompt, friendly and accurate. Now, it's the definition of hit and miss with both the service and the food quality. 

For example, a recent visit saw being served cold burritos. And not the exaggerated cold, which some people say when it's really just not piping hot. I mean cold to the touch, as if it were made 10 minutes before we even sat down. 

They also messed up our orders twice on recent visits which meant we had to wait nearly an hour for our actual food. They apologized and they gave us some free drinks, so at least there was some kind of recognition of the problem. 

We also order takeout often from this location and they have been on a streak in terms of getting our order wrong despite reading it back perfectly at the time we place it. 

I'm willing to give this place the benefit of the doubt and I'm really hoping that they clean up their act. They have a captive audience in terms of locals traffic in Montecito wanting Mexican food. It just seems like either they are going through some growing pains or they have become lazy and a bit complacent.

This review is for my VEGETARIAN friends - the vegetarian ramen is super delicious. It is creamy and hearty. The broth is miso soup with veggies like mushrooms, bok choy, mushrooms, sprouts and bell paper. The veggies have a bite to it and I really like that. 
I also ordered their Kale Yakisoba. It was delicious too but it had a fish sauce kind of taste. So I wouldn't call it vegetarian at all. Or may be it was sea weed.. idk. The smell is just way too strong for me to overlook and that sort of put me off. 

This place is quite busy on the weekends. We had to wait for about 20 mins (group of 4) for a table. 

The service is quick and the place is clean.

column11:
Best Birthday Brunch Ever!!!!

I attempted to make reservations for my Birthday Brunch but I kept pushing back the time as I wasn't quite ready yet to leave the house. I called and spoke to the front desk and a woman assured me walk-ins were welcomed.

It's definitely easy to become lost when locating the restaurant. I passed multiple cottages, the spa quarters and an endless sea of green trees and golf courses before finally finding dining.

Once inside, a serviceman of the resort directed me to the front doors of the restaurant and I was greeted by a lovely young woman. I was given the option to either dine outside and take in the ocean view or dine indoors. I become chilly easy and she quickly recommended that I be placed inside near the window so that I could still view the ocean.

My seating table had pillows and comfy cushioning; It was reminiscent of breakfast in bed. 
I ordered the Lobster Panini, Parmesan French Fries and the Biltmore Raspberry Smash. The serving was prepared rather well and quickly. I was joined by small birds that entered from the patio and nibbled on small slices of bread from my table until shooed away by a passing server who offered to remove the bread ( I was done anyway)

The final cherry on my meal was the Happy Birthday swirled in chocolate syrup accompanied with white and dark chocolate dipped strawberries!
column13: Four Seasons Resort The Biltmore Santa Barbara

column11: We came for Fiestas last night and we will never be returning. I have been to this club many times before but last night was one for the books! We got to Tonic around 9pm and they wouldn't let my boyfriend in because... His shirt was too long!? We were told if they can't see your pockets you can't get in. He was wearing a nice button up shirt and you could see his pockets!! We offered politely to have it tucked in, the short bouncer refused. We offered to go buy a new shirt from Macy's, he refused. We offered to cut his shirt!!! He refused. I then asked to speak to a manager and guess what!! He refused. He stated "my manager doesn't have a ear piece and he's on the dance floor". We stood by the door as many other people got in and questioned this bouncer why several other men were allowed in who's shirt was not tucked in. And he just kept stating "oh, his shirt is fine". Sad to say we will not be returning to this club again.

column11:
Everything on the menu is so perfectly curated. The restaurant itself has a cafe kind of vibe, and the dishes offered are very homey. I'd describe it as modern comfort food with none of the frills that come from eating out. You can really tell that the owner put thought into every item that went on the menu.

Got the pesto zoodles with shrimp and it was delicious! It's rare for restaurants to even offer zoodles, so I have to admit I was already excited from the get-go. The zoodles were perfectly cooked and it was well balanced with olives and a generous amount of goat cheese. The shrimp was succulent too.

Also got a cup of the tomato bisque, which was light on the dairy/cream, just the way I like it. The waitress was sweet enough to let me sample it before I decided to order it!

This restaurant is located in the touristy area of Santa Barbara, but it wasn't too crowded when I went for a late dinner on a Saturday night. I'd recommend it for a meal if you're in the area!

column11:
I was very, very hesitant to come here because of all the bad reviews I've seen.  I came here on Saturday for lunch for their $9.95 all you can eat Brisket and I was pretty impressed.  The food quality is not as good as Ventura/Oxnard or even LA, so please don't base your reviews on areas with larger concentrations of Korean BBQ restaurants.  

For Santa Barbara, this was a pretty good place and my wife and I enjoyed it quite a bit.  The service was quite reasonable.  There were about 14 diners in the restaurant and one older lady taking care of food, drinks, condiments, etc...  She delivered our meat quite fast while the other items were slower than what you would expect but still reasonable.

I will certainly come back again to make sure it wasn't a fluke but so far, my first impressions were quite high and quite good for this establishment.

column11:
This place is similar to Chipotle. You can choose your sauce and toppings or choose one of their pizza combinations. We were so hungry, we just started choosing toppings without reading the prices! All in all, we spent $18! I would recommend getting their pizza combination which was around $11.

We had marinara and pesto sauce. Then added mushrooms, salami, spicy sausage (made in-house!), artichoke heart, roasted garlic (so yummy!!!!), olives, and jalapeno. It was really spicy but oh so delicious! Love the crust! Fresh ingredients, homemade sausage, and delicious pizza!

I wish I could return but this place is a 3 hour drive.... I hope one opens near Irvine!

column11:
First time here & I doubt I will come back. The service was good & we were greeted immediately. But, we did get there right at 11am when then opened. The food was average at best. The cilantro ranch dressing was awful! The chicken in the taco was supposed to be shredded, instead it was chunks. I will say that they are fairly generous with the cheese on top of the enchilada & the beans were runny. It was $31 for 2 meals & we didn't even get any alcohol. That's a bit pricy to me. 
If you're looking to just refuel, then I'd say go here. If you are looking for authentic Mexican food, this isn't the place!

column11:
Personally for my every day groceries, I prefer to shop at VONS! I have always liked the fresh produce and delicious, perfectly-cut deli meats. It's close to my work, so it's super convenient for me. I often come on my lunch break to grab a sammy from the deli counter. 
The employees here are always ready to help you with whatever you need, from fresh cut deli meat and cheese, to figuring out what aisle has what you need. I'm surely never running around like a chicken with its head cut off in this grocery store, because help is everywhere! 
Also, I've noticed that the last couple of times that I have been to this Vons location, they are stocked with the freshest and prettiest flowers. I can't help myself whenever I walk by them, I HAVE to purchase the cutest set I can find. 
Was never a fan of the grocery store that was here prior. Happy this Vons is here!

column11:
A hidden gem in SB Funk Zone!

Lafond is cozy, clean and sleek tasting room with indoor seating and a cute selection of wino merchandise including home decor and foodstuff.  Tastings are $12 for 5 pours, and I like that the servers are knowledgeable about the product and offer descriptions without being asked.  The atmosphere is intimate, quiet and low-key, which is in contrast to other rowdy neighboring establishments.  Members and guests of the Lafond/Santa Barbara wine club receive free tastings!  Woot!

I love that they offer breadsticks to clean the palate!  Extra star for that.

column11:
Freebirds' prices can seem very daunting but the portions are YUUUUUGE.  If you get their Monster Burrito it can easily last you two even three meals.  I can't quite particularly say I like Freebirds more than Chipotle but I can't say I like Chipotle more than Freebirds either.  It really says something when one of the biggest "Mexican" burrito joints that is known for top quality ingredients is playing on a level playing field.

The nachos are delish, although I'm not sure if it's worth the price.

Freebirds is open late for all those midnight adventures.

column11:
Everything about this place looked super promising but it just didn't come together quite well enough.

Could tell from the second that I walked in that something was a little odd but couldn't quite put my finger on it. The decor was nice, staff was well-dressed and  friendly, and it looked like your typical hipster cocktail spot (usually a pretty good sign).

Let's dig deeper:

The layout of the place was kind of strange, the lighting was odd, and the music didn't really fit the mood. The place seemed to be going for a cozy, intimate vibe but bright lights didn't really help anything.

Drinks were fine, not great, and things got weird when one of the bartenders started fussing at the others. We made it one and done and retreated back to our hotel room.

column11:
My husband decided to surprise me and our sweet 14month old to a weekend getaway. So when we drove up to this cute house with a nice garden you can imagine how thrilled I was. (Very short lived) We've been to B&B's before and had I not and had this been my first B&B experience, I would never go again.
 As soon as we get to the door and ring the bell this man comes out to "greet" us. But he immediately looks at us like we're strangers that are inconveniencing him to come to the door. No smile, no friendly hello, we get a yes. So my husband explains we have a reservation. So he says what room? My hubby says I don't remember, he asks for the last name and says i'll be back. Again, no courteous come on in and have a seat, I'll be right with you. Nothing. Just curt short responses. He left us at the door so I told my husband lets go in and sit. We wait about 5-10 min.
 He comes out and says "sorry I had to move your room, it's a bit of an upgrade. You see we're not really baby friendly here. our website has a no child policy, so if the owner sees you she could ask you to leave. So he insinuated he was doing us a favor. My husband explained he didn't see anything on the website that said no children.
So he walks us across the street to a completely different house to a small not cute room in the back, with only back door access as the inn keeper continues to what will be a restless attack on kids by saying couldn't find a babysitter? and I said, we planned this for the whole family. He looked surprised and said Oh. As if vacation is only for the childless. I Was so upset that after he left I started crying. I felt unwelcomed, and especially my little girl and above all like we were being shamed for bringing her, so they hide us in the furthest place they possibly could.
After composing myself we head over to tell him this was not the room we paid for. This is where he proceeds to be an even bigger jerk. He says "I can show you the room we had for you originally but i can't put you in there because of the kid." I said well what's the point. As oblivious as he was, he asks "what's the problem?" I explained that wasn't the room or house promised or reserved by my husband. So he says "yeah, but you have a kid, I can't put you up there there because kids are loud and we have other guests. Maybe your kid isn't bad, but as soon as people see kids they get upset. If the kid wasnt here we could put you up there. People come here to get away from there kids." 
I explained I felt like they were hiding us in the back. With no shame he said "well yeah cause of the kid." I wanted to yell in his face I get it WE HAVE A KID!!!!!!!!
He was rude, had no manners or tact. I have no idea why he is the innkeeper. I didn't want to continue to make a big deal since my husband planned this and he was trying to surprise our little fAmily on our first family trip. but had I planned this I would have asked for a refund and spoke to the manager immediately on hiring someone with more tact and friendliness. 
I felt discriminated in the worst way because I have a child. The innkeeper was inconsiderate at best and went out of his way to make my family getaway feel like an inconvenience to him and those around us. Yes I understand kids can be noisy, loud and obnoxious. Howerver, did it ever occur that you could convey the same message with a smile and some tact, especially when you're paying for an overpriced room with a big jacuzzi hot tub that has bricks under it holding it up, that you can see the outline of and feel them at the bottom of the tub. With a lumpy bed that you constantly slope into the middle of. No refreshments at this home, no you have to walk to the other home for service.
This home only gets one star because it's close to state street, the food was good, and the outdoor appearance of the first home is cute. 
I would love to speak to the owner and forward this to them and will do so.

column11:
We heard good things about Sun Sushi, but unfortunately we had a bad experience. The most disappointing was the sushi. Both such rolls (Box and Rainbow) has no flavor. The fish was too cold and very low grade sushi. 

We've been all over the world eating sushi and even lived in Asia (Japan for 2 years) for more than 6 years. This was some of the worst restaurant sushi we've experienced. When we got home we both had to eat something to get the taste out of our mouth. 

We're heading back to Arigato Sushi -- they are consistently great with sushi.

column11:
This is the 2nd time that I've just joined friends outside on the Terrace to look at the ocean (this time near sunset).  Food is good, drinks rock and the view is unparalleled.  Pure Mediterranean meets Mission luxury.  It was cold though.  I can' wait to actually stay at the hotel, but if you are in town it's definitely worth stopping by for a stroll, the view and some nibble and drinks.

TIP:  You can't actually see the sunset from there.  A couple of minutes drive  South to the Golf Course will give you a gorgeous sunset view though.  We were lucky to have it pretty much to ourselves.

column11:
I am new to the area and walked in here by accident. Wanted to use the restroom, but it is for customers only! *they are the only ones who has a bathroom unless you walk four blocks to the beach or somewhere along State St. 

However, walked in, noticed that there were only girls who worked there and there were also lots of old men? Ordered an iced vanilla latte and asked for an extra pump of vanilla and they didn't charge me (which is more than what I can say for other coffee shops). It tasted great! They have a lot of things on their menu and their ice blended drinks looked delicious. 

They also have a bigggg roaster which I thought was very cool. 

I also noticed that this coffee shop is huge! They have a separate area to buy beans and they literally have a HUGE variety of beans. It was confusing at first, but do not worry! The barista who worked at that counter definitely helped out in deciding what to get. They only sell 12-ounce bags, which is very unfortunate, because I went through it in a couple of days :/ But apparently, if you are local to the area, you can get a stampcard and after 9 purchases, get a tenth bag for free. And you get a cup of joe while you wait. They also grind your beans for no extra cost, so if you have coffee you need grinding, definitely go to them! 

I definitely am going back here, maybe to try their ice blended!

column11:
Olio is to Santa Barbara was Mozza is to LA.  There's an upscale / fine dining side and then a side that specializes in pizza, which is a lot more low key (but still not completely casual). The pizzeria was perfect for the group of 9 of us that wanted a nice dinner out, but didn't want to be somewhere too stuffy where we wouldn't be able to talk.

The drink list is HUGE.. they have a lot of specialty cocktails and beer, on top of an extensive wine list. I had a hard time deciding what to get, and ended up with the Italian mojito.. which was more carbonated and less sweet than a typical mojito.

The garlic toast wasn't too great and a bit disappointing.  It was like small pieces of stale-ish bread with some butter on top.  Definitely my least favorite thing. 

Everything else, however was delicious.

SALADS
Di Bietole - Beet Salad
Di Carciofi - Artichoke Salad
Rughetta e Scaglie di Parmiggiono - Arugula Salad

PIZZA
UMBRA - my favorite - Mushrooms and Black Truffles
Parma - Prosciutto and argula
Carbonara - pretty heavy - delish but a bit heavy for me

DESSERT
pesche allo zenzero - caramelized roasted peaches.  Amazing.

Super delicious and if I lived in Santa Barbara it would definitely be a go to spot for me.

column11:
Still great after all these years.

We stopped by on a Thursday night to see if they had an outdoor table for us and our dog. After a quick check to make sure it didn't interfere with any reservations, we got seated right away at a table on the sidewalk and our dog laid on the ground and got lots of attention from the employees.

Because of Covid, they also built a little outdoor parklet, which I hope they are able to continue using because it is a really great addition to their set up. It was also really well constructed and you could tell they put a lot of effort into building it, with the paint job, the cute lighting and shade sails, etc.

Additionally, their website is updated everyday with not only their specials, but updates about the restaurant itself and how they're running it. Today's update was to mention that their staff will continue to wear masks for another month just in case there's any unexpected consequences of re-opening. It's nice to see how much effort they're putting in to keeping everyone safe and informed.

Onto the food and drinks.
I got a passion fruit martini and my husband got an old fashioned. Both were delicious.

They still offer a bread basket which was great and the butter was nice and soft.

We got the salmon tacos for an appetizer - it was really good.

My husband got the pasilla crusted steak and loved it. I've had it before and it is really delicious.

I was really in the mood for seafood, so I got the lemongrass crusted salmon and it was phenomenal. The salmon was HUGE and the curry sauce it came with was really, really good. It also came with rice and julienned vegetables which were light and refreshing.

Forgot to take photos of the food this time, but next time we are in Santa Barbara, we will come back like we always do and enjoy a delicious meal.

column11:
Short Rib and Sweet Potato Hash Breakfast!!

We were returning back from the bay area and the little one found this place on Yelp. The restaurant itself sits inside a hotel. It was early and no wait whatsoever. We parked out front on the street and were eating within fifteen minutes.

~Short Rib and Sweet Potato Hash- 4 Stars!
The meat was super tender and juicy. The sweet potato hash, while very tasty, was dry. It was a little too dry. The dish will run you close to $20. Would I order this again? Maybe. The menu has several items I wanted to try.

~Kids Menu
The little one had French toast..of course! She liked it but it looked average to me.

~Servicer- 5 Stars!
Fast, Courteous, and Attentive! I had not a single problem with service!

~Parking-I actually am unsure where to park. However, it was early enough that there was free street parking right in front of the hotel. The restaurant is easily accessible from the street or from the inside of the hotel. Easy access on and off the 101 also.

Overall, I am a fan!

column11:
Best market in the area!! 

I'm so so so glad my parents helped me find this place when moving in to UCSB last year because now this is my comfort store. Recently, I had a stomach bug and couldn't eat anything until I realized I had a sudden craving for Korean food. There are so many staples here that I keep coming back for and the food is as authentic as it can get (at least in this area). 

There's a shocking lack of good Korean and Asian food around this area, but Choi's is one place I will always keep coming back to when I need good ingredients or good food.

column11:
Very worth it!

It's kind of hard to find. Don't expect a huge storefront or sign because it's basically a take out window that's next to a bar. There is a banner so look out for that and some outdoor seating.

I was shocked at how good the mac n cheese was by itself. I admit I was concerned this place would've been mostly hype and for the fun looking photos but I was proven wrong! It was delicious. Mayb not the freshest hot cheeto crumbles but it was still a great topping! For St. Pattys day, they were also adding in crumbled avocado chips. 

We also ordered their smores waffle. There was a lot of nutella which I was really happy with!! The lady also handed it to me just like a burrito/taco and I thought that was surprising and funny that it was just handled in that way. Very tidy, not messy, and marshmallows definite hit with a blow torch a bit. The girl who was working that night was great and gave great customer service.

I'll be back again to try something else for sure!

Ridiculous.

column11:
Great view but that's where it ends.

Patio seating on the edge of the surf can't be beat but the very limited selection let me wanting more. 
Scrambled eggs
Bacon & Sausage
Waffles
Breads
Omelet bar
Smoked salmon
And that's about it.

With most people self serving form the buffet, the wait staff has little to do. I guess they were too busy to come by and check on drinks. We had one round of mimosa and never offered a second round. The next time we saw our guy, we asked for the bill. 

Sure this could be a romantic evening or family filled Sunday brunch and if the service was better, I could justify the cost. The Bistro is just too much for too little.

column11:
WORST FOOD!!!

Seriously, this is the worst meal I've ever eaten.  I ate here 10 years ago and didn't care for it.  For some reason I was tempted to give it a try again, given the high YELP ratings and that I was craving a chili burger.  Here's my review:

The burger was soft and disintegrated after two bites.  I started picking up pieces to eat with my fingers, which was a blessing because this allowed me to discover that the meat was this grey and grisly slab that had zero taste.  The chili-cheese fries didn't come with chili or cheese.  Rather, there was a separate paper boat with a lump of terribly tasting chili with a slice of cheese on top.  Because the cheese was on top, it hardly melted and was basically solid.  In the end, I had a few bites of each item and ended up throwing away the entire $11 meal in disgust.  

I will never eat at this place again.  As a note, be aware that any food ratings in Goleta are affected to by two things.  One, UCSB undergrad ratings contribute a lot and, sorry to make offense, but these kids don't know much about good food.  I was an undergrad and I know that when I was young I ate and drank a lot of things I thought were great, but now I know the difference.  Second, Santa Barbara is lacking in a lot of good food.  When someone writes that they had the best Vietnamese food in SB, they are probably right.  But there are only two Vietnamese restaurants in the city.  So the "best" is not really a good indication if the food is actually good.  Keep these things in mind when reading reviews for Goleta/SB.

column11:
Came a second time and this time I got a single scoop again. I got the Eureka Lemon & Marionberries, but this time, I "peared" it with their seasonal pear ice cream. I like their fruit infused ice creams. I've always been partial to ice cream that has fruits and I don't think they do a bad job with it. The Eureka lemon and marionberries' lemon zesty taste is the same and has a nice zing to it. Anyways, tried a few samples and the service was similar to last time. Very happy to let you try and not in a particular rush for you to pick. They are generous as it can be for an establishment like this. Aside from that, I chose the pear flavor, because it definitely tasted like a barlett pear, while having real chunks of frozen pear in it. I like that combination in ice cream and there weren't just tiny chunks, but sizeable and noticeable chunks in it that you can bite into.
 
Worth a try if you are near Stearn's wharf or go to their main location on State's street, which I will try to go to in the future now that I've visited this branch twice already. Can't wait to try out other seasonal flavors! Hope it's more fruits.

I was blown away by the food, staff and ambiance. Vegan or not this restaurant is a must! I'm a very picky foodie from LA and if your'e driving on the 101 and passing through Montecito, do yourself a favor and take the time to try Olivers, the food and presentation is amazing in a beautiful outdoor setting.

column11:
Sad that we didn't have the chance to review the food, cause the owner was terrible. 

They check your temperature when you come in, which is perfectly reasonable and something we appreciate! My mom made an off hand joke about why it's necessary since we're all vaccinated (maybe a little ill placed, but certainly in good humor), but nothing more was said, we got our temperatures checked, and we sat down to order. 5-10 minutes later, the owner comes out of the kitchen, and scolds my mom across the entire restaurant about how if the restaurant says we have to check temperature, we have to. "Scold" as in a very demanding, harsh, and loud tone. Which makes no sense, because my mom never said no to the temperature check! We're from the Bay Area mind you, where temperature checks + vaccine checks are everywhere. 

My parents keep asking what they did wrong, the owner keeps on saying we have to follow their command (which again, we did). I then try to step in, which the owner responds to by saying that he wasn't talking to me! The same person that was yelling at my parents said I couldn't speak up lol. Then he told us to leave, which we gladly did at that point. 

Terrible.

Edit: the owner claims I'm lying; would love if he could say exactly what I lied about!

column11: Okay, if you don't go to Book Ends Cafe for one their amazing sandwiches and/or salads, then you are missing out.  The space is great, the people are warm and engaging, and the food....I had 1/2 sandwich/salad combo.  Brisket Banh Mi sandwich -- tender, juicy meat with pickled carrots and radish, cilantro, and jalapeno vinaigrette. So happy with that choice!  The salad was a kale and tabouleh mixture that was light and wonderful.  All the meat is sustainably raised, the vegetables are farmers market fare, the pickling is done by the cooks.  The pickles on the side were awesome!  When I complimented the owner on his pickles, he brought me more on the house.  Do yourself a favor and take a midday vacation to Book Ends!  You will not be sorry.

column11: I'm writing this for my boyfriend.  He would give it five stars  He Loves This Place!!  Orders as follows:  #16, 14,19. Sopes (if available), Tacos de bistec.  Usually the same thing.  I'm pretty sure the #19 is the frijoles.  Not your usual refried beans.  This is how we make beans at home.  I don't eat tortillas, so, pretty pointless for me here. (My bf gets all my tortillas.)  But, the #16 is my favorite too.  Also the  roasted chiles pasillas stuffed with cheese.  The chile rellenos are very good too.  The owner has let us try a couple of new dishes to give him feedback.  Good stuff.  Not your usual Mexican food.  If you want the usual go to Del Pueblo or Rose Cafe (yuck) one of those type of places.   Yes the wait is long.  I usually end up talking  to the out of towners, see a lot of the regulars and lots of friends.  One thing I don't like is the table snatchers.  These are the people who send in friends or family to snatch a table way before they are up to order.  That's not cool.  Wait your turn like the rest of us.  Usually works out though.

column11:
Been in Carpinteria for few weeks. Always drive past. But didn't stop. I stopped , I got the best dam cheese burger I've had in town. This is a must stop , I will defiantly go back, it's my new goto place in carpinteria if Im in mood for a cheese burger , if the rest of menu 1/2 as good as the burger , you can't miss. Friendly staff , great prices. 
I'd pay 15 bucks for the burger they gave me. And only 4.95. And if you're heading north , it's worth getting off freeway.

column11:
Without a doubt one of our favorite restaurants in SB.  I love the Baba Ghanoujj, which you can get as a separate appetizer or with the Veggie delight plate (which has a great selection of the Baba, hummus [which is good but isn't the best hummus i've ever had], grape leaves etc.)..  

Most important, they've got the garlic sauce.  It doesn't come with every dish, and it isn't quite as good as Zankou's in LA, but it's close.  We usually get it with the Shwarma, which also is very good, and ask for an extra side of the garlic sauce.  My only complaint would be that in the last few months it seems like the garlic sauce has been toned down a bit, and isn't quite as potent as it used to be.  It's still great though; be prepared to stink if you eat it.   

We've never smoked the hookah here, but it looks like a great spot to do so.

It isn't super kid-friendly, but I wouldn't say it is kid unfriendly either.  we've taken our 2-year old daughter here many times without incident.  Take out also works very well.

column11:
I am obsessed with breakfast bagel sandwiches. This spot does not disappoint. Is it filled with college kids in the middle of IV? Yes. Should that steer you away from picking up an amazing bagel sandwich? Heck no! 

I had a egg, sausage, and pepper jack bagel on herb cheese with cream cheese addition. Amazing. I need to go back and see if they can put an over-medium fried egg in there next...because that would be a game changer. Thick, fluffy, and soft bagels. Tender and juicy eggs and sausage. 5 stars!!

column11:
If you're inside, and its not crazy packed, Tonic is a solid 5 star bar.  However, the line is too long too often, and sometimes it can get just too crowded.  The vibe is more "LA" than most bars in SB, usually you won't get in with shorts or sandals.  But it's still a solid bar with a nice outdoor area.

The best thing Tonic has to offer is Sunday sessions.  On a sunny Sunday afternoon, you can't ask for much more than a cabana at Tonic, with some pitchers of watermelon mojito..... except maybe help from your buddies when you happen to run up a four digit bar tab....

column11:
I absolutely love this place!! It's a small joint with tons of chairs! You can sit inside or outside. 

I usually come here for:
Breakfast 
Lunch (if i'm trying to fast) 
A guilty pleasure dinner 

I always get the Berry Bowl because it's just a great mix of everything berries! It's not too sweet and not too sour, a perfect combination of an acai bowl. If you prefer a sweeter bowl you can request for more honey!

I would recommend getting a small if you're sharing between 2 people (and if you don't eat as much as me - it's a huge bowl)! I would order a kids size if I was eating by myself. 

Parking is easy to find. The only issue I have with the bowl is finding out how to mix the bowl evenly! Starting off you're eating the fruits on the top, next time i'll have to request another cup to be able to mix the bowl in more.

Only issue is that requesting extra rice or beans costs an extra $3, which is pretty ridiculous.  But I'll keep the 5-star review, seeing as they have a massive unlimited salsa bar of some of the best salsas you will ever taste.  Prices are very reasonable as well, with most non-special meals being under $12 (including chips and the salsa bar).  100% recommend.

column11:
Chirashi don, $13 for lunch!

The dish is fast to serve up, filling, well-priced and no complaints about the chef's choice of fish.

It's simply a bowl of sushi rice, topped with an assortment of sashimi. My fish were very ample cuts, too big sometimes and I had to cut them in half. Two slices each of four fish (salmon, maguro, yellowtail and some other white fish), two shrimp and some avocado and krab salad. Effectively 10 very large nigiri, once you doled out the rice amongst the toppings. 

It also comes with some miso soup.

The fish assortment is perfect for a typical sushi eater, nothing crazy and obscure. And for being "scattered sushi" it was nicely presented in a pretty bowl. I uploaded a photo.

Very pleased with this.

column11:
Restaurant is set up nicely outside due to social distancing. The menu is an eclectic mix of contemporary fare. We had.a nice table but after our meal was served, we didn't see our server until we were done. No dessert menu or coffee was ever offered. 

The crab cake while having decent crab flavor is missing any sort of lump meat that would make it shine and worth the $17 for the one.

The lemongrass salmon was the highlight of the meal. Cooked nicely with a balance of lemon and curry playing in harmony with the salmon.

The honey glazed duck over risotto wasn't as successful. Although the duck was cooked nicely, the honey sauce would benefit from some balancing as it was overpoweringly sweet. Also the risotto was overcooked to the point that it was mush. 

We really wanted to like this place more but it is not a place we will be likely to return to.

column11:
Yikes. After 2 very bizarre and confused phone calls with them my husband and I were seriously considering bailing and not picking up our called-in order. 
We chose this place based on it having a 2for1 on the Access card but we had never seen/noticed the place before. If we had seen it in person prior to calling in we wouldnt have eaten here, primarily because it is clearly an Asian style establishment serving American style dishes (see posters for Korean ice cream).....not that there's anything wrong with that but personally I wouldnt go to a Thai restaurant and order eggs Benedict. 

We had ordered reubens. 1st impression: they were very small and thin. I miserably ate half and it was terrible, my immediate thought was that it seemed to be made by someone who had never even had a reuben before (this was before i noticed the ice cream posters). The cheese was not normal cheese for a reuben AND tasted bad (it was some kind that had been melted down with milk giving it a semi liquid form). And there was virtually no sauerkraut (find it in the photo if you can). When i spotted the tiny bit of kraut i tasted it and it was awful and not a normal kraut flavor. Needless to say i didnt finish the other half of my sandwich.

column11:
One of my worst dining experiences in recent years, so this review merits a re-post. Buyer beware.

* *

HORRID ENTREE ALERT!!!!

Only reason did not make a stink about last night's nearly inedible Sea Bass - dinner was a special occasion with my 87 year old Mom. This is her favorite restaurant and keeping the vibe fun was the goal.

Shame on you Petit Valentien for putting on our plate (wife I and I shared...) that dried out, nearly shoe-leather slab of fish. Looked more like sole? But mostly looked like the institutional food I used to feed the old folks at the home I worked at as a teen.

Since I tend to email these reviews to management, here's more. Ordered just one Sea Bass to share. Waitress brought out 2 and gave them to us. A minute later, realized her mistake, and took one back. Nice waitress, but that is tacky. Your mistake- just leave it.

It's not easy to keep quality standards high but that Saturday 6PM kitchen needs a talking to. Pay attention to what you put on the plate.

column11:
I went to this restaurant with my mother and sister-in-law. I fell in love with this place right when I walked in. It was like eating in someone's personal home and the lights were dimmed ever so slightly for ambiance.
We were seated in a matter of minutes. The place was pretty full, but not overwhelming and was pretty easy to maneuver through. Once seated we got our drink orders right away. I love how all the meals came with the same elements (side, entree, dessert, etc.) you just chose the size you wanted. I ordered the Filet Mignon with a side of rice. The meat was cooked just the way I ordered it and was absolutely delicious (and filling).
The dessert was a slice of homemade pie of your choosing. I was expecting to choose from a selection of three or four different pies, but there were more like 12 different ones. I had a difficult time choosing but eventually went with the peach. They give you the option of having your pie plain or a la mode (I went with the ice cream).
The staff was very friendly and was fun to talk to. I would definitely come back and bring more family and friends with me.

column11:
A-MAZING!

I give credit to The French Press for being the start of my "coffee-snobiness" that has developed over the past year. Being from Orange County, unique coffee shops like this one are much harder to come by. Loving to press my coffee at home, The French Press was the first coffee shop I ever encountered to specialize in this method! 

So, I obviously had to try a mug of their French Pressed Coffee. Not only was is smooth, full-bodied, and delicious, but it introduced me Verve Coffee Roasters from Santa Cruz. 

Oh! and let's not forget about the Shakerato on their menu! I feel in love with this drink in Italy and The French Press is the only place I've seen it in the States. Shakerato is a slightly sweetened iced coffee, where it is blended with the sugar in a martini shaker and shaken until the sugar dissolves and then poured over ice, leaving a nice generous layer of foam on top. It's a fun version of an iced coffee...I think it has to do with the martini shaker! ; ) mmmmm

On my next visit, I tired the Chai Latte, with an overwhelming aroma of cardamom and nutmeg spice will fill your senses from the table. Fellow Chai lovers, you'll like this one!

column11:
Take this review with a grain of: Lifelong vegetarian with loose convictions comes to restaurant and shares a plate of lamb shawarma with carnivorous mealmate.

This place is beautiful! A lovely surprise off of State St., emanating light down Canon Perdido if you happen to go there at night (go there at night!) This place is definitely romantic, with hundreds of fairy lights, slightly sensual lebanese/mediterranean music, and unintentionally erotic firepits at each table. You can also get hookah here, many people seemed to be having a grand time making eyes at eachother through smoke clouds. A sexy destination indeed.

The food was yummy, reference my note at the beginning. The falafel appetizer we ordered was delicious and served with tangy tahini sauce, and had the consistency of hush puppies. The hot water I ordered to treat my incoming cold was delightfully watery, and served in mugs one might find at Ikea, or one's kitchen. The lamb shawarma was well balanced, served with a fattoush salad (fun to say, fun to eat), golden & satisfying steak fries, and digestible little pieces of lamb that carniverous dining partner said were "cooked really well" and "solid".

the DESSERT. YUM.
Get the chocolate cake! ignore the fancy but beautiful desserts and get the chocolate cake.
It was basically a lava cake, topped with vanilla bean ice cream and Nutella drizzles. I lapped it up. 

Both dining partner and I were really hungry, but the falafel, sides of pita bread, lamb shawarma and dessert managed to fill both of us up for $25 each. Maybe a different experience for two people who are both really into meat. 

Sweet staff, speedy service. Wasn't particularly exciting food tastewise, but they do what they do well. Could be a five star place if they had a few more novel dishes, maybe that's just not what they're about.

column11:
There is something special about going to a restaurant when the owner is charge. 
You feel taken care of and you never doubt or question the integrity of the food or the service. This is after all their investment, their livelihood on the line. 

Ive been here several times and overall I love the owner's service and I love their food. I wish the owner the best of luck in making it, here in IV, the area is saturated with restaurants and its very competitive. 

Im not sure how long the owner will be running the show, but for now, I think this is the best time to go eat at Sorriso's. 

Make sure to get the Nutella dessert, it is just amazing!

column11:
Von's Chicken is on the pricey side, but their chicken is certainly flavorful that is delicious to have alongside a big bowl of rice! Personally love the Yangnyeom seasoning, which is very well flavored, a perfect mix of sweet, spicy, and savory! 

The half size is enough for me to split into 2 meals, and the full size into many more meals... however, I would recommend consuming in moderation since eating a lot results in an uncomfortable aftertaste and feeling...

Lastly, want to shoutout their coleslaw and pickled radish. While they serve these as sides, these provide some much needed acidity and creaminess (and it tastes great!) to balance out the meal since the chicken is quite heavy! 
 
Overall, one of the better places in IV, though its on the pricey side.

column11: Went there with a group from LA that came up on the Santa Barbara Daylight Vino Train.  I've had the Salmon with a dijon fennel sauce in the past and that's fantastic.  Today I had the the sea bass and it was great.  The clam chowder was a touch salty.  The big problem was the service.  Our drink orders were taken right away but it took forever to get our food order taken.  In the meantime, two of our group not only ordered their food but got it delivered and had dessert!  The wait for our order took a bit too long as well.  When we did get our order is was quite tasty.  When I got the bill for my portion I was charged for the chowder which should have been one of my sides that was included with the meal.  I will say our server was quite nice but I think she was a bit overwhelmed with our large group and her other customers.
