column11:
My husband and I walked by this wine tasting room while celebrating our anniversary in Santa Barbara. Being born in August, I was biased and wanted to check it out. We had low expectations because we've done many wine tastings now and finally became wine members at a couple wineries. We weren't planning on becoming members of yet another wine club, but since we LOVE red wines and that seems to be their specialty, we signed up for another wine club!  Hope and Elise were great and let us try more wines than were on the menu and soon my husband and I found ourselves buying 6 bottles. The wine club is great though because you only need a minimum of two shipments a year and you can pick how many bottles you want.

The other couples visiting the wine tasting room were lovely and so were their dogs!!!! This place is dog-friendly so be sure to bring your pups!

column11:
Such a fun place!! Came here with my boyfriend one evening after dinner and I was sold because there was a sign saying "Frose Fridays" AND you can play board games while you enjoy your drink-totally me! 

PARKING: I came here after 7pm and luckily found street parking for free. Otherwise there are structures nearby that are free for first 75 minutes.

Love how they are so dog friendly, as they offer dog treats for purchase ($2) and raised dog beds for smaller dogs and other dog beds for bigger ones. They have both an inside and backdoor patio (with some heaters). I found some seats inside because it was cold out. You self-seat yourselves and seats are first come first serve and you order at the bar (signs all around to remind you). Their menu is on the simple side. I wish there were more options, but then again it wouldn't help my indecisiveness haha. 

FROSE: $9 They offer 3 flavors that are pre-made in a slushie machine.
-WHITE PEACH: I loved this and ended up ordering this! Would get this again!
-BLUEBERRY BASIL: Not so much a fan. I feel like you either love it or hate it. The basil is a little too strong for my liking. 

CABERNET (THE FABLEIST): This was one of the two cabs they had available. Loved this and would get again!


GAMES: Lots of games, which are first come first serve! Be respectful and replace the game in its entirety after using. Also don't hoard the games! During my time there, I played bananagrams and scrabble with my boyfriend and had a blast (also because I won both games :D haha)! Some of the games include more than 2 players, which is fun because maybe you can meet others seated around you to play a game! Plenty of games available. 

Excited to come back again whenever I visit in the future! (:

column11:
I'm giving the restaurant a 3.5 & the lounge a 4. I actually did not eat in the restaurant. I was staying at the Best Western adjacent to the restaurant & they do the room service for them. On day one we ordered room service for breakfast. It was your standard scrambled eggs, bacon, toast & fruit. I had no complaints with breakfast, but my wife didn't like the scrambled eggs. Bacon, well, it's hard to mess that up and the fruit & toast were fine. 

The following night I went into the restaurant and ordered a Cobb salad, burger & fries to go. Again, not difficult to prepare and even more difficult to screw up. My wife & I were both pleased with our meals. Their service was fantastic. The manager and waitstaff was very friendly. 

I visited the lounge a few times over the weekend for a quick drink with my family members, since we were in Santa Barbara for a wedding. The drinks were good and the bar tenders were great. I don't remember the woman bar tender's name, but she stayed after the restaurant staff had gone home, so we could keep enjoying our cocktails and spending some QT with family members. My family's spread all across the country & we don't see each other that often, so it was really appreciated that she did this.

column11:
I was craving a eggs Benedict so I searched and it brought me to State & Fig. My girlfriend ordered a burger and we both shared each. The service was top notch! Everyone in the entire place did such a great job that I felt very welcomed and comfortable. 

The food used good ingredients and tasted fresh. They gave us the wrong burger though because it came with bacon and we ordered a basic one. Interesting combo to use a sweet fig sauce on the burger which wasn't the one we ordered. I doubt they make mistakes like this often though because they really do seem to care.

I am glad I came here and am also glad they stayed open until 3pm. For whatever reason so many similar restaurants in that area closed at 2pm.

column11:
I've lived here how many years without trying this place??!! I'm not sure how I did it & I don't want you to have to go through that so let me tell you why you've got to eat here today, right now..

Skip the lines! This sandwich joint has Yelp 24 set up where you can quickly assemble your order, pay online, & pick up quickly after. 

They have actual veggie filled veggie sandwiches! So often I come across a "veggie" burger or sandwich that has lettuce, cheese, bun.. Basically because it lacks meaty goodness it's considered "veggie." Oh no, not here! My super veggie sandwich had flavorfully marinated mushrooms, cucumbers, peppers, pickles, tomatoes, & more! Plus you can customize what veggies you want on off or added; it's never ending veggie madness! 

And finally, they have M&M cookies! 
Best way to finish a darn good meal is to sweeten your palette with an American favorite, the M&M cookie! 

(Just a tip- Even if you do use the splendid Yelp24 take out service.. don't get as excited as I do and eat in the car. These sandwiches are carefully constructed and need full 1 on 1 attention, otherwise your lap will be getting full attention.)

column11:
This was my first visit to the Summerland Beach Cafe, and it certainly won't be the last.

We arrived on New Years Day, the sun was shining and the view of the Ocean was crystal clear, making this a hot spot for tourists and locals alike, there was most definitely a wait time. 

Putting our name in they gave us an electronic pager and advised us it would be about a 25 minute wait,  they only have two small benches for people waiting that should be taken in account for anyone that suffers from leg pain or injuries.

This is also a dog friendly restaurant, you just never know what breed of canine you will see and if you are an animal lover this is a plus, if you aren't an animal lover then be warned that your not going to just see one or two dogs, there are many.

We were lucky enough to be seated on the porch, our waitress was about the sweetest lady ever, she had our ice teas to us in record time and when we decided to get mimosa's she was back in a flash.

The menu is massive, I decided on getting breakfast and ordered the Engine#2 Omelet which consisted of Jack Cheese and Ortega Chile's with a side of sour cream, and also consisted of home potatoes, a slice of cantaloupe, and and English muffins which was well buttered.

Now I've had many omelettes in my time, but that was without a doubt the fluffiest omelet I've ever had, and the flavor of the Chile's was amazing, I had worried after I ordered that it might be to bland, boy was I proven wrong, that was delicious and I wouldn't hesitate to order it again.  The potatoes were cooked to perfection and the as I said previously the English Muffin was buttered perfectly.

My plate was clean as a whistle when the waitress came back... that should say something about how good it was, and then she was sweet enough to get us to go cups for our ice teas.

A great way to start the day, good food, a beautiful view, and great conversation.

Don't forget to stop in today, and if you have a large party call ahead and make reservations this could save you some time.

column11:
Great Margarita's Good Atmosphere. 

Came here on a Sunday afternoon.  The restaurant is on a quiet block two blocks East of State Street.  It's right next to an historic adobe, so you get that real Spanish Colonial vibe. 

Sat out on the patio. Ordered margaritas and the carne asada with cheese enchilada. Order came out quickly and was tasty.  

Margarita's definitely had a kick.  I could only have one and a half! 

Overall good place for Mexican food in Downtown.

column11:
I was told presto pasta was a good place to go for cheap Italian and that was right it was cheap but not good. It wasn't the best place I have ever been too but it wasn't the worse. We ordered the chicken piccata, fettuccine alfredo, fried artichoke, and meatballs for to go. We didn't have too long to wait for our food it actually came out really quick. It wasn't that hot which was unfortunate because when we got home it was already kind of cold. 

The fried artichoke was not good at all. It was soggy and not crispy at all. The sauce that came with the artichoke was really good but the artichoke wasn't at all. 

The chicken piccata was good but not very warm. There wasn't much sauce on it either. 

The meatballs were really good and had alot of sauce. I think they were the best things we got. 

The fettuccine alfredo was not good at all. It was all clumping together and the sauce was not good at all. 

Overall I probably will not go here again or if I end up going there I will not get it to go.

column11: I have memories of In-N-Out being the best thing ever, but you know what?  After living on the East Coast for the last 15 years, I think I actually prefer 5 Guys now.  I like 5 Guys fries better, and I think their burgers are meatier.  My In-N-Out burger was pretty small and flat and dry, the tomato was mealy and tasteless (so I pulled it off), the onion was good, but it was overpowering (so I pulled half of the rings off), and the fries were fine, but not killer.   I really did like the grill-fried bun, that was a nice touch.  The rest of it... meh.

column11:
I'm fat and white and my wife is smoking hot Laotian not that it matters because this is a food review. Anyway, the point is we know Pho, we make it at home with my wife's mom and grandma's recipe.  We're not from Santa Barbara so not to bag on your city but the reviews for this place are not accurate.  I don't know what your experiences are but this is D- at best. The flavor is bland, the egg rolls and spring rolls taste are not authentic.  We've been all over the country having eaten Vietnamese, Thai, Chinese, Japanese, Korean, you know "asian food" like Miss Whitney K stated. But this place is not all that yo!!  Oh, and I'm not that fat really.....  

ps the lady was nice but her help was all thumbs dropping dishes at every table. Also the prices were twice as much anywhere else....

Come on Santa Barbara get out more or I'm going to move here and open a delicious spot to cash in =)

column11: Hands down the best bakery in Santa Barbara, everything is made fresh each and every morning and everyone working there are the most friendly and welcoming people ever. They offer fresh bread, sandwiches, breakfast burritos, and soups daily. They honestly make THE best sandwiches, and all your requests will be fulfilled. Want extra onions? not a problem. anything you want done to your sandy, just ask. There's plenty of parking, so you never have to worry about meters or anything. A couple of chairs and tables are outside so you can enjoy your breakfast and lunch outdoors. Definitely a go to place if you want good food fast.

column11:
This place is AMAZING.
The ambiance is so relaxing and refreshing.
From the greeting staff to the servers, SMILES all around.
The food was so great. The hardest thing is choosing what to order because they have such an approachable menu with amazing options.

You won't be disappointed.
I can't wait to go back!

column11:
Two words: Go vegan

Try this place and go vegan for a meal! I was a vegan for 10 months during my third year at UCSB. I remember going out to eat at vegan restaurants and I found most places to be overpriced and lacking flavor. It gave vegans a bad name!

We ordered the mushroom tacos, falafels, and risotto. I would recommend just sharing dishes to try out the items. My favorite was the risotto which had a rich flavor and spiced chirozo! The mushroom taco is simple, yet hearty. They are seasoned to perfection and had the right amount of spices.

I really wanted to order dessert, but I was so stuffed. Next time, I will have to try their baklava. I heard that it comes with a pomegranate molasses sauce. 

After my dining experience at Mesa, I may try to go on a vegan diet again! As long as their chef cooks for me... :D

column11:
I got to try this thanks to a Groupon (2 for $20) and it was so worth! First of all, you can add the chocolate pairing (additional $10) which I highly recommend! We got to try 6 different wines, staring with 3 whites, and ending in 3 reds. The whites were naturally paired with the white chocolates, and the red were paired with the darker chocolates. Whoever designed the chocolate pairings should get a raise! The wines by themselves are great, but the chocolates definitely elevated the taste! Our server forgot our waters, so he ended up not charging us for it. Great service, great wine. 

The location is also perfect, as it is downtown and there's a nice breeze, and we were physically distant from other parties by at least 6 feet. 10/10 would definitely come back here!

column11: My go-to brunch spot every other weekend. It's a huge plus that it's at the beginning of State street since you're not around many noisy restaurants and the only people around you are the ones eating there. Definitely recommend the Chorizo Hash special. They have some of the best chorizo in all of SB. The Kale and quinoa salad is also a must if you enjoy a good salad. Great flavor and the produce is fresh and clean. Coen at the front taking orders is always very energetic and explains everything each dish has to offer. Kevin was a great server and always brought a refill of water when needed. Thank you Dawn Patrol! You guys are a staple whenever I'm downtown out and about.

column11:
I find it so strange I've never reviewed Kalyra, despite having been going here for over 5 years (before we realized it was the winery in the movie Sideways! that clicked years later!!!) AND being a wine thieve (their term for wine club members).  This was also stop #3 on our wine tasting tour in August; obviously, I try to go here at least a couple of times a year and typically go quarterly for the wine shipment ... unless we find difficulty making the day trip or weekend of it.  (That is rare b/c we love going to S.B.)

Anyway, we love:
+the vibe of the tasting room w/its tiki theme (different from the tasting room at the vineyard)
+their reds
+their desert wines
+the MC2
+the customer service (props to Trevor in the tasting room, Evie with wine thieves, and really all of the staff... I just only remember their names right now)
+the winery itself (separate review, if I haven't already gotten to it)
+the price of tastings (in the rare event we have to pay because we bring more than 4 of us)

Bottom Line - My hubby and I are wine thieves because we love Kalyra!  Check it out if you haven't already been!!! Yes, it gets crowded, but it is super fun!

Tip - Make a reservation if you have a larger group... It's a small tasting room, so check in w/them on the size you're bringing in.

column11: Tried to come in for a quick bite and cocktails tonight, but the tables were all being held for reservations so the hostess said we could eat at the bar. After being ignored by the bartender (blonde younger guy)  for 20 minutes, he finally acknowledged us to ask for ID. I told him my boyfriend was drinking but I was driving so I wasn't drinking, and left my ID in the car, and he kicked us out. Now I'm a bartender in Montecito, and I know for a fact people of all ages can eat at the bar of a restaurant. Not sure if this is the restaurant's specific policy, or the bartender just made it up because he doesn't want people eating at the bar, But the hostess definitely should not have told us we were welcome to eat at the bar if we weren't welcome to eat there, and wasted 30 minutes of our time.

column11:
Was driving through Santa Barbara with my father when we got hungry.  He said to look up a place to eat.  While I was searching Google he says, try using yelp.  That caught me off guard, would never have thought he knew about internet services such as yelp.  

Anyways, back to the review.  This place really is a hole in the wall.  They only had tacos but they were good.  I had 6 tacos on my first serving,  carne asada and chicken.  Threw some onions and cilantro on there and a little bit of salsa.  Topped it off with a coke.  They were so good I went for another 4 tacos and another coke.  If I'm ever in Santa Barbara again, I will definitely be stopping there again.

column11:
This luxury resort charges rates almost as high as the Four Seasons, but is not as consistent, as it is tough to compete with perfection. Still, we had a wonderful time here overall, and would return for more. Just don't dine here often, as the food is fine, but the prices don't justify it. 

First, the bad, which wasn't terrible, but for the room price, you'd expect more. We pre-requested things on the Bonvoy app, for example foam pillows instead of feather, but none of them were provided. We also asked no less than three times for a third patio chair for my kid, but never ever received one. We were on bottom floor, so this would have been an easy deliverable. We got a room in building 15 which is next to busy Hollister, so if traffic noise bothers you, stay in a different building. Next, we had planned our day around one of the craft activities we signed up for, but apparently the Ritz person was there, but hid next to the bar, didn't announce herself, nor ask around if anyone was there for her class. She left exactly at noon when it was supposed to start, so obviously didn't feel like teaching it. We were very disappointed, and wasted an hour of our precious vacation day. There are carts driving by every few seconds, and the workers drive fast, so be careful around corners. This did annoy us when they wouldn't stop as we walked the path. 

Now for the good. The staff in general were all quite professional and accommodating, especially at the front desk. We were provided free dining for the craft class being canceled. Btw make sure you sign up for your activities far in advance of your stay, as they get booked up. Still, some activities had spaces left even though it showed sold out, for example the pool/jacuzzi reservations were available even though we were just walk ins. Whenever we needed anything from Housekeeping, it was delivered in minutes, and they gave us a microwave to use. The resort itself is impeccably maintained, and the Spanish decor was tasteful. The beach below is beautiful with miles to explore, including tidepooling. Our room was generally nice and quiet, and they love dogs here with plenty of lawns and poop bag stations.

column11:
Visiting Santa Barbara was just about the best thing we needed after being cooped up, quarantine style, for months. 

Santa Barbara was quite busy on a Saturday in August. Apparently other people had the same idea about getting out. The weather was warm, but the cool beach breeze made up for it. We opted for Bluewater Grill due to the reviews and the amount of outdoor seating available. 

We were lucky enough to get the second story terrace spot which gave us beautiful views of the Pacific Ocean and beach. The sun was hot, but the multiple umbrellas provided a nice respite. 

I opted the for Lobster Roll. They asked if I wanted it chilled or warmed, being that it was a hot day a chilled lobster roll hit the spot. It came brimming with succulent lobster on a toasted roll. Paired with a spicy bloody mary it hit the spot!

Pretty decent food, yummy tacos, pretty tasty tuna melt- a classic burger, beer & fries joint. Their greatest jewels are their excellent ocean views, gigantic sandbox for the kids to play in while the adults get to relax amongst other adults, and great live music (beach music)! Had a great time and fun in the sun, you will too!

In contrast to the very poor food at other beach front food shacks in the Shoreline beach area, the food here is pretty good and beer selection good too.
Enjoy!

column11:
Ordered: 

-Dixie (Dixie Brewing Company is a craft brewery based in New Orleans, Louisiana. In 2005, the Dixie Brewery was severely damaged when Mid-City New Orleans flooded from the levee failure disaster during Hurricane Katrina. Courtesy: Wikipedia)

(DIXIE BEER is NOT on the MENU. Have to request! Nice light taste.)

--Popcorn Crawfish (Lived up to the hype.)

-Jambalaya Piquante (Lacking more dirty rice but, overall, not bad.)

-Louisiana Bread Pudding Souffle (Everything I could have hoped for and more. A MUST order while you place your app order. It needs prep time so it is piping hot when it arrives after the main course.)

Price: Somewhat Pricey. High-End Moderate.

Service: Could have been better but sensed I was dealing with a rookie waiter. Sorry lone star...

A solid 4 stars from the State Street stand-by.

column11:
I have to say I had great expectations when I ate here on my Birthday in October.  I was very disappointed because I was expecting a awesome steak.  Since it was my bday I ordered the Cowboy cut rib eye thinking it would be one of the best steak dinners I had ever had and I was very disappointed.  It just didn't have any grilled flavor, it was kinda grey all over and even though I ordered it medium rare it was well done around the edges and pretty rare in by the bone.  

 Service left something to be desired as well.  Someone at my table had to ask the waiter what the better and oil were for before he noticed we were never served any bread.

I will go to Ruth's Chris next year in search of a top notch steak.

column11:
I will never go back to this place and I hope no one else will either. For me service is paramount especially when you're going to provide average food for above average prices. 

I was in here one time with a friend, it wasn't too busy and we had ordered some food to go to take to the beach. After 25 minutes, we asked them what the hold up was and they said it's almost done. After another 15 minutes we asked them again, this time they told us that they forgot to put our order in. THEY DIDN'T EVEN APOLOGIZE! I was livid, the whole experience took an hour. I'm writing this about a year later and I'm still getting fired up. This was one of the worst restaurant experiences of my life. I understand things go wrong, mistakes happen, but to have the gall to not apologize for it happening makes me wish the worst upon this business. 

I'm going to have to write a good review now to put my mind back in a good spot.

column11:
For my first Santa Barbara morning in 3 years, I ventured down to carpinteria for some local joe. Crush cakes was unique and I liked the atmosphere. They played music from the 60s and 70s with some classics mixed in. There were black antiques chairs and benches, refurbished concrete floors, and hanging lights with a "peace love cupcakes" sign on the wall.  Sort of an industrial meets boho vibe. 

The pumpkin muffin I had was moist and tasty in general but I wasn't aware it contained golden raisins, so I had to pick them out...not a shriveled grape person myself. (Fermented grape juice on the other hand......)
The house blend coffee was nice and bold with a slight spiciness to it. Deep flavor. I also had an herbal tea which was nice and fragrant and served to me in an adorable little red pot. I tried the espresso chocolate chip scone my friend got and was not impressed...dry (even for a scone) and too crumbly. I expected a burst of flavor and had to search for it with my taste buds. Which brings me to another reason for only three stars...price. For what you get for the price you pay, just not the best deal in town.

I'm of the opinion that most places do a few things very well. They often have a myriad of other things on the menu to cater to a broader demographic, but for the most part I stick to what they are known for. Today was the perfect example, and while I enjoyed my trip to crush cakes, I will probably only return to try the cupcakes. They smelled delicious baking while I was having breakfast.

column11:
My first visit here was an experience in perfection. Nothing over the top, or wildly "foodie" innovative, just good classic food and cocktails, done right.

There are two distinct dining areas, to suit your mood. The front area is the bar and bistro area, for when you're feeling casual or moody.
The back area is for more formal dining, although there's no stuffy feeling in the atmosphere. It's quieter, with brighter lighting, linens, a view of their extensive cellar, and larger tables. 

I went with four friends for a quiet weekend evening and the first thing we noticed on the menu was the cocktails, with dates next to them. The dates are the accepted years that each of those cocktails was devised. It was our first hint that this place had purist ideals.  
We sat at the bar to sample some of these cocktails where we learned:

* they make their own orgeat for mai tais,
* they make their own tonic water,
* they use real Marasca cherries in their Manhattans,
* and the Zombie really packs a punch (limit 2 per customer).

We sampled more than this, but I do not want to appear like a total lush, so I'll leave it at that. The bottom line on the cocktails is that Sly's is serious about them, making sure they're done proper. I have no doubt the other cocktails on the menu are just as good.

We stuck around for dinner, and remained at the bar. The bartender knew the menu forwards and back, including the specials, and could name the sources of all the dishes we inquired about, especially when they came from local businesses. I think it's important to note here that the more questions we asked about the food, the more pleased they were to answer them, because I feel their knowledge of ingredient sources and preparation is what makes Sly's different to other steak and seafood places. And it's really something to be proud of.

I had the mussels, Spanish style, which came with firm chorizo, caramelized onions and a tomato-based sauce that was so delicious we used our hot bread to soak up all those good juices. I even resorted to scooping it up with a spoon since there was so much. The dish was also generously portioned, about 20 mussels, and it cost $14. There are several other sauce options, and they all range in price between $12-$14. So reasonable.
I also had the streak frites. It was also a sensible price of $14, with a sensible 4 oz portion of steak, which was cooked perfectly to my request. There are sauce options as well, and I had mine with a green peppercorn cream, my absolute favorite sauce for steak. The french fries are also perfect, and the meal reminded me so much of simple dining in France and Belgium, I had to ask for a little mayonnaise for my fries and was rewarded with a dish of delicious housemade mayo. Everyone in the group dug into those fries with mayonnaise, we never even removed the cap of the nearby ketchup bottle.

Nothing could top a meal that brought back those European memories like a round of profiteroles for dessert could. I swear I had no idea what was on the menu and when I was offered the dessert menu I flat out said I could not be tempted, unless there was profiteroles.  And guess what was there, prominently displayed on the menu. YES!  A handful of choux pastries filled with vanilla ice cream, topped with chocolate sauce and a warm pot of housemade dark caramel sauce on the side.  The price on this varies, depending on the number of profiteroles requested. I selected 5, and that was $13.

There are many other items on the menu, different cuts of steak, bigger cuts, lots of fish and shellfish. The prices are generally on the upper end, as these are sourced from reputable specialty companies, not mysterious agri-beef businesses or large scale produce corporations. But still, the items we happened to order were very affordable, especially given the attention to detail and the quality of everything. 

I took photos of the food we got and some of the cocktails. Hope that's helpful!

column11:
Me and my bf went here with his friend because he told us that we should try the quesarrito. A quesadilla inside a burrito. We came and it wasn't so crowded so cool. This place reminds me of a Chipotle with how it's like a build your own burrito kind of thing. But anyway after we started building our burrito, the group after us ordered the same thing as us. So, thinking to myself, it must be pretty good then! 

What we got:
Quesarrito($11): yes it was good and pretty interesting, however I don't know if it was worth it. Me and my bf decided to share since we weren't that hungry. We got it with steak, black beans, refried beans, sour cream, tomato, lettuce, cilantro, and salsa verde. I think the only thing that killed it for me were the beans. I'm not a fan of beans and the beans just overpowered the whole thing. Once I ignored the taste of the beans, I enjoyed it much more.

Service:
It was good. Our burrito maker was very friendly and gave us generous portions of whatever my bf wanted to put into the burrito. I think I would still rather go to Chipotle though...

column11:
This place has a very family-friendly diner feel. I came here on a Sunday morning for breakfast. I ordered some sort of chili omelette with fruit and an English muffin, and my guy ordered a bacon and cheese omelette with fries and an English muffin.

Reason this place isn't a 4/5 Star - some of the egg in my omelette was underdone .. I don't really have a problem with this but I would understand if other people would not like bits of raw egg white. I've never had food poisoning in my life and I've eaten some crazy stuff so I just rolled with it (didn't get sick or anything either). The fruit on the side was also pretty lackluster.  As far as my guy's order, an avo was accidentally added to his omelette (like folded into the egg so it couldn't really be picked out), but both the cook and the server were great about getting the correct order out quickly. 

Based on all of the regulars here (there were 4 other couples, all a bit older that obvs knew the server), I suspect my experience was probably just a one-off and I would still return. The portions are huge and while my omelette was underdone, it still tasted pretty freakin good. The service was amazing and the coffee refills were much appreciated.

column11: HAHA! Boy oh Boy, I was a regular here when I was a student at UCSB!  Nearly every single Saturday, I would be hungover from a night of drinking.  I would always order the same thing, the super size pho dac biet or just the large pho before the super size came in!  The broth is just so delicate and refreshing.  I usually add a buttload of the chili oil and the fresh chili to make my broth have an extra kick to wake me up.  The bean sprouts...I fu%^in pour that in as well as the jalapenos.  No basil cuz I hate it.  The meat is so delicious as well.  They do not skimp on the portions.  A double plus.  I never really had a bad service here before.  I mean, I don't expect a 5 star service.  It's a small restaurant and the owners are just trying to do their best.  The vietnamese lady owner knows my friend and I.  She would always make fun of us and stuff like that!  "ALWAYS WITH THE TO GO BOX!"  LOL!  What?! It's so good and delicious I have to take some home for Sunday morning when I need to recover cuz you guys close Sundays!  I'll always have fond memories here at Noodle City!  When I visit Santa Barbara, I'll be sure to pay a visit to my favorite pho place.  Oh, and their Chow Fun isn't that bad either.  Its deeelicious!  :)

column11:
The restaurant is located more in a corner location that is hidden away from the street. The decor is relatively modern, giving a nice feel when you sit down. Optionally, you can sit outside, where there is a nice open decor but lacking in shade. 


Now, on to the food: The food is what really
penalized itself causing it to earn only three stars. I really wanted to love the food, the colors and food was off to a good start. For starters, the soup was great. I had their clam chowder, the only wish I had would be for a thicker chowder, but not everybody shares the same opinion. The other soup that I sampled was a kale soup, which was a unique offering that many restaurants don't traditionally serve. Overall, the soup was off to a fantastic start and got me excited. 

However, things took a turn when I had their entre. I had ordered their State Burger which has glazed onions and bacon. The taste wasn't awful, but the taste was definitely odd. But, the kicker that forced me to give it two stars was the plastic that I found in my burger! There was an entire piece of plastic that was stuck in the center of the party. That was a horrible turnoff for the restaurant. 

After informing the manager, their response was not the best. They offered no apology and quickly tried to run away with the dish. Unfortunately, I was in a hurry and had no time to wait for another one to arrive. But, their overall attitude regarding their mistake was summarily unapologetic. 

Overall, the restaurant may be a good one. But for me, their service and food caused me to give them a two star review. Maybe if I am in the area again, I can try again and see how they do. But for now, two stars is all it gets for it's food and service.

column11: The Arts & Letters Cafe provides an excellent dining experience.  We went in for a brief lunch break and we were very impressed with the atmosphere of the restaurant.  It is very well known by locals as a high end eatery, and we were not disappointed.  The entrance to the restaurant goes through an art gallery with fine paintings on display, and the dining area is outside in a shaded patio area.  Everything about the environment was excellent, and the food was great.  The only thing I would be cautious about is the fact that the sandwiches are messy and the menu is limited.

column11:
After reading the reviews on yelp for Sandbar I really thought to pass!! Thankfully we went anyways and could not have had a better experience!!!  The patio is perfect for  people watching and spending a long afternoon with good company.  We never  felt rushed!! As visitors we were simply looking for good ambiance and the outside patio  was GREAT!! Firepits and heating lamps!!  

The service was friendly and attentive and would not hesitate to return.  The guacamole was fresh and Fajitas were very good.  We were lucky to be there for happy hour which is actually a real happy hour w 2 for 1 drinks!!  Oh and they have flat screens everywhere with various sports throughout the day!

Many compliments to the manager Art and his staff as I was really expecting far less and felt compelled to ask for him only to to offer my compliments after reading less then desirable reviews.  Great experience at Sandbar and obvious they care about your experience!  Highly recommended for a chillin good time!

column11:
First off, I only ordered delivery but I feel confident in this review as I have eaten in the restaurant many times over the years . The only reason I'm giving this 2 stars instead of 1 is because they actually delivered the food on time on Christmas Eve. I probably should have known better. My taste for Chinese food has waned over the years.

We ordered beef with broccoli , dry sauted green beans and vegetable chow mien. The beef sauce was heavy and unappealing. The chow mein was bland and worse of all The green beans tasted like fish! I literally threw over half the food in the trash and wound up eating christmas cookies all night instead. I will not be ordering from them again.

column11:
Thank you, Yelp! I can't go anywhere without checking the rating and recommendations first, and because of that, we found this delicious meal in SB!

My BFF and I started with some draft beers, and their homemade sausage and potato skins for appetizers, which were both great. They also served a few pieces of delicious garlic bread. Ooh, I almost forgot their yummy split pea soup and salad!

We shared the NY cut, and it was really yummy. Their meat was exceptionally flavorful, I think because they get it from a local supplier. It came with a potato choice and veggies.

We were here for at least two hours, and had so much good food! The service was great, and after everything we ordered, the bill was ~$70, which is not bad at all for the quality! I highly recommend Shalhoob's.

column11:
Get ready for a very authentic Chinese Hot Pot dining experience!  

I am so happy this restaurant opened in Santa Barbara.  I recently moved back to town after being in LA for the last 20 years.  It's been hard adjusting to the food options here after being so spoiled in the greater LA area.  When we moved one of the things I knew I would miss the most as going for Hot Pot at least once a month in Monterey Park.

I have to say the quality of everything is outstanding!  The staff are super nice and helpful and didn't even flinch when they offered to make a special vegetarian broth for my partner (all if they're broths are chicken based)  Be careful of spice level because the chili is authentic as well.  They were consistently checking on our table without being bothersome and tirelessly restocked the appetizer and sauce bar several times while we were there.

The sauce bar has more options than you can think of with something like 25-30 ingredients you can chose from to customize your flavor experiences after ordering exactly which proteins and vegetables you would like to cook in your soup.

There are also a small buffet of 8 appetizer options and 4 dessert soups to round out your meal (and your belly)

The only thing I see hurting them $6+$2 per person buy-in is a little steep compared to LA but I can imagine the State St rent is effecting that.   The second negative is the fact that the tables are a bit crowded, especially when you add the carts holding all the extra dishes.  I understand the appeal of being ON State st., but ultimately I think they would do just as well in a less touristy and lower rent part of town where they could charge less and have more space while still making the same profit per customer.

If they added vegetarian broths to the menu and were slightly cheaper we would probably eat here a couple times a week!

column11:
I really appreciate the authenticity of this place. There is nothing I love more than authentic Mexican food and this place does not disappoint. They are generous with portions and have something for most dietary needs. 

Today I ordered the veggie burrito and was very satisfied. The veggies consist of zucchini, celery, mushrooms, bell peppers, and onions. It also comes with Mexican rice, beans, cheese, and sour cream. I asked them to hold the cheese and sour cream and it was still very tasty. 

I'm giving this place five stars because I've been to a couple of other Mexican food places around town and their veggie options are not as good as here. The portions and prices are also great!

column11:
My intention with this review isn't to be mean or rude, just honest in order for others to avoid this place if they don't want this experience. 
1 star because I have to, 2nd star because the boba is good, and 3rd star for them fixing their mistake
So, first off, they didn't have the flavor slush I wanted for my boba but I ordered a different one and liked it anyway. I liked that it wasn't overly sweet, for reference, I can't do Hana Kitchen's slush anymore, it's just way too sweet for me. I got the cheese foam with it and that was really yummy, had a cream cheese-y taste. 
I ordered the hainanese chicken bowl with chicken rice and the veggie croquettes. The total for my order including a 15% tip was over $30. I drove all the way home (downtown SB) just to see that they didn't give me any of the sauces it was supposed to come with and they gave me plain white rice instead of chicken rice. So it was literally just white rice, boiled chicken, broccoli, and corn. For $14. It was honestly one of the most unappetizing things I've ever seen. I ate the veggie croquettes because I was too hungry not to, and they were good, but I absolutely would not pay $7 for them again. They are WAY overpriced. Maybe the bowl might have been good with the sauce but I wouldn't know. I drove all the way back to IV and even had to get gas, which I wasn't planning on doing at 8 pm, and asked them politely to refund the meal. They offered to remake it correctly this time but the sight of this food turned me off of it so I was firm in my request for a refund, especially since I had to drive all the way back to IV. They were nice and apologetic and refunded the meal with no hassle, which I really appreciated, and that's the reason they get the third star. But I would never eat here again, the food is so overpriced, and they seem to have some quality control issues based on the other reviews I see, with other people also having things left out of their order, only to realize it once they finally get home with their food. 
I would maybe stop in here for a boba if I was in IV again for some reason, but would not go out of my way, I'd rather just go somewhere else closer to me.

column11:
Another place I can't believe I haven't reviewed yet!

The husband & I have been going for YEARS now to this place and it all started when we saw a sign with two arrows, one pointing to parking and one pointing to BEER.  We pretty much hit this place up 99% of the time we go to Carp, whether we're camping, staying in a hotel, and/or just passing through to Santa Barbara.  We were part of the Island Nation for a while 

LOCATION/AMBIANCE:  The brewery is where they actually brew, and used to be more of a warehouse.  They've since renovated and its even cooler.  It is next to the train tracks and on the other side is the grass and campsite area, so the ocean is viewable, though somewhat in the distance.  Bummer part is that there's now a park in the grassy area that blocks the awesome view they used to have.  Great for the kids, but sucky for those sitting here.  The crowd is all casual and there are often kids and dogs joining their parents and owners, respectively.  There are locals (some of whom we've met over the years) and there are out-of-towners passing through or who, like us, have this is as a regular destination.  Very laid back and not at all a bar-type feel (except for, of course, the beer).  What I mean by that is that I've never seen a fight, loud drunks, people getting kicked out, etc.  It's a very pleasant experience.

BEER (& OTHER DRINKS/FOOD):  So, it's a brewery and they only have beer, with some bar munchies.  My fave is the hef and the husband's fav is the IPA.   Since they don't serve other drinks or food, they allow for food to be brought in or delivered.  I've also seen women with wine while their husbands come in for beer.

STAFF/SERVICE:  We absolutely adore their staff.  Some of them we don't see any more b/c they moved shifts (and we only come on weekends since we're not locals) and the newer ones are still very nice also.

Bottom Line - Go for a pleasant & relaxing time, but don't get rowdy.  This is not the place for that.

column11:
Alito's is a colorful New Mexican restaurant on lower state, and one with big competition.

While Alito's lunch prices are a few dollars cheaper than Los Arroyo's a few blocks up, the food is unfortunately a bit bland. 

The chicken in the chicken carbon tacos was under seasoned, which unfortunately wasn't saved by the similarly-uninspired salsa.

The service was lovely, attentive, and prompt.

To be fair, they're new and are likely smoothing out some kinks. I'll definitely give them another chance in a month or so!

3/5

column11:
BREAKFAST BUFFET 

We ate breakfast here everyday for the week we stayed at this lovely resort. The service is good but we had the buffet daily so there really wasn't much service needed. We where sat right away daily, mainly sat outside on the patio where there was outdoors heaters to keep us cozy. 

The omelette bar was marvelous, hubby was all about it. The freshest ingredients and lovely presentation of each omelette. There was a fruit bar, cheese and cold cuts, yogurt station, breads/bagels and some random hot foods including breakfast tacos, grilled veggies etc. 

The view though takes the cake at this little spot. We will definitely dine with them again.

Stopped at Rosales in the middle of our road trip, and it was absolutely the right choice. The food was so fresh, service was great, and portions were excellent. 

We ordered a shrimp ceviche tostada, 2 veggie quesadillas which came with guac, and one order of fish enchiladas. They have a nice outdoor setup, so we enjoyed our food in the cool weather outside. Definitely a place we would revisit!

column11: The place is inside of the sandwich place The Three Pickles which was surprising. I was kind of exited to try this place but I'm kind of disappointed. First the miso soup was served boiling hot, we had to wait 10min to drink it, then the food took pretty long to arrive for 2 rolls in a place with only 4 other customers, but I don't mind waiting for good food. The rolls were good but not amazing, and definitely not worth $16. We paid $40 without tips for 2 miso soup and 2 rolls. If it was amazing I would understand, but amazing is not the word. Good yes. But so overpriced...

It's a must visit when in Santa Barbara, EARLY though lol.

column11: The food here is delicious but the manager is horrible shes disrespectful and very rude. I used to come in and have lunch at least once a week but now I just can't make myself go into the place. I've never felt so uncomfortable to order in a restaurant. Really wish they would get rid of the rude women so I could come back in to enjoy the wonderful food. I'm giving this place a 5 stars for the food but for customer service I have to give a -1 star. I've walked into the restaurant and have witnessed the women yelling at the cooks degrading them, when you try to order food she rushes you and gets your order wrong and blames you for it.  This little burger joint can be the best pearl in goleta but she just runs the people away. Very sad.

column11: I wish I could rate this so much higher!! The food was amazing. My Bloody Mary was perfection. The host was a super sweet, cool dude. Went in with a great first impression. It took a super long time for our waitress to check in with us or even offer us water. We finally had to ask the host if anyone knew we were seated in the corner. Our waitress wasn't apologetic at all. She moved fast but I don't know what she was doing exactly. The outside was moderately busy but there wasn't many of us in the inside dining area. It was a beautiful Saturday morning and again the food !! Every interaction with our waitress was ok but it was probably the longest meal we've ever had because there was such a gap in her timing. Service is so important.

column11: Note: This review is based strictly on service. Rude rude rude. This place needs a major AA (Attitude Adjustment). I wish the staff members had nametags so I could single out the two people that were so rude to me and my new fianc the day after we were engaged. As we arrived we were greeted with an expression and comment that made me sick. The waitress looked up at me and questioned us sitting down to wait for my parents.. She gave me a rude look and sharply told me that if I wanted breakfast it wasn't available. Then my fianc attempted to order from the cashier inside and the man behind the counter without any words spoken through his arm with his thumb out pointing to the other register. I had enough and we walked out (wasting $4 in parking). We are now at another place and loving it.. Note to the owner/manager. If you're trying to save money by hiring cheap labor you're making a mistake. Sometimes cheap wages can make an employee unhappy and in turn they treat customers poorly in turn driving away business. I hope you get that point.

column11: I'll be honest: their donuts are amazing. Second only to maybe Anna's. But, Their service is awful. AWFUL. We ordered three drinks and after a 20-minute wait, put came two. We waited for the third, but the woman walked out of our view and after we patiently explained that we ordered three drinks (and showed her our receipt) she groaned loudly and slowly began to make our third drink. She stopped in the middle and after waiting even longer we walked out. Not an SB native but I've been to Anna's a few times and compared with them, God was this a bad experience. Worst I've had here. Wish I could say that the donut quality outweighs the service, but it just doesn't. I wouldn't come here again. Go somewhere else

column11: Food was fair but overpriced for the quality. Server was nice but was not very attentive. Maybe spread too thin? Never got our appetizer, ended up going to another table. Still was on our bill and had to request it to come off. Our dessert went to the wrong table as well but they sent it back this time so we eventually got it. Asked for flour tortillas vs corn said no problem and it came out corn. Asked what was on the burger and she forgot to say pickles so pickle juice all over the bun, which is ok if you like pickles. They did replace the bun though after we asked. There's a reason the locals don't go there and it's just the tourists. Wouldn't go back. Not worth it. I can put up with mediocre food but service can make or break a visit. For the food- I would have rated them a 3 star. Service a 1 star so hence the 2.

column11: Plant based, delicious options from breakfast to dinner.  We are delighted to discover Leslie Durso is in the house at Four Seasons Bella Vista.  Look for her items (LD) next to the item.  We had the bruschetta, quinoa bowl, plus the pumpkin desert.  All items are vegan offering plenty of protein, filling and yet light enough to carry on the day without that food coma feeling.  The bruschetta offered four unique flavors and toppings.  We cut them in two and shared each.  The bowl was big and more like a kale salad with quinoa, sweet potato and other goodies.  I would LOVE to see a warm bowl option and suggest they call this more of a Kale & Quinoa Salad.  They have vegan waffles on the weekend and i think coconut whipcream.  The vegan options are expanding.  Some of my family members are not vegan but they love these healthy plant based options and they are sooo good.  I forgot to ask if they source organic products/produce & hope they continue to offer increasingly gluten free vegan options.  Thank you Four Seasons and Leslie Durso, you have made us come back to Bella Vista.  We have already made reservations to return.  Oh and i hear the bar will soon have some LD offerings too!

column11: Dee Tours was absolutely amazing!  We used Dee Tours for my husband's 30th bday trip to Santa Barbara and I am so thankful we found  Dee.  She picked us up from our hotel and gave us a wonderful driving tour of the main attractions of Santa Barbara pointing out all kinds of things we would have never known, allowing us to get out and see different sites as well as take pictures.  She then drove us to the Santa Ynez area for our winery tour which was amazing.  See stopped at a great variety of places even taking us to an olive oil and vinegar tasting which was a great break in the middle of all the wine.  She took us through the adorable town of Solvang and brought us lunch to have at one of the vineyards.  She even went out of her way to purchase my husband a customized cupcake which was such a sweet gesture.  Dee was so patient the entire time never rushing us on time, we have been on other vineyard tours and most companies charge by the amount of time you 'go over' your scheduled tour not Dee we almost had to convince Dee it's ok to take us back even though we were having an amazing time.  We will definitely use Dee again!  Dee Tours gets more than a 5 stars from us!

column11: A solidly good breakfast in Santa Barbara. The location on State St isn't very big and the weather on Christmas Eve morning was perfect for a patio breakfast. We snagged a table, ordered at the counter and the food was delivered to our table in a decent amount of time. My husband loved his huevos rancheros and I had a great spinach salad with berries, figs and goat cheese. We had to ask if our coffee orders were forgotten and were reassured they were coming. They were dropped off towards the end of our meal with an apology that they were backed up. We asked for to-go cups and rolled with it. Overall, the food was tasty, the drinks hot and a place we'd recommend for breakfast.

I was hesitant to order here because of the prices being slightly out of my range, but I'm SO GLAD I did it! 

I got and ice blended espresso and the avocado toast. 
The toast was as filling as a full meal and absolutely delicious.

column11: We ate here on a recommendation from a friend.  They raved about it.  I thought, OK I'm from the San Joaquin valley near Fresno, and we have excellent tacquerias....but we'll give it a try.  Everyone says in their reviews that it's authentic Mexican food.  I chuckled as I looked at their menu board...I saw an item called "melted chesse between 2 tacos"...isn t that a queadilla??  Let's be authentic!  When you order your food, you can see a gal making homemeade tortillas behind the counter...the tortillas werevery good.  The guacamole portions were big.  But.............I would never wait in line for 1-2 hours for their food.  That's really ridiculous.  I've had much better Mexican food for a wait of 5 minutes or less.  Come on people.

column11:
We stopped by with our fur children this afternoon on an afternoon stroll through downtown Santa Barbara. Craving something sweet, we spotted McConnell's which happened to be on our 'to try' list. 

Pretty much every flavor looked appetizing and I had trouble choosing. With the help of a very nice cashier/scooper, (what exactly do you call an ice cream store employee anyhow?), we ultimately chose a two flavor single scoop in a waffle cone. We got sweet cream caramel brownie and sea salt cream and cookies: both were absolutely delicious!  As if that wasn't tasty enough to earn a five star review, the employee went one further offering a small scoop of vanilla ice cream for the doggos to share! They seemed to enjoy it more than we did if that's even possible! We really appreciated the employee's thoughtfulness and will likely be back!

column11:
Deep Sea Tasting Room gets 5 stars for the location. It's located right on the pier and if it's a beautiful day (typically it is since it's Cali) then you get views of the city, mountains, and the ocean all on the patio deck. The venue is small, but they have as much seating as they can with the space that they have. 

There were two girls working and they recommended the flight to us. They weren't the most friendly people. They explained the wines as they poured them but it was just like a rinse and repeat cycle. 

I ordered the Santa Barbara Signature Flight which came with a sample of their Sauvignon Blanc, Chardonnay, Rose, Pinot Noir, and Dolcetto/Petite Syrah. If you drink wine often enough, then honestly, the wines here are not that great. The best one was probably the Chardonnay out of the five that I tried. Also, the samples themselves are the smallest that I've ever had. I've been to many different wineries and wine tastings before too. After going to other wine tasting rooms in the area, all of the other staff told me that Deep Sea is just known for their view and their pours are known to be the smallest and the wines aren't that great. This was my impression. 

If you are interested in wines I would go elsewhere, but if you don't care about the wine and just want the view then I would recommend you coming here.

column11:
I drove to Santa Barbara for my birthday, without any reservations and stumbled upon this inn, which looked quaint and comfy from the outside. I was pleasantly surprised by this lovely property, and the beautiful room with an ocean view that they provided for me.

Alexa, at the desk, and Dario, the owner, were extremely kind and generous with recommendations and coupons for local restaurants and bars. 

The location is pretty spectacular, 1 block from the beach, and 1 block from the popular State Street. I will definitely be returning here on my next trip.

column11: I honestly don't understand how the staff here can be so incompetent. I have been coming here 3-4x a week for over a year straight ordering the same thing. Unfortunately, every single time the donkeys here fail to recognize my regular order. They over charge me, mess up my order, and always put things in my food I clearly don't ask for. I don't understand how you can mess up such an easy task. I come here as a regular and order the same things yet each time I come the price is somehow different? You kids are one of the only few if not the only Fish market in goleta yet for some unknown reason can't hire competent staff?? Tell that stingy owner to get his shit together or maybe hire some people who have a brain. I stopped coming here because of this insolence. Pathetic losers

column11:
ok, their gelato is DEEEEEEEEEE-LISH! but i have to take off two stars for the following reason:

1.  no a/c?! it was a cool 75-80 day but inside the store it felt like 90! i was sweatin' just standing there trying to decide what to get

2. the lady behind the counter was sooooooo unfriendly! i hate coming to such a beautiful and quaint little town like this and get such horrible service with attitude

anyhooooo!  i had the opportunity (reluctantly served by the unfriendly staff) to try the pistachio, fig honey macaroon, and the regular hazelnut . i felt a little NUTTY on this gorgeous sunny southern california day so i chose the pistachio and the regular hazelnut as my 2 scoop choices in my $5 medium sized cup.

they have a wide variety of gelato flavors including chocolates, fruits, sorbets...etc.

column11: Staying at the Best Western about 800 ft away. Have past by here so many times, so we decided to try. This is a little hole in the wall. We were seated in the back room. It was a great night!!!

column11:
Have you ever wished that Applebee's would triple their prices? Well then, this is the restaurant for you. This food is not particularly better than most frozen entrees at the supermarket. The cauliflower misto frido was smothered in a thick flavorless breading then coated with a thick corn syrup-like sweet/sour sauce. Imagine the shitty Chinese food from your local strip mall. The 5 "bacon-wrapped large scallops" just sucked. The were tiny bay scallops totally overpowered by the size of a normal strip of bacon. They were dry and unappetizing. Didn't think it was possible to make bacon unappealing but I stand corrected.  The fish was meh. The wedge salad was the best thing we ordered. The environment is nice. The service was great. 
Basically this joint is an overpriced tourist trap lacking any love in the kitchen.

column11:
We first started out with the complementary tostada and salsas that also came with a bean mixture that was pretty tasty. Great way to start off the meal. I shared the elote which came whole so I'm assuming you just chomp your way through - we asked them to cut it in half so it was easier to eat though. It was pretty good but nothing exceptional. 

We got the shrimp and fish taco which were both pretty fresh! I liked the shrimp over the fish a bit because it had more flavor, but at least they didn't give us a shortage of lime! 

Churros were what we ended the night with and it came with 3 sauces - dark chocolate, raspberry and a white chocolate. The raspberry one was my favorite. The churros were tasty but a tad stale. I don't think they make them fresh? They weren't as soft as I was hoping.

column11:
To be fair, the place is an extraordinary visual dream.  The counterperson was very accommodating when asked if I would like to order breakfast at 5 to 11.  I did and he asked the chefs not to put the breakfast acudaments away.  Very kind and great service.

 I was terribly excited to meet my husband for brunch during the work week but was slightly disappointed with my order.  Being vegetarian I thought I might try the biscuit egg dish without the egg and enjoy the tomato jam.  It was over cooked, could hardly bite into the biscuit and the jam far too sweet.  

Oh well, perhaps I will just have coffee next time because that was delicious.

column11:
I was checked in yesterday afternoon and checked out this morning for a one night stay.  The hotel is older with no air conditioning.  The elevator was like a chamber of horrors with dangerous doors. The room l was in could use updating of furniture.  

The furniture is old and the bed was also on the tired side. The television was new.  The shower and sink were newer.

The positive is being across from the ocean.  

One final note when you pay for a room with the ocean view make sure you have a full ocean view.  You may want to call about that after you reserve the room.  I paid for an ocean view and got half a view. Not cool at all.

column11: Maybe we just didn't order the right thing, but my boyfriend and I both got spaghetti and meatballs. Priced at $23 each I was expecting it to be one of the best spaghettis I've had, but unfortunately it didn't taste like anything special. It wasn't bad, but $23 is way too steep for this. It tasted like spaghetti you could make at home and the meatballs were packed so tight and were so dense and just really not that good. We asked for extra Parmesan and they gave us two packets similar to those you get at pizza hut or dominoes. There was no bread included, no salad, no nothing except the spaghetti and meatballs. I feel bad writing a less than stellar review during covid, but I can't help but feel a little ripped off and I feel that when people spend $23 for a pasta dish it should be much better than this.

column11:
Jonny and Pour SB bartended my wedding this past May and I can't praise him and his staff enough. 

Jonny was very communicative throughout the planning process and was always so nice and friendly, which I really appreciated while in the depths of my wedding-related stress. The bartenders that worked at the wedding were so friendly and nice (per my husband, they were also very cool and funny) and were so quick and efficient with their setup and their service throughout the wedding. 

Jonny put together a beautiful and delicious bar service. I am picky when it comes to alcohol, wine and beer especially, and Jonny totally understood my vision and executed everything excellently. For the wine, I told him the types of wine that I wanted (in this case, Rose, Chardonnay, and Pinot Noir) and Jonny found excellent bottles for great prices. He also hooked things up with beer from one of Santa Barbara's breweries, which was very important to me. The signature cocktails were incredible, with everything made from scratch. I had to try everything because it was all so good, and the morning-after headache was totally worth it! My husband (and our guests) also couldn't stop talking about how good everything was.

My "dream vision" for my wedding, more than anything else, was that it would turn into the most rollicking-good-time ever and Jonny and his team were crucial in making that a reality. Everyone had the best time and I know that we have Pour SB to thank!!
column24: Bartenders, Event Planning & Services

column11:
That's probably the cheapest Japanese food you can find in Santa Barbara that serves decent food.

I often eat there whenever I need to grab something to eat while shopping in paseo. Their rolls tastes good, as well as their chicken curry bowl, my favorite.

The lady at the counter is very nice and always smiling, even though she doesn't speak English that well she'll do everything to get your order right. However, once served, there is no "waiter" present, since the restaurant is very small, it's more of a to-go / take out kind of place vibe so don't expect a refill on your water!

Side note: Don't drink the tap water they have, I believe they just pour unfiltered tap water into the water fountain.

column11: Came here this last Sunday for brunch and had an amazing time! The food was not your average buffet food. It was amazingly delicious! They have more food than you can imagine, and all of it tasting fresh and delicious. The salads were fresh and dressing was good. They have a good variety of fatty foods and not so fatty foods, which was perfect for our party. The dessert bar is full of cake, cheese cakes, flan, creme brulee, fresh fruit, and a chocolate fountain. Bottomless mimosas are also delicious! I was thinking they were going to be more juice than champagne, but they were pretty strong so drink cautiously! And the atmosphere is great as well. I loved it all, had an amazing time. I will definitely be going back!

column11:
I've never been a huge fan of cupcakes, even as they became the trendy food du joir over the past several years with big name companies like sprinkles and cooking competition shows such as cupcake wars making them all the rage. I didn't see the appeal, cupcakes as they were made at sprinkles were practically a meal in and of themselves. Though they had interesting sounding flavors, they were oftentimes so sickly sweet you couldn't more than one or two bites before you felt sugared-out.

Flash forward to the opening of the public market and man, has my view of cupcakes been changed! I loved every flavor of the flight, with favorites being the lemon lavender Chardonnay (which I mistakenly thought at first was an actual glass of lemon lavender Chardonnay to go with the cupcakes HAHA. But a girl can wish right?) and the salted caramel pretzel cupcake. 

What I love about these cupcakes is the size, intricacy and uniqueness of each cupcake in the flight. It was a delight to look at, but even more of a delight to eat them. Moist, with a delicious cream in the middle that leaves you feeling surprised that it's so good. 

I took my flight in the cute little egg carton that they package the cupcakes in to go urban wine tasting and had many people ask me where I had gotten all those lovely looking cupcakes from. They must have had the drunchies for some awesome cupcakes! Can't wait to try their other flavors :)

This is a fun new spot by The Mill on Haley. They have a  'PIY' (pour it yourself) wine system and feature small production wines. They also have beer on tap and a nice food menu.

Try their grilled cheese sandwiches! The Pulled Pork with Caramelized onion and Fontina was very tasty and the couple next to us were raving about the Wild Mushroom and Truffle flatbread.

We have seen the owner Michael in there on the two occasions we were in there and he is very personable and friendly. 

Come support a local business! Cheers to it's success!

column11:
Had dinner there last week with some friends.  Couldn't decide between the venison (which the waiter recommended) or the duck (which I have trouble passing up when I am at a good French restaurant).  I ended up going with the duck and it was fantastic.  My buddy opted for the Venison which was great as well.  Everything from the starters to the main course to the wine list was top notch.

Highly recommended!  Overall, one of the best I have been to.

column11: Blenders is easily my favorite smoothie in the SB area. Far better than any Jamba smoothie I've ever had. Their smoothies are smooth and creamy, and tast rich and fresh. Of all the smoothies I've tried here, my regular is the Red Pineapple. The simple mix of pineapple and strawberries is deliciously sweet. A lot of people love the Pink Lady, which isn't on the posted menu, so make sure to check out their secret drinks that they keep in their nutritional facts binder.

column11:
Every Sunday, my family drives to Santa Barbara for the beach, the sun, and the surf. But one of the best parts about our beach day is ordering food from Padaro Beach Grill. I can't say enough how this restaurant brings me and my family pure joy. The food is fantastic, of the best quality, yet not overpriced. My kids love the burgers, my wife is a huge fan of the veggie burger, and the fried Baja fish tacos topped with the smoked tarter sauce are MY favorite. We always order online and the order is ready when they say it will be. They always offer condiments at pick-up, which is a nice touch, and there's always a smile to go along with the food. 

Some people say it's the little things in life that make life worthwhile- when it comes to this phenomenal little restaurant tucked next to the ocean, I'd say that's an observation proven true.

column11: Mark is an amazing chef. His food is consistently delicious and jaw dropping. He's passionate about his craft and it shows in each bite. I've eaten several meals prepared by Mark and each one has left me full but wanting more. His multi course masterpieces where each step complements and contrasts the previous one are masterfully executed, every time. He's prepared food I thought I hated or never imagined I would like and turned me into a lifelong fan of them.

column11:
This place was great! 
Loved the view while eating brunch, and the food was delicious. Several chooses to choose from on their menu, I had an omelette and my significant other had pancakes with chocolate chips and a side of fruit. The pancakes were so good! Probably the best I've had(and I'm not a fan of pancakes). And their orange juice!! Definitely order some orange juice. I think it's homemade, kind of pricey but worth it. 
Overall, go! And enjoy the beautiful scenery!

column11: what an amazing and super filling breakfast/lunch joint!  I have tried other Cajun Kitchen locations, and this is my favorite by far. I went on a sunny Saturday, and even though it was packed, we were seated and served coffee within 5 minutes( I was in a group of 4). We had prompt customer service and the food....OHHH MY. At my table we had: the cajun style jumbalaya with two over easy eggs (shrimp, hot sausage in the jumbalaya was so hearty, spicy and amazing. We also had the eggs benedict add avocado and the hollandaise sauce was fantastic! Very flavorful. Lastly, the corn beef hash was nothing less than perfect, amazing flavor and very tasty. I will be a regular!

column11: We thought we would enjoy trying out the new restaurant and weren't disappointed.  The tri tip sandwich was excellent.  We also really enjoyed the steak and blue bite appetizers...tender cuts of steak with crumbled blue cheese.  Additionally, the dinner salads that came with our meals were the best I have ever had.  Overall all of the food was awesome.  Yes, the service was a little challenging, but as a newly opened restaurant that is to be expected.  The new owners have done great things with the decor and the patio is amazing!  I can see great things happening at this place.  We will definitely be back!

column11:
I enjoy going to this place. One thing that stuck out the most for ne was their excellent customer service. Almost every worker came by our table and helped us out weather it was to give us water or handing us our food. This place is definitely one of a kind. 

I love it when they have that special time in the day when everyone sings together to a classic jazz song. When I was there we sang "wonderful world" by Louis Armstrong. 

Their food is good too. This place is prolly the first place I've really started liking cajun. Their pasta are all good. And their little muffins they serve as appetizers are  soooo good! I can get full off them alone. 

Overall good experience.

column11: We went for fish tacos and margaritas and sort of a last hurrah last night and have to say that the experience was easy, "safe" and the food was delicious. I had a shrimp taco. The drink was stiff and didn't disappoint. What I really want to comment on was the kindness and joyfulness of one employee in particular. Mason. Smiling ear to ear and thankful for our business. He made our night! Keep it up, Mason. And see you next time we are at the harbor.

column11:
Fine dining at reasonable prices. What more can you ask for.

My wife and I almost always go here, either for lunch or dinner. Wife loves the Scallop spinach salad. Me I am a slut when it comes to this menu and will eat anything and walk away happy. The pizzas are great. Seafood fresh. Yum Yum Yum.

The wine list is excellent and has many great California wines and they are priced well.

In a town of great restaurant Opal is a standout.

column11:
Excellent service
Delicious, seasonal food

My favorite restaurant in the Santa Barbara area.  Unlike the 5 Points location, the Goleta one has ample, hassle-free parking.   They have tons of seating inside and out.  

The menu has fresh, seasonal ingredients.  They have daily specials in addition to their regular menu.  My husband enjoys their pasta dishes and halibut fish and chips.  I love their quiches, salads and sandwiches.  Their fresh made soups are delicious and flavorful.  My favorite is the corn chowder.

Best dessert - the chocolate mousse "ball".  I forget the actual name of it, but you'll know it when you look in the pastry case.  

Also - a great venue for private parties.  I hosted my mother's birthday there and they did a fabulous job.  We've used them numerous times for catering as well and have always been satisfied.

column11:
I am going against my strict policy of not reviewing fast food restaurants but yesterday I was at In-N-Out Burgers and had a Double Double with ANIMAL FRIES!    Why didn't anyone ever tell me about Animal Fries before???    Animal Fries are fries with cheese, grilled onions and animal sauce (like thousand island or McDonalds "special sauce")   So good, will probably kill me in less than a week, bus SO good!   

You can also order your burger "animal".  Next time.

column11:
What a great location, right across from the beach.  You can enjoy a cup of coffee and feel the sea breeze through your hair.

I stopped here for breakfast on my way up north.  Fresh squeezed OJ, mimosas (I didn't have one, but they are made with fresh OJ, so they are probably great), an excellent Bloody Mary, with a very nice little breakfast menu.  I enjoyed my omelet, filled with real crab, avocados and jack cheese.  And my partner liked his eggs Benedict, with a nice thick slice of ham.

It is a little on the pricey side, but this is Santa Barbara, right across from the beach

column11:
Longboard's having a 3-star rating is exactly why you should take Yelp reviews with a large grain of salt - except mine, of course, which are always super spot on. The rating is laughable because Longboard's is ON THE PIER, with the best views of any restaurant in the city. Sure the burgers are $15. You know who else has $15 burgers? Every sit down restaurant in SB. And you're staring at the harbor instead of a brick wall with a fern on it in the funk zone. And the portion is legit instead of that $15 silver dollar sized lamb slider you just ordered. And you are ON THE PIER. 

I'll stop shouting now, but if you're gonna pay the $300 a night to stay in SB, grab a beverage and some delicious food here. You'll feel like you're on vacation. Or if you're lucky enough to live here, bring your visitors here. Then for dinner you can shell out $45 for that really fancy hard-boiled egg poached kale-loin with the fancy garnish and salt that comes in its own little dish with its own little spoon, because you had a real meal for lunch.

column11:
I've been hearing rave reviews about this place's food so I ventured over with a friend 2 times to see what all the hype was about.

1st Time: Apparently we walked in 15 minutes prior to closing, so the lady (owner) rudely yelled at us to get out. Definitely left me a bad taste in my mouth but I kinda get it since most places need you to come in 30 mins prior to closing. Whatever.

2nd Time: We came in an hour or so prior to closing time. Lady let us sit down but blurted that we had to hurry and order....no idea why that is so since we gave them more than 30 mins of preparation time. Anyways, I ordered my usual at Vietnamese places - charboiled beef over broken rice. I don't know if it's because they were rushed to close or what, but I received the smallest portion of beef ever - literally thin slices (6 max or so) over a large bed of rice. Are you serious? And to bring back the bad taste in my mouth from my first visit, the lady rushed us once again, rudely asking us to hurry up. I barely set down my chopsticks after sifting through what was good on my plate when the lady made a beeline for my table, grabbing my plate away while curtly asking, "You done? Done eating?" YEAH, I AM DONE....SINCE YOU JUST GRABBED THE PLATE FROM ME.

Taste of the food is alright, not too sure about the actual pho vermicelli/noodle stuff since I'm not a fan of traditional pho cuisine. However, the stingy portions put me off and the attitude of the owner here is in dire need of a change. You won't draw in diners with that type of attitude.

Overall though, I don't get why people rave about this place. I guess since it's SB and there's no legit Asian food around, everyone goes bananas. Either that or I'm spoiled for having grown up in the 626 area. Whichever way it goes, I won't be coming back here. If you are a UCSB student, I reckon you find a time or weekend to make a day trip to LA - get some legit Asian food or pho (whatever you want) - I guarantee afterwards, you will never come back to this place!

column11:
My friend and I experienced the rudest service of our lives at M. Special. On the night of April 21st, my friend and I visited to watch the Washington Capitals/Toronto Maple Leafs hockey game. During the first two periods of the game, we both drank two beers each. In the third period, one of the bartenders was nice enough to give us a couple samples out of the blue, which was much appreciated. Finally, with five minutes left in the game another bartender noticed our sample glasses, and came over to ask us if we wanted some 'big boy beers.' This  already seemed strangely antagonistic, and we declined as we were both driving after the game. Immediately, he went to the television and changed the channel away from the hockey game. We thought it might be a mistake, and asked that it be changed back, and he refused, saying it was 'kind of weird' that we weren't drinking any beers. 

We were both shocked and furious that he was being so petty and mean-spirited. We left the bar and missed the end of Game Five of a tied game in a tied series. This kind of service is just unfathomably rude and completely outside of our experience. Needless to say, neither of us will be returning and we're encouraging all of our friends to patronage other, more friendly establishments.
