column11:
I think I've died and gone to vegan heaven!!

This place is AMAZING!!! I've been here twice and both meals were probably the tastiest meals I've eaten in a restaurant ALL YEAR. No joke.  I'm not even vegan and this place knocked my socks off (not to mention my picky boyfriend's).

So far I've tried:
Appetizer nachos: pretty good, I love the "cheese'
Eggplant Parmesan:  FABULOUS flavor and crunch on top of a bed of saucy noodles!
Quiche:  Melts-in-your-mouth, close-your-eyes GOOD!! just try it.
Adama AFC:  Tastes like home-made mozzarella sticks and yummy mashed taters.
BEST OF ALL: Pecan pie and almond ice cream... my mouth is still watering.

When I first pictured vegan food, I immediately thought, "vegetables, salads, bland flavors"... Boy was I WRONG.  Do yourself a favor and try this place.  You won't be disappointed! Can't wait to go back and try more :)

column11:
Had friends come in from out of town and they asked where to get great Italian food at. I recommended Chase of course. After we placed our order, one of us ordering the lamb medium rare.  The food was brought out and the lamb was well well done where you could barely cut it with a knife. There was no excuse for the lamb to be over cooked to that extent considering my friend ordered medium rare as it was written by our waitress. We called the waitress over showed her the very well done lamb and she whisked it up to let the cook no. In the meantime our friend sat there without her meal until what she ordered in the first place was remade as she patiently waited while watching us all eat. She insisted so our food wouldn't get cold. 
  I was embarrassed because I recommended Chase to our friends who traveled 2 1/2 hours and there was no apology or a care in the world or can we offer her a slice of pie for her inconvenience, but yet was told by our waitress she called Jack the owner and he said no discount for them!!! Wow! It wasn't about looking for free food or a discount it was about the moral of the situation Chase restaurant and lounge. We have been loyal customers for a long time but after this, not any longer. I'm a true believer in making things right when things go wrong!

All in all love this place!

column11:
On our way to Santa Barbara we saw that traffic was getting heavy and decided to pull of the freeway to have breakfast. 

Our first time in Summerland and I was charmed by the "village feeling" of Summerland, such a breath of fresh air when living in LA. 
No matter how great LA can be, I sometimes just crave silence, small-town-feelilng and  have to get out of the city. 

Summerland Beach Cafe appeared to be quite a popular place, very very charming. 
We ended up on the terrace, shaded by a wonderful big old tree. 
Before we knew we were served a big cup of coffee by a friendly smiling waitress. 

I was not too hungry, but still ordered the Eggs Benedict and before I knew my plate was empty. 
The eggs are very tasty, excellent Hollandaise Sauce and fresh, fresh, fresh.

My husband ordered the Waffle and that was -to me- a seriously big waffle. It came with a choice of fruit, he had the flambeed bananas. 
Delicious and for those with serious sweet teeth an absolute must on the menu. 

If I would live closer I would visit this place regularly and sit with a book or newspaper under the tree while sipping coffee and enjoying breakfast or lunch. 

I can highly recommend to try this out.

I usually work at night so the majority of the time I come here is during the day.  I like to come in and try something new on there extensive menu.  Haven't had a bad meal which is why I continuously come back for lunch.   
This place is a far cry from what it was 3-5 years ago in the sense that the staff has seriously been upgraded. Before I would have to poke my head in to see who was working and either keep walking or come on in.  Now I know I can just walk in no matter who's behind the bar.  
Also make sure to try there breakfast/mimosa deal on weekend mornings. Probably the best deal you can get in town for that combo.  Favorite thing I've tried so far for lunch has been the jalapeo burger. Keep it up guys

column11:
I came here on a recommendation from a friend so I decided to check it out while I was in the area. We walked in during lunch time on a Saturday and we were surprised to see an empty restaurant. 

The waitress told us the portions are huge, so we decided to just share one half order of pasta. We went with the grilled chicken & brie capellini. It seemed a little pricey but once it came out, we understood why. The portions are enormous. Even while sharing a half order, we still had leftovers to take home. 

The garlic knots weren't that good. I love garlic knots but they somehow ruined it. I couldn't exactly put my finger on why it wasn't good. It's just, something about it was off. Same with the pasta. I was very disappointed in our whole meal in general. The pasta was overloaded with salt that I had to take several sips of water after each bite. There was also some kind of spice they used that just didn't go well with it at all. The quality of the food was similar to a mess hall.

We were here for an hour and half during peak lunch hours and no one else came into the restaurant. I guess it was cheap considering how much food we got out of the meal, but you get what you pay for.

column11:
Top tier tri-tip. Can't make the drive out to Santa Maria or Firestone Grill in SLO? Stop by Shalhoob's instead.

They're located in the Funk Zone, but very off the beaten path. It's a very interesting mix of single family residences and businesses on this street, with the street itself feeling like a large alleyway. Parking is free for all; basically park anywhere your car will fit and make your own spot, but don't block the driveways.

The patio menu consists of tacos, sandwiches, burgers, salads, and barbecue dishes. Since it was my first time, I had to get their signature tri-tip sandwich. First off, the quality of the meat was phenomenal. Each slice was medium rare and cooked evenly, with a nice pink hue. Combined with pico de gallo, garlic bread, and a dab of barbecue sauce, this sandwich was bursting with flavor. It was served with a side of fries (you can choose salad instead), which were hot and crispy to my liking.

Their Mac N Cheese is awesome, probably one of the best renditions I've tasted so far. It's super creamy and heavenly, and topped with extra bread crumbs on top for good measure. Using Orecchiette pasta was also a unique touch.

They also have a butcher shop on-site with various poultry selections, cuts of beef, sausages, pork items, and wild game (bison, boar, buffalo) to mention a few. Definitely something to look into if you're planning a special dinner and as the holiday season kicks into high gear.

column11:
I went to this restaurant twice, but only ended up eating the second time. 

The first run with Meun Fan was a complete disaster. My party was lazily motioned over to an empty table, where we sat at and went unattended to for the next 10 minutes. My party wasn't given a waiter and even when we tried to initiate some kind of reaction from the staff ourselves, we remained ignored. This was perplexing to us, especially since the place was not very busy, so we simply got up and left the restaurant. 

My second time with the same group of people was a far better experience. This time we prepared a little more by calling in a reservation. Upon arrival we were seated in an already set up table and promptly received a waitress. The waitress was just fine and from the last experience it was almost just a relief to be talked to at all by the staff. The food turned out to be excellent. All of my party was happy with a mixture of dishes ordered; curries, noodle plates, chow mien. The Thai iced tea was also refreshing and slightly above average portion sizes of the food were provided. The prices were competitive, if not some of the cheaper Thai food you'll find in the area. 

I would be happy to give this restaurant higher than 3 stars had it not been for the very poor service that we received on our first trip to Meun Fan.

column11:
This is a play by play review:

We arrived at 7:20 for our 7:30 reservation. It's a Friday evening and place is packed: a good sign. I had to use the restroom and asked one of the hostesses for directions and she walked me there! Very very good start. It's 7:45 now and we are still waiting. Don't mind it too much as I am not famished, and it's a great spot to people watch when it's this crowded. Heat lamps are on and the two fire places and fully lit. Every table is taken and the aroma of deep fried then broiled Brussel sprouts is in the air. The management is quite visible here; broad shouldered ... Hmmm looks like he is my size and a half tall, so he gotta be Blake Griffin tall, making his rounds and scoping out the entire establishment for unwanted guests... he's actually politely escorting a lost transient now away from the restaurant! Eventful!

Got seated at 7:54. I was entertained so really  didn't mind. Our table is in the back, facing the opened side French door. This is such a lovely place: no bright lights , only string lights giving off enough illumination to see people's faces and your food. Kind of romantic ... except for the noise. Heat lamps are everywhere. 

Coffee,Belgian beer, and hazel nut beer. All good. 

Beet salad - beautifully arranged and delicious. Yellow and red beets, a few leaves of basil and mint, grilled strawberry halves, and caramelized hazel nuts. I would order this again. 

Wedge salad - they use the lettuce hearts here instead of the typical full lettuce heads. Instead if being drowned in blue cheese dressing, it is lightly coated with a vinaigrette dressing with blue cheese crumbs, glazed whole pecans, and crispy cubes of pork belly. Very nice. Hubby didn't care for it as much as I, but that's his problem.

Brussel sprouts - heard about Bouchon's Brussel  sprouts being better from one other yelper... not sure that's even  possible. Can't really describe it except that it's really really good. And I think it would be really good with a bowl of white rice!

Pork chops - their special. It was okay. The server who brought this to our table spent a good deal of time telling us what was on the plate. And it was complicated. It has good flavor, but it was served room temperature, soft and dry. Served with homily .. salty, just not sure what to make of it. And there was this green sauce that I could not figure out its flavor. The presentation was very nice though. I would not order this again.

Chicken - full very juicy baked chicken with crispy skin, served  on a bed of grit that had been prepared like mashed potatoes with a kick. Ham hock, pickled okra, and frise leaves were the side kicks. This is a five star chicken. Side kicks get 3.5 stars as I would like to have more non-salty veggies as side kicks to offset the saltiness of the grit. 

I would come back just for the service here. Lori and Matt were our servers. They never left us in need of anything, aside from being pleasant and knowledgeable with our orders. Throughout the evening, servers, bust people, and the management were everywhere. Everyone was efficient, polite, and attentive. I totally understand why this establishment is so highly rated. 

The only recommendation to make this a 6-star place is cushions for chairs. My bony butt hurt sitting so long on their metal chairs.  Killing me.

column11:
My now husband and I got married in Santa Barbara on November 5, 2016. We had a small intimate wedding of 70 guests at the Santa Barbara Courthouse with a cocktail reception that followed at Cadiz Restaurant and Lounge. 

We knew very early on that we wanted to get married at the Santa Barbara Courthouse, but really had no direction as to where to have our reception. I went to the internet, and Cadiz was mentioned a few times. I sent an e-mail through the website, and received a phone call within a hour. After speaking with Messina for 20-30 minutes, I scheduled a time where my fiance and I could meet her and check out her restaurant. Unbenounced to us, she had a full tasting prepared for us upon our arrival. The food and drinks were superb, and we loved the look and ambiance of the restaurant. It was really important to us to have our reception at a location with a lot of character because I didn't want to spend money decorating it... Cadiz is beautiful!!! It has a lot of exposed brick which I love. 

A few days later, my fiance and I made the final decision to have our reception at Cadiz. When we booked, I had to pay for the price in full. That covered a valet parking, an open bar and food for the number of guests we had planned on inviting. I was very unsure about paying in full, but it all worked out. 

Shortly after booking, we asked Messina for a DJ recommendation. She booked someone for us that she worked with a lot. We didn't meet him until the day of the wedding, but he was awesome!!! Everyone was raving about DJ Calvin Riley.

After all the plans were set in place, Messina and I didn't really talk until the week before the wedding. At that time, we reviewed the wedding details and just made sure we were on the same page for the weekend. 

Our event was flawless!!! The food and drinks were on point. Messina is very professional, and she frequently checked in with me throughout the night. If anyone is looking to do a small reception in Santa Barbara, I would highly recommend Cadiz. Messina knows how to throw a party!

column11: Finally a poke place in Isla Vista. I have gone here a couple times and have accumulated 5 stamps. The decor and environment is okay. Nothing special just a basic set up with chairs and tables. I came in on Sunday night and the employees are helpful and the value is good however the tuna as of late has been tasting off. I don't know how to describe but the tuna does not have the correct texture tuna has. The salmon is okay and the albacore is as well. However I'm more worried about the tuna because it is my favorite fish. I like how you get seaweed salad and spicy tuna or spicy crab as sides. You're basically getting extra protein for the same value as the other poke places. The rice here is clumpy I don't think it's that great but my girlfriend thinks it's alright. Overall this is the best poke place in goleta. Way better than pokemee which overcharges for everything and pokeceviche with even worse rice and although they do have more variety in rice and noodles they taste way off.

column11:
My wife and I have been going to Aldo's for over 4 years. We went there for lunch for the first time (we've always had dinner there) and were very surprised to discover (when I checked in on Yelp) that our favorite Italian Restaurant has 2.5 stars!!! WTH!? 
Now I know my review can't restore Aldo's to it's former glory but at least it's a start. Here is why I think you should give Aldo's a second shot:
1) They are under new management (as of January 1, 2011 it has been 1 month under new ownership)
2) Our waiter was very professional and helpful. In terms of attentiveness he gets 4 stars because at the end of my meal my Coke was empty (not really a big deal I was done...and he was training a new waiter by himself while running the whole floor...)
3) I got the Blackened Salmon Sandwich (1/2) with Sword Fish Chowder and both were very good, flavorful and in the perfect portions.
My wife got the Fetuccinni Alfredo in the half portion and she couldn't finish it all. A very generous portion. 
4) The prices were very reasonable $21 for lunch for 2 with drinks (non-alcoholic).
5) The outdoor seating area is great, nice fountain for ambiance and perfect for people watching. 

So there, give it a shot, don't let the previous owner ruin your chance to enjoy a great meal at Aldo's.

column11:
Been super solid as far as the ingredient quality, the staff kindness, and despite the need for shorter spring break hours, I've managed to go in make a new fan out of my boyfriend he's visiting from the East Coast. He absolutely loved his custom selection this evening and mine was delicious as well.

I highly recommend the customization, I love it in wheat with pesto/sauted spinach/ mushrooms /cucumber/red onion/artichoke hearts/a fried egg and avocado... 

The portion is really large and they use the pulled out inside of the bread bowl as well as the sliced off top to make super yummy garlic bread that saves well if you get too full and a need a snack later!

Love the later extended hours during the normal school year and really have been enjoying the strawberry basil change... Picnic style bench tables inside and out relax chill atmosphere with wall murals and a low-key vibe, 

I prefer takeout but if you need to get out of your apartment or are here on a vacation and it's right across from a park and you can even go over and have a little picnic by the water wheel and the pond...
Yum yum!!!

column11: I am so thrilled to find Uncorked during the pandemic. We have ordered gourmet takeout dinners twice and they are phenomenal: perfectly tender salmon, abundant, smoky brisket, incredible ahi salad, chocolaty desserts. The amazing thing is the price, which is about the same as pizza takeout for a five-star meal. I received excellent advice at the wine counter about a local Pinot noir to go with scallops. The service is wonderful. These are creative local businesspeople working tremendously hard during a challenging time. Let's support them enthusiastically.

column11:
Prices have increased so honestly, you'd get more bang for your buck if you and your friend are getting two kids acai bowls, might as well share a small or medium instead. 

I like the Island Bowl personally because pineapple and coconut are bomb. They top your acai bowl with strawberries, blueberries, banana, granola, honey and shreds of coconut. I don't normally like coconut shreds but it compliments the bowl with texture. 
I highly recommend getting this and sitting on the tables outside on a nice sunny day. 

This place is pretty hyped up but it's worth to at least try it once.

column11: Very nice location, i'd get a reservation or opt to sit at the bar.  Everything here is fresh, just don't be caught off guard by the prices, paying for what you get, which is excellent food, but you are also across the street from the ocean (so pretty much every spot has a ocean view) and everyone knows that Santa Barbara isn't the cheapest place either.  They do have a happy hour which if you are looking for a quick and small bite with a beer, what we did, this place is a good choice, won't break the bank and is good.  The service from the hostess to the bartender were quick and professional.  Overall, its a good place to go.  If you are price sensitive hit their happy hour or check out another spot.  It also would be a great place to take a date if you are looking for seafood based meals.  Good luck!

column11:
I have been employed by the Albertsons in Carpinteria for 4 weeks as a front end person.  I am a 75 year old Lady and I wanted to work about 20 hours a week the more hours that I work then i would loose my SSA and medicare. 
I have talked to the women supervisor and all she does is you are doing what I say your hours are and I will not change them. Every shift that I work and she is on also she will tap me on my shoulder to say you just make so many mistakes, I replied to her I sweep the floors and do the carts and  human poop in the restroom with no gloves. I think that this is not right!
Today Went in to talk to Mr Martinez the store Manager this was his reply
dam it, you do so many mistakes and about my hours the remark was I will not change them, Are these concern for me, dam it yes. I feel that they treated me unfair and force me into quitting my job. I love all the customers they just love me.  I just do not like the discrimination that they have shown towards me.  Gladys Robinson Carpinteria

column11: Used to be so good, even just a short time ago. Just got home with the most paltry burritos of anywhere in town. That used to not be the case. This was one of my sons favorite places to get a BRC burrito and usually they were delicious and very filling. Tonight for some reason it was the thinnest layer of beans, rice and cheese and a lot of tortilla. The $11 veggie burrito was shamefully also the slimmest layers  of beans, rice, cheese and some old, mushy  tomato inside a tortilla. Potato taquitos were good so that's worth the two stars. I'm hoping it was an off night as I've never had this experience before, but to be honest not sure I want to spend 30 bucks to go back and find out. There are really too many great places in town to risk going back for the same disappointment.

column11: This might be the most beautiful store in Santa Barbara!  It is so magical!  And beautiful! The Turkish delights are delicious!  Not too sweet - and the flavors are wonderfully exotic!  I want to buy all of them!  I bought a box for my friends birthday- I know she will love it!  It was recommended to me by my son-in-law - he said the Delights were out if this world and he was right! I will come back many times I know and wish the general manager the very best of success for his kindness, openness, hospitality and for a beautiful store and letting me try some of this amazing candy!  They have other desserts as well and also traditional Turkish coffee and tea- next time!

column11: This is my new favorite restaurant in the world. We tried the soup,  which was a delicious puree of mushrooms with vegetables. The flat bread has a seasoning called satar. It is a mix of herbs,  sesame seeds and salt. It is TO DIE FOR. The street tacos are made with home made tortillas! The Caesar salad had huge caper berries and a delicious cashew dressing. We ate so much!  Including the empanadas, pumpkin cheesecake, chocolate cake,  chai tea and prosecco. By the way,  the Pumkin cheesecake had a tiny sprinkling of thyme on one corner,  served over marigold flower petals and a coconut cream canelle. Did I spell that right? It doesn't matter!  The food was beyond delicious. It was such a wonderful experience! !!!!!!! Thank you thank you thank you. And one final thank you to Rami, for guiding us through it.

column11: Came to visit Santa Barbara with some friends and came across this place. Sarah pulled my friends and I in by greeting us as we walked by and asking us if we were hungry. She was so sweet, we were won over! Their happy hour is amazing. For anyone visiting or passing through, you have to check it out. You can get basically any drink buy one get another one for a QUARTER. And the vibe is laid back with awesome staff. The guys and I are definitely stopping by whenever we pass through again. TRY THE WINGS you'll be hooked.

column11:
I was driving on the 101 and wanted to stop in SB to have healthy food.  I found Silvergreens to be quick and healthy with a wide variety of menu options.  

I wish we had a Silvergreens in LBC, its quick like a take away chicken place crossed with super healthy food.  The receipt even has the calorie, protein and health food numbers similar to labeling of store products so you know what you are eating.  

I will be back again.

do yourself a favor a try this spot!

column11: The sushi is good, but the place is super tiny crowded. Don't expect to have a romantic or private conversation here. It's really dark so bring your glasses and a flashlight to read the menu. The sushi is always good and fresh and the presentation is beautiful but you pay for the location. There are better sushi places in Santa Barbara, but if you want to stay in Montecito for sushi you will get good sushi at a premium. If there is a wait you'll have to wait outside or stand next to someone's table, and I don't think it worth the wait, unless like I said your in Montecito and don't want to go into SB. I sort of recommend this place.

column11:
Y'all. The ideal local coffee shop is Old Town Coffee! Close parking, plenty of seating, fair prices, tons of accessible outlets, dog-friendly patio, and AMAZING coffee!

My husband and I were excited about having another local coffee shop nearby, and we love that this place is located on Hollister in Old Town. There is street parking available and a public parking lot about one block away, which is quite convenient.

The vibe here is welcoming and it's suitable for families, study groups, coffee dates, and all types of people. There are seriously plenty of areas to sit in, too, depending on the purpose of your drop in! I enjoy bringing my dog and sitting on the back patio near the corn hole set-up. The patio tables and umbrellas make it really comfortable to enjoy my Brule Mint tea.

And for you grad students out there: OUTLETS. There are plenty of outlets stationed throughout the space, so you can settle in, order several drinks, and finally work on that paper you've been putting off without your computer dying.

One of my favorite things is that Old Town uses Rise Coffee Roasters and these beans are *the best* I've had in Santa Barbara/Goleta. They're not too dark, not harshly acidic, and each blend has a distinct flavor. In other words, these beans make good coffee and espresso in every application! Bags of beans are a great price, and the drinks themselves are a great price, too. And the Old Town Coffee baristas have also been pretty consistent in their beverage execution. Or if it's not perfect, let them know! They'll happily help you get the best beverage possible.

The owners, Tim & Rachel, are kind souls. Tell them hi, become a regular, and support their hard work!

No bike racks out front, but I'm sure you'd be able to wheel your bike to the back to rest on the back patio!

column11:
Customer service gets 5 stars. I can't remember our server's name but she's a beautiful red head from Dublin, Ireland. 

We ordered two starters the sauted shrimp and the crab cakes. The sauted shrimp are a 10+. Absolutely fabulous so we ordered them again with our meal. The crab cakes came to the table luke warm at best. More were brought to us but honestly the heat didn't help them. They're more filler than crab. Skip them. 

We ordered one entree the halibut with twice baked potato (and another order of the sauted shrimp). The halibut is delicious. So was the potato but we were too stuffed to finish the potato. 

As a treat we were surprised with cheesecake for our Anniversary. 

This is a nice restaurant to people watch if you're sitting outside or if you're table is in the front window. 

I would definitely go again.

column11:
Rusty's came through for us late night when us East Coast kids were starving and weren't used to the early bed times for most West Coast restaurants.

We tried both the thin crust & pan crust - Rusty's Special in a 48 hour window.  Both were delicioys, but I highly reccomend the "Rusty's Special" in a THIN crust, no olives, add bell peppers - flipping delicious on my hotel bed!  Tasted very similar to Round Table Pizza.  Lots of juicy meat.

The guy taking my order was hilarious and I think if I met him on the streets we'd be serious friends.

FAST delivery.  If you don't have any utensils make sure you ask for them as we had to get craft w/our salad that came delivered with no fork.

column11:
I split the Cowboy Burger with fries with a friend and we also got the onion rings. This place rocks. Everything was so good. I don't generally get excited over burgers because they're really hard to mess up, but once in a while you have one that stands out. This was it.  I asked for the BBQ sauce that the burger comes with on the side because I'm particular about where I put BBQ sauce and I found this burger was better without it. But that's just a matter of taste.  The onion rings are the super wide onion kind, they're serious onions, like the kind you use a fork and knife with.  They were good and so were the fries. 

We were seated immediately and our young college boy servers were attentive - perhaps a bit too attentive.  We felt like we were getting interrupted a lot for silly questions and check-ins on how we were doing. Also, one guy grabbed a plate while my friend's hand was on it picking up fries and dipping them in the ketchup - he's grabbing it asking her if she's done when she's clearly still eating.  Hello!  

This place got really busy, so it's clear it's a favorite.

column11:
After reading Angelo's review and knowing I was going to be visiting Santa Barbara, I decided to visit Tupelo Junction.  I was there for the late afternoon time about an hour before closing.  There was a large festival going on outside, tons of well-dressed people going to a theater event just outside the door, and yet despite this, there were not a lot of people in the cafe.

It's not a good sign that an eatery would be nearly empty with a crowd outside, but I figured it's the end of the day and that's probably why.

Our amazingly attractive waitress Rachel helped us with our order ("My pleasure," she says).  We both ordered a salad (can't remember the name of it right now!) and the greens were quite fresh with a vinagrette dressing.  There were no choices on dressings though -- it's vinagrette or nothing, I guess. 

I loved the little biscuits!  Tasted like pancakes! 

The water drinks use little mason jars.  I noticed this in other places throughout Central CA; little mason jars seem to be the "in" thing. 

After this brunch I ordered the apple pie and ice cream.  And then waited.  And waited.  And waited.  After a friendly reminder to the waitress, it finally arrived.  Realize that the dining area was nearly EMPTY so there's really no excuse. 

Pros:  Delicious salads and dessert, friendly staff.  And those biscuits and the ambiance (the cute tables and chairs, the posters, the colorful water cans and so on). 

Cons:  Waiting forever for a dessert.  Oh, also there was another server gossiping on her cell phone just inside the dining room.  Woman, take the call outside, not where customers can hear you! 

Somewhat recommended if you got nowhere else to go on State Street!

column11:
Hit or miss! First time I went, it was with a new person, and I was impressed. I think we were both confused if it was a date or just a hang out... Either way, the first time around I liked the food enough to want to revisit! 
Several months later I went with my current boyfriend (different man) as a treat for his promotion and unfortunately discovered that my first experience had over-exaggerated the flavors of the food in my mind.
He loves prosciutto so we ordered the Prosciutto di Parma and found it very salty! We make this dish at home sometimes, but I had to eat twice as much melon to counterbalance the salt and we quickly ran out of melon. 
He also loves broccolini so we ordered the Broccolini with capers. Same story! The broccolini was cooked to an almost burnt crisp and covered in salt... I found it hard to eat and could only really get through it with the complimentary foccacia. I don't send food back, but perhaps I should have. I was embarrassed, but my boyfriend was being a good sport about it all! 
We ordered the Maitake Mushroom (with extra arugula) and Pepperoni Pizzas. Other than the fact that the pepperoni pizza was dripping in grease, it was tasty, but not the best.  
I don't know if it's because we were there on a Wednesday night and the A-team wasn't in the kitchen, but I was not impressed by the food, only the service and the atmosphere. 
The bar is great and the staff is great, but I will not be returning for the food.

column11: This place has an amazing atmosphere and really great drinks. They always have some vinyl playing of an awesome old jazz album. Ideally, I would give it a 5. However, they often only have one bartender. The place is rarely packed (except late on friday or saturday), so one bartender works. But here and there, it does get crowded and if it does, you may end up waiting a half hour to even order a drink (because each cocktail takes much longer than popping the top off a beer). So, DO NOT bring a big group (which will arrive at the same time). You will wait forever to get a drink.

column11:
I have recently been in World Market and have had the pleasure of having sales person Courtney help me. I had a project I was working on  with college students to show them how to eat healthy foods with little or no cooking. Courtney took the time to walk the aisles with me and give me excellent suggestions. I was incredible grateful. She made my life much easier as I did not have to go to any other store. 

I returned on July 4th as we were were hosting a very big party that day and once again Courtney was on the floor. This time she helped me in the wine department. Her suggestions were excellent and fitted our budget perfectly. She made my day! BRAVO to her and to World Market!

column11:
After a surf session at Hendry's my oldest son and I decided to have breakfast at the Beachbreak. I have fond memories of this place when it was called The Come Back cafe. It became the Beach Break a few years ago. The restaurant itself has indoor booth and table seating (a few flat screens hanging about, muted). They also offer outdoor seating under a large alcove. 

It's a nice, casual, dog friendly location with fairly easy parking located across the street in the city lot. The menu offers the basics (pancakes, french toast, eggs, bacon) as well as the attempted reinvented. Such as Beachbreak Benedict. A lunch menu is also offered in standard fair and flair. All menu items are offered anytime until close. The food is common variety american diner. 

The location is nice and bright with a lot of large windows without direct sun. About 25 tables inside and out. However, based on my latest experience, if more than 7 or 8 tables are occupied I would suggest another restaurant. Simply put, the staff needs a lead waitress or waiter. They seem to have enough personnel,  just very poor communication, with almost comical floor disorganization. 

When we arrived there was no wait for tables, though nor were there any clean tables. Not to worry, we were in no hurry, but after being told to sit anywhere (remember there were no - none - zero clean tables) we waited a good 5 minutes at our chosen table for it to be cleaned. Which, It doesn't sound like a long time, but it is when you're face to face with someones waded paper napkin soaking up whatever is left of their egg and hash combo plate along with their food impacted  fork pointing at you -  mocking your every move. Relief appeared in the form of a busser and as he tidied our table he assured us someone would come by for our drink order ... drink order ? ... it's just juice and coffee, black simple, The cups and pot so close they would cast a shadow upon our heads if direct sunlight was available. Another 5 minutes or more pass and several muted tragic CNN stories later we are greeted by a server and asked our drink order, which as you already know if you got this far, it's coffee black and O.J.  We add to that poached eggs on rye, with bacon. My son requests the Pancakes and eggs. We settle in to another wait another 5 minutes (a pattern) for the cup of Joe to appear, and then correctly assume the food order will take at least 5 times as long.  

While waiting we're asked by two other servers and the original bus boy if we would like something to drink. Clearly being an equal opportunity restaurant in regards to service, other not so patient diners get up and leave, with one asking to see the manager. Suddenly my attention is diverted from my wrist watch and/or attempts to lip-read CNN. "There is no manager" we over hear someone in the kitchen say. The customer leaves to join his departed group on the sidewalk, and as if on cue a waitress brings their food order to their table, now empty, though leaving the food to remain. Our order comes but not before seeing another table vs waitress order confusion, the show continues in that fashion. Our meal arrives edible. Though the toast cold, as were the poached eggs. It seems like a server issue, not a kitchen problem. I did feel bad for the waitresses, they were busy but the place wasn't stormed with customers. The floor staff appeared seemingly very unsure how to handle a workable number of tables. They indeed remained friendly to us, it just didn't seem like they knew what to do. 2 stars.

column11:
So my sister and were looking for a New Mexican restaurant to try yesterday as we usually go to Los Agaves but the only item we really like there is the ceviche. We were craving those street tacos that are delicious but not every place can make them well. We liked up Aaron Sanchez recommendations in SB and came across Monys. What a great find. We got there around 3 and there was a line and all seats were taken as seating is limited. But people are eating and leaving so up to you to wait for a table. I'm glad we took the small one inside next to the fabulous salsa bar. One was better than the other they had like 8 of them. Peanut salsa was my favorite it had a nice kick to it and went great on the tacos we ordered. Tried al pastor Asada and carnitas. Pastor was our favorite although all 3 were delicious. Loved the marination and flavors. The pineapple added a little something extra to the meat. The tortillas were fresh and had chewy texture. My kind of tortilla not the one that falls apart when you start biting into taco. Also the price was super reasonable like $1.75 each. They give you chips and salsa on the house. Staff was friendly and efficient. Can't wait to come back here. Definitely worth the drive from LA. So this place is in the Funk zone of SB but what was interesting that no local could tell us why or how it got its name but we found out how expensive the new condos are going for. Mucho mucho dinero!!!$$$$$$ 
Two thumbs up for Monys!!

column11:
I was looking for a new place to get lunch and luckily I saw that there was a Luna grill here.  I was out here for work in Santa Barbara and where I live in LA I haven't seen too many of these locations but when I was out in Oxnard I did see a location out there in the menu looked really good.

I placed my order online and it was really quick and easy to do. It said that my food to be ready in about 20 minutes. Once I've gone to the store they had shelves where I could pick up my food and lo and behold there it was. The design of the interior was really nice. A lot of people were opting to eat outside since it was a nice day out.

I ordered the Gyro combo and I was able to select a side and I went with the salad. The salad was amazing tons of delicious and colorful ingredients in it. There are a lot of different components in it and it was wonderful. The gyro itself was amazing as well and it was very filling. They toast the pita so there is an extra crunch to the texture of things and it all worked very well together.  I also got a baklava. I honestly could have eaten 20 of them but I only bought 1.

The food was amazing and I definitely will be checking out more of Luna Grill locations out whenever I'm back out here for work.

column11:
If you have ever strolled down State Street in Santa Barbara, then you are aware that it is the home of a plethora of both local and chain restaurants and cafes. It can be overwhelming to choose the "right" one for your eating/drinking/socializing needs. La Arcada is one of the many options to choose from. How does it stack up?

La Arcada is a cute bistro located on a corner real estate offering indoor and outdoor seating in an Irish meets Spanish- ambiance (which makes sense as the owner is Irish while his wife is Mexican). During the early afternoon, it is calm and inviting but apparently can get rowdy on weekends when there is live Irish music reverberating the air. Think: Irish bar meets cafe with rustic wood trim but stuccoed walls. 

Although La Arcada didn't have too many customers at the time of our patronage (between 2 and 3pm); I didn't feel quite that welcome. It isn't that the server and staff were rude per se; they just weren't that inviting. Not to mention: slow. Very, very slow. Despite this, we browsed the menu having not yet eaten lunch seeking some light fare. My boyfriend and I decided to share plates and went with the House Salad (Grilled chicken, fire-roasted red peppers, red onion, blue cheese, toasted pine nuts,red delicious apples and mixed greens tossed with balsamic vinaigrette-- $16.00) and the Irish Soda Bread (with Kerry Gold butter and Dubliner Cheese -- $6.00). Due to it being Happy Hour, we also shared a Bellini ($5.00). 

The key to La Arcada is presentation. The salad and bread arrived at the same time and had an elegant but approachable feel. The salad was absolutely delicious with just the right amount of vinaigrette, tender chicken, and veggies. Although it was enough for my boyfriend and I to share; I still think it was much overpriced though for the quantity. Not necessarily satisfying if you are very hungry. The Irish Soda bread was a good deal with plenty of bread and large slices of cheese. I found the bread to be a little dry (and I love Irish Soda bread so I've had it plenty of times). It wasn't awful but I wasn't blown away. The Bellini was a highlight though. It was tasty and strong which is great being that it was a happy hour price and sometimes restaurants water down drinks during those times. 

A minor note but still worth mentioning is that the bathroom is a single-stall meaning that you have to wait quite a long time if someone is inside. Plus, it is an awkward back of the house area next to run down soda machines. Not good if you really have to use the bathroom!

There honestly isn't much more to be said about La Arcada. The experience wasn't bad but also not memorable on the positive side; making it simply an okay medium-choice on State Street but not life-changing. If nothing else though, the outdoor seating is quaint with great views of State Street. I would say this is a hit or miss option in lovely Santa Barbara.

column11:
Most of the reviews for this place will be about a crazy busy night at the shitty kitty while being drunk off your ass trying to get some play....but I'm yelping about a great quiet night I spent with no-one but a few friends and a fantastic bartender.

I went here on Christmas Eve, hardly expecting anyone there, and I was right this place was downright empty....perfect. Yes its covered in red leather, but on a quiet night this place looks a little sexier. I sat down during their happy hour with $3.50 well drinks and started a fantastic evening with my good friend Peter and one of the best bartenders ever (whose name eludes me). First the bartender grabs a bowl of barnuts and asks for the drink, but then as we talk we begin a night of a simple crossword puzzle....yea I know its random, but you'll be surprised how fun they can be at bars. Then she asks what pizza we want.....yes...free pizza during happy hour. And when you're only one of a few people there you get to pick it and EAT IT ALL TO YOURSELF. I ended up spending a few hours here just having some small quiet fun in the early evening until it started to fill up and return to its shitty kitty status.

So even if you're down for a quiet night....check out the same place you may enjoy the crazy ones.

column11:
One of the best restaurants in SB. Great food, menu options and excellent beer. Amount of spice/heat was perfect. 
Restaurant was packed on Thursday night. Service held up well when busy. Gracious and polite service, yes it's still possible. Owner/Chef cares about your experience. He puts food quality and service above all else. Does not use oil, butter and uses very little salt. Definately a big step above a typical Californian Indian restaurant.

column11:
Nothing "special" about this place.

Beers are fine but not great... No happy hour prices here, a "pint" sets you back $6 all day/every day (except Mondays; $1 off during HH)... I put "pint" in parenthesis, their custom "pint" glasses are closer to 12 ounces than 16... Food trucks are apparently on-site on a regular basis; just don't show up and expect to have a food option without researching dates/times/menus beforehand... Plenty of patio seating to take advantage of our beautiful SB weather. The barstool tables in this space are great, but the short picnic tables will give "dead-leg" fatigue after a few minutes to patrons of even average height... 

Not terrible, but there are a handful of Goleta establishments that offer superior beer, better prices, consistent food options, and IMO a more comfortable setting.

column11:
This place is awesome!!! I was a bit apprehensive as this place is a no frills kinda restaurant. I am so glad my husband insisted!

We ordered the shrimp ceviche and clam chowder as appetizers. Both were delicious! They did not skimp on the shrimp and the chowder was filled with buttery goodness. For the main course, my husband ordered the dungeness crab, our son the shrimp tacos and I had the crab sandwich. All dishes were tasty!

The best part about this restaurant is the price! All of this food and drinks for less than $70...can't beat that!!!

column11:
Overall 3.5 stars is all Rose Cafe (2) gets?  
This is an amazing anytime place.  

This review is based on the ambiance and one glorious dish.  

Rose Cafe is relaxed, low lit, old red vinyl seating, and delicious.  I know everyone's got their SB hotspots and hangover cures, but I'll be damned.  The guadalajara chicken tacos are a great.  Loaded with guacamole, these lusciously stuffed shells of amazing, burst with flavor and scream satisfaction.  Rice and beans, loaded with lard and salt are a perfect side car.  And balanced with the light refreshing lettuce and and tomato, are super tasty.  

Please try them.

column11:
I love their food. I can't tell you how many times I have eaten here, but it is a very large number. Until I moved recently, I lived just a short walk from here, and I never got tired of it. The best thing they make is the mole enchiladas, but the sad part is, they don't make them every day. Just on Tuesdays. Just telling you about them makes me want some right now. 
As others have mentioned, you have to pay for the chips, but the salsa bar is complimentary, so it balances out. The salsas are all great. Really. I can't say enough about the food here. If you are able to go here, then go here. That's about as good a review as I can write.
column13: Los Arroyos Mexican Restaurant & Take Out

column11:
I must admit that I'm a little late in the game finding out about La Super-Rica but very happy that I did.  On a recent drive down from SF I stopped in Santa Barbara to check out this fabled and legendary taqueria.  Having frequented my share of excellent taquerias up and down the coast I have to say that I was blown away by Super - Rica!!  

My eating partner and I managed to put away 5 items that with tip came to $20, a great price for an even better feast.  The tamales with chayote, zucchini, corn, potatoes, and a few other ingredients I can't remember is one of the tastiest and most unique tamales I have had (and that's including the amazing tamales I had in Mexico City at LOS TAMALES EMPORIO).  The cheese and adobo pork in tortilla (forgot the name but I believe it was #15) was great too along w/ the bistec and various pork and bacon tacos.  Salsa bars can range from the divine to the extremely scary, Super Rica is on the divine side with beautifully fresh pico de gallo.  

One dish I didn't have but will be sure to order next time is the #17.  It's a pasilla pepper stuffed with cheese, roasted, and then chopped with other meats and placed on top of a handmade tortilla.  You can't get much better than that.

Santa Barbara is a great city to visit and now I have yet another reason to make the drive north.  

One last note; luckily we didn't have to wait in line but the food is so good I wouldn't mind waiting in line.  You can also check out all the cooking going on.

column11:
I truly cannot say enough great things about this B&B. My husband and I were visiting friends in LA and decided to take a couples retreat trip up to Santa Barbara for the weekend. Knowing absolutely NOTHING about the area and relying completely on internet research, I found this gem! Honestly, it can be so hard trying to weed out truly great places on the world wide web but, man, did we luck out! 

We stayed in one of the 2 bedroom suites and could not have asked for more. The innkeepers could not have been more accommodating (putting up with my dwindling cell reception and late check in time), the grounds are unbelievably gorgeous and the walk to State St. (the main drag in S.B.) was more than reasonable. 

If you are looking for a romantic, relaxing location - look no further. The two bedroom suite was the perfect amount of space for two couples and the private hot tub on the back porch put our experience over the top. If it's not apparent already, i highly recommend this spot to anyone traveling through the area. Not only was our experience wonderful but the price was perfect...even cheaper then two separate rooms at comparable locations. If you're going to S.B. anytime soon - RUN don't walk to the Cheshire Inn!

column11:
"Solamente una botanita para matar el hambre..." 
We woke up hungry and wanted some really good tacos. Yelp directed to El Sitio, and we were very pleased. Cute little place with little need for atmosphere or seating capacity. Apparently it is named after a little town in Zacatecas which is where my suegros are from - small world. Anyway I got the veggie burrito, my traveling companion had the breakfast burrito. The food came up right away, served with chips and rosted chiles on the side. Although the price was a little more than we were used to, we figured Santa Barbara is more expensive, so we didn't mind. The burritos turned out to be delicious and more than enought to satisfy our hunger. We finishd our road trip all the way to SF without even getting hungry. Would eat there again.

column11: Olio E Limone is easily one of the more artful fine dining experiences in Santa Barbara. The quail is beautifully presented on a bed of seasonal vegetables, the duck ravioli is decadent without being overwhelming, and the panna cotta is so delicate you might not want to eat it (but you will, and you'll love every second of it). The food is delicious and refined in the way you would expect from a white-linen-tablecloth establishment. That said, the ambiance is a little stiff. Servers try very hard to execute on the white glove experience Olio aspires to deliver, resulting in a somewhat stilted dining flow. The food and ambiance aren't quite elevated enough for all the pomp and circumstance, but the overall results are elegant, romantic, and classy.

column11:
This was our last stop for our bachelorette party last night! What a fun place to get together, we enjoyed the live music with Susan and Cliff who were both amazing musicians. They were able to sing so many different kinds of songs and took requests. 

We got to the Red Piano at around 8:30pm, paid a $5 cover and went inside, there was only one or two tables left, I think we were lucky to snag a table that could fit all 5 of us. We ordered pizza from Patxi's right next door and they were able to deliver our order to us. Thanks to the fellow Yelper who left that tip! After sitting and eating and ordering some drinks (Moscow Mule, Amaretto Sour, Paper Plane) we got up to get closer to the Red Piano and dance! It's a fun atmosphere and the cocktail waitresses are nice. The crowd was a little older than us, so the songs requested were geared more toward that crowd, but that's okay. There were still many songs we recognized and we could still dance and enjoy the music. I'd come back here again in the future.

column11:
This Hyatt Centric has changed names and ownership several times throughout the years. Sadly the only positive thing about this hotel is the location, since it is located on Cabrillo, directly across the street from the beach. Even then, is is not walking distance to the shopping on State Street, as the hotel is on the eastern part of Cabrillo. The only place you can walk to is the SB Zoo, and even then, you have to cross a tight, busy street with a lot of traffic, so it this may not even be a selling point. This is a prime example of a tourist trap, it is over-priced for what it offers, and the quality of the property. The rooms are dated, cramped, and you can hear your neighbors talking, watching television, etc. The pool is unusually small for a hotel of this size...what were they thinking? The staff is not friendly, you get the same level of service as you would at a generic motel, which is significantly less money. My advice...save your money and stay anywhere else, sadly even Motel 6. 
Sadly one more thing, if you find a less expensive room here (which is a rare), beware they also own a building behind this hotel, which is actually across the street from the hotel. It looks like it was another hotel at one time, and is not even worthy of a stay. If you can, avoid this Hyatt Centric!

column11:
Started going here recently, and originally loved the vibe and atmosphere of the place. However my several occasions of terrible service here has made me start to avoid it. Twice now I have showed up over an hour after the posted opening time to a closed shop, with no explanation sign or anything. I have to assume that the employees just show up to work late or didn't at all.  There was also an incident where I ordered a chai tea, and received one with espresso in it. I politely told the guy that was working there that I didn't want espresso in it. The guy went off about how they always but espresso in their chai and that he didn't know what I wanted him to do about it. I had gotten several chai's there before and not had espresso put in them, but l I said ok and that in the future I would specify "without espresso" and asked if i could please just get a new one. He literally rolled his eyes, put chai powder in some hot water, and handed it to me. It was absolutely disgusting and pretty shocking behavior.  Besides that particularly bad experience, about 1/2 of the employees have been rude and 1/2 nice. 
Coffee colab could be a wonderful place if the would just get their employees together,

column11:
This is truly the most amazing food I've ever had. We visited this place about 12 times over the past month while on vacation in Santa Barbara.  Everything we ordered was of the highest quality and tasted fabulous! Our favorites being steak tacos, steak fajitas, and the wet burrito.  The steak is just so absolutely tender and juicy. Truly comparable to a fancy steak house. The salsa bar had so many choices and everything was extremely fresh.  

As others have said do not freak out about the crowds or not being able to find a seat. I don't know how they do it, but somehow the waitstaff and owner (who was always on hand) find everyone seats before their food comes. Truly the system works somehow: order, get a number, tell waitstaff how many in your party, they find you and seat you, eat chips and drink and voila your food arrives.  No need to worry. Honestly, we really did visit this place 12 times over one month and I would freak out every time thinking we'd never find a spot or that the waitstaff forgot about us, but nope they never did and we were always seated with time to enjoy the chips before the food came out.

column11:
The last time I reviewed the FisHouse I was mad!  I felt wronged.   I was disappointed by a policy concerning a Groupon.    One of my Yelp friends told me I was too harsh (and of course I was) and that it should be more about the food...   So I went back and gave it another shot!

1)  Hostess was super nice!  My wife wanted me to give her a shout out for that-- her name is Devon!    

2) Our server was great!   Wish I remembered her name too but she was awesome!  

3)  Lobster special:  $22.95!   And it was a GOOD lobster!   Well cooked and a lot of meat!    Maybe the first time I have had a Maine lobster that had more meat in the claws than in the tail!   It came with clam chowder--also delicious! 

4) My wife's halibut was excellent too, or so she says as she wouldn't share it with me!! 

5) They still do free corkage on bottles of wine purchased from Corks n Crowns!   (maybe other places too--you can ask)  

6) A manager came to the table to make sure that we were having a better experience than the previous visit!   And of course we were.  

We ran into a lot of friends who were enjoying the happy hour and they were having a great time too!!!!

OK I have eaten my lobster and my humble pie and corrected the review to a much more appropriate star level.

column11:
The Coffee Bean in Goleta is one of my pit stops I make as I'm traveling up the central coast.  
There's always lots of people outside chatting and catching up with one another, inside there's always students studying.

I'm a huge Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf fan, all things equal I would definitely rather go to a coffee bean over a Starbucks.  The drinks taste better overall, and they're more robust and flavorful.  I usually get a Mocha Latte with an extra espresso shot or a Tea Latte of some sort.  Their ice blended drinks are really delicious as well.

There's usually tons of parking in the lot in the plaza.  It's a matter of how close/far you find a spot at.  Sometimes there's a lot of cars coming in and out of the driveway and with Trader Joe's a few stores away it makes it a bit congested.

They have a new app that came out not too long ago and it's cool to now collect points to redeem different treats and what not.

column11:
Max's is quickly becoming my go-to stop for a satisfying breakfast while running errands in the upper State/Samarkand area. My husband and I have been twice now and each time the food and the service have both been excellent. 

The prices are reasonable ($10-15, plus a few extra dollars for coffee or juice, is pretty standard for breakfast in Santa Barbara) and most meals come with your choice of a delicious homemade muffin or biscuit (you can also get toast, but why would you?). Plus, there are quite a few options for vegetarians like us and my scramble included a pretty generous serving of avocado. 

If you're looking for a hip, young, local vibe, then this isn't the place, at least not on Saturday morning. Many of the other diners were either older residents or tourists and, maybe they were aiming for a cozy, homey feel, but the dcor mostly just felt dated to me.   

The food and friendly staff more than make up for a little lack of charm, though, and we'll definitely be back. Be sure to bring your Axxess card to take advantage of the buy one, get one deal (and 10% off each time after).

column11:
I always had assumed that any chance of getting food after 10pm would have been limited to some fast food joint. Boy, was I wrong. 

I knew that this place had been in existence for a little while, but wasn't aware of the phenomenal fare it offered. 

The first time I set foot here, I was with a group of friends who were positively raving about their fried rice. Drunk food? Sure. Drunk food with awesome flavor? Definitely. 

PSA: the fried rice is very spicy. For a guy like me, it's a cough-inducing spice. They are happy to make it sans-spice, and this works just fine for me. The dish comes in a traditional Chinese food-style takeout container and is filled to the top with a number of tasty items. So good, in fact, that my drunk self can usually put the entire dish down in one sitting. It's a must-try for sure. 

The cashiers are always super friendly, light-hearted, and attentive. They probably receive their fair share of nightly bar characters, so have to put on that easygoing persona. I commend them!

This isn't JUST a late night restaurant - I believe that they are open during the day, though I haven't been. The next time I find myself in that particular section of downtown SB during the day, I will give them another try!

column11:
This place is great! I heard about it from a friend who lives nearby and when he said it was open today, I had to give it a try! I love the decor with the wood wall and the chalkboard was a lot of fun. The kids that were there all had fun playing on it.

But what really stood out was the food! Wow, my burger was perfectly cooked and tasty as could be. I mean, how can you go wrong with something called the "Cheesy Pig"!?!? I went with a classic wedge salad as mu side and it did not disappoint. Fantastic blue cheese dressing that you can tell they make from scratch. 

I'd recommend it as a lunch place for anyone in the area.

column11:
The service at this Funk Zone restaurant is fantastic. The atmosphere is great; it's cozy and a bit loud but for a restaurant the serves family style being cozy with more opportunities to talk to neighboring diners or at least eavesdrop on them unhindered is part of the fun. 

The food itself is where it begins to unravel for me. At a dinner of brussel sprouts, bone marrow and biscuits and whole branzino the individual elements of each dish were well executed but failed to come together in a way that made me want to come visit again.

Take the marrow dish; as a lifetime member of the marrow addicts club I can appreciate the generous helping served up. But pairing the fatty marrow with an equally buttery biscuit was a bit too heavy handed for me. The accompanying blood orange marmalade was appreciated as a way to cut through all that fat but was difficult to pair with the biscuit--buttery biscuits disintegrate too easily--and seemed a poor fit with the marrow itself when tasted together. Or take the branzino; a delicate fish prepared in a lovely style with a good fry in the skin then paired with some fried items on top--fried on fried was again a bit heavy handed. The accompanying sauce was delicious but was a bit thick in texture and and muddled in flavor to pair with such a delicate fish.

The brussel sprouts...ok, they were epic. But the meal can't stand on the one dish alone. 

I like the free popcorn served at the beginning though; a very playful start to the evening.

column11: Heard about Christine's wonderful reviews and e-mailed her to set up a tasting for our wedding. Received a curt response saying she was too busy for a wedding "that far out" and would have to reach out to her a handful of months later if we wanted to set up a tasting. Sorry, but some of us like to plan ahead! Because of that interaction, we crossed her off our list immediately and went with Montecito Confections, who was happy we were planners. If she were nicer, it might have been worth waiting for. Good customer service goes a long way, but I guess Christine Dahl wouldn't know anything about that.

column11:
Just had a lovely three night stay here.  Had a first floor king room with fireplace, jacuzzi tub and balcony.  The room was very nice, super clean, and charming without being fussy.  The bed was very comfortable.  The only thing I would change is to have a bigger closet so bags could be stashed out of sight, but this was only a minor inconvenience.

Breakfast was very good and the menu changed daily.  We liked that the servings were good size, but not too large.  I did see people ask for seconds with no problem. The staff on check-in was pleasant and helpful as was the breakfast staff.  We had no need to call on them for any issues so I can't say how helpful they'd have been.

I have no regrets about choosing this spot for our 20th Anniversary get away!  We'd come here again and recommend The Eagle Inn to anyone planning a trip to Santa Barbara!

column11:
I was staying in SB for an overnight work stay and decided to walk here to build up my appetite. I love the vibe here- straight selfish shack! Since I was alone, I was seated fast and immediately helped by a server. 
Decided on a Lobster bisque- which is by far the best one I've had! Not too creamy, which is what I like, but just enough to be the comfort food I was hoping for. I also ordered the Crab Ceviche. You get a great amount of crab with fresh avocado and cocktail sauce. I made sure to ask for a side of the warm sourdough to top off the delicious meal.

column11:
Oh McConnell's, you are the highlight of my Santa Barbara trips. 

No matter what the weather is, hot or cold, I am getting some ice cream.

The great thing about McConnell's ice cream is that all of their ingredients are all natural, local, sustainable, and organic. Plus ALL of the flavors are good. ALL of them. What other ice cream shop can you say that all of the flavors are a hit. 

This time around I ordered a flight which is 3 small scoops of whatever flavors you want. I went this route because I just couldn't make up my mind and so I figured getting 3 flavors would allow me the pleasure of having it all or close to. 

These were my 3 flavors:
-Chocolate almond brittle. I always get this flavor no matter what. It's a rich chocolate ice cream with chunks of nutty, toffee, almond brittle that is the perfect compliment to the chocolate. The brittle also nice and crunchy and doesn't stick to your teeth which makes me a fan.
-Boysenberry Rose Milk Jam. I got this flavor because first, I had never heard of a flavor like that before and after tasting it, it was just a really nice summer flavor (being that it's about 90 degrees outside right now in October).
-Whiskey & Pecan Pralines. This was one of the fall seasonal flavors and I knew I had to get it when I saw them change out the ice cream pan as I was waiting in line which meant that it must be good if it was going that fast. And yes, it was delicious. You can taste a hint of whiskey and the pecan pralines brought it over the top. Plus who doesn't love swirls of caramel if there wasn't enough awesomeness in that ice cream already.

Come in and get yourself some McConnell's ice cream. Endless options and really great service.

I'll be back! :)

column11:
If you wanna sit right on the beach, with your feet in the sand, this is a must stop in Santa Barbara! 

The food is ok. I ordered the grilled shrimp tacos and my mom had the ahi tuna tacos. Not the best tacos in California. You get a choice of corn or flour tortilla and the tacos come deconstructed. The fillings were a ton of cabbage, black beans and pico. Didn't really feel like I had enough filling for all four tortillas. 

Plenty of adult beverages available, with drink specials from 4-6pm. 

This place wins because of its location!!

Also wanted to add the manager was sitting right behind us eating a meal, which I thought was a little inappropriate due to the staff kept talking to him, he was literally sitting in the walk way of clientele entering the restaurant

column11: Must try the potato croquettes. I was walking along state street with my husband and we were disenchanted with the number of bars that had out of control drunks or just gave us a bad vibe. We were hungry and tired and just happen to be near this pub that we decided to give it a try. We didn't regret our decision. We had a pint of beer, by the way Harp is some really good beer give it a try if you haven't. Loved the atmosphere as well, we ended up talking to our bartender quite a bit and met some of the locals.  Overall had some fun and some good memories.

column11: This was by far the most disappointing meal I have had in the Santa Barbara area, particularly because a friend recommended it. We ordered a burrito, soup, and chicken tortillas. The burrito was large and greasy. Really unpleasant. The soup was lukewarm. And the tortillas were filled with pork, not chicken. We asked for the bill and never received it. Eventually I had to walk up to the Take-Out window to pay, since our waiter seemed to have forgotten about us. I can't think of the last time I want to a restaurant where every dish was disappointing. Save yourself the trouble. With so many good Mexican restaurants in the area, this one deserves a miss.

column11:
We dined at Toma, mid-week, with local friends who highly recommended it.  What an unexpected surprise!   Honestly, we had never associated Santa Barbara with fine dining and expect fine food even less often at an Italian restaurant.  Wrong on both counts!

Toma was great.  The location, just across from the beach, couldn't be better.  The room is warm and charming, with an elegant, high-end feeling.  Service was excellent and the staff seemed very knowledgeable about both the food and the very well done wine list.  

The food was sumptuous, with unique combinations and presentations.  We particularly liked the lasagna, which had a wonderful assembly and texture, rather than the mush that is often served.  Proteins were perfectly prepared and presented and even the customary Minestrone  and the Rigatoni were outstanding.

Toma was a great choice and we expect to be back at our next visit.

column11:

column11: Does it stand the test of time? Oh yes! It absolutely does! I have been a fan of Woodstock's pizza since I first tried it in 2002. After having been deprived of this quality pizza for 16 years, I'm finally back in town and ready to welcome Woodstock's back in my life. I went a little nuts and ordered the Kickin Carnitas pizza, All Meat Orgy, Bikini Zucchini, chicken buffs', and Of Course the cinnabread. I ordered online through Woodstock's website and scheduled delivery for later in the evening. Delivery occurred at my time requested. The delivery person was friendly and professional! Now the deets! All delicious. Big fan of the carnitas pizza! Wow! Never thought of that combination and I suddenly feel deprived from years of ignorance. Now, I am not-at-all a veggie person so the zucchini bikini pizza was just a last-minute add on without expectation of enjoyment. I was not only surprised but pleasantly converted! Hello delicious Sassy Chipotle Sauce! Sassy makes all the difference in the world! I would eat a full jar of this magical substance. Seriously. I already hid a container away so I won't have to share with guests. Bad Dara! But seriously. The cinnabread has always been my favorite. It has all the delight of a cinnamon roll mixed with a donut but a pizza. The Cinnabread tastes good at any time of the day. What's not to love about Woodstock's! The location is in the heart of Isla Vista, a fun college town.

column11: While away on a day trip to Santa Barbara we checked out this ramen restaurant. The seating is a bit awkward outside unless you get a spot lined up against the wall to people watch. So when the waiter asked where we would like to sit I immediately went for a spot there. The server was quick to get us drinks. Since we were in a bit of a hurry due to a day filled itinerary, we ordered right away and paid. I got the spicy pork tonk kont su ramen bowl dish. It was absolutely delicious just very very hott. I enjoy spicy things, so the more spice usually the more excited I am to try it. I also felt like there was a good amount of protein in the dish as well. My husband got the spam sushi roll and he liked it. He wasn't that hungry otherwise he would have ordered more. Anyways good ambience outside, great portion sized tasting ramen and right on the downtown strip of Santa Barbara. You can't go wrong stopping here for some soup if you're in the mood for it!

column11:
My gf and I had a good meal here. Our server was pleasant, very helpful and politely conversational.

I asked him to recommend a beer, and the Dogfish IPA he chose was perfect. It was smooth, round, thick and hopsy. I was (initially) a little pissed he conveniently recommended the 2nd most expensive bottled beer, but it had 9% alcohol by volume, so it really was the equivalent of 2.5 beers, if getting trashed is your goal, I guess.

The popcorn shrimp appetizer had shrimp that were MUCH larger than I was expecting. "Popcorn" sized shrimp are usually the smallest possible, like 60 count (60 shrimp in a pound), but these were at least twice as large. The spicy hot tartar sauce that came with them was excellent.

My gf's salmon was perfectly cooked and seasoned with a light crispy texture on the skin side. My jumbo lump crab cakes had generous amounts of real crab meat and very little filler or binding. The sides of garlic mashed potatoes were well-seasoned, rich, creamy and had real chunks of roasted garlic in them.

The desserts also sounded awesome, but we did not have any room for them.

Overall, this place is not getting its due respect. For myself and my gf, it was a great meal and pleasant experience.

column11:
As someone who is very nutrition conscious, this place is a gem . 
PokeCeviche offers more options than any other poke places I've been to; for example, they have kelp and zero calorie noodles as bases , which is awesome for people trying to watch their diet .
I think they are very generous with the portions of protein as well, a medium bowl had about 4-5 oz of fish. Toppings are unlimited, so if you get everything, it's a hefty amount of food!
They also have cool stuff like creatine and protein powder if you need extra boosts in your drinks.
The owner Andy is also so sweet:) always smiling and welcoming !

column11:
My boyfriend started his brewing career here as "beer slave" to ex-NASA physicist, current head brewer and Santa Barbeerian Pete.  Pete is the most personable rocket scientist you will ever meet and he knows his stuff about beer.  The Condor Pilsner is a nice refreshing summer beer, and there is either a rotation of Belgian beers or English beers.   The Doppelbock has won first place in the bock category a couple of years.  And, the award-winning Habanero Pilsner is taaaaaasty.  

The food is very good and reasonably priced.  I went through a phase where all I wanted to eat was the warm goat cheese salad.  

They have live music, but I am not such a fan because it gets really loud in there.  

In terms of patrons, it ranges from Santa Barbara locals to tourists to UCSB students to the ever-present corps of Santa Barbeerians - the homebrewing club in Santa Barbara.  They are a cool enough crowd though and if you're lucky you can join them for Beer Camp or the 12 Beers of Christmas.

All in all, Brewhouse is the perfect sunny day spot - grab a table outside and order some pitchers.  Also, if you're in the area, go there for Oktoberfest especially if you want to tie one on and listen to a 10 piece tuba band. 

I have had a ridiculous number of good times here and I would send anyone there if they want a casual atmosphere, good beer and food, and to get away from the tourist trap of State Street.

Yay Brewhouse!  I love you.

column11:
FIRST TIME EATING POKE!!

I've always been a little nervous about trying raw seafood, but Choppa Poke helped ease this transition. The chunks of ahi tuna that I got tasted fresh and delicious, and along with the bounty of other toppings, it felt like i was eating a buffet in a bowl. The sauces are amazing, the rice is perfectly cooked, the add-ons had a huge variety of textures and flavors... and in great portion sizes, too!!! You do get what you pay for, which I really appreciate. 

Definitely coming back to this spot; the food is delicious, the place itself is super hygienic and COVID-friendly, and it's just a super great, filling meal to end my day with.

column11:
There's a lot to enjoy about this place! They made some mistakes with my order however, and I feel as though the quality could be better.

Food: I like how they have pre-made bowls available but also the variety of choices to create your own. They forgot to put cucumbers and fried garlic in my bowl however, the crabmeat is a little dry, the rice is also quite clumpy and the fish portion was a bit small. In addition, I can't taste any sauce. I did come at the last hour though so could totally be end of the day mishap. The quality of the rest of the ingredients was still pretty good and I like how they have Nori. The matcha kiwi drink is also to die for!

Service: Besides messing up my order, they're really nice and very timely with the orders so this made up for other cons.

Overall, not the best experience but would still come again as the food was still delicious regardless!

column11:
There was a healthy line on a recent Sunday morning when we walked up but nothing unexpected or totally overwhelming. We waited in line for about 15-20 minutes to order and just chatted until we reached the front. The gal at the register was v helpful in choosing what to get as a first timer. We had a small dog so she showed us to a table where we'd be comfortable and await our food. 

FOOD:
I ordered the shrimp and grits. They were just ok for me. I ate them but they are not your typical S&G's. I'm accustomed to gourmet southern style S&G's and these are definitely a reinterpretation with a more spicy flair. The French Toast we're scrumptious! I'm an aficionado and these were yum. I also am obsessed with the Anna's Cider Rose. My friend had a bit of a struggle with trying to sweeten her coffee because there were none readily available. 

OTHER STUFF:
Outside seating is nice and open. It's also super dog heavy so we had to monitor our pup so he wasn't setting any of the other dogs off. But not a huge deal. 

Overall, loved it and will def be back!French Toast

column11:
Hands down one of best tacos I've ever ate in my whole life!! First of all, you can't go wrong with $1.80 per taco!!! I don't think I've ever been to a Mexican place where you can get such cheap tacos anywhere. You could literally get a full meal for less than $10. The menu is nice and simple. The workers are friendly and informative. The restaurant is nice, clean and spacious! There's also a count where you put your own sauces and onions and all the other yummy toppings!

I ordered four tacos b/c I really wanted to try all of them but I just decided to go with my top four. I went with chicken, beef (asada), marinated pork and beef tongue! My favorite was beef tongue and the chicken. They were super juicy and flavorful that even after I finished eating my tacos, I had to lick my fingers lol. It's that good!!

Overall, it was definitely a good experience and great food! If this place was in SF, I'd be there in a heart beat. If I'm ever in town again, I would definitely come here!! :)

column11:
I came here with my boyfriend for Memorial Day weekend. We initially booked it for Valentine 's Day weekend, but we had a change of plans. They were nice enough to cancel it 24 hours in advance...which was great. So we changed it for Memorial weekend. They had good prices for a motel in Santa Barbara.

When we arrived i thought the place was cute. My boyfriend considered it "eh". The staff at the front desk was very friendly. We got a one bedroom motel. When i first walked in i noticed the huge bed and the flat screen TV. We definitely watched a movie one of the nights :). The bathroom was really nice. Finally a motel with decent water pressure in the shower. My boyfriend loved it.  They had a microwave, but we didn't bother to use it. He took me out on dates the whole weekend =]. Overall I would rate the place 4 stars.
