column11:
I booked a shared tour with Sustainable Vine Wine Tours as part of my wife's birthday outing in Santa Barbara. I booked online after speaking with Scott Bull (who put my mind at ease). 

After picking us up in a very spacious 8 seat Mercedes Benz (sprinter type van) we were toured around to three very nice tasting locations. The first of which was a behind-the-scenes look at how wine is made at a small boutique type winery, next we had a tasting and lunch at a very elegant private winery and finally we had an outside tasting at a very historic winery. All three tastings were unique in their own right and we enjoyed every minute of each of them. By the way, all of the wines we tasted were made via organic growing methods! Can you say: "Awesome Sauce!"

Our group consisted of 8 individuals (including the two of us) who "jelled" from the first minute we introduced ourselves at the start of our adventure. By the time our day was over it was difficult for us to part ways.

Scott did an outstanding job of explaining what we should expect as we journeyed along our tour. He took care of our lunch, our water, our chocolate cravings, etc...oh, and he makes an awesome cheese plate! He basically took care of whatever we wanted/needed during our outing. Scott was awesome.

We would most definitely consider do this outing again in the future.

column11: Such a fun experience! column11:
Great location. Lovely atmosphere. The positives end there. I don't know any other way to say it: the food is just plain bad. Lamb meatballs needed something. Salt? Pepper? I don't even know. They were so bland. My husband ordered the sea bass. Not edible. I'm not kidding, it was horrible. I got the bucatini which was actually decent, which was a good thing since my husband had to share it so he wouldn't go hungry. We told the manager that the sea bass was bad (they asked if we wanted it boxed when they saw it was barely touched - answer, no) and they gave us a free desert. I got a coffee which was neither hot nor fresh, and we tried the caramel hazelnut chocolate bar. The gelato was pretty good, the bar was not worth a second bite. It was like a giant piece of really mediocre candy. 

I usually do not complain at restaurants and leaving this sort of review makes me uncomfortable but I am really hoping this place gets it act together. We have needed a nice restaurant in the east beach area and I am rooting for them. Here's hoping they can shake up this menu and get some food worthy of the location.

column11:
Solid experience. Outdoor seating is spacious and atmosphere is super nice. I got the Chitarra Pasta which was pretty good. A dish full of shrimp for all the shrimp lovers. 

My husband got the Angel Oak Signature 52 Day USDA Prime which was very good! It did not need any sauce (although you can ask for one for an additional $5). Also got a side of mashed potatoes which were very buttery and creamy. Lastly I got the banana split dessert. If you're looking to finish your meal with a dessert I recommend passing on this one and try a different one. Wasn't my favorite. 

Overall, service was solid. Not as bad as I thought it would be (considering the reviews) and a very nice place to go if you're staying at The Ritz-Carlton and looking for a nice fancy meal with good wine.

My boyfriend surprised me by taking me here for my birthday dinner. Great choice because everything was on point.
Our server was by far the best that I have had anywhere. She was fun and happy and made sure we were having a great time. Not only was the service the best, but the food as well.

column11:
How unoriginal!!!  The Dr Suess whimsical world of cupcakes has been done, and guess what? Its right down the freeway in Montecito called Whodidily cupcakes.  I walked into the Santa Barbara store and immediately asked if they were affiliated with the Montecito store...to my surprise the answer was no!  From the theme to the colors, from the cupcake metallic papers to the way they decorated their cupcakes it was EXACTLY like the original store.

I am a pastry chef by trade so trying desserts isn't a hard thing to get me to do.  My friend and I split the dough dough bird cupcake (otherwise known as the lolligager at whodidily), which the chocolate cake was good, but the "vanilla" buttercream wasn't vanilla flavored at all, more like slimy shortening flavor. For $4 a cupcake, I was beyond thoroughly disappointed.

They are a pathetic unoriginal excuse for a cupcakery....same ideas/themes/flavors as another successful business, with much less flavor.  If in Santa Barbara, go to crushcakes instead...better yet, take the 101 south to Montecito for the delicious original.

column11: We both grew up in Santa Barbara, and this is one of our favorite go to restaurants for a comfortable evening out to dinner with friends, by ourselves, or just for happy hour by ourselves at the bar.  Tonight we opted for Happy Hour after attending a really cool free walking tour of the waterfront area of Santa Barbara.  When we come for happy hour we sit at the bar.  The bartender is always super friendly, and makes really great drinks!  Tonight I had Cosmopolitans, and hubby had a beer on tap.  They have a great wine selection too!  We always start with Jill's potato skins (they are the best!).  But all other appetizers on the menu are awesome too!  Tonight we both had the Tuesday evening special, Tri Tip Sandwiches served with salad and fries.  We've tried just about everything on Jill's menu.  The steaks are fantastic!  Nonna's Spaghetti Bolognese is one of my favorite.  Love that when you order a main entre dinner it comes with soup, salad, & bread (no need to order sides unless you want something extra).  The food is fantastic, prices are fair, and the service is great.  A local's favorite!

column11:
Finally stopped by to this place yesterday after wanting to try it for a while. It's definitely the best place in SB if you're a vegan or vegetarian since it's nice to be able to pick ANYTHING off the menu. No needing to substitute this or leave out that.  

Overall it was a great experience - the service was friendly and the food was good, what more could you ask for? 

As expected from all the photos I've seen, when the food came out, it was beautifully plated! We ordered the Picadillo Empanadas and Smoked Pulled Mushroom to share. The empanadas were delicious although I couldn't really distinguish what the ingredients inside were (all I know is that chimichurri on top was spectacular). For the smoked pulled mushroom, I asked for it to be on tortillas (shout out to Danah for mentioning that, cause it's a great idea!). The tortillas tasted homemade and the mushroom/jackfruit mixture was the closest thing to carne asada I've had since becoming a pescetarian. I mean they're definitely not carne asada tacos, but with that excellent texture and fantastic seasoning, I'll take what I can get! 

I can't wait to return and try all the other stuff on their menu that people have raved about - I'm coming for you baklava.

column11:
Tried calling to get any reservation but unfortunately they were all booked as the dining room was closed and only outdoor seating was available but already full. The host who answered recommended we just do a walk-in and might valet lucky. So we had reservations for The Lark but the menu here just sounded better. We canceled the other reservation and took our chances. 

Fortunately we were seated almost immediately. They had hand sanitizer for every table which was really nice and tables were apart enough to enforce social distancing. 

We ordered apps with the kids food. We ordered the margarita flatbread and the lamb koftas. Wow, just amazing. The right way to start off the meal. 

For our entrees we ordered the scallops and the gnocchi. Recommend by the server. And, I was so happy and satisfied with the meal. When food is seasoned properly it's so goooood. Also the cook on our food was perfect to my liking. I also loved that they had a salad app for the kids then their entrees and a sundae to end their meal. We had the chocolate torte for the dessert and it was so decadent and delicious. We were stuffed. I will most definitely be back here again. 

Everything was good. They were following all guild lines related to COVID and the staff were pleasant and the food was so good why would you not want to try it. Highly recommend trying it out if your contemplating where to have a nice meal I don't believe anything could beat this restaurant!

column11:
Petrini's gets four stars for the friendliness of staff, reasonable prices, small town restaurant feel and not to mention the awesome food.  The second I walked in the door, I was greeted with a warm welcome, seated right away and given the menus.  They accommodated my large family with no complaints and grabbed some munchies and crayons to keep the kids occupied.  When ordering the waitress gave useful suggestions which I always appreciate.  

When the food arrived, everything was amazing.  The portions were huge and the extra plates they gave us made it feel like we were having a true family dinner.  I tasted each entree and was amazed by each one.  Very flavorful and unique.  A big plus for me was they serve local beer.

If you're in Santa Barbara, save your money and the hassle with the crowds downtown.  Eat at Petrini's you will definitely walk out pleased AND full.

column11:
When I first moved to Santa Barbara a year ago loved Edomasa amd went almost 1-2x week. Around 2-3 months ago things went downhill and fast. The last time I went in December my order was not written down by the small Asian lady who does not speak English well. After apologizing they brought out my Katsu which was so over fried I couldn't bite through it. The older man stationed at the cashier didn't care that I was a regular or that my order wasn't taken down or that my food was inedible. 

I went last night to give it one last chance and because my girl wanted to go. She ordered a tempura udon, I ordered a tempura donburi and we shared a hamachi roll. Except my order was never taken and again I had to ask what was going on. Same small Asian lady waitress who doesn't speak english well. Same reaction from older cashier, doesn't care about patrons. sad.

column11:
Excellent spot for a quick bite. Had the pastrami on rye--very flavorful with the correct ratio of meat/cheese/sauce. They also have a dispenser that gives you free tastes of their dill popcorn while you wait, tangy and tasty! 

Only reason it's 4 stars instead of 5 is that the chicken orzo soup wasn't seasoned at all. After adding some salt and pepper it was much better.

If you're downtown in SB, do yourself a favor and visit P&S, you won't regret it.

column11:
Itsuki is one of my favorite japanese restaurants in Santa Barbara. It's relatively cheap comparing to the other ones here, such as arigato, sushi teri, etc.

I love their salmon kama. It's the BEST salmon kama i've ever had and it's cheaper than the other restaurants. They also have really good ramen (both hot and cold), although they dont have much meat. (I'm a meat lover!) 

But itsuki is definitely worth a try if you are craving for japanese food in santa barbara.

column11:
(*Cue movie trailer voiceover actor)  "In a world...where there are many tasting rooms battling for the ultimate in wine experiences, only one has the courage to fight and make their indelible mark on the storied Urban Wine Trail...Corks and Crowns:  Part One. The Destination"

Their tasting room on Anacapa is rustic and inviting.  There are two things that set them apart from most other wine tasting rooms in the area.  First is that they do craft beer tastings as well.  So it's perfect if you're with someone doesn't care for or about wines.  But, Mr. wine detractor, I ask you to open up your mind and palate and give their wines a try.  Well worth it.  The other thing that is different is they aren't a winery and therefore aren't limited to just one label's wines/beers.  They sell and promote what they like, mainly of California, and what they think their customers will appreciate.  Viva variety.

They offer different flights at varying prices.  The Gold (Award winning California wines), Platinum (California 90 point+ rated), and Diamond (California 93 point+ rated) are priced in ascending order.  They have a Pinot Noir flight and an international flight too.  If you are a member of their wine club (Oh shit!  Foreshadowing), you get a free tasting corresponding to the wine club you're signed up for.  (Gold wine club, free gold tasting, so on and so forth)

Buy a glass after your tasting, enjoy it on their front porch and breathe in the fresh ocean air.  (*EXT.  Sunset on the Pacific Ocean)

TO BE CONTINUED...

(*Back to Mr. V/O)  "You thought the review was over.  You thought the past was all in the past.  Well...think again.  From the writer that brought you Part One:  The Destination, comes the most anticipated paragraphs since just a moment ago.  Part Two:  Members Only!"  (*cue loud thunder clap)

Hi kids.  Thanks for joining us.  Speaking of joining, their wine club is awesome.  They do monthly shipments, never mind that quarterly delivery nonsense and every month it's from a different winery.  Not the same wines circulated every few shipments.  (Kalyra, I'm looking in your direction.)  Each month, we look forward to a delicious new discovery.  Besides, who doesn't love getting packages?  Remember Christmas?

So cheers Corks and Crowns!  We look forward to each visit and the gifts you send us every month.

THE END(?)

(*Roll Credits)

column11:
Service was good. Food was not.  Coffee drink was burnt.  

I have high standards coming from the Portland restaurant scene.  So, I thought that maybe the burnt latte was just a fluke.  The homemade vanilla syrup had nice flavor, but unfortunately the latte espresso was quite burnt.  It had a cute little face as latte art, though!

Next, my husband could not eat the french toast, it was so hard.  I get that challah bread is hard, but when he couldn't saw through, that's saying something.  

My omelette was super greasy.  I mean grease oozing out.  I don't think it was cooked that well either as the cheese wasn't melted.  And, I'm not sure, but I think they forgot the cheddar cheese - even though they said it was white like the gruyere. 

The home potatoes were pretty hard and seemed old.  They didn't have much flavor either.  Definitely not worth the price for anything we ordered.  

Their homemade toast was pretty good - not amazing, but good with their jam.  

Because we both couldn't eat our food, they ultimately brought out our dishes a second time.  They were a bit better - the French toast could be eaten easier (at least with a steak knife which was provided with it on Take 2), and the omelette cheese was more melted.  Instead of pure grease on the omelette, it was mostly mushroom juices oozing out - still a no-no for omelettes.  My toast on my second plate was only toasted on one side - and not at all toasted on the underside.  The potatoes still tasted old and chewy.  Bleh.  

We were told the chef was brand new and having a rough adjustment.  I hope they get that ironed out as the restaurant has a lot of promise - great location, friendly staff, and a nice owner (at least, we think our primary server was the owner as she waived the cost of our meal, went back to help the chef at one point, and gave us some free pastries for the road - which were tasty).

I would give it another try, but I would inquire about the chef and his experience first.  I would also request that an experienced barista brew my espresso.  The best part of the meal was the fresh squeezed orange juice - expensive, but AMAZING!  I love fresh squeezed OJ.  But, they really do need to get the food quality way up - especially with such high prices.  

Overall, nice service, bad food (except the pastries and jam), and burnt espresso.  But, they are nice to their customers and try and make things right to make up for the bad food.

column11:
I'm so glad I stopped by on my trip to SB! My friend said they had the best chicken torta he's ever had and it was also recommended by a friend who goes to ucsb, we had to try it. 

Parking-Not sure if theres a lot behind, but there's street parking available. 

You get in line and order first before sitting down. All the empty tables have a number on it but you give them the number that was on there once you sit down. I think it's so customers who order first have a table reserved for them. Also if you plan to order to go, I'd recommend calling your order in. There were a lot of people standing by the salsa bar while waiting for their food. Also you can't really tell who's waiting in line for the restroom and who's waiting for food since everyones just standing around. 

My bf and I tried a bunch of different places before coming here so we wanted to split something small. We couldn't find the torta so we asked when we ordered and the girl said they only have the torta at certain times of the year. hopefully the next time I stop by, they have the tortas. 

We got the beef enchilada plate with a beef taco on the side. You get chips once you sit down and grab some salsa from the salsa bar. The chips were so good! I don't know if they make them there but I really liked it. Also the salsas were really good. the green/avocado salsa had a kick to it but I loved it. 

the enchilada was really good and had a lot of meat inside of it. The rice.... omg SO GOOD. probably the best I've ever had. Also the beans were really good too. I really don't like beans and they had the refried beans but it tasted so good. I could actually eat it with my food. The taco was also good too! my bf really liked it. 

overall I really liked the food here. Tastes really good, fresh and authentic. Def will be back for those tortas (if you're reading this and work for los agaves, please bring back the tortas!!!!)

column11: Wow..where do I get started: horrible service, bad food, rude staff. So I came in on the weekend at 8 pm, a whole hour before their closing time. At first I thought, this seems to be a decent place, and I was proved very,very wrong. So first of all, when it was time to order, I ordered several things, including naan, samosa chaat, tomato  soup and chana bhatoora. The waiter said they didn't serve naan and samosa chaat at the time..what the heck! The main thing on their menus that people come for, they don't serve that! So angrily I said fine, I'm just here for dinner I can get through..ugh. So then I talked to my family and friends and my nephew started crying because he was thirsty. It's normal to bring water to your customers isn't it? Well we never even got our water after asking. Finaally after a long wait, I got my chana bhatoora, and man was I happy. And as soon as I took a bite...disgusting! I couldn't even finish the meal! And I never leave wastes. So to make the meal better I asked for onions. I waited 10 mins, then asked again. Once again the waiter ignored me. The third Time I asked, he finally listened to me with a grouchy attitude :( soon as I finished eating, he brought the onions..woow. Then I asked for the bill. It was half an hour before he even brought the check. That was unbelievable considering besides us there was one family of two, so why would it take so long to give me my check? Well so I decided to talk to the owner, who was outside. And it was unbelievably rude! He was on the phone outside, and as soon as he saw me walking towards him, he turned his back and pretended not to see me. I said excuse me in my most patient voice, and he said no I cannot talk shoo away :/ i can't explain how much u should not come here. They are lucky I gave them one star, they should deserve 0 stars!!Don't ever go there. Horrible I tell u

column11: This was my first time doing a wine tour with a company.  Our guide Shawn was funny, informative and we had a great time.  They picked us up at the hotel and took us all around.  We went to Kohler and Shoestring which had great wine and a great location!  Also did Roblar and Presidio didn't care for either of their wines, we poured out (gasp!) almost everything we tried.  Roblar had a beautiful location however.  The 2 great ones and our great guide made up for the 2 of the 4 weak wineries and rounded out the trip!  It included lunch from a local deli that was very tasty.  Great souvenir glasses to keep, big ones, not tiny little ones you get at some places!  Definitely a great company to go with!  They take groups to a variety of places, so contact them if you have preferences (or no-gos).

column11:
Let's be real. You eat here for the location not the food. The bar scene can be fun too.  This review is regards to the food only and based on suitability for people who don't eat animal products. A tough call perhaps - but as more people are waking up to the cruelty and sustainability and health issues with animal products, let's have a few options for those who opt out.
There are two options: a tofu asian inspired dish which I don't think I have tried (at a beach cafe?), and for lunch a mandarin salad, you can request no goat's cheese. It tastes fine, mostly lettuce, not satisfying as a meal and probably cost $20 with tax and tip. 
I love this locale, let's get a few plant-based options so us those who don't eat animal products can join the fun and not have to eat elsewhere.

column11: This is regarding their catering, which is amazing.  Areli and Pauline are superstars to work with.  Areli is beyond knowledgeable and will actually come and stay onsite for the duration of your event.  I recently worked with them on a 150 upscale event at the SB Historical Society and the whole staff was gracious and kind.  Service was fast and there was TONS of food.  A little grease was spilled on the ground by accident and they immediately mopped it up in order to avoid having the client lose any of their deposit.  All in all, they were polite, put together, tidy, hard working and quick to smile.  They made it all look fun and easy, which is saying something!  I'd strongly recommend them to anyone looking to cater a large event!

column11:
We booked a Sunday brunch reservation with Boathouse for a Bach weekend I was throwing a good friend of mine. I called and let them know it was a special occasion and that I wanted to make the meal very special for the bride. 

After being told this place doesn't take reservations on the weekends I was disappointed but willing to still make it to Boathouse and wait for such a great place. Checked their site and left an email on their inquiry page requesting for the reservation for our large group and hoped that they would make an exception. Sure enough they emailed me and called me back. They let me know they were going to be able to set the reservation but not only that, they also offered us a table VIP bottle service at their local club spot Indocine for the night before our reservation. This was such a great surprise and delight! Of course we took them up on their offer and changed our night plans to make sure to stop in for the table service. I loved that they offered such a special just because we were dining with them and celebrating such an occasion. Goes to show... you should always tell people if youre celebrating a special occasion. 

The club was locally known as a not so upscale place and definitely didn't have the reputation my friend would want to go to - solely because she's a more wholesome gal.... and yet Boathouse exceeded our expectations again! The club played a great mix of hip hop and old 90 classic songs that made us feel very young again and overall had a great time. 

When we arrived the next day for our Brunch reservation... the one thing we didn't plan for was parking. I'd recommend you drop your party off before parking as the overfill lots were a very far walk. Prepare for not a huge lot but know they have two lots and looked like there was more parking when we left at 1:30PM. Our table was already ready by the time we arrived at 11:30AM and the hostess was able to walk us back immediately. Our table was the best table in the whole restaurant :) Front corner table on their patio facing the water shore. Couldn't have asked for a better ending to our great weekend in SB. This was definitely the cherry on the top. Evan was our server - who was amazing!!! So attentive, helpful, suggestive, and we never had empty water glasses which is huge for me. I drink a lot of water and love it when the staff can be on top of their game with the refills. 

Food was awesome. We had all the specials... lobster mac and cheese, chowder fries, and special lobster salad. No one left that place hungry or unsatisfied. Couldn't believe how fresh the seafood was. I ordered the poke and was thoroughly impressed. I'd definitely order the Calamari, Burger, Cornbeef Hash, and Crab Cakes.. which the other girls ordered and loved. 

If you're looking for a friendly staff, a great view, and delicious lunch and brunch options in SB - you MUST stop at Boathouse. I'll be back and will be bringing friends and family so they too can see what this place has to offer....which is more than just their food.

column11:
I am OBSESSED with this place. It oozes with history but feels new. It's like a jungle in dry Southern California. The rooms are beautiful, we had a bungalow and my eyes felt like they were overwhelmed with beauty. 

The pool is incredible! The diving board totally and I mean totally brings out the little girl in me, front flips yep. Can't stop won't stop. I still got it.

We rented bikes and took the trail ALLLLLL the way to the pier, so much to see. You must do this. The next day we ran it! It's like an adventure, you run up through a gorgeous neighborhood overlooking the ocean, then down a hill past a gorgeous green cemetery, follow the trail (it turns into a bike path here officially) around this amazing pong with benches birds and fish, and then you real the beach. AMAZING.

The Sunday brunch was a little different, I don't know about you but I'm a "pancakes, crepes, French toast, waffles, scrambled eggs and potatoes" kinda gal, oh and I love buffets. I was so sooooo excited for their brunch it looked huge and so many options. 

Huge yes, so many options - yep.... but no pancakes, crepes, French toast, waffles, scrambled eggs or potatoes in sight. What did they have? Well I guess some people like gnocchi, spaghetti, sushi, lots of sushi, wonton soup, crab legs, peanut butter and jelly sandwiches, just think of something way random and not breakfast-ish and they had it. 

We will be back of course, MANY MORE times.j

column11: Very disappointing. My experience started off great. I was first greeted by a very pleasant receptionist and the Hotel was beautiful. We were checked in quickly with no hassle. column11:
My wife and I decided to try out the El Encanto for afternoon drinks to celebrate our wedding anniversary on the afternoon of July 29, 2017. 

We arrived around 4:30 pm and were seated on the upper patio. The view was very nice. We settled in and had a look at the bar menu, which was brought to us by a male server. To be honest, this young man seemed a little out of place at an establishment such as this. But, what the hell... let's see what he can do!

My wife ordered an iced tea ($6) and I ordered my typical gin martini. Nolet's, no vermouth, with a cucumber garnish. ($14) The server arrived with the drinks soon thereafter and asked if we needed anything else. 

I said, "Yes, could we please get some sweetener and..."
"Of course." he replied and began to walk away.
"...and some water?" 
"Of course.", as he attempted to walk away again.
"I'm sorry, are you in a hurry?", I said.
He said, "No, no." And so I said, "We would also like to try the Carpaccio." 
"Of course!"

My wife and I chuckled, and shook our heads. After the sweetener arrived, we both picked up our glasses to toast our anniversary and I noticed my cucumber garnish on the rim of the martini glass looked a little strange. I hate to admit I've seen a cucumber like that in my fridge after cutting it and leaving it out in the open in the fridge for a week. The slice was dried out and bumpy on both cut surfaces, and had certainly been sitting like that for quite some time. It was petrified! I was already to the point of not wanting to deal with our server about it, so I carried it into the bartender in the palm of my hand like a child who had just found a dead sparrow. I stood at the end of the bar and looked at him sadly. 

"Look.", I said.
His face morphed into a visage of disbelief and shame.
"I am so very sorry!"
"I am too, I really hate to complain, I really do.", I said.
He promptly propped two new slices of cucumber on a tumbler glass and handed it to me, he apologized again, and I walked back to our table. There weren't many people frequenting the patio at the time, so I felt slightly less embarrassed.

We were still waiting on our water, just tap water. Yes, this all happened before we were served any water. When the water arrived, I snatched it up and was just about to take a huge gulp (I have a cold/cough and was in need of some H2O) and just as I brought it to eye level I noticed a bunch of STUFF floating in the water. Fibers, black sand at the bottom, unidentifiable floating objects. Gunk. Yuck! I took my glass of water into the bartender again, poor guy. He apologized again profusely, and I just walked away. I figure he would tell our waiter to bring us some new water glasses. Instead, this professional young  man decided to serve us the water himself!

"I'm sorry about your water. Here's a bottle of Evian for the inconvenience." and proceeded to pour us two glasses of water. Well done! We thanked him, and continued with our conversation.

A while thereafter, the carpaccio arrived. It looked wonderful! Well plated, and fresh looking. Our server set the plate on the table between us and began to explain what the dish consisted of. Lemon, fresh grated parmesan, and black garlic gillette. Gillette? WTF? What does that even mean? As we began to eat , another server came by with a plate and said, "Carpaccio?" I would have loved to have two orders, but we had only ordered one. I decided to double check with this second server about "gillette". It turned out it was gelee, which we had assumed.

The carpaccio ended up tasting lovely, and  we decided to try another snack. We ordered a cheese plate which was not on the bar menu, or on the dinner menu, it was on a third menu we received. When it arrived, the server (not our main server) brought out the cheeses and asked if we would like to know the names. I am always curious about the cheese.. He rattled them off in no particular order, and that was fine, we were familiar with some of the types. As he walked away, we realized we didn't have anything to eat it with (no knives to cut it). Our main server came by a couple minutes later and asked if everything was alright, and asked if we wanted to know what kind of cheeses they were. I looked at my wife, and we both said "Yes!". We got a list of five completely different cheeses! My wife and I laughed, and I said, "That's amazing! The other guy named off completely different ones!" He seemed a bit flustered. I said, "If I had something to eat it with, I can probably tell you what they are!"  "Bread?!", he asked. I said, "No! A knife!" 

As we got the check, the server said, "The water is free. And I didn't charge you for the second iced tea."  

HAHAHA!

Well, that was sweet of you. This is the only place in town you don't get a refill on your iced tea. 

$103.00 later, it was totally worth the entertainment. Drinks and a (sh*t) show!

Anyhow, this place, on this particular day was a comedy of errors. 5 star hotel? NO WAY! Get it together people!

column11: Our new favorite. The Upham offers exceptional customer service in a lovely hotel built in 1871. The Upham does not feel old, it has retained it's classic, upscale, charming feel without losing general modern day conveniences. The rooms are very small, which is not a surprise for an older hotel, but Santa Barbara is not a town where you stay in your room. Beds are extremely comfortable and the room and hotel is very clean. The Upham offers a simple breakfast to help you start your day with wine and cheese in the afternoon (the cheese selection could improve/vary) and oreos (we wished for fresh baked but still a nice touch) and milk at night (there is also a well rated restaurant on the premises but we dined elsewhere.) If you are seeking a big hotel chain where you are treated like the number on your door, where rooms are bigger, this won't be your place; but if you are seeking a classic, upscale, discreet, small hotel to call home during your vacation in Santa Barbara in a great location, look no further this is the place.

column11: I have never been to this place before, and was told they are better than Saigon Noodle house. I have a 30 min lunch so I called to see if they have Pou Soup. Than man who answered stated that they do carry it, but pricing depends on which option. He recommended coming in to look at a menu. I asked if there is a menu online and he stated: "We don't pay for advertising." I asked what the options were, since I have a 30 minute lunch and would have to order ahead of time, and he said: "Honestly, we make the order very fast when you come in, and you'd be better off just coming in and looking at a menu." He then ended with: "I'm only one person running around and it's very busy so I can't spend anymore time on the phone so I'm going to hang up now. Ok, Bye bye." REALLY???? I understand if you don't have time in the moment and need to put me on hold, but this place needs to get some more staff then! I'm sure he was doing the best he could with the situation he was placed in, but I will be sticking with Saigon Noodle this time. I will still try this place in the future, but when I have more time to meet their needs.

column11:
Surprisingly, I was very underwhelmed with the Hyatt in Santa Barbara.  My husband and I traveled to SB for our anniversary and given the room rates, I suppose I had pretty high expectations.  The rooms were very dated, small, and oddly laid out.  Overall, things were clean, but not spotless and you could tell that the furnishings and carpet were old.  Our tub also flooded a bit if you stayed in the shower too long (fortunately, the front desk was able to have this repaired slightly mid-stay).

Highlights included the pool area and beach access.  The staff were also very friendly and helpful.  The hotel is located on the west end of town next to the zoo so does require having a car to get downtown (valet parking is $26/night).

While there wasn't anything terribly wrong with our experience, I don't think this Hyatt is worth the cost and was hoping for a bit more luxury.  I would probably explore other options next time...

column11: We hired omni catering for our wedding. They did such an incredible job, we got compliments from all of our guests as to how beautiful the set up was, and how delicious the food was. I would say this catering company was more on the expensive side compared to other catering companies in the area, but if you want a beautiful job, definitely the company to go with.  Our catering manager was friendly, but she did not respond to e-mails as punctually as I would like. That was the part I liked the least, but since the event turned out beautifully, I think she redeemed herself.

column11:
So glad that we have a great restaurant in this spot!  The Fish taco's are TO DIE FOR.  The baked clams are AMAZING.  I could live on those two dishes alone.  

The first time we went, it wasn't maybe a week after they opened.  They were very attentive, which is to be expected.  But our server went above and beyond for us.  Made sure that our daughter was happy, brought her extra fried chickpeas.  We were so impressed that we asked to speak with his manager.  We ended up talking to one of the owners. So nice, really enjoyed talking with him.  He told us that he really wants to impress the local foodies in the community, because thats whats going to keep this place open.  

Since then, we have brought our daughter in multiple times, with no problem.  It can get loud, but we usually go to dinner with our daughter around 5:30, so we usually leave when it starts to get loud.  

I have also taken my uncle and cousin here, and both were very pleased with what they ordered.  We will be back!

column11:
I know its trendy but it also happens to score on all fronts.

Servers have a passion for the food and they will take time to tell you about it. I had the cheese plate which was prepared with love and a dessert wine flight which made the grade. The Mr. came for dessert and it was a decadent threesome of chocolate.

I haven't had an entree yet but given the service and the platters that I saw come out of the windowed kitchen, I cannot wait for my next trip to SB just to head to The Lark.

column11:
Of all possible burger joints in I.V., the Habit is indeed the best. Most people don't know that this is the almost-OG Habit, and are still franchised, so they don't accept coupons from the statewide chain. The original Habit was located just across the street, where South Coast Deli now stands, but it seems like many things haven't changed.

I love the efficient service. The person at the counter doesn't make me feel rushed, but rather, I like the fact that they get to the point and never mess up my order. Most of the time, I get a charburger with cheese and no pickles, along with a chocolate malt and some of their delightful fries. If I'm not feeling too hungry, I'll get just the charburger, as it's currently the cheapest full meal in I.V. (damn you, Hana Kitchen price increases).

You should try the Santa Barbara style charburger when you're here, especially if you're an avocado or sourdough fan. It's the perfect way to enjoy a sunny, beautiful day in SB, after all! There's only enough space for a couple of seats inside, so your dreams of the Habit are dashed on rainy days.

column11:
Probably one of my favorite places to go with friends. Drinks or tea at the bar before dinner or even just for after dinner tea. The best place to people watch. 

Pickled veggies presented upon seating. Nice. 

Deviled eggs are yummy. Creamy and a bit different from the regular recipe other places use. 

Beet salad is light and delicious. Small so if you share like I did with 2 others, you'll only get a few bites. 


Seabass is so good. Perfectly seasoned and crispy skin on top of a bed of veggies. One of my favs. 

Service is always attentive and great. Make reservations ahead of time unless you're ok with hanging out at the bar for an hour or so for a table at dinnertime.

column11: I am truly disappointed with my experience. I am a big fan of Los Agaves and Santo Mezcal, but this is by far my least favorite. I went in this evening and I wish I had chose somewhere else to have dinner. We wanted to sit inside and the hostess said there are only outside tables available, even though we saw some we sat outside (we were never offered to move inside once one inside became available). At our table it took 10-15 minutes before anyone even acknowledged us. Eventually they came, but during our entire wait they kept coming to our table to give us food that we had not ordered ( Not a huge biggie I understand they are new and probably don't know their table numbers). Once we got our food the waiter disappeared. They did not come to check on us until it was time to give us our bill. I saw the manager and servers check on all the tables around us, but not once come to our table. We do not like to complain so we did not say anything, but we do hope they improve. This was not worth a $100 dinner. The reason I gave it 2 stars was 1 for the view and 1 for the drinks.

column11:
It's horrible when you're a fan and you stop by and it's not what it's expected

CRUSH MY HEART

So... years ago, I found the spot in Santa Barbara, Ca. I took my little guy there and it was the place to be! I always, made it a little adventure for us to pick up lunch or cupcakes or both

We would get the yummy red velvet pancakes, this turkey and brie sandwich (I think that's what it was...), and of course cupcakes. The food here was good-a little different yet-tasty! 

The ambience at that location was rather small but, nice! You could really tell they were still new at the time when we would go because, of the customer service from the young girls or maybe, the lack of training. However, I would STILL go back to the one in SB.

This spot was open not too long ago. Carpentaria is adorable! It took a while to find this place When we got there they have the most adorable patio. Walked in through the back. 

I was starving and wanted some food. I placed an order and the girl said the kitchen was closed. 

It was an hr before closed and it was sad they could've serve me. The girl had no style to greet anyone or offer options. I just ended up taking 4 cupcakes to an 1 hr drive home. 

The cupcakes were a little dry. Nothing like, I remembered. I was surprised with the customer service I received this is way I rate this 1 star. Make sure you're not starving when you come...

column11: This place was soo delicious that we came not only for dinner one night but then for breakfast the next day before we left town. Amazing! Our dinner consisted of mostly appetizers that we shared, we got the oysters, pork, crab cakes, lobster mac and this scallop plate and they were all amazing!!!! We ate every single item and left stuffed but totally worth it lol. Also they rested us pretty fast, we thought we would have had to wait for so much longer,  but they worked it out to seat us out on the patio and with a high chair for our little with enough room around us to not feel squished in. Then breakfast was the same thing, we had eggs Benedict with the. Crab cakes and the house plate that was soo delicious with the potatoes on the side. Ohh makes me want to go back!

column11:
Found Los Agaves on the first night I arrived in Santa Barbara/Goleta, and have been going back pretty much every week or so! Cviche is my favorite and the portion is huge! If your tummy cannot handle their big plates, I would recommend that you order it to-go, that way, everything will be fresh and the tortilla bowl (?) will stay crispy.

I did try burritos, enchilada, and fajitas, and they're all wonderful!

The salsa bar is also the reason I keep going back, there're 6-7 kinds of salsa offered that make me lose count of how many fresh and warm tortilla chips I've had.

People there are super nice and friendly and they make sure that the tortilla basket is never empty :)

column11:
This is, in my opinion, the best option for delicious, authentic Indian food in Santa Barbara that doesn't break bank. I have been for both the lunch buffet and for the regular dinner menu, and both are great in their own way. The food is really 5/5, especially for how difficult it is to find authentic ethnic food in Santa Barbara. For me personally, they lose a star on service. The owners are super attentive and helpful, but from my experience some of the junior waitstaff are quite unhelpful, especially when orders are incorrect. The person who fills the water cups though, that person is always on it which is much appreciated.

I love the selection offered for the lunch buffet. It's definitely the way to go if you are unfamiliar with different types of Indian cuisine, as they offer a great variety from their menu, including what I imagine are the more popular chicken and vegetarian dishes, as well as the different types of condiment options and naan included. The downside, obviously, is that the dishes offered are on the more mild side, but even without being spicy the flavor is great! I'm super impressed that they can offer that quality and quantity at the same time. I love going for dinner because it's a little bit quieter, and you can personalize how spicy you would like your food to be. I always make sure to ask for the highest level, then one above, which I think is perfect. Some favorites from the dinner menu: chicken tikka masala, shrimp biriyani, lamb vindaloo, and vegetable samosas. Each dish is more than enough for two people to share. Love this place for a group setting, because it's perfect for family style dining where you get to try a little bit of everything they have to offer.

If you prefer drinking beer outside there are two separate outdoor sitting areas as well surrounded by lots of greenery!

column11: If we're not eating a big lunch on a road trip up or down the 101 we stop here for a bowl.  With the congested (but free!) parking, healthy ingredients, chalkboards and girls in earth tones and unbrushed hair this is like the Trader Joe's of acai bowls.  Good assortment of bowls. Always busy, so don't expect a seat, and always loud, so expect peace, and never a bathroom so don't expect pees.  There is NO backyard, btw, only a dark garage.  Bonus: heavy, real bowls if you eat it here, ice cold acai, big portions, a varied menu, and well-staffed, including the girl who looks like Jessa Duggar. (Her mission is to deliver you a bowl). Minus: no ginger shots, and the high noise level (thumping radio, whirring machine, self-important monologues about sustainable living).

column11: I love the outdoor space at this brewery. We stop here once in a while just to sit in that great outdoor space and enjoy Santa Barbara sunshine. I have not been the biggest fan of their beer however. I was so happy that we stopped here again this week, they have greatly improved their beer list. They have now added a couple IPAs which are my go to for beer and I really enjoyed them. Third window is connected with a small kitchen area that will serve a limited menu of food. I have been here before when they have had an outstanding soft pretzel but right now they are not making those. I do wish they would bring them back along with this great IPA it is a win-win. But do come by and visit and enjoy the great open air feeling of the area and the great outdoor space to sit.

column11:
A Santa Barbara native,I often recommend this as the best coffee shop in town. This is a quaint little place that is an eclectic mix between modern and natural decor.  It feels homey the moment you walk in. Because of their background in cycling, they get a lot of cyclists traveling from all over the county/state.  It gives an overall feeling of community-you never know who you are going to meet on the patio!

Their coffee tastes extremely hand crafted.  It is smooth and decadent with just the right amount of creaminess.  Even as I write this, my mouth salivates for the smooth roasted cappuccinos.  I always take my coffee out on the patio and ritually add the right sugar blends to create the perfect cup!

Highly recommend-if you are out of towners definitely make the extra couple blocks away from State St to this establishment!

column11:
Having heard me speak fondly of my days spent in Santa Barbara almost a decade ago my gf surprised me recently with a last minute trip to The Four Seasons Resort Biltmore for a couple days and it really was the perfect getaway for two.  
       For those unfamiliar with the area the Biltmore is near Montecito(a few miles East of SB) right on Butterfly Beach which may be one of my fav beaches in CA.  It's clean (meaning no dodging balls of tar that you have to deal with at some beaches in the area), the sand is white and soft between the toes, with the channel islands just offshore and  the east-west orientation of the coastline here, you get both breath-taking sunsets AND sunrises.  So the location couldn't be better.  Literally every time you turn a corner on the grounds of the resort it's like you just stepped into a postcard.  And with the sprawling mix of lush but immaculately kept gardens and the early twentieth century architecture cottages throughout, I half expect to stumble into a party thrown by Mr. J. Gatsby himself.  Maybe I've just been living in SF for too long and miss the beach and lush greenery but yes, this place is that grand.    
       Of course being the Four Seasons you expect top notch service but they really outdo themselves here.  It's not the generic blank faced but smiling friendliness you get at most large hotels but actual greet you by name type of service.  Incredibly soft robes and bedding, quality toiletries, fresh flowers everywhere, and the pool at a constant, perfect 80+ degrees....I could go on all day.  Be sure to check out the Beach & Cabana Club nearby which is private but open to guests at the Four Seasons.  The Santa Barbara/Montecito area really does have a glut of great dining options so be sure to venture out for a meal or two but I'd be remiss to not mention the excellent meal had at Bella Vista.  You can socialize at the lounge, wander the beach or find a secret spot for two to lounge privately in the gardens.
       While, beyond the occasional mani-pedi or massage I've never been much of a "spa" guy, but being the good sport that I am we signed up for a couple of the in-house spa treatments.  The couples aromapothecary (that is totally a word I swear) and stone therapy treatments were mind-blowing.  Take my advice and splurge for the 80 vs. 50 min treatment.  If memory serves it was about $450 per couple for the 80 min treatment and was worth EVERY penny.  Wow I had no idea that hot/cold rocks could be so insanely therapeutic but in the right hands they work wonders.  I left there feeling like a new man and the gf was barely able to speak with a trancelike smile on her face as we walked(well I walked and she got carried) back to the room.  PS She had also gotten what I believe was an Avocado-Citrus(?) wrap the previous day which she could not stop raving about for 2 days so I promised I'd get her recommendation in here for any of you ladies out there.   
        OK so that's about it.  This is the perfect place to take the significant other and spend a few days sweeping them off their feet in absolute shangri-la.  I cant say enough about it(though I have certainly tried!).
column13: Four Seasons Resort The Biltmore Santa Barbara

column11:
I've always appreciated it when authors place their favorite restaurants or local bars in their books.  The Rula Bula in the Iron Druid series by Kevin Hearne remains one of those must-eat-at places simply because it's mentioned in all three books.  My rationale is that it must be great if an author goes out of his way to mention it in his books like that.  I've also always had a hankering to find a fish and chips place nearby that was so delicious that I would want to include in a novel, were I to write one.

Mac's may just be that place.  Sure, it might be all the way in Santa Barbara, but such a distance is a pittance when you can have a dish of fish and chips this awesome.  Not only is it everything all the reviewers make it out to be, but it's probably the finest example of it I have ever had in my life.  Not only was the breading not soggy or thick, but it was just the right amount of crispy and thickness.  The fish was fresh.  The one thing you can always tell is when the fish has been lingering around the shop for a few days or, worse yet, coming out of a freezer.  The chips were actually chips, thick-cut and more like nuggets of potato than mundane fries.

Everything came together so well, I'm amazed more places can't live up to the standard.  How hard can it be to have fresh fish cooked in a simple batter and served with chips that a ten-year-old could make?  I don't know--maybe that's what makes Mac's Fish and Chip Shop such a rarity, that they take the time to do it right every time.  And as long as good chip shops are this rare I'm going to be hitting up Mac's every time I'm near Santa Barbara.

Used to love going here when I lived in the neighborhood 10 years back. Tried again tonight and it was abysmal. The pizza overall was incredibly uncooked - the crust was bread-like, not crisp and the cheese felt barely melted - and there was too much of it.

It's pretty hard to screw up pizza this badly. Unfortunately, Taffy's did.

column11:
I have to say that Arch Rock is one of the most memorable restaurants from my trip to Santa Barbara. First off they had one of my favorite drinks, the Moscow Mule, and it was made perfectly and strong too (bonus points!). Second because of the fresh and delicious oysters! I cannot recall where they were from but it had a perfect balance of sweet and salty. On the side they had one of the best mignonettes that I have tasted with my oysters. I would totally recommend this. It was $14 for a dozen. 
Not so happy with my fish and chips though. Pretty standard. They seemed a bit on the tougher side too so they were probably overcooked. But everything else sure made up for it!

column11:
First off we went on a Tuesday and checkout out on Thursday so it was not crowded and so so quiet. 

The SPA Review (5 Stars):

Brown sugar scrub...OMG!!!
The spa is FANTASTIC. It is very spacious and luxurious. There are separate men and women sides, BUT the insanely beautiful rooftop sun deck is mixed. We went to the roof in our robes after our treatments and reclined on the amazing chaises and fell asleep in the sun. No one bothers you. It is quiet and again the view!  
I was told there are 47 treatment rooms.The jacuzzi, steam and sauna are located in each of the locker rooms. i guess I have been going to the Korean spas for too long. I  am so ok with not wearing a bathing suit, but everyone there had one on so I stuck to a towel and the steam sauna. The locker room is huge, plenty of showers and products.
There is pool right outside the spa as well. You can order food and drinks if you like. Supposedly if you are staying at the  hotel you cam  use the spa facilities even without an appointment. 

The RESORT Review (4 Stars):
I loved Bacara and can't wait to go back. I didn't even mind the $24 dollar valet only parking. I actually found the bellmen to be on top of things and our car was always ready for us by the time we got downstairs....we even forgot the phone in the car and they delivered to the pool. 

So why 4 stars only....We had a great room with an amazingly large balcony with a partial view of the ocean. I wish we had time to enjoy a mean out there, but next time. It was an upgrade room and on the end corner (bldg 20 - room 301). We  had to two dressing areas each with a sink so it made getting ready a snap. I LOVED the bathtub...it was deep and just the right size. The wall to the bathroom is just shutters that open. Which makes watching TV and taking a bath really easy. Plus you can talk to the person on the bed.  The downside to all this openness is that the actual toilet area is also "open" - just one open shuttered door separates you from the rest of the room. With all the stone sound travels or makes you think it is travelling. Anyway, it is a bit awkward.

The bed was comfy...Oh! we had a fireplace and they supplied some glorious big candles and matches to set the mood further. They deliver ice at night which is great. The TV got crappy reception.The business center was nice. i had to use the computer and it was lightening fast. 

We had breakfast one morning down by the pool. It was AWESOME.  They don't usually serve there until 10am, but we called at 8:30 and they said "no problem". We spent most of our time by the pool closest to the ocean and not the cabana area, but would definitely get a cabana if it was a weekend or crowded. The downside to the infinity pool is that it SLURPS all the time. You can't hear the ocean over the slurping. A regular pool would have been fine. 

It is awesome and romantic and everything you want in getting away. There are plenty of deals online from Amex, Travelocity etc. so you can stay at Bacara for a really great rate. I am told that they have specials in the winter that are crazy cheap but you have to keep checking back.

column11:
Quite a surprising experience last night. My memory is that Your Choice is usually quite tasty, but last night it was truly terrible.

I have been happily eating Thai food for three decades, and my companions were one newbie and one other seasoned Thai palate. Here are our thoughts:

Tom Kha Soup had ample chicken, but the total lack of straw mushrooms was disappointing. Also, like the other dishes, this dish was missing both heat and broadness of flavor.

The one dish that was ordered at an extreme heat level was only mildly hot from our perspective. And we have been given food before that was too hot at other restaurants, so we do think of ourselves as calibrated.

One dish that was spot on, was the pumpkin curry. Perhaps a bit milder than what we thought we had ordered, but with deep and bright flavors.

But the epic fail was their Pad Thai. I have never been served such bad Pad Thai, with painfully overcooked and gooey noodles, and a total lack of pleasant flavors beyond the peanuts and cabbages. I think of Pad Thai as an aromatic and texturally complex dish, but this was anything but.

So sad!

column11: We did my 3 year old's birthday on the Lil Toot - it was perfect. An hour is all you need with 7 preschoolers on a boat. We arrived early and the captain was nice enough to let us and our guests board early. All of the kids got to steer the boat as many times as they wanted and they made sure to drive us out to see the sea lions up close. We brought our own drinks, sandwiches, and cupcakes. column11:
Friends and I went to this version of El Torito on Tuesday night and unknowingly wandered into the midst of "Taco Tuesday".  One of our party was interested in the $.99 taco special but we were told that you must sit in a designated area and they were currently full.

We sat outside of the designated area and ordered.  The food was surprisingly good but we soon noticed others seating outside of the "Taco Tuesday" area taking advantage of the special.  We talked to the manager Martine and he was one of the nicest, most gracious managers I have ever talked to.

We will be back, mostly thanks to Martine but I recommend this restaurant with the reminder, if you want the special, go early or reserve a table in the area designated.

column11:
My hubby and I "discovered" Silver was on our vintners visa for the harvest weekend. How lucky were we to call and find that Benjamin Silver would be open all day Monday. A very small winery...one man production is a true gem. 
Call make an appointment. Take your time. The wines were all unique and flavorful. 
I personally loved the Chardonnay  but the show stoppers were the "super Tuscan" and the the Syrah. 
The tasting room is NOT a super fabulous decorated space. It's about the wine. 
We really enjoyed spending a few hours here. Really tasting he wine. And learning the differences in the terriors and varietals 
A wonderful experience
We are looking forward to our next visit

column11:
Yum! The best thing to happen to IV, bar none. 

212 Hotpot is a new hotpot place in Isla Vista where they serve hot pots of soup filled to the brim with meats, veggies, and delicious broth! 

There was a line when I got there, it took me about 30 minutes when I got there to when I got to order. The ordering process is a bit different to traditional sit down restaurants, where you have to pay at the register before you sit down. Seating is wherever you want; you choose which table you wanna sit at. 

I ordered the #5 which is the Pork and Quail Egg. We got our food about 8 or 9 minutes afterwards, and they lit our burners afterwards to get the soup to boil. The soup was delicious, the stuff that came with the soup was great, and there were some delicious condiments that made the meats and stuff better. I really loved the garlic soy! Only thing I thought they messed up on was that they didn't put vermicelli in my soup, when it was supposed to be in it. I enjoyed it too much to notice. 

Overall, 10/10 food! Will come back.

column11:
IV Deli is a classic when it comes to getting late night food. They deliver pretty much anything you need (from candies to tp..) even late at night.

I like to get their custom "build your own sandwich" with dutch crunch bread, as well as the fat Italian that is delicious! The only thing is that the order system is a little confusing, when they make you order at the normal counter. I could mention that the delivery usually takes about 45 minutes to get to you depending how busy they are.

Good spot for late night food! 3.5 stars.

column11:
My friend called this the "JV Target" once, and it's definitely stuck. The property isn't at all big enough for a full sized Target, but Santa Barbarians were tired of driving to Ventura for reasonable home goods, so this one got built in a fancy looking mini mall who's best previous tenant was a bagel shop. Then within a year, a real Target moved in to Goleta, and we now have a JV Target. 

That said, this has been THE best place to get groceries during the pandemic - really short lines and plenty of goods. Also, it doesn't smell terrible like the Smart and Final in 5 points. They have a good selection of toys, beauty products, and booze, good prices, and an unhurried atmosphere. If you're going to a birthday party anywhere near La Cumbre, or need a couple quick items, this is your spot.

column11:
VEGAN ALERT : this review is especially for my vegan/vegetarian friends. 
I did enjoy my visit to Lao Wang. The place is lively and quite busy most nights. I love Ramen and finding the perfect vegan ramen has been a hurdle as most of the soups are made with chicken/beef broth. But Lao Wang did not fail me. Their vegan ramen was delicious, flavorful and fresh. The veggies used were seemed very fresh and gave a burst of flavor. Highly recommend it.

I took out 1 star because you don't get the vegan version for the hot and spicy noodles soup. There should be one for those vegans who love spicy. However, they do have a spicy sauce stand... But that doesn't cut it. 

Overall, great place, good ramen and quick service!

column11:
I have been couple of times to Cajun Kitchen at Goleta but it was not much satisfying as compared to one at Santa Barbara. I haven't tried all the menu at this place but I do eat chicken or salmon salad every time I get there. 

To be specific their quality is same but the problem is with quantity.  Cajun kitchen at Santa Barbara servers really good quantity on their various salads such as chicken, shrimp, and salmon. 

At Goleta I have experienced that the quantity is almost half of what they server at SB such as small piece of salmon, chicken, etc. I think they should improve their standards because being a franchise there shouldn't  be any difference in quality and quantity at any of their restaurants.

column11:
After reading the reviews of local restaurants while visiting the area for the weekend my wife and I were excited to try the food at Trattoria Mollie however we weren't even able to make it that far...

We were in the area about an hour before they opened for dinner service and (based on the reviews about the food) decided to wait for a table. After waiting outside for half an hour a couple walked up and a staff member unlocked/opened the door for them, sat them, and took their drink orders (all of this 30 minutes prior to their official open time).  When I walked up to her to see if we could be seated as well, my wife and I were told that the other couple was "an exception to their rules" and that if we wanted a table we would have to wait outside the additional half hour as there was no one ready to take care of us.  Before we could even ask why would couldn't just sit down with a glass of water and wait for the kitchen to open, she turned around and walked away. She didn't try to accommodate us at all let alone apologize for the inconvenience.

At that point we felt completely disregarded. It was as if we didn't even matter to them. When we go out to dinner we love to have the full experience; a nice staff, a good bottle of wine, appetizers, deserts, ports, etc. We both have experience in the food service industry and were shocked that this sort of discrimination had happened to us.

Such a pity, we would have loved to taste the food but unfortunately we will not be coming back.

We fly a lot and never expect too much from restaurants in an airport.  But, this little place hit the spot.  They have nice big tall draft beers, I think $8.  Not terrible for airport beer. Same price as the beer you buy on the plane but twice as big.
We had the beef tacos which were very flavorful and nice and hot.  Our waitress was friendly and did a great job.  
We were not in a rush, so we can't comment on how speedy the service could be if you were in a hurry.
We will eat here again.

column11:
The best two things about Chipotle (these apply to every location):

1) picky eaters paradise! Don't like guac, etc? Don't get it. Much easier than ordering a burrito without guac, etc
2) the commitment to semi sustainable food (organic, locally sources when possible, etc)
3) jalapeno corn salsa

That's three, but you get the idea. Authentic Mexican this is not, but tasty food it is. I always get the barbacoa because I don't like the carnitas here, the other meats always seem dry, and I've had more than my fair share of dark meat in my chicken burrito, no bueno. Cheaper and closer to home than Freebirds, if Freebirds had this corn salsa I'd probably skip Chipotle. Can't get enough corn salsa!

column11:
I was craving empanadas and my wife and yelp saved the day!   I don't know what the difference between Argentinian empanadas are, but these are some of the best empanadas I've ever had.   They're folded in different patterns to help you distinguish which fillings are in which empanada.  My favorite fillings are the carne and the pork verde.  Great flavor and nice flaky crust.

We showed up close to closing time and they were very accommodating and friendly.  If you are ever in the area, the place is a little hard to find and we circled around a couple of times, but I think there are some trees with white Christmas lights out front!

column11:
Prices are excellent.   The combo for less than $9 comes with a good size fries, double cheeseburger, and a drink.   Very simple menu, which I liked!

It's a hole in the wall location with several outdoor seating areas.  Nothing fancy at all.  Didn't look like it's changed in 30 years.

The food is sort of like a non-branded In-N-Out.  

If you wanted melted American cheese on a double beef burger for a good price, this is your place.  It's not a fancy burger, but they stay in their lane!

Was recommended by a local, for locals, during my stay in the area.

column11:
Best tri-tip sandwich I've had in SB! I highly recommend trying the Tri Tip Bauru. This comes on fresh ciabatta bread that is toasted with garlic butter plus chimichurri say whaat? A perfect match made in heaven!! The bread was toasty yet soft. As always when I order a tri tip Sammy from here the meat is always tender and thinly sliced. No chewy/fatty meat going on here!

You get one side item to choose from - Potato salad, macaroni, coleslaw, fruit, or pasta salad.

I have yet to try anything else because I'm hooked on the tri tip but this place offers prime quality beef that's hormone free, no antibiotics, non-GMO feed, and such. Chicken, pork, lamb, and wild buffalo! So if you're looking to have a catering event they got you covered!

Give this place a try if you haven't been here yet! You won't be disappointed.

column11:
Upon the recommendation of our hotel, (Milo; who received a negative review) we dined at brophys.  The food, except the salad was sub par at best. The house salad was great, you could tell they made that salad dressing in house. The calamari was well cooked and the fryer oil was clean, no notes of burnt oil at all. The crab cakes, we're terrible. I suppose being from Maryland, an area who's only attribute is its crab produxts, I can be a snob... but these tasted like they came pre made from safeway. The blackened sea bass was burnt, there is a difference between blackened and burned. The mai tai was all clear rum and quite devoid of flavor. Kudos for attempting to get us drunk but we didn't order shots. 

The service was great, the only thing saving the second star. A plethora of attendants made us feel very well taken care of. 

Over all I would say they need to make their food match their menu descriptions and they would have a solid recipe for success.

column11:
Spent the weekend in Santa Barbara and was craving something savory. Lo and behold we find a pretty yummy Indian restaurant! We appreciated the fact that it was a little away from the busy areas in downtown Santa Barbara. Good for keeping away from Covid. 

Service was acceptable, with an average wait time for food to come out. The chicken tikka masala and veggie masala was pretty good, but not the best I've had. Samosa's weren't bad either. I would def try the latke as it was perhaps the best food I had from the restaurant. Overall, while it may not be the best Indian food I've had, it definitely hit the spot and perhaps the best Indian restaurant in DT Santa Barbara.

column11:
This is a prime spot to have dinner here in Santa Barbara. It's on state street but the prices are a great value for its portions. I ordered the Chicken Vindaloo but have eaten the Tikka Masala and the Rogan Josh here as well. If you're a fan of spicy food, I recommend you to try the entrees here.

The Naan and Garlic Naan bread here is soft and compliments the different sauces well, the Samosas here are also hot n fresh. If you bring a friend, split yourselves between Rice and Naan bread to try between your dishes. The flavors here are really strong without rice or bread so make sure to order one of the two.

The service was expedient and took care of my friends and I. We came on a really hot day in Santa Barbara and they made sure that our water was always filled to the brim.

column11:
I used to love this place, but it seems to have been ruined by its popularity. Good food, yes, though the prices are high. You might have a reasonably good experience at an off-hour. But in prime time, the lines are long, and the staff are grumpy. The constant whirring of the blenders in close proximity is almost deafening and must be stressful for them to be around all day.

I started using the iPhone app to avoid the long lines. The signs say you can avoid waiting altogether by ordering ahead in this way. Simply not true! Most recently, I placed an order through the app, waited until my order was supposed to be ready, showed up, and the place was mobbed. It took me ten minutes to get the attention of a staff member. Now 20 minutes past the time my food was "promised" to be ready, and 35 minutes after I ordered, they hadn't even started making it yet! I left, late for work AND hungry. 

I'm hoping they will move to a larger location and improve their work flow. The food itself is tasty. Just don't expect to get it quickly, or even on time, regardless of whether you phone or app your order in.

column11:
Finally got to try Brophy Bros and we didn't haven't to wait in line for hours! This has been one of the most recommended restaurants in town since I moved and it didn't disappoint. 

Food - Some of the best seafood in town. The calamari was so tender and crisp. For the main course we had salmon and sea bass which were cooked perfectly. Portions are generous and the prices are very reasonable.

Ambience - You must sit on the second floor outside patio! The views of the harbor and the Santa Ynez mountains in the background are incredible. The restaurant definitely encapsulates old school Santa Barbara.

Service - Compared to the other reviews on here I think we lucked out, as we only had to wait 15 minutes. Waitresses were friendly and our food was prepared quickly.

column11:
The Coast Restaurant & Bar is the lobby bar and restaurant for the Canary Hotel, previously called the Hotel Andalucia.  Why they changed the name, I'll never know.  "Hotel Andalucia" had a Santa Barbara ring to it whereas "Canary Hotel" doesn't seem quite as inviting.

As for the restaurant itself, I think they did a great job on the remodel which seems brighter, more open and inviting, and the bar is happening.  This was actually my second time at the restaurant, the first time was for dinner on Valentines day where they had a prefixed menu that had a limited number of entrees, which was disappointing to most of the group.  This evening, however, we had thought it would be a good place to come as a group of six to have some good food and conversation.  Overall, however, the food was just ok, nothing very memorable.  Within our group, we had a Grilled Red Snapper sandwich special, Grilled King Salmon, Flat Iron Steak, Seared Tuna, Grilled Chicken Breast and Fish & Chips.  Again, nothing out of this world.  Perhaps next time we'll need to try the french dip and beef ragout.  As for the conversation, we could hardly hear one another as it was so loud - noise coming from a single large table and the bar area.  

Cudos on the beer list though - not a big selection, they did have some interesting microbrew and imported beer which were a hit with our group.

column11:
Appalling service (if I could give zero stars I would).

I just came from dinner here. I've had better service drunk at 2am at IHOP.

I've been coming here for birthdays and other special occasions for over 15 years, and tonight, that tradition ended.

We wanted to celebrate our sister's engagement, so we thought the Biltmore would be the perfect place to do that. 

Here's what went right:
-The red wine.

Here's what went wrong:
- seated at kitchen entrance, after calling twice earlier that day requesting we be seated at a quiet table specifically away from the kitchen.
-wine glasses and water glasses were used interchangeable by the waiters - who had no idea that there is a difference between red, white, and water glasses. I enjoyed white wine water when the waiter filled my white wine 'glass' with water.
-we had to ask for the candle on our table to be lit.
-the waiter never greeted us to go over the menu. In fact, I'm pretty sure two bus boys waited on us the whole night.
-the white wine was warm, and although the bus boy brought an ice bucket to put it in, left the white wine on the table.
-after no one waited on us for 20 minutes, my Dad flagged down the manager, who immediately waited on us, but had no knowledge of the menu. When we asked how big the appetizer size was compared to the main course size, he said, "The app size is nice, and smaller than the entree." 
-We noticed a chef hat by two items on the menu, so we asked the waiter/ bus boy what that meant, and he said, "I don't know."
-once our salads came out, we had to ask for fresh pepper.
-at one point, a female seeming manager came over because clearly she could tell something was off, so my Dad told her the above, and she proceeded to do nothing about it. We didn't see her the rest of the night (pretty sure she hid).
-They brought out a 'Congratulations' dessert, which we couldn't eat because we had no silverware, even though the honoree asked for forks, but those utensils never showed. For the tenth time, we asked for our water glasses to be filled, but they weren't.
-At the end, the waiter brought the check to one of the daughters and then a male manager approached us. Instead of being apologetic, he argued that he was overseeing 190 guests and "did his best." Despite him paying the check, which he thought would make everything better (clearly he missed the point), our sister's special night will be remembered as a joke.
-the food, which was unmemorable, was overshadowed by the horrific service.

We will never recommend this to anyone, despite being Montecito residents (and believe it or not down to earth), and we will never go back.

column11:
ABSOLUTELY AMAZING!! My friend and I decided to give this NEW place a try, and I'm glad we did. Everything here is perfect: the open-to-the-street design, the food, wines. 

I ordered the ORO PURO pizza which is the one with black caviar and 24k gold flakes. I've never had gold on my gourmet before so I had to try, and besides, the caviar was amazing so that's what was giving the pizza the rich flavor. The dough is black unique dough which makes it feel like fresher than white dough. My friend got the AVOCADO SALMON in a jar--so very fresh! The plating/utensils/the cork menu are unique: the jars, the bottle-plates (you'll understand what I'm saying when you go here). 

The OWNER is a wonderful man from Pravia, Italy, and he has so many amazing stories (and recommendations for travel). I loved listening to him! And he quotes the beginning of Dante's Inferno by heart. How can you not love this place after all this?! Go here please!! I want them to be successful and stay open. Oh yeah. Try the sweet wine he recommends with your dessert: out of this world!! HIGHLY RECOMMENDED

column11:
Just woke up and decided to drop by because this place was right across from where me and my girlfriends were staying at. 

Was seated outside and had a terrific view of the water.  Our waitress was really nice and introduced her favorites on the menu.  Overall the food was standard, not spectacular, just standard. While we waited the seagulls kept us company but we were told not to repay them back in food. 

I'd say it was a nice place to chill with fresh seafood. 

The lasting impression was made by the shrimp shooter. Its like a shot glass with cocktail sauce and a piece of shrimp or oyster depending on what you order. It was A M A Z I N G G G... I think it'll be the closest I'll ever get to knowing how Peter Parker felt when he first transformed into the Spiderman. My friend described the feeling after you take it as, "heightened senses"... I cannot agree more... haha. You literally SEE clearer, HEAR better, BREATH deeper... That shot definitely woke us up. A Must Try! 

I'd definitely come back for the shooters, not so much the seafood. 

check out my pictures :  )

column11:
Roy is the perfect compromise of hip and fine dining. The bread is freshly made, the salad greens come from the local farmers market, and the entrees are delicious. This is the only restaurant downtown I know of that offers a reasonable prix fixe menu of quality courses, about $25 for soup, salad and main course with a side of vegetables. I often order the duck breast or almond crusted fish, but I know that the bacon-wrapped filet mignon is very popular. If you have space for dessert (ordered a la carte), I highly recommended the flourless chocolate torte. Not to say that the mousse or creme brulee are bad, but the torte is so so good that the other desserts pale in comparison.
Roy himself is often there, and can come by the tables to chat and check up on patrons. On weekends there might be live music, like Spencer the Gardner. On other nights Spencer might even be your waiter!  And hey, Roy serves food up to midnight, that's no lie, I know this from first hand experience. 
The bar is also very popular, so much so that sometimes service gets a little gridlocked there.  Maybe I need to harden up my elbowing abilities or project myself better.
