column11: Growing up in Hawaii there are L and L's everywhere but this is the cleanest and nicest one I've ever been to. I've lived in sb for 11 years and was blessed to have this place open. Without the comfort of Hawaiian food I would be so home sick as there is no where else in this town that sells plate lunches. During the years I have even made friends with some of the employees that work there. The manager Alan is super friendly and full of Aloha, he is also from Hawaii to add even more authenticity. BBQ anything is good here while I definetly recommend trying a musubi if you have never had one

column11:
I'm a little disappointed, is it me or did they used to give you bigger portions? Last time I was here I was a little disappointed that they didn't give me as much as a I remembered. 

The saag tofu (that green stuff that most people don't get because it looks like baby poo but its really good.) wasn't as bright of a green as it should be if it were fresh. The saag tofu is usually pretty good here I'm guessing I just went at a bad time and the old batch still there. When its fresh its really good with your naan.

All the chicken dishes are pretty good (you can't really go wrong there).  

As far as boba goes, I would definitely stay away from it here unless you're really craving it.

column11:
JUST NO.

Haven't been here in YEARS. Decided to give it a try.

First off, FYI- you can call and make a reservation, but not on the actual day you need them. You have to do it ahead of time by at least a day.

They are dog friendly on the patio, which I appreciate.

They are open at full capacity inside now, but still have outdoor dining.

Being a group of 6, with no reservation, we were sat pretty quickly outside. 

Problem started with the bathrooms. The sewer smell was so incredibly horrible, we could barely breathe, and we had masks on! It wasn't the cleanest either. I was informed by a server that they are having issues with the city about it, but it put a bad "taste" in my mouth, quite literally, upon arrival. 

Walking back to my table, I started to see what a dump the place had become. It's filthy, I got grossed out  walking back to our table. The bread and salsa station is filthy and is actually falling backwards as both the legs up front are off the ground. Food and trash all over the ground, everywhere, and it was only 6pm on a Saturday. 

The front entrance of the restaurant is where the kitchen is, but there is a table at the front for their to-go orders right when you walk in the front door, and it was just complete chaos and looked horrible, dirty, and unorganized. 

Now the food. It was gross. If you came for the stiff drink, go for it, but pass on the food. Trust me.

Steak was over cooked, I even asked the waitress how their chef was on his temps so I could plan accordingly. I was assured that if anything they are a lower temp than normal, and I could always cook it up more if need be. The baked potatoes are old, precooked and then reheated so much so that the entire first half of the potato is hard, dark, and inedible. 

My friend ordered the burnt ends sandwich and was stoked because she had never heard of that before and loves the burnt ends. But they don't serve a burnt ends sandwich. We were informed by the manager that they don't have enough to do that for every sandwich and they just chop up meat from the prime rib and tri-tip to mix in with whatever burnt ends they have. Here's a thought, how about you just only serve the burnt ends, and when you are out, you are out. Elevate your menu like you care about what goes out to your patrons. OR explain that when someone orders so they are not disappointed. When she discussed this with the manager, there wasn't an apology, he just took the plate and they went and fried up the pieces in a pan and brought it back on the same bread it was served on. It was disgusting.

Not once did anyone ask how our food was for me to correct it quickly, and we had to be somewhere, so I just doused the steak in salt and ate it. $25 for a steak, I can do better at home. 

When we told the waitress about our experience and the frustration with the food, she apologized but nothing else. You'd think they would have comp'd something. Anything. Or had the manager come back over himself.

Sliders and fries were good. 

Clam chowder has always been good. 

But nothing else was. 

It's a shame, the history and nostalgia of this place is what made me want to bring our friends and family to experience. Hell, I even was one of the very first staff to open Harry's, under the new management of John Scott. 

We won't be returning, not unless it's for a stiff drink at the bar.

column11:
This place is great. I'm a coffee fanatic from the Bay Area, but I was in Santa Barbara this last weekend. I walked in because of the ivy all over the walls and walked out with a really good latte. Prices are fine. Not cheap, but not overboard. The coffee shop itself is really well put together, and there's lots of space in the back where people were studying (although it was a bit loud for that). The building was packed on the sunday afternoon when I went, and the cashier was less than friendly to me because I was wearing an absurd, 3 pound feathered peacock necklace that was a but distracting (there's an explanation)

anyway, good coffee, good ambiance, good location. If I lived near, I'd go all the time.

column11:
Go when you're turnt. It's pretty much a hit or miss for me when I go after the clubs close. The Mac n cheese is always really good for those 2AM nights when you're stopping by from other clubs. Come only after a party. They have the vegetarian, meat and ultimate option but personally I find the vegetarian to be the best value for the biggest fill. Always go for the hot cheetos on top for a $1 extra because it's so worth it.

The wait can take either 5 minutes or 30 depending on their stock. I do with they had another person to call out names instead of having the server having to call out people's names because that slows things down. 

It got bad at one point when there was a small fight that happened in the line, though it was definitely just impatient drunk people. 
The staff are nice, it's just that having 3 staff people handle everything seems too few given the crowds of people late night. Maybe a 4th staff member can handle things better.

column11: Having not eaten at this restaurant for over two years, my girlfriend and I thought it would be good to pay Your Place a visit. We were greeted quickly and politely, and our drinks were brought to us speedily as well. The real star quality of this restaurant comes from the menu. There are so many great dishes, it will probably take a while to pick your meal. While we decided on what to get, we had the waiter bring us some fried wantons. The appetizer came out very quickly, and we had finally chosen our entrees. Being a curry fan myself, I went with the panag curry house special and substituted tofu for meat. My girlfriend got the beef and bellpeppers. The food must have arrived a mere 7-8 minutes after we ordered. We were delighted with the food and the service from the evening. The only thing I would recommend to the staff would be to provide water after seating customers.

column11: Hubby & I were driving back from Santa Barbara and we hadn't had breakfast yet. So I started looking on yelp for something that caught my eye... and the food pix alone did just that! I started the directions and we headed to Rincon Beach Bar. It was very easy to get there and found parking right away. As soon as we walked in I thought it was beautiful! The garden style seating was my favorite, there was plenty of shade, greenery all around, and the best part was the sound of the ocean greeting you at your table. The hostess was very pleasant and extremely helpful with the ordering process ( contactless ordering). You order and pay from your phone.... gratuity is already included in the bill which she explained that it was equally split with all employees. I ordered the huevos rancheros which weren't as spicy as I would of liked but they were VERY delicious. Hubby got French toast casserole w/strawberries.....let me tell you I'm still thinking about how decadent it was! The crispy brown sugar on the edges was to die for!! The orange juice was on point & they don't mess around with the coffee.....tasty & strong! All the food was amazing and customer service was great. I have to say this has been one of my favorite places for brunch, this will be our go to place every time we visit Ventura or Santa Barbara. Thanks for a memorable meal Ricon;)

column11:
I generally really like Giovanni's but tonight was an unmitigated disaster.  I called in at 6:30 to place my usual order to-go. The guy on the phone was only half paying attention to me, he had to ask me twice what I wanted. That should have been my first clue.  Then he asked me to give them 45 minutes because they were busy. I thought, good for them.  When I got there 45 minutes later there was NO parking anywhere. I drove around for 15 minutes looking for parking. When I finally found a parking space and walked in the sound level of the place was through the roof. A huge party of maybe 20 adults and kids were there. Very disorganized. They obviously hadn't pre-ordered and they were very demanding of the staff who were totally disorganized and overwhelmed.  I waited another 45 minutes while I watched people from the big table keep walking up to the window asking for one thing at a time. One man walked up no fewer than 8 times each time asking for 1 thing.  Each time pulling a cook away from what he was doing to go fetch that man a fork or ranch dressing or Italian dressing or remake his complicated pizza that he didn't order correctly the first time.  When I finally walked up to the window to ask about my order they pulled my pizza from on top of the oven and told me they were just waiting for my salad to be made.  I'm sure if I hadn't asked I'd have waited another hour.  The guys were so overwhelmed all they were doing was responding to whomever was asking loudest for something.  Or GrubHub, their orders were always ready when a GrubHub driver came in. They were in and out in a matter of seconds. 
I ended up with a cold pizza and poorly thrown together salad with the wrong dressing.  And the worst part is the guy at the counter wasn't apologetic, not really.  He told me to look around and see how busy they were.  As if that was an appropriate response.  Yes, they were busy but they had 6-8 staff on so they knew they were going to busy.  They were disorganized and overwhelmed and when that happens you apologize to customers, you don't ask them to feel sorry for you. Especially not after they've waited an hour and a half and you just handed them a cold pizza and a poorly made salad.  I won't be spending my hard earned money there any more.

Lots of fresh seafood on the menu, but also a few options for those who do not do fish. The clam chowder was excellent. However, we found the lobster bisque disgusting. I indulged in the drink specials- "man-mosa"- a mimosa in a pint glass! Can't wait to visit Santa Barbara again for another lunch at Enterprise!

column11:
Husband and I walk by this place frequently on our evening walks about town. Decided to try it last Friday night for dinner. Read the Yelp reviews; hit or miss it seems. Menu was easy to find on the Yelp page (thank you!) and the food was exactly what we were craving. Burgers, pasta, salads. What really intrigued me and have to admit is the main reason we went, was the pic of the artichoke app on the site.  I LOVE artichokes! I really love artichokes done well and that pic won me over.
Place is very large with outdoor seating on two patios and large indoor seating. This does not include the bar area attached. We sat outside on the top patio.  Greeter was friendly, sat right away. Waitress came over right away. Friendly greeting. Mentioned it was our first time and open to suggestions. She offered a couple (don't recall them) and I shared my excitement for the artichoke app and how it was the reason for us being there.  Ordered the artichoke along with the pappardelle pasta, side of black bean soup, side of mashed potatoes. My husband wasn't super hungry so the side orders were his.  Great way to try a variety of items that all sounded soooo good!
Artichoke app arrived and it was GREAT! Garlic, onion, tomato, yes, yes, yes. Cooked perfectly. Easy to eat the meat off the leaves, leaves pulled off easy from the heart. So happy this was as good as hoped.
Black bean soup tasted ok.  Really thick which was fine but it hardened up pretty quickly and reminded us of chocolate pudding. Mashed potatoes were ok, nothing amazing but liked the skins included and not a lot of butter.  
Pappardelle pasta was very flavorful! Garlic, onion, tomato, olives. Noodles a bit al dente (sp?) which made me very happy. Love big wide noodles. Very large portion, should have shared it but good news, took half home and ate it for lunch the next day! Love pasta that holds up to being as flavorful as the next day. We will be back & try out the bar next time. 
We had an iced tea and water on top of our food, total was $48sh.  Seemed a bit expensive but the overall experience was A-OK!

column11:
Horrible. Came here for lunch with a colleague at noon. We quickly ordered off the  very simple lunch menu which has about 10 options. The staff didn't know if coffee or espresso drinks could be made. Huh? At an Italian restaurant? Someone figured out how to make one but asked how it tasted (it tasted burnt) as he wasn't sure if he did it correctly. 
15 minutes later some stale cold white bread was placed on the table without any accompaniments. The server said our food would be right out. Another 20 minutes went by and we had to inquire what was taking so long as we had to leave soon. It took some time to figure out and the staff came to apologize and ask if we wanted the food to go. We said we would take it to go if it would be ready in 5 minutes. They said that wasn't possible. 
Wow, this place needs to figure things out quick to have any chance of surviving the location

column11:
MEH! 

Stopped by on the way to LA for Xmas. Why the lowly 1 *? Here's why

Pros:
Cleanliness is 5 *'s; tables clean, chairs aligned, the banos very clean.
Counter person somewhat pleasant 4 *'s.
 
Cons: 
- Not all tacos $1.75. Was charged $1.90 for Lengua. The register didn't have Birria so it was rung up as Asada @ $1.75. Basically they charge what they want as the menu board does not list prices. 
-  Nice salsa bar with plenty of chopped cilanto, diced onions, sliced radishes and lime wedges. No containers readily available to taste rojo or verde salsas, only the large serving spoon. Looking around later it appears you have to ask for them. How cheap. Settled on a rojo which appeared spicy but was not. It was gringo style mild. The other is tomato juice.
- Taco tortillas are SMALL, like 3.5" not the 5-6" I'm accustomed too. This makes the meat portion look large when in actuality they are small. Although fresh the tortilla has a mild corn flavor. Not a good sign.
- Lengua 2.5 *'s, was over-boiled lacking in flavor. Hey, ever hear of an onion, salt, or pepper? Tongue skin not removed you get chunks of skin with each bite which has the consistency of fat. 
- Birria should be minus 2 *'s and not served at all. It arrives swimming in an off beat red sauce. Dipped my baby finger tip in it and saw paprika grinds and swimming in oil. The taste was paprika with no salt, no peppers, no nothing but the overabundant stale oil and paprika. Here's the nasty part, the shredded birria itself was as tough as shoe leather, not soft and tender as I've had in Mexico or numerous other taquerias up/down Calif. That was it, one bite and I spat it out.. Yes, we're talking TOUGH, show leather tough. 5 *'s on the YUCK scale!

I wouldn't eat here again even if it was for free.

column11: In my original review, I stated we'd be back, well we came back.  We had an outstanding waitress.  However, the food that morning ~10:00 was so bad, possibly they had a "rent-a-cook" preparing the food.  Both of our breakfasts were not good at all and it took forever for the food to show up - was not hot.  I could go on and on, but I'll leave it at that.  I am sure glad we didn't have our friends with us that morning.  So disappointing as we had hoped that we found a new "To Go" place to eat in Santa Barbara.

column11: Curbside seating and takeout for COVID. Grab your own table or let staff know. We had our dog so he was able to sit with us too. Order inside and they'll bring your food to you. The menus posted in the window too so you can browse in line. We ordered homemade sopes (chicken and beef), arroyo burrito (fish and shrimp), protein burrito and 1 item plate asada taco (rice and beans). The food tasted alright, lacking a little flavor/seasoning for me to give it more stars. But the ingredients were fresh. Generous with the meat which was also very tender. Complementary chips and salsa with the meal, the chips were still hot! Staff was polite and we left stuffed and happy. The nearest parking would probably be lot 4(?) behind CVS or on the street.

column11:
My family and I ate in store.  I went to my car, saw a homeless man and asked him if I could buy him something to eat. He did not ask me nor was he in front of their store. I went to order something for him while my family was eating and was told by the male cashier I was not allowed to buy for the man outside. I asked why and he repeated his manager has told him he won't allow it but the manager didn't come out. I explained that he didn't ask me to buy him anything and that I asked him and was buying while he was waiting outside. They would NOT let me buy him anything to eat.

We left.

I have emailed them to ask why this is their policy and after following up I finally received a response saying they would look into it. I heard nothing.  Followed up again and was told this shouldn't have happened and they would find out but never heard back again.

I recommend dining at a different place out.

column11:
Commonly known to the locals as The Biltmore, this is the definition of luxury at it's best! The grounds are amazing, and service is top notch! From the moment you walk onto the property, you are greeted and are welcomed. When they say you get what you pay for, with The Biltmore, you really do. The Biltmore was recently renovated within the past few years, and from what I understand the new owner is the founder of Beanie Babies (Ty Warner). The rooms are elegant, with modern amenities, while keeping to the integrity of the Spanish architecture. I was fortunate enough to stay in one of the suites, which included a fireplace, and even an ocean view! I was celebrating my anniversary, and upon return to my room after dinner, I was greeted with champagne and a strawberry chocolate tower. Now that is service!
With that being said, this place is not cheap by means, it is probably one of the most expensive resorts in the Santa Barbara area. However if you can afford to splurge just once, The Biltmore is definitely worth it!
column13: Four Seasons Resort The Biltmore Santa Barbara

column11:
It's the convenience and the location that keeps me coming. I can walk here in a couple of minutes and I always get the same thing for breakfast. Unfortunately, I always get it made differently every time and that is my pet peeve. 

I typically order a breakfast bagel sandwich (bagel, sometimes mayo, sausage and egg) and it seems that everyone has a different way of making it. Some of the times I can tell that these employees don't enjoy making it because it requires effort instead of grabbing a donut and ringing them up.

I definitely think they have their moments with employment from time to time and it's never consistent (cause it's a college job) but they have definitely had their fair share of employees I can live without.

They usually have a vast selection of donuts but if you are going there late at night (last hour of closing) don't expect a variety of donuts. They are closing up and making more for tomorrow morning. What it seems like is that they make all their donuts in the morning and sell them throughout the day which makes sense to why people aren't getting a variety of choices late at night.

The wifi is good and to study there is alright. It's impossible for me during the day but at night it becomes a little more tolerable.

UPDATE: I did want to mention how hard working the manager is and that is he the only reason this place really deserves a 5* rating.

column11:
Although I didn't get a chance to actually shop here, I walked inside for a while during Christmas Eve and thought this Spanish colonial revival mall square is definitely a really cool place to check out! Paseo Nuevo is downtown Santa Barbara's biggest shopping square so most festivities will probably happen here. You will also find your typical mall chain stores, although even if you don't shop, a stroll through here is a nice experience as well! 

Its parking garage allows 80-minute free parking, so why not come by and check this shopping center out?

column11: I have been coming to Juice Ranch ever since it opened. The juice is great, no complaints. However, every single damn time I am in there the employees are so rude. It has been on multiple occasions where the rudeness has occurred. Before class one day I was in a rush to get a juice and there was a parking spot right in front, perfect right? Until the OWNER snakes my spot (you would think she would be kind enough to give the spot to a loyal customer who is in a rush and will be leaving in 5 minutes. After I park down the block, the woman who I am guessing is the owner is just sitting there on her laptop and does not even greet the customers. If the owner doesn't even greet any customer then why should the employees? Its a shame because the product is delicious and healthy, however I will not be returning to juice ranch. I am over paying $10 for a juice then getting treated like shit on top of it. If you want a great cold-pressed juice/elixir I recommend going to The Alchemy Cafe in the Alchemy Art Center. Everything is made fresh and they have wonderful customer service. It honestly sucks I never write reviews on yelp but absolutely nothing has changed, same thing every time I am in there and the sad thing is i've had friends say the same thing to me about the service. Hope this can change because I truly do love the juice.

column11:
Drinks are okay.  They use milk powder and syrup to flavor and sweeten their teas.  The vibe and decor is cute.  Targeted for college students with way too much $ and willing to spend big bucks for mediocrity on drinks and snacks.  
Ordered the popcorn chicken...small size for the price...fried pork chop...literally a box of pork chop cut into strips...on the dry side....but comes without anything else, no sauce, not rice/noodles...fish balls with curry...was cold...they didn't microwave it enough or something...they was cold...yikes!

All things considering...I knew what I was walking into and was prepped to pay for over priced bobas and snacks...however, what annoys me the most are the unapologetic dismissive attitude and rudeness  of the girl working there!  So rude, go to order, never greeted me or made eye contact.  Her body posture told me that I was bothering her for ordering or asking questions about a drink.  Snatched my credit card, ran thru the system...no thank you, here is your receipt...nothing.  Handed me the curled up receipt with her 2 fingers.  Seriously?  Bad service, I understand but bitch face service is a whole new level. Felt like I was dealing with my teenage daughter the whole time after I grounded her.

column11:
We stopped here for breakfast which we normally do each time we are here in Santa Barbara and have always had  a decent breakfast both from the tasty standpoint of it and the service has always been good.
This time, something was a miss, because we were seated right away and had our order taken, our coffee arrived and they the wait began.

We waited, and waited, meanwhile the other table next to us that ordered after us was served. 

The server came by and refilled our coffees and said our order would be right up.  Well ok it was after another 10 minutes. Mind you the place only had about 5 tables full and it was after the morning rush.
 The food did arrive and it was hot, and it tasted ok.  This was the time I wish I had my phone with me with the camera because I would have loved to have taken a picture of my egg dish. I ordered a couple of sunnyside up eggs and sausage.  What I saw on the plate instantly made the whole plate unappetizing. 

Usually I remember getting sausage links in several links.  What I got this time was a piece of sausage about 1/2 and inch  in diameter, about 6 or 7 inches long, that was curled up around it's self.
 Unless I had know it was a breakfast sausage of some kind, I could have mistaken it for something else, especially if it was placed on the sidewalk outside.....

Next time I will bring my camera, you had to have seen this to imagine what it looked like.   I almost sent the whole thing back, but after waiting for such a long time,  I opted to eat.

Aside from the lost order or whatever, either the cook has changed or something else because what use to be a nice hearty breakfast , eggs,  some great potatoes was now a couple of eggs with about 4 or 5 small pieces of potatoes.  Come on, potatoes are cheap, you could at least load the plate so it looked like you were getting something for the 15 bucks to put down in front of the customer.  Denny's for 8 bucks can do it all day, you would think they could make a better effort. My only thought was that they must of run out of potatoes,  and the usual garnish of a sliced orange or fruit, and just decided to plop down the eggs and half handful of potatoes and so be it.
Bring back the old Tre Lune, we'll try it one more time, before we totally write it off.

column11:
Eh... I wouldn't recommend this place for anything besides breakfast, but if it's a breakfast you're looking for, this place is a definite go to spot.  The service is kind of slow so if you're the impatient type in the mornings, call in your order and then come pick it up.  If you're a slow starter like me, well we're good to go.

All the food they serve here are excellent and while the price is a bit pricey, in return you get a whopping large meal for it.  If there's any downside to it, it would be that the foods aren't really cajun.  They just make use of some cajun recipes.

column11:
Had high hopes for Alphie's. The reviews are generally positive and I love going to new towns and finding no-frills, solid diners. 

We had no complaints with the service, which some have focused on. It wasn't necessarily warm, but certainly nothing to complain about. The design of the place is traditional American diner with Hawaiian inflections, which was cool with me. 

Judging from the reviews, it seemed like there were two go-to items: the omelets and the biscuits and gravy. I ordered both. The omelet was fine, but nothing to write home about. Technically, I don't even think it counts as an omelet, which I've always understood to be an egg dish to which meat or vegetables are added or folded into while cooking. The Alphie's "omelet" is a sheet of scrambled eggs laid on top of whatever other ingredients you've ordered. In theory you'd think that this would make for some tasty eggs.  In reality, they were pretty dry, though the mushroom/avocado/ham "filling" underneath was well-cooked and tasty. 

The biscuits and gravy were the real disappointment. The biscuits were tough and stale. The gravy was fine, but not warm or flavorful enough to makeup for hard biscuits. 

Next time I'm in the area, I'll have to try one of the other local breakfast/brunch spots.

column11:
Being new to the area, I've explored different types of places for food, drinks and entertainment.  Somehow, I find myself gravitating back to Eureka.  The Santa Barbara location is as good as it gets in the area for multiple reasons.  The food selection is diverse, yet simple enough to sort through for a quick and casual meal.  Their burgers, of course, being their hallmark; try their fish tacos.  I've yet to grow tired of them-they're fresh, definitely full of flavor, and resonably priced.  But you won't be able to go wrong anywhere on their happy hour menu, so try everything at least once.  If you sign in for a table and there's a short wait, be patient; it will be worth it.

The over 30 beer selections available represent the best of every variety brewed in the western U.S.  Try testing your bartender by letting them know what you like, and I guarantee they can offer you 2 or 3 terrific selections that will make it difficult to decide on just one!  It's not just about being able to brew your own.

One thing that keeps me coming back is the staff from top to bottom.  The bartenders are friendly, respectful, and true beer geeks.  And with their rotation of brews, they really do keep up with the best beers in the area.  The place is managed extremely well;  I've met the management staff and it's evident they truly care about their customers, about service, and about the food quality.  We've all been to places that lack good management, and it shows.  This place is a well-oiled machine.  Every staff member I've been in contact with has demonstrated true hospitality.  Whether an afternoon lunch, or dinner time, I have really felt comfortable here with every visit.

column11:
This place deserves a solid 5 stars!! I've been around and in the food bus most of my life and TOMA HAS IT ALL! Great service, innovative delicious food, ambience, great cocktails and wine list. 
Service-We were walk-ins at 5:15 on a Monday. Found it on Yelp as we were passing through town. The host was very kind, welcoming and accommodating. Our waiter, Gabe C, was knowledgeable, not pushy, didn't rush us, he was very attentive, interactive and made us feel relaxed so we could enjoy our meal. And he used a crumbed! A lost touch of class art. The bus boys were attentive and made sure dishes were cleared and our waters were filled. Amazing staff!
Food- So crazy great! The tuna cones were the right amount of spice for the tuna wrapped in a medium sweet delicate sesame cone. The combination was perfect!
The lasagna was by far the best I ever had. Flavors of red wine soaked braised beef with ricotta spinach filling and well balanced sauce. Fabulous!
The very light pillows of gnocchi were accompanied by succulent rock shrimps, baked tomatoes and bits of truffle. Again, the best I've ever had. It's light, not like most heavy gnocchi I've experienced.
Our waiter sent us out a taste of their raspberry mousse with strawberries that can be found in their phyllo crisp...outrageously good!
The Local starts with a reduced balsamic swirl on the inner rim of the glass, then filled with muddled strawberries and basil, mixed with cucumber vodka, agave and lime...the perfect cocktail...I had two!

Do not take a second thought, make a reservation now! By 5:45 this place had almost every seat filled!

Thank you to TOMA and the amazing staff!

column11:
I have to preface this review by saying most of my negative experiences here I think have to do with the fact that this is a very old property, but several of the problems I noticed are easy fixes that should not fly under the radar at a Four Seasons hotel that charges around $700/night for a normal guest room.  The staff was absolutely fantastic pretty much across the board from the front desk to the breakfast buffet and pool staff, the food was great and the place is absolutely beautiful.  

However, some aspects of this property in my opinion fell below what I believe would be par for the course for a Four Seasons property, such as thin, course bath towels and somewhat chintzy bedding that you'd more likely find at a Best Western.  I was also shocked to find a tub shower with shower curtains in the first room they put us in.  I'm not sure I've ever stayed at a Four Seasons, let alone any 5 Star hotel, that had a darn shower curtain.  I was also pretty surprised that one of our sinks had a very slow drain, which eventually completely clogged by the end of our stay, which was gross.  We had a few other friends staying there that said they noticed similar plumbing issues.  These items should be easy fixes and IMO are inexcusable, especially at a property charging $700/night for normal rooms.  

What was very unpleasant was the fact that this building is old and there is virtually zero acoustical engineering done, and I mean it quite literally that when you are in the guest rooms you can hear people outside your room as if they are inside your room.  We were first placed in a lower level room, and the first morning we were woken up at 6am to the people above us walking around.  They were not being unreasonably boisterous, the sound just traveled right down to our room.  Then construction began at 7am, which I think was directly next to the hotel (not on the hotel property), which kept us up.  Not the fault of the hotel at all, but if the acoustical properties was better, I don't think it would have been so horrible to deal with.  We asked to be moved to an upper level room, and our request was immediately granted, so we stayed our next two nights in an upper level room.  The only problem then was the fact that this room was directly above some kind of meeting room, and our next morning we were unfortunately woken up by a door constantly slamming shut.  I went down to see what the commotion was, to learn it was the door, which did not make much noise when you're using it, but the sound of it slamming shut resonated directly up to our room and was horrible.  The staff member who was going in and out of that room immediately and pleasantly granted my request to simply keep the door open as they went in and out, so the problem was solved, but not after we had our second night of sleep cut short.  The door was not used the morning after our last stay, so our last night of sleep was not cut short and it was a quiet morning, thank goodness. 

Both of the rooms I stayed in had a musty odor, sort of like an old library, although it was much worst in the first room we were in.  The second room was somewhat tolerable.  It was bad enough in the first room that the smell permeated into the bedding. 

Although not a big deal, when we returned to our room after the wedding we attended (at the hotel), neither of our room keys worked, so we had to go all the way to the front desk to get new ones.  They were, of course very apologetic, but it was not what I wanted to be doing late at night. 

My only other unpleasant experience was on our first night at the Tyde's restaurant.  The food was amazing, but the service sucked, and I would have to imagine it was due to the fact that they included gratuity, so their servers weren't working for a tip.  And we only had a 3 person party, and they slapped us with an included 18% gratuity, which I find to be totally tacky, especially at a Four Seasons hotel.  I wouldn't mind it for a large party, but we were three people.  

In sum, if you are looking for a getaway to a very beautiful property and don't care too much about peace and quiet and being able to unwind, this is a great spot.  Between the gardens, tile work and architecture, the property is honestly a piece of artwork.  But, the flip side to that coin coin is the fact that you really don't have peace and quiet in the guest rooms,a and many other problems existed that I felt fell way short of Four Seasons properties.  The sound issue is likely tough to fix without an 8 digit renovation; however, the stupid things we encountered such as crappy towels and bedding, clogged sink, included gratuity on a dinner with bad service, shower curtains, etc, are easy fixes.  I picked this hotel because I had thought paying extra for a Four Seasons experience would guarantee that things like this won't be present, but I was apparently wrong and will be more scrutinizing towards their properties in the future.

column11:
I was searching Yelp for somewhere to eat brunch/breakfast on our getaway to Santa Barbara and scrolled through all the fancy brunch places with their special rendition of eggs benny or french toast and zeroed in on JJ's as the place I wanted to go and I was definitely not let down. 

Right on State St it is pretty much walkable from anywhere in downtown SB and they have both outdoor seating, indoor booth, and counter top. I haven't been to many diners, but this is definitely what I imagine when I think of a diner. 

Service was awesome and sometimes you're just craving a black cup of diner bean water and that's exactly what I got this morning. 

I might be getting old or something, but I no longer crave those fancy brunches, but really love corned beef hash. Some places try way to hard and use fat chunks of corned beef or try to make it pop. What I really want when I get corned beef hash is that stuff that comes out of the Hormel can, call me uncultured, but that stuff when it gets crispy is better than anything else. What they have at JJ's is the closest I've gotten to the Hormel can at a restaurant, but with nice strands of corned beef. They really got the corned beef together with everything and nailed getting everything crispy on the griddle. A+ 

GF got steak and eggs and for a diner the steak was cooked perfectly and actually tasted damn good. Her hash browns as shown were also cooked splendid. Both eggs were cooked well to liking and sourdough on the side was nice. 

Definitely come here!

column11:
The Santa Barbara Art Foundry & Gallery is located off of Santa Barbara Street.  The space is also the home for Fox Wine Co., in which you can do some wine-tasting while perusing the art pieces.  This loft-like gallery features local artists, and I became a fan of Kevin Gleason's and Wallace's pieces, as they had a great use of color!  Gleason's landscape paintings were very cute and whimsical, while Wallace's pieces were very pop-art ish, using noticeable brand labels that were implemented within.  You can also rent the place for events, such as parties, weddings, as well as corporate get-togethers.  Definitely a cool place to check out, and there's plenty of street parking available.

+check out Gleason's and Wallace's pieces!
+Fox Wine Co. wine tasting located within
+free street parking

column11:
Last time I came, I had my favorite brunch ever. I'm sorry to say that this time, it was not the best experience... After waiting for a table for a while, we were seated right next to some sort of exhaust fumes from the kitchen. I ordered some orange juice and the Scarlett Cheeseburger (well done) and after 25 minutes, the burger finally came out... medium rare. And instead of the bacon marmalade written on the menu, I found a two-inch chunk of bacon under the cheese. The waitress took it back, and I waited for another twenty minutes for my burger to come back, and another ten minutes on top of that for the orange juice. 

The servers were courteous, but honestly I did not feel cared for or respected. This, on top of the botched meal and expensive prices, just didn't make the visit worth it.

column11:
It's the little things in life that make us happy right? Well this bakery does just that! After trying their cupcakes at a birthday event, I immediately wanted more. I love desserts, but if it's overly sweet then it's not for me. By far these cupcakes are the best that I've ever had! I've pretty much tried every flavor they offer and they are all equally delicious. The ingredients are top quality, and the amount of sweetness is just right. They are light, airy and melt in your mouth. I love that they offer the cupcakes in mini form or whole, so if you want to try all of them, then the mini cupcakes are perfect for sampling. They make these daily, so you don't need to order them unless you want a specific flavor or amount for a special event. 

After eating the cupcakes, I knew that I would order my son's birthday cake from this bakery. I placed my order online, which was very simple to do, but the hard part was choosing the flavor of cake, filling, and icing. Mind you, my son likes any cake so I knew whatever cake I ordered he would be happy with. I decided to order the 6-inch mocha cake with Bavarian cream filling, fresh strawberries and whipped cream icing. I was able to customize the cake online by choosing a decoration, color, and wording. Due to COVID times, and not being able to have large gatherings we had a safe celebration at home. Hence the reason for keeping the cake dcor simple.  

The cake was perfect in every way! The whipped cream icing was not too sweet, the mocha cake was moist and flavorful, and the filling was creamy and light. This is the type of cake you could eat without your teeth hurting from the sugary sweetness of a typical store-bought cake. 

I will definitely be ordering from here again, and now that I've written this review I am craving their cupcakes ha ha.

column11:
We had our wedding here in July, and oh my goodness I cannot describe how incredible the staff is. Prior to the wedding, Maria worked day and night to make sure our wedding would go off without a hitch - which she did so gracefully. Not only was she quick and thorough in her responses, she was truly thoughtful in order to make sure that our day was exactly what we would want it to be. 

The day of our wedding, my wedding coordinator (external of the Biltmore), was a disaster and missed much of the detail - the flowers were late, the timeline was off, etc. Maria, Guillermo and Ruben were there to quickly pick up the pieces. 

Beyond the disaster wedding planner, the Four Seasons staff made sure that the bride and groom always had full glasses, and that they saved plates for us so that we always had enough to eat. Everyone always says you'll never eat anything during your wedding.... well this is true unless you get married here! Thanks to the staff for keeping us well fed, because the menu was also nothing short of incredible. 

After they saved our big day, Maria had made custom embroidered robes for my husband and I, and she had also booked spa appointments for us, and she had left late-night wedding treats for us (chocolate covered strawberries and small cakes). I can't thank her enough for this. 

Last but not least, I want to just point out a quick little thing that I think is really special about the Biltmore. On the Sunday before everyone departed, my family hosted a brunch. Ruben was there, again, to make sure we were well fed and our glasses were topped. We asked him how long he had been there, and he said for 33 years.... that's right - since he was 16! 

You see, the Biltmore is an institution, and they keep the quality by keeping the same staff over years. The people who work at the Biltmore love the property and the people who come to visit. 

I know that our wedding would not have been as magical as it was had it not been for the staff, so I cannot thank them enough for everything they did.

We can't wait to celebrate anniversaries with you guys. You do an absolutely incredible job - thank you!
column13: Four Seasons Resort The Biltmore Santa Barbara

column11: The Hungry Cat use to be my favorite Santa Barbara Restaurant.  Now that they take reservations we thought we would be safe and we made our reservation in advance only to be seated by the door.  We asked the host if we could simply slide a table over 2 feet to join to another table and we were told no. I asked who could make that decision and he said his "management" who, of course, was not there at the time.  So, we took the table by the door.  One look around and I thought oh, oh.......  The seafood which is usually stocked with yummy oysters, clams, prawns, etc., was empty except for two lonely lobsters on the bottom shelf.  As we were leaving, three hours later, some crab claws appeared.  Our past visits to the Hungry Cat there I noticed a beautiful iced bowl with wine and champagne and we didn't see it this time, we ordered champagne anyway, but the big iced bowl was always a festive, welcoming sight.  We ordered a big seafood platter, however; there were only two types of oysters offered, Malepeque and Sunset from WA state. There appeared to be only 2 waitstaff and occasionally the host pitched in, and they forgot about us several times and therefore the duration of the meal was about 3 hours. Before we ordered our entre, I ordered our desserts (the famous bread pudding) because last time I ordered it, it was ice cold in the middle.  When we did get out dessert, it was disappointing as it was more pudding than bread.  And, the waitress had "attitude" about the doneness of it.  So, getting back to the entrees, we decided to play it safe and three of us got the Pug Burger which was delicious and my husband ordered the chorizo and clams which we have had many times before and he was not disappointed. In addition to the seafood tower of oysters we ordered the Tandori Artic Char and it was very good, very flavorful and different.  The food was not disappointing, but the staff was.  I think we will give it a break and not hurry back.

column11:
I had really low expectations for this when I bought the Groupon and decided on a whim to go with a couple friends last night. Let me tell you, I have not laughed this hard in a long time!! It was absolutely amazing and my cheeks are still hurting this morning from all the belly laughs! At one point the four of us were crying with laugher as the host just ripped through the crowd bagging on all the guests... it was absolutely hilarious!

We immediately bought another groupon and have encouraged all of our friends to get them as well so we can get a big group together and go again. I would highly recommend this!! The only downside is the food is kind of blah...

column11:
During vacation we drove to Santa Barbara to tour, and we were hungry. Decided to stop here and have lunch. We got seated and got our drinks. Two tables whom were seated after us, were done with their food by the time we got our food.  We ordered our food at 1:20 and our food didn't arrive to 2:05.  I ordered the "fried combo" which consisted of fish, shrimp and calamari, fries and coleslaw.  When it arrived, it was "warm."  Usually when food comes out of the fryer, it should be too hot to start eating immediately.  Very disappointed in this place. It looked very nice, but like they say, "looks can be deceiving."
By the way, we had a party of 9, so an 18% gratuity was automatically added.  If it was up to me, they would have received no gratuity.
Also, when we complained to the manager, she said she was "sorry they're backed up."  From the looks of the restaurant, it didn't look packed.  There were a lot of empty tables and quite a few servers.

column11:
2.5-3 Overall

Price
It's Santa Barbara, so be prepared for it to be as pricey as just about every other restaurant in the city. I would definitely consider it pricey based on the quality of food. But, I will talk more about that.

Food
This along with the price is what dropped the score so significantly. When I go to restaurants I try to try a variety of menu items in order to see the range of the menu and this is quality a few chances. Unfortunately, the quality was not there. I ordered the fried raviolis, a flat bread, and a pasta dish. The fried ravioli was either previously frozen or just have a breading that was too thick and raviolis that were not hand made; which resulted in it being really dense. The flatbread, although assumingly handmade, had a really dense dough as well. Lastly, the pasta dish had overly cooked meat (chicken) with more thick breading and bought in bulk pasta that was, as you can guess dance, and a cream sauce that tasted purely like cream. Water was good (which is important) and just like many other places in Santa Barbara they don't do warm bread.

Location
Great, location on lower State Street. The atmosphere at the restaurant is nice and the music isn't too loud. It would be great for a date night.

Service
Although, they were down a server the people on were super friendly. 

Overall, 2.5-3
the service I received and the location and ambience of the restaurant is what saves this from being a place you should just avoid. With that said the food and price needs significant work. Either the quality of the food needs to go up in order to match the price or the price needs to go down to match the quality of food.

Omg, this place is amazing!!! We came up from LA to visit and saw the rave reviews on yelp. IMO, the hype is worth it.

I ordered the Enchiladas Guadalajara with shredded beef and salsa roja. Some of the best enchiladas I've had, honestly. My boo ordered the shrimp molcajete and he thought it was fantastic. 

I also wanted to highlight their salsa bar - so good!!! All of them, we tried like four and they were all bomb.

The food here is so flavorful. And the price point is so reasonable. Casual vibe too, good for families or a casual date. I highly recommend!

column11: This restaurant has AMAZING food!!  We were riding bikes in SB on a vacation there, when we decided to Yelp a good lunch place. We were blown away by the absolutely delicious vegan food!  We had the BLT flatbread, the pulled smoked mushroom sandwich and the polenta fries. All were FANTASTIC. We loved the food so much that we returned to this place for dinner the same night. All the staff were wonderful as well, and the owner even brought us a complimentary dessert of the best baklava and soy ice cream we'd ever tasted. Only wish we lived closer. Even the dedicated carnivores in our group loved the food. It's THAT GOOD. We will certainly be back the next time we are in Santa Barbara.

column11:
Man, where to start.  Came here because read it was awarded the Michelin plate.  Later read the criteria for Michelin plate and it is based solely on quality of food; no mention of ambience or good service.  Of which Bibi Ji has very little.   We felt like we had been invited to dinner by college guys in their apartment, even down to the water spotted silverware and a can of unopened beer plopped down in front of us.

We opened the door to music blasting so we asked the host if we might sit outdoors.  We were seated out front in an area of metal chairs and tables on concrete enclosed by an iron fence.   The wine list had no by the glass prices listed and the waiter said that if  we wanted it by the glass we would just have to have what was already opened.  We asked for his suggestions for what to order and he said most people just order a variety of things to share so he did not offer any suggestions.  I started wondering if I was in the wrong place so checked out the review that mentioned a verdant patio.  Since I saw no sign of verdant, I asked the waiter about that.  He said "oh, we have a patio in the back" so we asked to be seated back there.  It was a little more pleasant with some flowering vines, but the music was still so loud that we had to yell to hear one another across the table.  Fortunately, the new waiter that came with the new location was much better and gave us some helpful suggestions.  We also asked if they had beer and he said yes, it just wasn't on the menu and rattled off a few.  

As far as the food goes, we thought the butter chicken and the Nan was great, as was the wine we ended up with, so perhaps the Michelin review was right as far as the food. However, I am giving it a 3 because of the lack of ambiance and poor service,

column11:
Let's start with service:
A group of 4 of us arrived at 12:34 on a Thursday afternoon with a lot of empty tables, and left at 1:52 which is way to long.  We had minimal visits from our server, but the first visit told a  lot.  He apologized for the delay, I jokingly said how dare you (he knew I was kidding), and he proceeded to say what a hectic day it's been because the Health Inspector is coming today.  My co-worked asked how it went and he said, we don't know yet, you could be the Health Inspector for all I know.  Not something he should be sharing I'm sure.

Now for the food:

I ordered the Butternut Squash Soup and a side Caesar Salad.

Soup - Eh, I liked it because I really was really looking forward to it but it did not taste like butternut squash at all.  My boyfriend said it tasted one notch down from cream cheese, and actually, he hit the nail on the head.  Definitely pass on this.

Salad - Just your average Caesar, nothing great, nothing bad.

My BF ordered the Smoked Turkey Club with the Caesar on the side.

Sandwich - Very good.  He's had it before and it was just as good as the previous time.  But really, how do you mess up a club?  Actually, he tends to go for the club most places since you really can't mess it up.

One co-worker ordered the Smoked Tri-Tip Sandwich with fries on the side.

Sandwich - So-so.  Tri-tip was sliced extremely thin and didn't resemble tri-tip.  His exact words were "this is not good for $13".  another pass.

Fries - He said they were "really good"

The other co-worker was going to order the Jersey Boy Pizza which was on special but once he heard there was tri-tip on the menu he checked it out and decided on the Smoked Tri-Tip & Bacon Pizza and added Jalapenos. 

Pizza - He said it was "ok".  Again, the looks of the tri-tip failed.  Looked more like strip steak than tri-tip.  They put a few slices of raw jalapenos on the pizza and charged $0.50 which most restaurants will let you know there will be a charge for something, but I have never been to a place that charges for jalapenos.  Again, they were raw, which means they are more spicy, and usually the staff advises on that too...but not at Hollister.

If you go, stick to the basics and you'll probably be ok.

column11:
My girlfriends and I stayed in Funk Town over the weekend, so we scoped out this place on Saturday morning.

It's definitely a fun spot to grab a cup of java with a buddy.  They even have a little coffee bar when you can serve yourself different brews.  I didn't indulge, but my friends and I overheard another customer complain that most of the self-serve coffee was out at the time.

Although the menu online says they have a macchiato, the baristas claimed that they did not make such a beverage.  They suggested if we wanted something similar to a Starbucks caramel macchiato, our best bet was to get a caramel latte.  I didn't bother wasting time arguing with them, but anybody who knows even a little about coffee knows that lattes and macchiatos are completely different in composition.  So, I opted for the non-fat white chocolate latte instead in the hopes that I would receive a similar caffeine and sugar burst.  The latte was alright, but it wasn't anything I would write home about.  It was a little bitter for my taste, but I tolerated it because I really needed the energy jolt to start my day.

I wish I would have gone the same route as my friend who got the chai chiller.  This gem was an ice blended chai tea latte; it was just the right amount of sweet and spicy!

Despite the mildly snarky baristas and mediocre latte, the next time I'm up in SB, I'll revisit this cute, little coffee shop to try out another one of their blended beverages.

column11:
The El Encanto dining room is an spectacular dining setting with enchanting ambiance. 

The views of the Santa Barbara channel islands (on a clear day) only makes the food taste better. Such a dramatic setting, such good service, such good food. 

If you enjoy a velvety, chocolaty indulgence, the chocolate souffle was rich, creamy and decadent; but it is advised to order it with your entree and have the waiter/waitress bring it to you after you have finished your entree. Alternatively, you can order the souffle around 15-20 minutes before you expect to finish your main course.    

After dining, you may stroll through the grounds and make a wish at the wishing well.

column11: Is it a five star restaurant?  Uhhhh no!  Are the tacos excellent?  Not if you are looking for Taco Bell.  If you are looking for authentic Mexican street tacos that are tasty and cheap, then you have found the right spot.  I had the beef, pork and chicken fajita tacos.  The pork tacos were my favorite, and they were tasty.  I'm glad I trusted Yelp and tried this place.  You could easily be forgiven for passing on this restaurant if you did not know any better.  They take credit cards, and the service was friendly and fast.  I would eat there again if I found myself in downtown Santa Barbara craving some street tacos.   As near as I can tell, they only serve tacos, but you can get tacos made from beef lips or eyes or tripe (see the pic).

column11: My favorite food in Santa Barbara. My friend took me here and everything was spot on. The layout is very casual; you go up to the counter and order what you want, pay there, and sit down with a # where they will bring the food directly to your table. In the interim, you will get house-made fresh chips, which you can eat with any of the salsa from their grab-your-own-condiment station. That in and of itself is already where you know you're going to have a good meal. But then the main courses come and you've treated to dishes that hit all the marks; fast, affordable, delicious. We had ceviche which was fresh and came with a very generous portion of seafood; it is enough to be a dinner in and of itself. But then I had mole enchiladas which were deeply savory and sweet. You're likely to have leftovers, which is a double edged sword. Good because it's delicious, bad because it means it'll take you longer before you're hungry enough to come back and try the rest of the items on their menu.

column11:
"Thank you, Yelp app, for helping me find a nice little spot to rest before heading out towards LA." That was my original tip.

While driving back to LA from Paso Robles, I took a detour and stopped by Santa Barbara for a quick pick me up. Drove around downtown but was not in the mood for the fancy shops and chains. I wanted somthing very unique. After all, I don't make it up here as often as I would like to.

My yelp app landed me at Handlebar Coffee Roasters, a small coffee shop located across from one of the missions. After checking out the mission and doing a little sight-seeing, I walked across the street and had a cappucino and a chocolate chip cookie. Very friendly service, answered all my questions and most importantly, their cappucino was delicious. I also bought dark chocolate from a local chocolatier company which they happen to carry.

They seem to have a strong customer base, particularly in the bike community. Love seeing that with independant companies.

column11:
I don't go to chain restaurants Misch, I'll admit that up front. 
When I do go, I enter with a preconceived notion that the offerings have been vetted by the customers and therefore are the best choices available. 
That was my first mistake. 
I looked and my meatless choices for breakfast were limited to oatmeal, one of the salivating-worthy sugar bomb sweet offerings, oatmeal or an egg and cheese panini. 
I chose the latter. 
That was my second mistake. 
After a few minutes I got a flat, sad sandwich on the edge of a long white plate. 
Somehow, there was no flavor whatsoever, no condiments, nothing but bread flattened in a sandwich press, an egg or two and a slice of a white cheese. I couldn't tell what kind of cheese b/c it was devoid of any flavor. 
I got up and asked for salsa and was given the choice of Tabasco or pico de gallo. 
Somehow that was flavorless too. 
Mistake #3?
Ever repeating this 
  Pass.

column11:
The food was perfect but the service was so-so (hence only 4 stars).

We started with the MOZZARELLA E POMODORI which was very good.  The cheese was soft and very fresh!

For the main course, my wife ordered the Risotto with chicken and prosciutto...very creamy and very good.  I had the TAGLIATELLE VERDI ALLA BOLOGNESE...again, very good.  The meat sauce was rich yet did not overpower the Spinach tagliatelle.

As far as the service goes, I like a place they think ahead...your glass is near empty, fill it up, ask if you would like more bread...maybe I am being too picky but so be it!

All in all a very good dining experience.

column11:
Let me first say that this place is awesome! I was having an adventure with Chef and we decided to head to Santa Barbara because he had never been. I was told that SB is the place for fresh seafood. We didn't have a destination in mind so we yelped it. (har har) This place came up so and we saw there was fresh uni and oysters! It's not a big market but what was there was of high quality! 

We got two sea urchins and half a dozen of oysters. For all of that, it was under $20 bucks!!!! Of course it wasn't a meal but it was a very nice afternoon snack! This isn't a restaurant so don't expect to sit inside, however there are a few benches located outside. After our snack, we walked to the beach and enjoyed the rest of our day in SB!

column11:
Super disappointed in this place! Their service was nice but their breakfast burrito is almost $9 even though its advertised as $6.99 (i didnt get any additions). 
I would have been ok with it except the burrito was so puny when it arrived! Almost the same size as the little burritos youd get at a cafeteria on a school campus. 
By comparison, super cucas and daily grind are both substantialy larger burritos with better flavor. 

From a flavor standpoint it was also subpar, and i ordered a chorizo burrito and they put in some other kind of random pork cut. 

Get it together el sitio. Mexican food isn't difficult  and it shouldn't be expensive.

column11:
Was taking a day trip to Santa Barbara and saw this cute little seafood shack on the wharf. There was a decent amount of people waiting outside and a clipboard to add your name in the front. Once we got seated service and food was friendly and fast. I got the steamed clams in white wine sauce which were super fresh and delicious. Served with warm and a little charred bread. The broth is light but also a little creamy, loved it. The clams themselves were super pretty too. My boyfriend got the steamed crab with slaw and onion rings, the meat was insanely fluffy and just fell apart once you got it out of the shell. 

We happened to be there while Man vs. Food was filming and got invited to join the show! They brought out the uni on scallop and lime and chapino for us to try on camera. While being on the show was super cool, the food was unfortunately left out for a while waiting for the shoot and got a little cold. I love uni and the uni was sooo fresh, super rich and creamy. Unfortunately not a huge scallop fan so wasn't sure how I felt about the pairing. The chapino is essentially this seafood stew served in a bread bowl. While it looked awesome, I felt the sauce was too heavy for the delicate seafood, almost like a pasta sauce. However, my boyfriends mom had ordered it for lunch and seemed to really enjoy it so perhaps it would have been a lot better if it hadn't been cold. 

Prices are affordable, especially for such a great location. Put your name down, wander the wharf a little, and maybe you'll get to see some seals like we did!

column11: The people at Trader Joe's are rockstars. Two weekends ago shopping was crowded, chaotic and stressful with the start of the Shelter at Home order. This past Sunday was absolutely civilized and relaxed by comparison. I waited in an orderly line with everyone separated by 6 feet. They let in only a certain number of people at a time. The shelves were fully stocked. I found everything on my grocery list except canned corn, and I'm sure they'll have some next week. The Trader Joe's employees were cheerful and chatted with me like usual. I know they have to be exhausted and stressed and worried about their own health, but they didn't show it. I just want to thank them for risking their own health and lives so that I can go home and cook healthy, delicious meals for my husband and me while we wait out the pandemic. Thanks!

column11:
Great place to eat! My wife had the cioppino with pasta and I had the lobster roll with onion rings.

The cioppino comes in a bread bowl but they substituted the bread with pasta. It was served hot and was delicious! The bowl was crammed with mussels, shrimp, sea scallops and a king crab leg. Loved it!

My lobster roll was nothing to write home about. Bland on flavor and very salty. The meat was minced and unrecognizable as lobster. However, the onion rings were crazy good! Fresh onion wrapped in a light and flakey batter. 

The service was great and our server, Sam, was very nice. We'll be back!

column11: I am so disappointed with this place.  I walked up and there was no host.  After a wait, a server told us to seat ourselves.  After a sitting and asking for a high chair, we eventually had to get one for ourselves.  Then we waited, and waited with no menus.  After getting up and asking for service we finally ordered.  While waiting for our food we watched as three servers rushed around to handle the whole restaurant with no sections or semblance of order.  A line formed at the entrance constantly.   The servers openly argued about who was doing more and moving faster.  I watched as one server spilled water at a table and came back with a towel only to wipe the floor first then after the table with the same towel.  Ewwww.   Once we were finally served, my veggie ramen was so thick and creamy there was no liquid or broth at all.  My husband did enjoy his Spicy chicken ramen.  I ended up ordering take out at Sachi Ramen and picked it up to eat at home.

Highly recommend this spot for breakfast!

column11:
I imagined this restaurant had to be up to par considering the yelp reviews, however, it sadly falls into the category of overpriced for the quality, quantity, and service.

My family ordered several items to-go. This was a mistake because it took so long we might as well have waited for service at a fantastic restaurant. I asked for utensils and they were out of plastic knives- the girl said their shipment would be in that week.  What good does that do me? They also had no salt and pepper packets which was a shame because my omelette was so bland! It was also swimming in water when I opened the container. My family was not impressed with their sandwiches to say the least. 

If you're taste buds are shot perhaps you may like it here.

column11:
Came into the Nook wednesday night with my boyfriend and our dog! The patio is dog friendly so that's awesome! 
We ordered the Rockfish tacos, Topa Topa burger with truffle fries and the german pretzel!
The girl at the counter was super friendly and recommended gluten free options for me! the fish tacos come on corn tortillas and are super flavorful and tasty! My boyfriends Topa Topa burger was cooked a perfect medium rare, the bacon jam is amazing!! The burger "house sauce" is so good, like thousand islands on crack :) truffle fries were cheesy and they also had pesto on them with the perfect amount of truffle!
the pretzel is served warm with cheese and mustard and it was so soft! 
we are so happy that SB has such a unique place, that's dog friendly with amazing food!! we can't wait to come back!

column11:
So I spent the summers of my youth on a boat in the harbor.  I used to take our Dingy, at like..age 8, and scooter it over to the dock by here.  I used to always get a quesadilla with a salsparilla (I was OBSESSED with cheese) and fish tacos for my parents.  Then I would dingy back to the boat and enjoy it.  I went back abut 18 months ago and it is EXACTLY the same.  Got the reg, add some chicken, and sat at a random table down the way.  

Even after these years, it still put a smile on my face.  You gotta remember this is supposed to be a hole in the wall, quick bite while you enjoy the ocean kind of place.  For what it is, it is awesome.  I hope it never closes.

column11:
I am so happy to have found this place! The happy hour cannot be beat and it's right by my office. The food is modestly priced and the service was very attentive when we went for lunch on a Friday around noon. This place is huge and I can definitely see returning here with a big group. My favorite part is how dog friendly they are. We sat inside and they brought my pup his own little doggie menu. 
All around great experience and I look forward to trying more things on the menu. The burger was so good though, I might order it again. I asked for my burger rare and it came out perfect :)

column11: Cute little cafe off the 101 on the way to Santa Barbara. Good selection of sandwiches and a decent kids menu. The Indian Summerland chicken sandwich was decent. column11:
Between Yelp and Open Table, we stumbled upon this amazing place on our last visit to Santa Barbara and lucky to find last minute reservation.  
I have done my fair share of fine dining and WOW, this place ambience had just top it all, I was very impressed.  
Arrived at the gate with a guard and drove up a dark road, didn't know what to expect but it reminded us of the arrival of the Meadowood Restaurant in Napa.
The pathway was dark and lit up by night light, beautiful twinkling lights adorned the oaktrees around the property.
There are two restaurants on the property, Stonehouse is upstairs.  We got seated promptly out on the patio walked through a very quaint dinning with a fire place.  There is large giant fireplace in the center of the patio and dimlite oil lamp is the only light source at each table.  How romantic, we were given a little flashlight to read our menu, and was surrounded by twinkling light like sitting under a blanket of stars.
Service was prompt and friendly.  The variety off breads was so good.
Food was good, but the steak especially amazing, table service for the sauces added a nice touch to the amazing experience.
Whatever you do, you got to order the chocolate cake dessert with the strawberry icecream, we almost lick the plate...lol
Too bad, our romantic experience was disrupted by a very loud and obnoxious group of peoples a few tables  away, it took management a good hour plus to tell them to quiet down, most of our neighbors were quite bother by it, I think they actually complaint.
Other than that, we enjoyed everything the restaurant have to offer.  
I can't wait to come back on our next visit, perhaps make a point to stay on the property.
Surely a night to remember!

column11:
We'd stopped by Oreana for a tasting but the place was loud and crowded and didn't seem like our scene so we drove down the road, parked the car and yelped "wineries nearby".  One seemed really good and nearby so I looked around to get my bearings.  Looked to my right and saw I'd parked right in front of La Tour...

So, first things first.  If you are remotely homophobic there are plenty of other places in Santa Barbara that may be more to your liking - I understand the Reagan Ranch serves a lovely merlot - otherwise, if you've evolved ever-so-slightly and are okay with people being people  you'll find very funny and knowledgeable wine stewards, a great looking space, fun clientele, great tunes, and very interesting and very reasonably priced wines.  

While it does seem a bit sacrilegious to be drinking Euro wines right next to Santa Ynez and the Santa Rita Hills the Old World seems to have learned a bit since Bottle Shock was released.  Had a flight of whites and one of reds and there wasn't a bad wine in the bunch and there were more than a few "oh-my-god-that's-good" sips.

Food-wise, I'm sure it's great but the menu is a bit sparse and veg-wise it's definitely underwhelming, so you'll have to read the other reviews to learn more.

If you want a fun, offbeat time you've come to the right place.

column11:
This place was pretty disappointing even though it had great service. I wanted to give it one star but because the service was pretty good, I'm giving it two stars. 

I came here with a friend for lunch because my future sister-in-law recommended this place. I ordered the salmon salad and my friend ordered the beet salad. 

I applause the chef for creativity and presentation, but the salmon salad was sooooooo bad. The salmon tasted too fishy and it was a little tough. The chef had also included potatoes and egg crumbles, and with the salmon, just was not a good combination. I also noticed that there was some sort of salad dressing, but it did not go well at all with any of the food. 

I don't know what the chef was thinking when he was preparing my food, but I've never tasted a salad so terrible in my life- and it's pretty hard to mess up salad! Suffice to say, I only picked at my food and didn't even bother to box up the leftovers because I don't think anyone deserves to eat this stuff. I definitely will NOT be coming back here again!

column11:
I love this place! Just knowing I'm on my way there makes me happy; once I get there I'm all smiles! The outdoor eating area is THE BEST! Even on a day when the weather isn't awesome this place is!  If you hit it on a sunny California day, you get a pitter-patter in your heart and your insides sing!

So that's just the environment alone, then you add the delicious food and you become completely giddy.  The prices are reasonable, I don't think other reviewers are taking the literal beach front location into consideration. 

When I'm here I smile from ear to ear and I leave this place blissfully stuffed- you will too!

column11:
The pulled pork was good but service wasn't. After standing at the counter in a nearly empty restaurant,  someone clearly with a cold finally waited on us. And it seemed more like we were an inconvenience rather than customers. If a food server is sick, I don't think they should be waiting on customers or handling food. 

Then there's the proselytizing. I don't care what religion people are but I don't want religious messages hanging on the wall staring me in the face while I eat.

column11:
Oh gawd, this place was good. So glad the bf saw the long line and made a stop here, because if there's a long line, that's always a good sign. :) 
Ordered three flavors and all were great! 
Strawberry - this was delish! Soft with fresh strawberries in it, it was fantastic. 
Cookies n' Cream - Can't go wrong with this flavor
Turkish Coffee - My favorite! This woke me up in a good way. The flavor of the coffee was great. 

Friendly service with great ice cream on a hot Saturday afternoon in SB, can't beat that.

column11:
My first time in Santa Barbara was last week due to bringing a convertible 3-series back to its rightful owner (it was consensual, settle down!).

A treat on the trip was the chance to walk through Santa Barbara with a friend of mine who use to live there for a few years and gave me a sense of the place and the current nightlife.

Though it was Thursday night in August Backstage was open, with duelling pianos, and a lovely atmosphere.  I wish I had more time to have soaked up the young and fresh atmosphere.  Next time through, I figure.

If you are looking to kick up  your heels or to throw back a few, Backstage is definitely the top choice in Santa Barbara.

column11:
To those looking for great food around SB,
The service I received tonight was absolutely terrible. The food.. I could have microwaved better. I have been in the industry for about 3 years and am horrified at the service. Our server said maybe 3 words to our table before being informed that my friend didn't like the way her noodles were cooked. He said they precook their pasta so there's nothing he could do, other than get her another dish. No apology, no explanation, no nothing. 

Following the meal, we then asked him to split our check. He told us he was not capable. Unless your computer system is years old and without an update, it is possible. He told us to just write out what we wanted for cash and for the cards from each of us. He put all of the tax on one bill making hers much more than her meal. He told us not to worry because it was just a few dollars... WHAT? Through her not liking her pasta, or being worried about paying for more than she should have, he NEVER apologized. Or said anything for that matter. As our beloved Jeremy walked inside, he openly mocked us. After telling us "So, the manager can't figure it out either, so you guys can wait or..." we waited at least 30 minutes for our bill receiving NO apology. Jeremy argued with one of us, and rolled his eyes at our other friend. Please inform me what kind of customer service that is. We informed the manager of our issue, and assuming we wanted something for free, proceeded to tell us Jeremy is the lead server and he couldn't do anything about it. He told us we could talk with the owner if we wanted, giving us a business card. 

The manager on duty did nothing for us, and not once did we hear an apology from him or Jeremy. With noodles cooked to order, and some server training, Pascucci's could have a shot. But for my friends and I who do live minutes from downtown, we will never be back.

column11:
Came here last night with a group after quickly vacating Sandbar across the street. The moment I walked into this bar my frown turned into a smile and the night was on. 

There was a live band upfront playing some Irish tunes. People were dancing all around me whilst slipping and sliding on the wet peanut shell covered floor. I quickly ordered a Guinness and watched the bartender do a great pour on it. About fifteen minutes later I was two Guinness' down and it was time for Irish car bombs. $7.50 is definitely not a bad price for this tasty concoction. I threw it down the hatch and proceeded to shoot darts for about half an hour, the whole time trying to maintain a fairly full Guinness in my hand almost the whole time. I'm guessing an hour and a half or so later and it was time to go. Out the door we went, wallets not that much lighter and a great buzz on. 

Make sure and come here if you enjoy a nicely poured Guinness.

column11:
Can you give zero stars?

I don't know how this place got rated so highly. The service was decent, but the food was horrible. The pancakes were tasteless, none of us took more than two bites of the food. Just writing this as a warning to those who want a good breakfast in Goleta because we only came here because of the high yelp rating. Sauce ordered the Moby Dick in my Ass, which didn't live up to its title. False advertising is already a huge problem in Goleta, and this is only adding to it. The place did provide decent entertainment though. I think the whole place enjoyed watching the 50 year old couple in the booth next to us rocking some otphj action. Not sure if I can credit this to the restaurant, but it's glad to see the type of crowd Alphies brings in. Great night for the boys last night, actually a great week for the boys. Very few things could ruin a perfect week, but Alphies, apparently is one of them. On a list of the top 5 things that could ruin this perfect week, Alphies sits at number 3, just behind getting raped in Mexico.
