column11: Came here recently with Trevor for my birthday and wow was i impressed. We had a long wait (it was Saturday night at 8pm go figure) but i didn't mind since we had spent the day wine tasting and i had a good buzz going. This restaurant is located right on State street so there is lots of good window shopping and people watching to do while you wait. We were seated at one of the two tops that has one side booth seating and the other chair seating. Our table was a bit wide and i felt far from my man but it made for lots of room when our food came. We started with the oysters which came with chives and a delish light brothy lemony sauce. We both thought the oysters were super fresh and very tasty but small ( it's the kind of oyster not the restaurants fault). Then we got the Yellow Submarine roll ( yellow tail, Asparagus, Miso sauce and soy paper wrap) which was good but the flavor combo was just a bit different not my fave. We also had the zippy roll which is a spicy tuna roll and damn it was good. Unlike many other spicy tuna rolls this one featured the tuna and it's fresh flavor rather then the spicy mayo most sushi joints use. lastly we ordered a California roll with eel on top ( the name escapes me) it was good it had real crab which i love and the eel was not fishy. The ambiance here is not so romantic as it can get pretty loud but that didn't bother us too much. If you appreciate good sushi this is a great place to come the specialty rolls range from $8- $22 ( they have one that is $22 but most are right around $9).

column11: I avoid this place at all costs possible, and I live one minute down the street. The produce selection is pitiful in terms of freshness and quality. The lines are usually ridiculously long to the point I walk in and just walk right out because driving all the way to Ralph's would end up being quicker. Normally, I love Vons. column11:
Made an overnight trip to Santa Barbara during my west coast visit back in April, located this place based on the good reviews & the fact that it was about a 10 minute walk from our hotel. There was about a 20-30 minutes wait. We got a round of drinks at the bar upstairs & ordered and appetizer but ended up getting a table sooner than estimated, which was fine as we were hungry. The place was packed so we were generally happy with the decision to eat here. The staff was very friendly & the service was efficient. 

We tried the beer boiled shrimp for appetizer, had a good flavor to it, shrimp  have the shell/skin on. We got their house cesar salads which were really fresh & the dressing had a bit of a kick to it. Two of us decide to go with their Seabass dusted with Cajun spices- served with a rice pilaf & coleslaw. I have to say it was one of THE BEST Seabass I've had. The Cajun seasoning added so much flavor. One of my friends ordered the crab cakes (served with fries & coleslaw) and those were really yummy too. 

We thoroughly enjoyed our meal, everything was really fresh & it was very reasonably priced as well.

column11:
Came here on a Saturday afternoon. Not too busy, but definitely the shop can be easy to accidentally drive by and miss.

The store is tiny -- almost seems like one of those places where you order out of a window. Seating is all outside on their covered patio area (with the most AWESOME, comfiest patio chairs I've ever laid my ass on). The staff was super friendly and eager to let you sample all their unique and delicious flavors (i.e. root beer)! I think we tried at least 5 flavors before deciding on a 2-scoop cup, which was quite generous in portion I would have to add!

More creative and unique flavors than the typical/traditional ice cream shop. Their ice cream is more bursting with flavor instead of being overloaded with sugar, which is how things should be!

Their mint flavor in their mint chip is quite strong, and thus, a bit too "herby" and "real mint" for me (I prefer McConnell's version). But their salted caramel is VERY good and blows McConnell's (way too sweet) out of the water. Root beer tastes just like the real stuff! Their ice cream is a bit icier than I would like though...

column11: For what we came to get, and considering the pricing of other things in the area, this place was great.  Specifically, we rolled in at 4, right at the start of happy hour.  We ordered two house margaritas (one negative note was that while the sign at the bar seemed to indicate 3 dollars each, we were charged 4) which were pretty strong.  Then we got a plate of $3 mini nachos and a $3 mini quesadilla.  They were pretty good, especially  with all of the fixings that came with the nachos.  Finally, my partner ordered a tequilla sunrise, which, at least in my recollection is made with tequilla and orange juice.  Hers was made with tropicana fruit punch and a lot of tequilla.  But that was what we were looking for, and for 3 bucks that justifies the 5 stars in my book.

column11:
The Shop Kitchen is a casual eatery near Santa Barbara High, where my husband Matt B. went to school. It's on the same street as La Super-Rica, and appears to be one of the newer, trendier places in the area, open since late 2012. We went for brunch on Easter Sunday, during an overnight visit to town.

It's essentially a fast food restaurant with fancier food and a beer and wine license. You order and pay at a window, then find your seat on either the patio or the somewhat gloomy indoor dining area. There was a line when we walked up around noon, but it moved pretty briskly. Service was quick and perfunctory. I ordered a drink and only asked after it when it didn't come with our food. It turned out it had been sitting out at a different window, where I was supposed to pick it up. If I was given that instruction at any point, I missed it entirely.

The Sriracha Bloody was okay, a little bit spicy and not very strong, as it must've been made with soju or some other 14% liquor. $7 was a fine price for it, though, and it came with some tasty pickled green beans.

My food was also okay. I got the General Sanders, a buttermilk fried chicken sandwich with apple slaw, sweet and sour carrots, and spicy mayo on a soft bun. The chicken was good, but there wasn't much to the other ingredients. More slaw, more carrots, more spice would've been great. I tasted a tiny bit of apple in like one bite, and the sandwich needed more texture and flavor overall. I did like the housemade potato chips, though not all of them were crispy. Matt's food was better. He got the Frenchie, a grilled french toast with real maple syrup, and it was solid.

This was a totally serviceable meal, and if we lived nearby, we might visit again. The Shop Kitchen strikes me as a useful neighborhood restaurant, an unfussy brunch stop where you can get in and out in well under an hour. There just wasn't so much to it that I'd go back again during a short getaway to Santa Barbara.

column11:
This afternoon my new fire pit was delivered, but I needed a propane tank and finding a place that sold them was becoming a big task.  When I found SB Ice & Propane on Yelp it wasn't clear if they just filled the tanks or if they also sold them and so I called.  The person on the phone was very helpful and even held on while I tried to see if my bbq tank could fit in the fire pit so we could determine the tank size I needed. 
Because of the low ratings, I was expecting him to be impatient and gruff and I was relieved he was quite the opposite.  
They had the tank I needed so off I drove to pick it up and pay the $45 to have it come filled.  A couple of tips:  #1Call first, it's a small business and you want to make sure someone is there (I assume they usually are) and too that they have what you need.  #2 Propane and office are in the back of the lot so when you arrive go straight back...until you see the tank.  The office is up the ramp.  

This note is for the owner:  Web site Yelp link is not working, people may wonder if business is still open.

The view is the best in Santa Barbara. The food... BE SELECTIVE and you'll be fine. 

Can't go wrong with their charbroiled burger and fries for $11 all the time. Calimari during happy hour for $8. I'm not a drinker, but the bar is hopping, so they're properly doing it right.

Other places may have better seafood - a LOT better, but that's not what I come here for. Better quality seafood, and it's 5 stars EASY! I guess because this is a touristy area they do better financially like this, in their opinion. This place could be so much more... 

Happy hour specials EVERY DAY, 4-6 PM.

The only star off is for the super long wait for the waiter service seating area as it is quite small. There is a self service window to order from but we opted not to do that due to the live musician. He was great, it's just a personal choice for me. column11:
Came here for brunch with some friends during an SB weekend and wow... the views are BEAUTIFUL.  The resort is absolutely stunning with gorgeous Spanish architecture - it really feels like you've traveled far away to some relaxing vacation hotspot like Hawaii or Cabo.  

We weren't that hungry so we opted for the menu brunch instead of the champagne buffet.  The buffet offerings did look quite comprehensive and delicious though.  

I ordered a mimosa and my friends all had bloody marys.  I'm not a fan of bloody marys but they were all declared to be excellent.  I very much enjoyed my mimosa as well.  

For our entrees, we had the mediterranean omelette, french toast, seasonal fruit plate, and bacara breakfast.  Everything was pretty good but I felt like my omelette was a little dry and boring (hence the minus one star).  

Overall, however, it was really quite delicious, the ambiance is AMAZING, and the service is excellent.  Next time I'll come later in the day so that I am hungrier and can fully indulge in the buffet breakfast!

column11:
Stayed at the hotel and had most of our meals there. First I have to say that the service is FANTASTIC! From the moment you walk in until your seated the servers are extremely attentive and friendly. We were there with our 2 year old and she was acknowledged and was made to feel very comfortable. That's extremely important to us that she's made to feel welcomed just as the adults are which was very apparent here. The waiter also suggested plates that were spot on and delicious!
I know other reviewers already mentioned it, but I have to mention it again since the scallops are amazing! They need to have there own review! They were cooked perfectly and were paired with a horseradish vinaigrette. They only thing I wish was that there were more of these yummy little guys! 4 is great but 5 would be better. 
Pork chop was equally as delicious and were paired with a very delicious compote and a butternut squash mash.
Kids menu looked good but your better off ordering the appetizer portions instead of the kids menu. I asked the waiter if the Mac and Cheese was "real cheese" and he said it was velveta type cheese. For my foodie 2 year old that would not cut it. He did mention that if I ordered the appetizer Mac and Cheese it would be actual aged cheese. This to us sounds like the better choice and our little one agreed. 
We did also try the deviled eggs as a starter but personally for us they didn't work. This is something we wanted to try but unless you Love eggs I'm sure there is something else you can try.

Of course since they have impeccable service we were offered desert on the house since they knew we were celebrating! We chose the lavender honey Crme brle and it did not disappoint. 
Overall the service, food, and drinks are impeccable. If your visiting Santa Barbara I suggest you eat there for at least one meal.

column11:
My husband and I came to this cute Bed & Breakfast, to celebrate our 4 year wedding anniversary. He told me I get to pick the city to go away for a weekend, so I chose Santa Barbara. He found Secret Garden Inn, showed me their pics and I immediately fell in love and said ok let's go there. The room I wanted, called Thrush had a private jacuzzi..but was already taken.  So we took the Whipperwill (forget the spelling), and it was a cute little room. We got in Saturday night, and we had missed the wine&cheese happy hour the innkeeper, Dominque offers. 

But we got side tracked at the wonderful Outlet stores, on the way in to the B&BWe got to meet Dominque before she left, as she doesn't live on the grounds. She told us she usually leaves at like 7pm. She was super sweet and friendly to us. Very welcoming. I liked her right away. She is orig from Paris, so you can hear her lovely French accent. The main house decor was very nice and well kept. 

The cottage we stayed in was cute and small, with the bedding and couch having a floral theme...which I love since I love florals!  In the bathroom, she provides you with towels, a bar of hand soap, and liquid pump soap (both can be found in her gift shop btw in the main house in the dining room area)..she has lotion and hair products for you as well. She left out brownies, tea, and cider at night in the kitchen. 

She serves breakfast from 830am to 1030am I believe. She made us cheese broccoli quiche, bread, jams, scones, and fruit bowl..she had OJ, hot tea and coffee as well. We met another nice couple @ breakfast on Sunday who were staying there too, super friendly couple! Nice Meeting you Lulu and Anthony! 

We'd def recommend this place, it's nice and reasonable priced. It's very homey feeling and pretty cute, we enjoyed our stay. We will come back again. Thank you so much Dominique!!

column11:
Julienne offers very good and very fresh food, sourced as locally as possible. That's a given.
But some days they get an item in that's so special, they create a one-off menu just for it, and that menu lasts 1, perhaps 2 days.

So if you want the skinny on the super special stuff, you must be on their mailing list. And even then, be prepared to call in your reservation immediately! You can join the mailing list in the restaurant, or sign up via their website.

This weekend I got the news that they came into a supply of live Dungeness crab, and were making a five course meal of it, with only 12 servings available. It sold out in 30 minutes, perhaps less.

There were two of us, but only one special menu to spare, so we took it, and ordered a couple items off the standard menu to supplement.

This included a warm potato salad with soft-poached egg. And grilled flatbread with radicchio and prosciutto. I am not a fan of raw radicchio, but grilled is mmm mmm, gorgeous.

And here's the crab dinner, which they called a Study in Crab.

The Legs: Crab cocktail, spicy mango sabayon, butter lettuce.

The Claws: Avocado flan, mandarin, red onion, mandarin vinaigrette.

The Shells: Crab bisque, smoked paprika crouton.

The Body: Crab noodle, green garlic, crab veloute.

The End: Crab cake, asparagus tips, hollandaise sauce.

Before the last course was a scoop of mango sorbet, to cleanse the palate.

The price for the crab dinner...are you ready for it? $50.

No fancy foams or molecular deconstructions, it was simple, really really fresh, and with just the right subtle twist on spices to balance the traditional with something new. 

Recently, they installed a mini-bar, which now benefits the diner with a view of the gang working in the kitchen and sometimes some chatting.  One fellow, Stephane, talked us through some of the dishes he was working on. And everyone working there is super knowledgeable, friendly and seriously into food. 

A picture's worth a thousand words? I've just uploaded 10 new photos, including all the courses of the crab dinner. This is good, otherwise I'd have to type out another 9500 words or something.

column11: I love the PALMS! Four of us drove up from Camarillo yesterday for my birthday. Overall our experience was similar to previous visits. We are familiar with the menu and the how the do-it-yourself idea works. The food was great. Almost everything went well. So why not 5 stars? THE SERVER WAS A BIG PROBLEM. We sat in a practically empty room staring at our water glasses for about five minutes before another staffer noticed us and reminded our server we were waiting. She did the bare minimum to keep from ignoring us during our entire meal. When two different groups of people she knew arrived it was like old home week - kiss, kiss, hug, hug. Meanwhile I was sitting with an empty glass and she never even asked if I would like another drink. Silly move, since tips are usually calculated on service, and the amount of the bill. I wasn't impressed when she handwrote suggested tip amounts for 15% and 20% on the bill.The "service" was barely worth 10%. If we have the same server the next time we go to The Palms I won't hesitate to ask to be seated in someone else's section.

column11:
This review is just for the Japanese menu as I haven't tried the Chinese menu.  A friend told me that a Japanese chef opened a sushi bar within Empress Palace and that the sushi there was phenomenal.  I came here after work with my family tonight and we were all really impressed with the freshness and quality of the fish in the rolls we had.  One would never have guessed to find AMAZING Japanese food in a Chinese restaurant.  It was a very unexpected nice surprise.  

Our favorite dishes were:

Sushi Nachos - tortilla chips with guacamole, spicy tuna and cherry tomato salsa.

Salmon Special Roll - it had a really nice sweet and thinly sliced battera kombu that was layered on top of the salmon that really wrapped the flavors together really well.  It was the perfect balance between sweet, tangy and savory.

Sushi Nuggets - crispy sushi rice topped with spicy tuna and avocado.

Jalapeo Yellowtail - super thick slices of fresh yellowtail on top of sushi rice and more yellowtail.  MEATY AND DELICIOUS!

Omakase (chef's choice roll).  It'll be different every time but order THIS.  The chef is very passionate about his work and this was I what really enjoyed about his food.  Trust the chef and he'll make you something tasty and really fresh.  Tonight we received a roll filled with salmon, yellowtail and tuna wrapped in thinly sliced cucumber and topped with salmon roe.  The salmon roe was a nice touch to the roll; they were like flavor bombs exploding in my mouth. 

Overall, we all really enjoyed the Japanese food here.  The staff are genuinely nice and attentive.  They just started serving Japanese food here about a month ago and I hope they do really well.  The sushi is very fresh and presented beautifully.  I'm very excited to have more Japanese options in Santa Barbara.  We will be back again definitely!  

Check this place out, ESPECIALLY THE JAPANESE MENU!

column11: Let's talk sushi! I personally love the Mexican Roll. 1/2 price sushi is ALL DAY Sun-Thurs and "All-you-can-eat" sushi @ the bar ONLY is ALL day Friday & Saturday. If you want Hibachi (the tables where they cook for you)  I would HIGHLY recommend calling in and making reservations ahead of time to ensure your seats; it gets pretty busy. And unfortunately they don't take Sushi bar reservations because there's only what? 26 seats? I mean if your dumb ass reserves 8 seats and you don't come in on time the restaurant looses money by holding your seats for someone who isn't there when there's people that could be sat =( So it makes sense that it's a "first come- first serve" policy. Anyways, the filet mignon is to die for @ the Hibachi grill and if you're looking for more bang for the buck try the Dinner Box or the Lunch Box at the sushi bar. It's orgasmic. OH, and don't forget dessert. If you've never had a tempura ice cream you need to try it! DEEP FRIED YUMMINESS. By the way, if you're 21 and up, don't forget to Sake-Bomb it. :) And if you're not into beer like me, try the plum wine. Absolutely love it.

column11:
I LOVE MCCONNELL'S! And I've never met anyone who doesn't! I probably shouldn't post this review because I don't want it getting any more popular, haha--the line is already always out the door--but I have to give credit where it's due. 

The hot, made-to-order waffle cones are superb. Add two flavors of ice cream (which you get in just the "single" scoop) and you've got yourself a bit of heaven. My favorites are the double peanut butter chip and any of the sea salt/caramel flavors, but you really, REALLY can't go wrong. It's simply the creamiest ice cream I've ever had. Oh, and it's all natural ingredients that you won't feel bad about eating. You've got to get McConnell's when you visit downtown SB.

column11:
First visit was about a month after High Sierra opened. Chalked up the paltry food and bad service to opening jitters. Second visit months later and not much better. Recommended this morning to order the brunch by waitress because, "it's better than anything we have on our regular menu." Asked at the omelette station where I could order a couple of simple eggs. Guy at the omelette station couldn't even speak English. Asked another staff member and was told omelettes were included but two simple eggs would cost me extra. ???? Tried instead to order eggs Benedict which is on the menu and was told that they stopped serving those and that I could get chicken sliders instead. Why have a menu listing all the items served from 9:00 to 2:30 and then not serve them. Total bait and switch. This third time was the worst and I've learned my lesson.

Gave it one star 'cause zero stars wasn't an option.

column11:
Stopped by for a late dinner and loved it. The staff are friendly, food came out quickly and it was filling and delicious. 

I got the Sal De Mar, cauliflower taco and the hibiscus lemongrass drink. My favorite was probably the Sal De Mar. I got the small and loved the combination of the fish and watermelon. The ceviche also had a nice kick to it--I love spicy food so this was satisfying. The cauliflower taco was also tasty but not as spicy. I had bites of the pineapple habanero in between and that added a good amount of spice. The pineapple was labelled XX Spicy, but was on the lighter end of the spicyness scale for me, though I do have a high tolerance for spicy food.

It's a bit pricey, but comparable to everything else in SB Public Market.

column11: Mattias catered a dinner for 13 people for my 50th Birthday. He was very communicative in the preparation. Provided great detailed information about his pricing and estimates. He arrived at the house on time, made dinner for the kids first so they could play while we had a leisurely dinner. He prepared a 4 course meal. It was beautiful and delicious. He decorated the table and cleaned up like nothing had happened! It was awesome. He was calm and chatted with all of us in the open kitchen. The whole experience start to finish was great. I couldn't recommend him more.

column11:
This place is amazing! You want a great way to start your day off, this place it it! I'm a fan of the Juicing that seems to be a popular trend these days, and yes I have done that as well, but this place leaves you full. If your on a diet or in the process of juicing, you can definitely fit this in your day. 

They start you off every time with a shot of mango flavored aloe Vera juice and an ice tea (you can choose btw peach, rasp & lemon) to get you going, then you choose your shake. I have been here 6 times so far and every shake is a winner. From Pumpkin Marshmallow Cookie to Pineapple Upside Down Cake, and everything in between! 

Definitely stop by here sometime if you have a chance..... and if it's too healthy for you, Little Caesars is right next door!

column11:
I searched Yelp for a place in Santa Barbara that had latte art, and the French Press was the first place to appear.  While in Santa Barbara, before coming for a coffee, we heard so many good things about it from locals, they even have an award winning barista that works there.  It was warm out so we ordered an vanilla ice latte, which they do make their own syrups in house.  I wish i would have gotten a hot latte, that way i could have really seen the skills of their talented staff.  The service wasn't happy, there was no hi, that was a let down, otherwise i would have given them four stars.

Overall, i enjoyed my drink, it wasn't much different from what i make at home, i would go here because of the great vibe of the place, i just wish the service were better.

column11:
This place is cheap, fresh and delicious.  I am a native of Los Angeles and have still never been to Enterprise fish in Santa Monica, maybe because their are so many other places to eat, but this is no disrespect to Enterprise Fish, I have been to the Santa Barbara location 4 times, each time being better than the next.

The most recent trip, the only one of the four I can still remember any details of, I had a very pleasant experience as usual. 

For starters- A lobster bisque, which if you enjoy lobster, give this lobster bisque a try.  If you don't appreciate this soup, you will never like any other lobster bisque anywhere, this is the lobster bisque to compare other lobster bisques to, LOL.  It comes creamy and rich, with pieces of lobster and a puff pastry baked on top of the cup, so every time you break into the pastry, it flakes into the bowl....outstanding, round of applause is an order!!!

Next, we ordered two fish lunch sandwiches, rare ahi tuna, and swordfish.  Both were perfect, with my swordfish being sooo fresh, soo flavorful and soo flaky and the ahi tuna sandwich was very clean, cold and red in the center, and the spread on top of both sandwiches couldn't have been better.  A round of Chardonnay and pinot grigio to wash the seafood down splendidly and you have yourself a satisfying meal.

column11: I will start by saying the pizza itself was very good, but the extended wait time to receive part of my order that was "forgotten" by the delivery guy was another story. I know everyone makes mistakes from time to time, but their nonchalent attitude toward me when I called back an hour later to find out where the rest of my order was, put me off a bit. The other half of my order finally arrived but by that time we were done with dinner and frustrated from the whole ordeal of having to call back to find out when they were going to bother to send the rest of our meal. It was like, we will get you the rest of your paid order "when we can bother to get around to it". Not good customer service and will probably prevent me from ordering from them again. The extra $3 delivery charge on top of the cost of the food is also a bit much, especially when you are expected to tip on top of that.

column11:
This place is so good, I kept going back night after night. 

First time I went, there was a live folk rock band playing that was simply amazing. The music set the tone for a great college crowd that drew mostly young professionals all of whom looked athletic and well dressed. I didn't see any frat behavior or drunkenness, rather, everyone was friendly, open to conversing with strangers, and up for a good time with a cold drink.

The next night I went, there was a live jazz band playing with vintage speak easy attire. The crowd was mostly a married mid-aged group, but there was still a healthy mix of yuppies around. 

Both times, i felt very welcomed and encouraged to mix with the crowd. The crowd is very friendly towards shy people, like myself, and I ended up having a great time both nights!

column11:
Stayed here for a romantic getaway for hubby's bday. 

First of all, the hotel is gorgeous.  Its location is perfect, right next to the beach, and the sprawling spanish style building feels true to the vibe of SB.  

However, there were a few things that kind of bummed me out.  There were a lot of little bugs/spiders in our room, and given that the hotel is surrounded by lush greenery, I suppose it's inevitable, but it's a little alarming to see a baby spider crawling across your arm while you're staying at a 800+/night room.

Also the video in the room mentions that there are complimentary bike cruisers available for rent, but when we inquired about it, we were told 10/hr.  

Lastly the bed... it was comfortable enough to sleep in, but it is very noisy and creaky, if you know what I mean.  And the walls are pretty thin, so I'm sure the bed was heard by all our poor neighbors.

Am I nitpicking?  Absolutely!  But it's Four Seasons.  For the amount of money, reputation, and prestige associated with it, you have to hold it to the highest standards.  So while I'd say that it was a pleasant experience overall, I didn't feel that it delivered a perfect getaway.  But it was pretty damn nice! :)

column11:
I came in for an early dinner on a Monday and was their only customer. I was highly confused if I was supposed to wait to be seated, seat myself or order at the counter. After approaching the counter, they said I could take a seat if I wanted (still confused- is that what I'm supposed to do?!) Anyway, I took a seat and they DO have table service for dinner. 

It is a cute caf style restaurant with a deli counter (some bakes goods and salads) and a mini-accoutrement shop off to the side with wine, jellies, some small gifts, etc. It is a pretty casual but modern atmosphere with not so casual prices. I gathered the theme was healthy food with a Moroccan twist. They don't have a large menu for dinner items, but I actually like that as I frequently have difficulty making decisions. I opted for the Kale Caesar and added Grilled Salmon. It was honestly just okayyyyyy- could've used some sea salt or more flavor in the dressing. Staff was friendly and I enjoyed my experience (after the awkward seating sitch) so I'd give this place another go.

column11:
Walking up to the place and seeing a line out the door, I knew I was going to experience greatness. Luckily for my party and I, my friend made us reservations at 5:30 and we just walked past everyone in line and straight to our seats. We were greeted by a friendly waiter and explained how the place operates. Everyone works together so you can ask any waiter for anything and they bring it to you in a moments notice. 

We started off with the popcorn crawfish and it was absolutely incredible. So good that my end of the table had to get a second plate of them. You have to try these. 

After the popcorn crawfish came great assorted muffins which were really good too. I had the blackstrap molasses one and it was great paired with some butter. 

For the entree, I ordered the filet mignon stuffed with crawfish and it was perfect. You must try it. One bite and you will never want the experience to end. 

Great food mixed with a fun atmosphere and you have a real winner here. Make reservations or if you have to wait, it would be worth it.

column11:
This place gets 5 stars for being open late at night! (And yes, I realize this is a college town, which is why things are open late, but I'm old...)

Stopped by for a cookiewich around 11pm on a Saturday night, and loved that you can mix and match your cookies. The cookie wasn't as great as I expected, but this was late at night so I can't blame them for not having super fresh cookies. There is a plethora of cookies available, so trust me that you'll spend more time deciding what kind of cookies to get rather than actually eating it. 

The ice cream selection is McConnell's (which if you've been to State Street lately, you'll know there's a ridiculously long wait out the door there), which makes the cookiewich that much sweeter (no pun intended). Each cookiewich was around $3.95, but I believe it's two for $6.50. 

All in all, totally worth stopping by for a late night ice cream treat!

P.s. You get your cookiewich in a small styrofoam bowl, which you'll come to appreciate as the ice cream and cookie dust get all over your hands. What..just me?

column11:
This is quite possibly the best restaurant ever.  It has aroused a feeling in me I have never experienced before.  I actually have severe anxiety that it won't last.  NOT because they are doing anything wrong, in fact they do everything right; its just that it feels too good to be true. It keeps me up at night.  

Mesa Verde represents everything a restaurant should be. It has incredible, local and healthy food, served in beautiful, artful ways, by some of the most pleasant people you can imagine.  Of the many times I have visited, I have been greeted personally by the owner EACH time. He always checks in and makes sure every person is having a great experience and if he can't accommodate someones wishes, he goes out of his way to make it right.  In fact, one time there were no seats available so he told my group to come back in half an hour and he would make sure there was space.  When we came back he acted sincerely grateful and ended up not charging us for one of our deserts.  It was honestly embarrassing because there is no way I would ever not come back to this place....

As if things couldn't get any better, I recently learned from a reliable source, unaffiliated with the restaurant, that Mesa Verde is the Santa Barbara Farmers Market's best customer. Proof of the quality of their food, and of their support for the local community.  

The only thing I will caution is that the Macro Bowl, under the entree list, is really more of a salad.  If you are looking for a super healthy, lighter meal, I highly suggest it; but if you want something super flavorful and filling, I would try ANY of their other entrees. 

The last thing I should mention is that you cannot die without trying their deserts.  I am not a desert person at all, but I get it every time I come here.  They are all super unique and delicious.  Enjoy!

column11:
I ordered the green dragon roll and the firecracker roll. The green dragon was pretty terrible, the fish was warm and I don't think very well kept as I felt sick shortly after leaving the restaurant. The cucumber was very bitter and I don't think that was fresh either. The firecracker roll wasn't good by any means but I think the ingredients were at least fresh. The ramen broth was only marginally better than instant, but at least the portion size was large. 

The service here is good, however. The waitstaff is very attentive.

column11:
Nice little hole-in-the-wall spot. 

If you're searching for Elsie's, you'll likely drive right past it. It's not really advertised from the street and I believe that this is intentional. While only a mere block or so from the best of downtown, its location is far enough off the beaten path that lends to the feeling of a speakeasy.

Elsie's is in a unique old building sectioned off into a few rooms. You'll find old couches (the kind you'll absolutely sink into), vibrant wall colors, and eclectic wall art. It's like a grunge-style garage from the '90s and truly brings me back to that era. There's also a great, large back patio along with a small front parklet area for Covid. There are two bathrooms which have seen far better days, but their dirtiness ties right into the old, endearing vibe of the place as a whole. 

Elsie's is beer and wine only - and cash only, although there's an ATM in front. I don't typically carry cash so must remember this fact when I come here. You'll find a very unique assortment of beers and I've tried a few good ones. I'd also tried their soju-based Bloody Mary once and it wasn't bad. 

Why three stars? Service can be a hit or a miss. I was here last night and the bartender was awesome. He was able to recommend some good beers for us and even provided a shot glass with a sample to try. Haven't always been this lucky, though. I was here about a year and a half ago (late 2019) and the female bartender working (dark hair, she's there often) was surly to the point that I'd decided not to come back in until just yesterday. I don't know if she's still here but I'd avoid at all costs if she is. Otherwise, a nice, comfortable local watering hole.

Highly recommend for couples or families.

column11:
By far one of my favorite restaurants in the area, no wait, the planet.

Each meal Mesa Verde offers is bursting with flavor and so beautifully presented and delicately thought through. Even though I'm not a vegetarian/vegan, I honestly prefer it 9 times out of 10 to "real" meat or cheese. 

I have consistently gotten the pizzas and never been disappointed. Left feeling satiated and like my taste buds went to culinary heaven and back. 

The service is somewhat slow, however. Everyone is super nice though, especially the manager who gave my friends and I a free cheesecake for no reason! The prices may be hefty, but so worth it.

column11:
Also know as the Pebble Beach of Santa Barbara, Sandpiper has some impressive views and some amazing golf holes.  If you only have time to play 9 holes, the back 9 is responsible for the 5 star reviews.

Even the middle tees are long for the intermediate golfer.  Not much water comes into play.  Rough is rough and will result in lost balls.  Largest sand trap is the beach along many of the holes on the back 9.  Greens are relatively flat with minimal breaks.

Service is top notch with attendants helping with your clubs before and after a round.  It's nice to throw them a few bucks, as they seem like a quality crew.

Clubhouse is tiny, and a small, but high quality clubhouse lounge serves golf food faire.

Pro tip:  Stay at the Bacara Resort, while booking a round at Sandpiper.  Both are quality establishments and will satisfy both the Mr and Mrs.

column11: Your Santa Barbara wine tour begins right here! With over 25 years of Santa Barbara County wine industry experience, Wine Canyon Tours gives you an informative and adventurous, yet casual exploration of Santa Barbara wine country. While we did go with the afternoon tour, they do offer morning and private tour options. During the afternoon tour, we visited two boutique wineries that included an olive oil tasting as well as a stop in Solvang, a city knowing for its Danish-style architecture. I'm really looking forward to doing it again. Big shout out to Rick for showing us a great time!

column11: This place is unbelievably delicious! The owner was so kind and helpful in putting together a birthday celebration for my grandmother's 95th birthday. My grandmother grew up eating home cooked German food, so it was a special treat for her and the food was everything she (and we) could have hoped for! The atmosphere inside the restaurant is intimate and accented with German heritage. My boyfriend, who had never before tried authentic German food and was dubious about it, keeps telling me how he can't stop thinking about the brockwurst and the homemade pretzels with mustard. He insists that we must return soon... and I have absolutely no arguments. Very good restaurant. Excellent service, food, atmosphere, and overall experience. Thank you!

column11:
Extremely inexpensive, unpretentious, tasty and fun.

Lilly's tacos does serve many offal meats you won't find everywhere, but it's not just a novelty. It's honest, very well prepared, very simple food, using all kinds of cuts that are unfairly underused. I will admit that the first time I had eye tacos, it was a bit of a dare, but now I order it from time to time, simply because it's good (and, really, not all that different from other cuts of beef).

Next time you go, one of your tacos should be tripe, extra crispy. The texture and the taste are different from the other meats, and it's become my favorite. 

The cart with all the fixings (salsas, herbs, lime, etc.) is always well stocked with quality ingredients which empower you to make each taco truly yours. 

The place is not particularly attractive, but the people are very friendly and the service is very fast. 

HIGHLY RECOMMENDED

We sat at the bar, enjoyed a beer and our sandwiches, and watched as they created all of their delicious sandwiches. It was clean, fast, and we got friendly service to top it off. I highly recommend this place. I will definitely be stopping back in when I am in town again!

tacos. soda. salsa. that's all you'll find in this place, and that's all you'll need. The first time i tried lengua was here, and it is one of my all time favorite cow parts now.
 I ordered the ojo (eyeball) once, but i couldn't get over the texture of fat and gristle and other "crunches and squishes", but that could just be me. 
All in all, if you want affordable, delicious, authentic nom noms, get your ass to lily's!

column11:
So here is the deal - Check was $208.42 for 6 people.  We ordered two of the Polpette entrees, a Ciopino, two Positano and  a Guancale.  One glass of wine,($13)  one beer, two cesear salads.  No dessert, no appetizers.  You had to ask for bread because they brought one slice per person only.  A round baguette slice around 3" in circumference.  6 adults, 6 small rounds of bread.  The Polpette entree boasts of hand made meatballs - these were not.  We thought possibly frozen meatballs, spongy and tasteless.  That entree is $20.00 ---

Portion size:  For a $20.00 plate of spaghetti and meatballs, you would think it would be shareable.....we thought so too.  So, we decided we would take our leftovers home -   The plate/bowl came with a tremendous amount of sauce and about 1 cup of noodles and about 7 small meatballs.  Needless to say, no leftovers.  We did not share, but had we, they have a service charge of $3.00 for each meal shared.

They had alot of people working that evening.  ......we had a minimum of two servers and a buss person to our table at all times....service was ok - they were clearing our plates before we had finished the last bite. Somewhat stressful if you want to enjoy your food.  It was just too much attention for the quality of food served.

Our check came out to $30.00 per person - no everyone drank, no dessert, no appetizer and we ordered very pedestrian meals -  My suggestion - Find another Italian restaurant to go to - this one really is a ripoff.

column11:
Use their pharmacy only if you don't value your time. You routinely have to wait 20-40 minutes just to pick up a refill. Unlike CVS, they typically have only one person helping customers (the rest of them are filling prescriptions or entering data into a computer). I waited just under an hour (58 minutes to be exact), after being told it would take 20 minutes to pull the pre-packaged prescription down from the shelf, and that was only after I called them on my phone from the waiting area and asked them to bring the box - which I could see - up to the register. UPDATE: I had enrolled in their automatic refill program. It worked fine, once. The next time, I got a voicemail saying, "Your prescriptions will be ready for pickup next week. Call if you have any questions." I figured, "OK, great." Two days later, I realized that I only had enough of one Rx to last me another day and that Walgreens should have auto-refilled my prescription last week, not next week! I asked the pharmacist how a businenational chain can screw up something as fundamental and basic as this; he shrugged and said, in effect, "Not my department." So, yeah, CVS can be frustrating, but they are infinitely better than Walgreens. If you still want to get your prescriptions at Walgreens, don't say you weren't warned. UPDATE: They recently called us and asked if we wanted automatic refills on our prescriptions. We said yes. (Duh...) Well, I recently ran out of one, and when I called, was asked, "Do you want to refill that?" (So much for automatic refill.) A couple of weeks later, my wife gets a call: "Your prescriptions are ready." She goes to pick them up and, guess what, they're not ready. The next time she gets an automated call saying they're ready, she knows better and calls and speaks to a human being, who says, "Sorry! They're not filled yet, but will be by 5:00 PM." My wife goes there at noon the next day and they're still not ready. Walgreens is one of the biggest drug chains in the US; they're not a mom-and-pop operation. How they eff this stuff up over and over again is a mystery to me. (We're stuck there -our insurance allows us to change pharmacies once/year - but we're out of there come January 1.  UPDATE #2: I'm supposed to have automatic refills for some critical drugs. I get a robocall from them saying "Your prescriptions will be ready for pickup next week." Well, it's now next week, I've run out of my prescriptions and they still haven't filled it. 
I've lived all over the country and have dealt with a multitude of different pharmacies, including Walgreens in other states. THIS IS, BY FAR, THE WORST PHARMACY I HAVE EVER DEALT WITH. Save yourself a whole lot of pain and frustration and go somewhere (anywhere!) else.

column11:
You can't visit a beach town in Southern California without indulging in some killer authentic tacos. I asked multiple locals where I should go to find the best tacos and not a single person told me anywhere but Lilly's. 

I got two adobada and two asada tacos, which were ready before I was even done paying. The topping bar is a nice touch for people like me who like to load up on the onions and cilantro. While both meats were insanely tasty, I loved the adobada (marinated pork)! It was exactly what I was hoping for and more. For less than $2 per taco, I was tempted to try every type of meat (I love tacos and I was pretty hungry).... But I'll have to save the rest of my taste-testing for my next trip back to Santa Barbara. 

The location is pretty central and easy to find, and there is plenty of parking for those who are driving. I would definitely go again and recommend it to amateur taco lovers like myself.

column11:
Durant mon looong sjour aux US et plus particulirement  Santa Barbara, j'ai eu la chance de tester pas mal de chose. Et en faisant le tour de yelp, je me suis rendue compte que je n'avais jamais cris d'avis sur mes petites dcouvertes. 
L'un de mes coups de coeur et rituel de mes virs en ville tait de m'offrir une glace chez Pinkberry ou encore YogurtLand
Ce sont des glaces au yaourt avec des parfums comme trs frais tels que  grenade, fraise, noix de coco, nature, th vert, mangue,chocolat.... Vous pouvez ensuite demander  rajouter des topings sur la glace  comme des fruits (fraises, myrtilles, kiwi, mangue...) des fruits secs  (amandes, noisettes et j'en passe) ou encore des friandises ( bonbons, chocolat, biscuits...). Alors l, vous vous faites plaisir mais a devient plus rgime du tout. :-). 
Le design de leur boutique est super sympa et rafrachissant, je trouve le concept original. 
En clair des glaces au yaourt sur mesure, on choisis son parfum et ses ingrdients, on pse et on paye et c'est juste dlicieux!!

column11:
Why, oh, why can't Ventura produce places like this? Well, until it does, this little gem is only fifteen miles up the road in Carpinteria. (And by the way, Yelp? It's Linden with an "e".) The place is wonderfully done, all perfectly appointed wood tones and yellow brick made from the local coastal range. (You can see it in the hillsides, driving up PCH.) Walk in and surrender to the inevitability you're going to sit at that bar and drink classic cocktails. It's meticulously outfitted for them, there's a starter list if you find that helpful, and they make 'em like they understand the appeal. The whole experience is suffused in charm and if you suddenly find a couple hours slipped by and you're pleasantly loaded, you'll understand why.

The menu has just enough bits of delectable delights to keep drawing you back to try something new, and just little enough to show they understand the power of focus and simplicity. Mr Sly knows his way around his kitchen as virtually any item off the menu will attest. Everything seems fresh and perfectly done, without a hint of the fussiness and pretense you'd find at some places like this in the major metros. Even the basic burger is simple perfection: pink and juicy inside, wonderfully charred out, and adorned with fresh local produce. Who knows what they cooked those fries in, but they might be some of the best you'll ever have tasted. And then there's the Blue Plate Specials. Anyway, just too much to tell. Take a peek at the menus online, then as you're motoring up and down PCH just pull over in Carp and treat yourself to something very nice.

column11:
If there was an award for Best Place to See and Be Seen in your Bedhead and Uggs, the Daily Grind would get my vote. Sometimes its popularity confuses me, much like the popularity of a nearby "cajun" style diner confuses me, but hey, it's a fact - the place is often heaving with people. 
I like their muffins, particularly the cranberry strusel and the maple pecan, but I always get it to take away. More often than not, there is NO place to sit. The regulars have camped out in their spot for, like, a week (which might explain some of the bedhead issues), along with their dogs, and I don't see much table turnover during the times I'm standing in the queue to get my muffins.  
I definitely support the Daily Grind over the coffee shop chains, and this shop can get you in and out in a time almost comparable to the chains, it's also not far from the Mission St. freeway exit/onramp, so quite convenient for a caffeine detour. A number of my friends put the Daily Grind on their list of weekend To Dos.

column11:
(A delayed review since I've recently joined Yelp) Like a prior review, finding a place can often come without trying. A truck had overturned forcing a giant parking lot freeway closure situation. We were fortunate to be at an exit and wound up in this little town of Summerland.  She spots "Winery" and it's done, of course we're going to go have a look. We didn't expect much being "outside" the typical region but you don't know. We're not heading anywhere quick so I even get to taste. 

This was an excellent place and completely unexpected.  I can't think of many wineries from Temecula to Oregon where we enjoyed each offering. It didn't take long to fill out the wine club and we were set. Their Pinot Noirs are excellent and the wife really likes the Viogner.  For us, picking any is going to be tasty. Some strike our palates more than others though neither of us have been disappointed.  In the 4 years or so, the offerings have been unanimously consistently pleasing. 

We had one cracked bottle in one shipment and another had a leaking cork. Each time, their response was quick and a replacement was at the door next day.  Excellent service and the knowledge of wine shows such support for a product that is top shelf. This is one of the wine clubs where we have no doubts in what we will get in a shipment. 

Much thanks to Nebil, Zach and Catherine who have been tremendous in answering questions and their courtesy.  We look forward to many more years and wines from this excellent producer! 

Big-Big thumbs up!

column11:
I was told to order the fried chicken.  I did.  It was huge.  It was as if a chicken on steroids was exposed to uranium and grew up to be Gigantor.

We were a party of 13.  I have to give our waitress credit for being completely organized and not screwing up anyone's order.  Plus the food was served at the table simultaneously so we didn't have to wait for some straggler to get their order.  She's obviously worked there a long time and knows how to be a great waitress.  

The clientele consists of older folks.  Geeeeeeeze, I'm probably in that category these days, but I'd like to pretend that I'm not.  The building itself is a little dated and filled with some stuff that would be better left at grandma's house.  There was even a decorative Christmas tree next to us.  In May.

The people who brought us here are regulars and love the place.  I think it's a case of this is the best place here in town kinda thing.  It's not bad and I'm not knocking it.  It's a local's hangout in "Carp" so I'm glad they have something to enjoy.

column11: Nikka Ramen is goooood!!! I've only come here for lunch. Interior is nice, contemporary, but casual. I've had the Tonkotsu original with pork belly, the Tonkotsu black and the Shoya with pork shoulder. The Tonkotsu pork broth is the real deal, akin to what I've had in Kyoto - incredibly rich and flavorful. The pork meat that floats in the soup is ridiculously tender; with a texture like it's been roasting for hours, it pulls apart with a touch of a fork. The pork belly is a bit juicier and more flavorful, but fattier. The shoulder is meatier, leaner - both are great though. The noodles are expertly made and the salad they give you (green or seaweed) with the meal is nice touch. It's not cheap for lunch, at about $13 - $14 a bowl, but well worth it. Portions are large and artfully put together. The Tonkotsu broth is so rich for lunch I can barely move after; the Shoya ramen is the lighter lunch option. Slurp!

column11:
What's not to love about this place?  I LOVE THIS PLACE!  Great location for any tourists, right on State St.  Cute mom/pop place with a very awesome vibe.  Live blues/band on Thurs, Fri, and Sat.  

You are greeted right off with super friendly staff.  It was a "me" night (Hubby took the kiddies for a 1D concert!) and I noticed people Yelping this place ... Walked in and sat at bar.  Moses welcomed all in and was super friendly (2012 SB award for friendliest place!).  Order glass of Cab ( that became the whole bottle;) of Babcock Red.  Went perfectly with my Poke (spicy and ginger flavored paired well!).  Made friends with Kim (co-owner) who's hubby was the cook (for many many yrs, French trained!)...  Wound up also ordering the seafood special of seared Scallops in coconut curry sauce that was AWESOME!

I want to recommend this wonderful place to all... Great food, great drinks, super nice/friendly staff/owners ... Please eat here -you won't regret it!

Beer and wine available!

It can be a bit of a mad house here on the weekends and they don't have enough outdoor seating, but the coffees and teas are good (I suggest the dirty chai) and the setting is nice. Also, if you are biking in from Santa Barbara or Ventura it is right off the bike path.

Pros are that it is right next to a super cool mercantile store so you can browse as you sip.

Cons are that though the baristas are working hard, there are so many patrons that isn't the fastest service; also they only have one bathroom/stall (all gender, which is good), so expect to wait in line.

column11:
RACIST OWNER: I wish I could give zero stars. The owner, Ms. Birte Anderson, has no customer service skills. After paying my bill I went inside the bakery to look for my husband who left the table to go to the restroom. While inside the bakery looking for my husband, Ms. Anderson  approached me with anger asking me what I was doing there - I confess I was shocked from the rudeness of  her tone - I had just eaten in her place, patronized her business, and she was extremely rude to me. I asked her if she worked there and she answered yes (extremely rude tone), and finally I told her she lacks  customer service skills, to which she responded: yes ok. She kept glaring at me angrily and walked away.  At first I was baffled by this rude behavior towards a customer until I considered the context:  there was a beautiful party in town, La Fiesta, and her bakery was crowded with Spanish speakers and Brazilians, like me. She was clearly angry, possibly for having us, Latinos in her bakery, which made me think that this danish woman does not appreciate immigrants in her bakery, even though they were spending money to eat her cakes.
I LEAVE MY ADVICE: IF YOU ARE LATINO DO NOT GO THERE, YOU WILL BE MISTREATED.

column11:
This review is for "The Santa Barbara House", a separate building from the main Hyatt Centric: 
The room was "nice" (comfortable) and the staff members we interacted with were polite and helpful. That's it for the good news. The hotel website does NOT clearly show that this part of the Hyatt Centric is very inconveniently located away from the main hotel. Including the restaurants and pool as amenities for the Santa Barbara House is like saying you can walk (or drive!) down the street and around the corner to swim have dinner at a neighbor's house. Our room overlooked the very small parking lot (we could barely fit our SUV) and the park across the street where homeless people (and the police) hang out. Plus, our room was near the ice maker, elevator AND front gate... very noisy. Our request to be moved was said to be not possible. I was very disappointed and annoyed. I feel strongly that the hotel misrepresented the Santa Barbara House. We definitely don't recommend this hotel and won't be back.

column11:
Bottom Line:  Average food and threatened to charge us for not finishing our plate

I was VERY excited to try this place out as I desperately miss living in Koreatown down in LA where I was for 13 years.
  The biggest problem is that most of the things that are brought to the table are not marinated in anything.  The bulgogi - which has always been my favorite - was super yummy, pre marinated and grilled up very well.  
   However things like the unmarinated pork belly, was just cooked meat at the end and not a lot of flavor despite my efforts to add things to it and even my attempt to kind of marinade it in my bowl of spicy sauce.
   Service was mediocre at best - somewhat attentive.
There are no vegetables - at all - except a bowl of salad that was periodically refilled for us.  Toward the end I was definitely starting to get the "meat sweats".

We hadnt quite finished what was left on the Bulgogi plate when the server came back and told us we would be charged $10 for not finishing all of the meat - that after we spend more than $50 for our dinner and received mediocre service.
  Not only that - this whole chargeback thing was the first that we had heard of this.  It's not on the menu and our server never mentioned it.

Having never heard about this, IMHO it was quite rude to charge us what they did for dinner, then threaten to charge us more for something we know nothing about.

This place was good but has some work to do in the customer service department

column11: Location, Location, Location! When I do Mexican fast food I don't do Taco Bell or Del Taco, I do Chipotle and for my SB friends and I, this is the mother ship. Service is great, food is like any other Chipotle (fresh, yummy) but the outdoor area, just like 4 or 5 tables with plastic chairs, doesn't sound too sexy right? Wrong! The view is priceless! Over the years I have met several girls and got several numbers while sitting here, you make the call!! Shout out to Warren F, Levi M. - Always the wing men at my Chipotle experience!

column11: We had an amazing time on Saturday with Sandy! He was the best driver/tour guide, made great recommendations, and suggested a switch to the itinerary later in the day as we were running a bit late (our faults for enjoying ourselves so much at each winery) which ended up working out so much better than our original plan. He made sure we were well attended to and taken care of at every winery and didn't make us feel rushed throughout the day. He set-up a full picnic lunch for us at our third stop, which was great! The cost of the wine tour per person ($140) includes the transportation for 6 hours, 3-4 wine tasting fees ($15-$25 each), olive oil tasting fee, and lunch- it's definitely well worth the cost. We will keep 100% be using Dee Tours next time! Thank you Sandy :)

column11: Two stars for effort. New customers to Recipes Bakery. We ordered a $30 lemon meringue pie for a birthday last week. The meringue looked perfectly toasted and we couldn't wait to eat it, until we cut into it. It was literally liquified lemon under the meringue. We've never encountered this before,sadly we couldn't eat it. We contacted them the next morning and they offered a replacement which we were happy about. We REALLY wanted that pie!! We cut into the replacement pie and were shocked, again it was liquidy lemon. We needed a spoon to scoop out the liquid. The meringue was delicious, the lemon soup was perfect in taste, just not appearance or consistency. We are extremely disappointed. Not sure if this is the norm for this bakery but we won't be back. I'm used to a firm/solid lemon under the meringue.

column11:
Terrible! I've never been to a donut place this horrible!! To start off all the staff looked to be about 16 and on their first day! No one knew what the hell they were doing or how to work the register! Then as we get up to the counter, there are nats and flies flying all over and on the donuts! I was instantly grossed out! Then when we told the cashier she said "that's normal!" ....normal?!.... to top it off the lady making the coffee made 3 hot coffees that no one ordered then waited about 20 mins to even ask me (the only person waiting) what I was waiting for! When I told her a breakfast sandwich, she pulled one out of a drawer and smashed in down and handed it to me! I took one bite and spit it back out! Not only was it cold but it tasted like it had be made out of plastic and had sitting on the counter for 3 days!! When trying to explain to the cashier my problem she goes "im sorry would you like another one?" It took about 30 mins to convince them I didn't want anything else from there and to give my money back, which no one knew how to do! It won't be long til this place goes outta business! 
So if your looking for a donut place go to spud nuts!

column11:
The muffinification of bagels in this country continues unabated, and Jack's is the latest West Coast perpetrator. Not only are these belly-bustin' doughballs unlike any NY bagel you've ever enjoyed, the egg-wich-type "florentine" breakfast sandwich featured two torturous, dessicated oeufs and two lonely leaves of spinach and was bereft of any fluff. Even a few twists of black pepper couldn't make it work for me.

Props, however, for a spacious, sunny patio. If you go, hope no yammering, complaining children are there to disrupt your tranquility.

column11:
We stopped at the Santa Barbara Ritz on our way back from a Northern CA wine trip. We arrived at 3PM, admittedly before the 4PM check in time. Said they call. By 4, no call, so went back to the now crowded desk. Got a so so room. No big deal. At 5:30 had two very mediocre messages at the spa. Oh well. Went to dinner at the high end restaurant around 8:30, without reservations. Couldn't be seated although 40% of the tables were vacant. A corner table opened up, but another host sat another couple. Dinner at the bar. While we can easily afford it, spending $2,000 for one night at mid range hotel leaves one feeling violated.
Beautiful location but not worth it.

column11: We stopped by this restaurant while on vacation in Santa Barbara, CA.  We found it through Yelp, it had multiple good reviews, close to our hotel, and wanted some good Californian style Mexican food.  Our experience was terrible.  Maybe we caught them on a bad night, but the food tasted like it was right out of the microwave.  My wife got the chicken fajitas and I got the colorado burrito.  The chicken was not fresh for the fajita and they brought her out 2 hard and crusty tortias.  My burito came out on a dinner plate with nothing else on it but one large dry burrito (very visually unpleasing) and the colorado sauce taste like it came right out of bottle and pouring over the meat last minute as opposed to what I'm used to with a good slow cooked and extra tender juicy meat.  I hate writing bad reviews and usually I won't, but I wanted to warn other potential guest like myself so they are not completely disappointed like I was.  I never leave food on my plate and usually eat the rest of my wifes dinner, but we both left with half plates of food and a bad taste in our mouths.  The service wasn't bad and hopefully I just came on a very off day.

column11: We were seated wherever we wanted when we first walked in, we were greeted by Robbie and promptly given menus, our young son was given a bucket full of toys to play with. Rick Sr. Came by and gave us some great suggestions to eat; corned beef and hash. It was a wait but it was to be expected for fresh made to order food. The food was perfect!!! No seasoning needed. Kids pancakes we're great. 2 egg omelette and corned beef ands hash with jalapeos was excellent! The drinks never went dry and Robbie makes  a mean hot chocolate and chocolate milk!! Three cheers for the two Ricks! We have told everyone we know to eat at the Worker Bee Cafe!!!

column11:
I had been looking forward to trying Trattoria Mollie for quite some time based on the great word. Was extremely disappointed after my dining experience.  The food wasn't bad, but it did not match the great reviews given online either.   The prices are inflated when considering the cost of ingredients, portions are very small for typical Italian food. 

My biggest complaint however is the service. We arrived at 5:45pm for dinner and were one of two other couples dining. Our server was hasty, rude, and impatient. My plate was cleared while I was still eating, we were not checked on, no coffee offered...very unwelcoming.  We couldn't believe it! 

I had ordered $10 minestrone soup to go for my fianc, and when we got home, it was a half a cup of cut up carrots and celery, no broth, and definitely not minestrone. When I called to let them know they had sent me home with the wrong soup, their only reply was that their minestrone was 'the very best'.  They did not offer to replace or even an apology for their service! 

I felt remorseful spending so much money on what I thought would be a lovely dinner out to only feel like I had thrown my money down the drain.  I would not recommend this restaurant to anyone, and will never go back. I am sticking with my local favorite via maestro. Much more friendlier and the food is better and better priced too.

column11:
Short and to the point- khao soi worth it! .. boat noodle .. abort it! 

My fat ass got two noodle bowls. Why not right?! . The first bowl was khao soi. Flavor was there and a good portion. The sour veggie in there was a great surprise! My poor ass taste that rich flavor. Thank you for making it authentic! 

The second bowl was the boat noodle..... so this one was disappointing but I got an answer to why. After my first bite I though ..well did I only fill my spoon up half way? Cause like the taste was half there. I had to ask myself was it because I ate the khao soi first. But no..my fat ass palate knows what's up. I ask for fish sauce for more flavor. It helped. I finished the bowl cause ..come on.. don't be wasteful with food and love the earth! The waiter guy ask me how was it. I told him the truth about the khao soi then with the boat noodle I gave him a look cause I didn't want to disrespect him like tat since he works there and that's their product. So when I gave him a look he knew what's up and explained to me it was use to be packed with flavor and in the end of the day it's a business and it needs to sell. Customers in Santa Barbara wasn't ordering so they had to adjust to their palate. It is what it is. I hate to say it but it does make me question other items on the menu. Oh well they in business and getting moneyyyyyyyyyyyy yassssssssssssssssssss .... yassssssssssssssssssssssssssssss get that money yassssssssss ... yas.

column11:
Our party of 8 showed up on a Thursday night and it was packed. Luckily we had a reservation so there was no wait. The water and bread came quickly, and our waitress took our orders shortly afterwards. 

The calamari appetizer was quite delectable. The batter was nice and light, but there were crunchy pieces in there as well. 

I had a small bowl of clam chowder, but it was very hearty. Every spoonful of soup had clams in it. However, the soup was too salty for me. I was not able to taste the clams as much as I would like. 

My entree, however, was very disappointing. As a college student, I don't often spend $26 on just an entree. But when I do, I expect it to be done well, especially when I'm ordering fish and the name of your establishment is Enterprise "Fish" Company. My cut of Salmon was dry and extremely firm. When I went at it with my fork, instead of flaking, the fish came apart more like carnitas. Every bite would get caught in my throat and refuse to go down. 

The rice that came with the salmon was also terrible. Every 2 or 3 bites, I would get a piece of rice that was hard, hard enough to get wedged between my teeth. I regret spending so much on my entree and barely eating half of it.

The service at the restaurant was not bad. Our waitress was very patient with us. My water cup was never empty (I must have went through 4 or 5 glasses of water). Our plates were cleared as soon as we were finished with them. Everyone was polite and friendly. Props to the wait staff! 

I would have given 3 stars, but according to Yelp, that means "A-OK". My experience at this establishment was definitely not OK.

column11: I tried their avocado salad with chicken & it was ok. I came with a party of 8 and the food came out around the same time. I was given a house salad with ranch & as I was going to pass it to my mom she turned it away because she asked for the dressing on the side. The salad I was holding had a HUGE glob of dressing on it & due to food allergies she can't handle a lot of dressing that drenched the salad. The waiter didn't want to take it back & everyone else had a salad so I just munched on it. Then my avocado salad came & this other waiter gave me a "no-no" & scolded me that it's not my salad. I also ordered ranch for my salad but got it on the side...& I was half way done with the avocado salad so that dressing was wasted.  Beside the salad oops, everyone said their dishes were ok.  A couple of people liked that their margaritas were heavy and definitely had them buzzin.  This place was meh for me and I'd probably check out another place before coming back here.

column11:
A 4 for service and decor and a 2 for the food.

I ate here a few years back and was curious to see what the owner had done with the place. We had breakfast and I found the omeletes to be filled with just enough stuff to make you feel Ok about it but not impressed and the bagel that came with my meal was probably fresh the day before.

We will search out some place else for breakfast the next time we are in town.....

column11: Enjoyed my brunch. The wild salmon was moist and had a nice, thin buttery crust. roasted potatoes were a little burnt and definitely recommend baguette  with a dollop of the marvelous orange marmalade jam. The pastries looked amazingly mouth watering. I think I gained 5 pounds just looking at them. Lol. Lots of Gluten free options too! Cute place overall - liken it to a mini-Whole Foods. Minus one star for the kinda expensiveness. Will be back.

column11:
After going to UCSB for nearly two years I finally went to Freebirds for the first time and got a steak burrito with guacamole. It's not an exaggeration to say the burritos are big and are very comparable to the burritos from chipotle. 

I wouldn't say the burritos were out of this world but I can certainly understand the buzz around it. For a place that's constantly busy they do make pretty good burritos that aren't sloppy/messy/falling apart but considering how Super Cucas is a hop skip and away I wouldn't make it a habit of going to Freebirds since it's ridiculously expensive. 

If you go late and on the weekends beware. From what I've seen on my nights walking by they attract a lot of drunks and the night I was there, a guy there was quite belligerent.

column11: We had a terrible experience on this "tour". Rick showed up with an attitude which only got worse as the day went on. We spent more time in the trolley  than we did tasting wine and while we all had fun together, the day was a huge disappointment.

column11: When I'm in Santa Barbara, this is my favorite place to let happy hour roll right into evening.  My friends and I go sit around the fire pit on the patio in the afternoon, drink 2 for 1 margaritas and eat the half off appetizers during happy hour.  I recommend the sampler platter, it never gets old!  Before we know it, it's always later than we think and sometimes there's live music or else a DJ and dance music gets going.  The club scene has never really been my thing, but at Sandbar I seem to always have a great time.  There's always fun people to meet and you can have a great time whether or not you like to dance.  I couple times I've been when they had a mechanical bull, we've got some hilarious stories from bull nights!  I wish they would have that bull more often...

column11: Teru is a newly opened sushi restaurant on State St. My boyfriend and I wanted to try it, walked by, and noticed there was an open table! We were promptly seated. The outside seating was 4 2-person tables and 2 heaters. The employees were respectful and kind. The sushi was so delicious! We ordered salmon, toro, and uni nigiri and a specialty roll. They have wine, sake, and beer on the menu. We will definitely be repeat costumers!

column11:
This restaurant, hands down, has the best complimentary chips and salsa I've ever had. This alone would make me want to come back! The green salsa is surprisingly creamy yet still hot. I'm still thinking about the chips as I write this post. 

The tacos de camaron were amazing as well. The shrimp included in the tacos were almost the size of my palm!! They were very generous with the amount of shrimp per taco too. The rice was alright--definitely not the highlight of the show but did it's job.

The taquitos de pato en mole coloradito was (duck taquitos with mole) was definitely interesting. The duck was shredded and fried into taquitos, and the mole was slightly bitter. I'm glad we were able to try this but I'm not sure if we'll reorder again.

The esquites Mexicanos was delicious. The corn was perfectly seasoned with cojita cheese and sour cream. Definitely the fanciest esquites I've had. 

Overall a great experience! The food was satisfying and the service was friendly. I'd recommend coming while the sun is about to set so you can enjoy your meal with a beautiful view.

column11:
Ah Pierre Lafond. My Lafond-ness grows for you after every visit. I have been visiting this coffee shop since I was a little girl and make it a point to stop by whenever I find myself in beautiful Montecito. My favorite time of day to stop is before 10:00 am. The kona muffins are to die for and they always have some sort of unique blend of coffee roasting and ready for you.

One thing I love about this place too is that you always stand a good chance of seeing a celebrity. I make it a point to sit outside at one of their tables for as long as I can stand in hopes of catching a glimpse of one of the many famous people residing in the area.

So definitely check out this quaint coffee shop if you can! I highly recommend it!
